[Black "Introduction to the Fifth Edition"]
[Result "*"]

{ With the untimely passing of the great Russian trainer and author Mark Dvoretsky, the question of how his Endgame Manual should be continued was raised. The book has been recognized worldwide as one of the classics of chess literature.  Dvoretsky had begun to compile a list of revisions for a possible fifth edition and had sent the list to the publisher. When I was offered the opportunity to supervise this revision, it was an offer I could not refuse. I was quite familiar with the book’s exceptional content; I use it regularly with my students.  When Mark Dvoretsky was working on the first edition in 2001 and 2002, I was asked to assist by cross-checking his analysis. For the fifth edition, American grandmaster and endgame authority Alex Fishbein was asked to fill this role. He put my suggestions under the analytical microscope and added a couple of his own discoveries. Most importantly, he reorganized much of the newer and more complicated theory, particularly in the rook endings section, to make it more accessible to the reader. A student of Dvoretsky in the 1990s, Alex Fishbein tried to make the changes and additions to this classic as close as possible stylistically to what Dvoretsky would have wanted.   Undertaking a review and revision is not the result of the work of just one or two people, and there were other contributors. In the section on rook endings alone,Jacob Aagaard’s plan in theSteckner position  (diagram 9-158)  ,Erwin L’Ami’s new Vancura-like plan  (diagram 9-168a)  , andAnish Giri’s discovery in R+4Ps vs. R+3Ps  (diagram 9-208e)  have all been added and recognized. Comments by Chessable followers were also considered.  Previous editions highlighted in blue the text that the author felt all players should study. For the fifth edition, that text is now emphasized with a gray background. @@StartSquare@@Ed. note: Chessable translates the book's light gray background → bold variation title@@EndSquare@@. This will make it much easier to follow. Some diagrams have been omitted, and others added. If a diagram is new, it will carry a lower-case letter after the number. For example, the new diagram after 9-168 is designated 9-168a. The omission of a diagram is also noted.  For the fifth edition, Mark Dvoretsky’s original introduction has been preserved. The other introductions and forewords which have appeared over the years have been removed. However, we are proud to add a new foreword by the fourteenth world champion Vladimir Kramnik.  I would be remiss if I failed to mention the valuable contributions either in this or prior editions by Artur Yusupov, Jack Jeffrey, Yakov Konoval, Michael Taktikos and Vincent Keymer. In addition, Vardan Pogosyan provided additional rook endgame analysis for the fourth edition, checked by Dvoretsky himself with the Lomonosov seven-piece tablebases. My gratitude is also extended to David Kramaley of Chessable for making the comments to the fourth edition on Chessable available.  Finally, there is no better way to close than quoting grandmaster Artur Yusupov, considered by many to be Dvoretsky’s most successful student: “I am sure that those who study this work carefully will not only play the endgame better, but overall their play will improve. One of the secrets of the Russian chess school is now before you, dear reader!”  Karsten Müller  Hamburg  April 2020 }
