{ The most common question and one that we constantly ask ourselves is how to improve at the game. My very first coach, WIM Margareta Perevoznic, had a clear recipe for success – endgames weightlifting. We spent hours on end studying the heavy volumes of Chess Endings Encyclopedias.  I still remember the continuous repetitions  (the interactive MoveTrainer™ is THE platform for that!)  , especially in the rook endgames that I somehow kept forgetting... Her philosophy had a huge impact on me, IM Alina l'Ami. In 1995 I joined the Romanian squad to the World Junior Championships in Brazil and took the title in the under 10 section! My strategy back then was very simple: liquidate into a better endgame and convert the advantage.  It has ingrained in me the firm belief that the endgame is a key component to raise one's game. Nowadays, and perhaps this has always been that way, the emphasis is mostly set on opening preparation. Someone can study the Sicilian and play it the next time their opponent goes 1.e4. This is understandable, as we need to know a move or two before reaching the final phase of the game.  Nevertheless, “Openings teach you openings, endgames teach you chess!” @@StartBracket@@Stephan Gerzadowicz@@EndBracket@@. Here we get to see the real strength of the individual pieces. What, to me, makes the endgame interesting as well is the value of each move. In the endgame, one mistake can be the difference between a draw or a loss, while in the opening and middlegame stages, a bad move merely hands a ‘worse’ or ‘bad’ position, where there is still everything to play for.  Sadly, in 2016 the renowned trainer Mark Dvoretsky passed away, leaving an immortal mark on the chess world. I am convinced that a balanced chess training is like a three-legged stool. Each leg – opening, middlegame and DEM 5  (Dvoretsky's Endgame Manual 5th Edition)  – is necessary to stay upright.  Endgames are not brain breakers. Maybe just a little bit, at times. But there is a solution to the scary unknown and incomprehensible → DEM 5! For an enhanced learning experience, this is what's new in the latest Chessable edition:  7-piece tablebases @@StartBracket@@will be released shortly@@EndBracket@@DiagramsVisual cues24 hours of video material by Dutch GM Erwin l'Ami, covering all the endgames that should be committed to memory.'Learn Important Only': this feature/setting allows you to study only the lines that Mark Dvoretsky himself deemed essential to memorize. DEM 5 has 'Learn Everything' by default but you can easily change it under 'Course Options' → 'Learn Important Only', in your chapter list for this course. @@StartSquare@@Ed. note@@EndSquare@@ the MoveTrainer™ editor'scontributions to the original book.
  And a short note on Diagram References: 
Diagram 1-16 = the first diagram in the Solutions section @@StartBracket@@there are 15 chapters in the book and 16 stands for the final part that includes the answers to the puzzles@@EndBracket@@; Exercise 1/3 = the third exercise of the first chapter; The text and the diagram references were kept consistent with the book for easier navigation through the printed material @@StartBracket@@in case someone owns both@@EndBracket@@.
  I find it a great honor to bring an iconic book like the 5th Edition of Dvoretsky's Endgame Manual to the Chessable platform. I am grateful for this opportunity, for the support from my colleagues and for the help from the dedicated testers throughout the beta testing phase. And thank you all in advance for your future comments! I tried to reduce human error as much as possible but, as always, kindly report any issues you might face and I will be more than ready to assist.    As chance would have it, I got to work side by side with my husband, Dutch GM Erwin l'Ami. He had the incredible privilege of studying the endgames under the guidance of the author himself! While I was editingErwin's new Vancura-like plan in theSteckner position, he was recording the videos for the endgames marked as essential in the book. And that's what I call a happy chess family!  It was an absolute joy to work on this project and I trust it will improve your endgame technique too!  Alina l'Ami  Chessable editor  January 18th, 2021 }
