[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 1 – Pawn Endgames I"]
[Black "Opposition"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/3k4/8/3K4/3P4/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Opposition is the state of two kings standing on the same file with one square separating them @@StartBracket@@'close' opposition, three or five squares between them, is called 'distant' opposition@@EndBracket@@; the opposition may be vertical, horizontal, or diagonal.   'To get the opposition' means to achieve this standing of the kings one square apart with the opponent to move @@StartBracket@@ that is, to place him in zugzwang@@EndBracket@@; 'to fall into opposition' means, conversely, to fall into zugzwang oneself.  Return to Key Squares 1-1, where we see the simplest case of the opposition @@StartBracket@@close, vertical@@EndBracket@@. With White to move, there is no win: }
1. Kc5 { Or  1.Ke5  Ke7⨀  . } 1... Kc7
{ Black to move loses, because he must allow the enemy king onto one of the key squares:   @@StartFEN@@8/3k4/8/3K4/3P4/8/8/8 b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Kc7  2.Ke6  +-; or  1...Ke7  2.Kc6  +-   Opposition is the main weapon in the fight for three connected key squares   (in diagram 1-1 they are c6, d6 and e6)  . When we are speaking of the opposition, it is usually not just one pair of squares, but several, which are under consideration: c5 and c7, d5 and d7, e5 and e7.   The stronger side gets the opposition in order to execute an outflanking  @@StartBracket@@where the enemy king retreats to one side, and our king then attacks the other way@@EndBracket@@.  The weaker side gets the opposition in order to prevent this outflanking. }
*

