{ H. Neishtadt, 1890  The only thing that saves White is getting the distant opposition. }
1. Kh1
{ White's king cannot move forward.  1.Kg3?  there comes  1...Ke1!  2.Kg2  Ke2  3.Kg3  Kf1!  -+   White would like to take the opposition with  1.Kf1  but this is also a mistake. After  1...Kd2  2.Kf2  Kd3  the f3-square his king needs is occupied by his own pawn, and the opposition passes to his opponent:  3.Kg3  or  3.Kf1  Ke3!  4.Kg2  Ke2  etc. }
1... Kd2
{ 1...Ke1  2.Kg1=  and if @@StartFEN@@8/8/8/4p1p1/8/5P2/8/3k3K b - - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...g4  2.Kg2!  Kd2  3.fxg4= }
2. Kh2 Kd3 3. Kh3 { Draw. } *

