{ Now let's examine  the mechanism by which the stronger side can exploit the distant opposition.  It is, in fact, quite simple, and  consists of the conversion of the distant opposition into close opposition by means of outflanking. If outflanking is not possible, then possession of the distant opposition is worthless.   H. Mattison, 1918  The pawns are lost, after which Black's king will control the key squares in front of the f7-pawn. But White has a tactical resource at hand: he moves both pawns forward to lure Black's pawn nearer to his king allowing him to defend the new key squares. }
1. g6 fxg6 2. f5
{ 2.Kg2?  Kg4  3.f5  gxf5  -+  and Black controls the opposition.  Also bad is @@StartFEN@@8/8/6p1/7k/5P2/8/8/7K w - - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Kh2?  Kg4  3.f5  Kxf5!  4.Kg3  Kg5  -+ }
2... gxf5 3. Kg1
{ Black controls the distant opposition, but he cannot convert it into close opposition.   The problem is that after  3...Kg5  4.Kf1  , outflanking with  4...Kh4  has no point; and on  4...Kf4  , it is White who takes the close opposition by  5.Kf2  - or in case of @@StartFEN@@8/8/8/5p1k/8/8/8/6K1 b - - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  4...Kg4  ,  5.Kg2  - and Black's king can't use the f5-square as it is blocked by his own pawn.  If the king and the pawn could both occupy this square simultaneously, then on the next move the outflanking would be decisive; unfortunately, the rules of chess don't allow such a thing. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 1 – Pawn Endgames I"]
[Black "Opposition 1-10"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/4k3/3p4/3P4/2P5/8/8/5K2 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ J. Drtina, 1907    Taking the distant opposition with  1.Ke1?  leads only to a draw. The opposition on the e-file is meaningless:  1...Ke8!  2.Ke2  Ke7  3.Ke3  Ke8  4.Ke4  Ke7  and White cannot get any closer, because the e5-square is off limits.  And if the White king leaves the e-file, his opponent will take the opposition forever, i.e.: @@StartFEN@@4k3/8/3p4/3P4/2P5/8/8/4K3 w - - 2 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Kf2  Kf8!  3.Kg3  Kg7!  4.Kf3  Kf7!  etc.   In such situations there is usually a 'major' line, in which is it vitally important to capture the opposition. And when the enemy king retreats from it, you must outflank it.  In this instance, the key squares are e6, f6, and g6, the middle square is f6, and the major line is the f-file. Imagine that Black's king was on f7, and moved to one side. White must move to outflank, thus: }
1. Kg2 Kf6
{ It's pointless to stay on the e-file: White's king will reach the key square g6. On the f-file it is necessary to maintain the opposition; therefore: }
2. Kf2
{ What is Black to do now?   Moving the king forward is useless:  2...Kf5  3.Kf3  Ke5  4.Ke3  Kf5  5.Kd4  and 6.c5.   If we retreat the king to the right, White's king advances left and takes over the key squares on the queenside:  2...Kg6  3.Ke3  Kf7  4.Kf3  is not bad either,  4.Kd4  Ke7  5.Kc3  Kd7  6.Kb4  Kc7  7.Ka5!  (diagonal opposition!)  7...Kb7  8.Kb5  ⨀  Kc7  9.Ka6  +- }
2... Ke7 { The only chance but now comes the algorithm we already know: } 3.
Kg3 Kf7 4. Kf3 Ke7 5. Kg4 Kf8 6. Kf4 Ke7 7. Kg5 Kf7 8. Kf5
{ The distant opposition has been successfully transformed into the close one. }
*

