{ F. Sackmann, 1913  The first thing White must do is seize the opposition. }
1. Kf5 Kb6 { Black's king must be the first one on the 6th rank. } 2. Kf6
{ The rest is the standard technique of converting distant opposition into close opposition. Here, the 'major line' is the 7th rank, through the middle square c7 in the three connected key squares c8, c7 and c6. }
2... Kb7 3. Kf7 { 3.Ke5?  Ka7!= } 3... Kb6 { 3...Kb8  4.Ke6! } 4. Ke8
{ Outflanking! } 4... Ka7 5. Ke7 Ka8 6. Kd6 Kb7 7. Kd7
{ Instead of the easily winning  7.Kd7!  , White might also play  7.Kxc5?!  Kc7  8.Kb4  Kb6  9.c5+!  Ka6  10.Kxa4  +- But not @@StartFEN@@8/8/1kp5/8/pKP5/P7/8/8 w - - 3 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Kxa4?  c5  10.Kb3  Ka5  11.Kc3  Ka4  12.Kb2  Ka5  13.Kb3  Kb6  14.Kc3  Ka5= }
7... Kb6 8. Kc8
{ The final, decisive outflanking.  George Walker analyzed a similar position as far back as 1841. We shall return to it in our next section − mined squares. }
*

