{ 1/2. H. Weenink, 1924 } 1. Ke4 Kg4
{ How should White continue? If he managed to pass the move to his opponent, he could force a favorable pawn exchange on the kingside @@StartFEN@@8/8/8/1p6/1P2Kpk1/8/6P1/8 b - - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  2...Kg5  3.Ke5  Kg4  4.Kf6!  , etc.  But how can this be done? }
2. Kd5
{ 2.Ke5  is useless: just not  2...Kg3?  3.Kf5  , but @@StartFEN@@8/8/8/1p2K3/1P3pk1/8/6P1/8 b - - 3 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Kg5!  3.Kd4  Kh4!  The only chance is to threaten the b5-pawn. }
2... Kh5 { 2...Kf5  3.Kd4  and Black loses the opposition. } 3. Kc6
{ But what can Black do now? To maintain the opposition,  3...Kg6  is required, but the king is too far from the g2-pawn then and  4.Kxb5  wins.  Otherwise White seizes his coveted opposition and then transforms the distant opposition into the close one by standard means @@StartBracket@@outflanking@@EndBracket@@. }
3... Kg5 4. Kc5
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed. Taking the distant opposition. The remainder of the moves is a perfect illustration of how the opposition can be taken advantage of.@@EndSquare@@ }
4... Kg4 5. Kd6
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed. Outflanking. Using this typical technique, White approaches the pawn on f4.@@EndSquare@@ }
5... Kh5 6. Kd5 Kh4 7. Ke6 Kg5 8. Ke5 Kg4 9. Kf6 Kg3 10. Kf5 { White wins. } *

