{ 1/4. N. Grigoriev, 1933 } 1. Ka6 { Of course not  1.b6?  Kb7= } 1... Kb8
{ 1...f4  2.b6  +- } 2. g3
{ The hasty  2.b6?  misses the win:  2...Kc8!  ∆ 3...cxb6  3.b7+  Kb8  4.g3  c5  5.Kb5  Kxb7  6.Kxc5  Kc7  7.Kd5  f4!  8.gxf4  Kd7=  Black saves the game by seizing the opposition. }
2... Ka8
{ Another defensive method also does not help  2...Kc8  3.Ka7  Kd8  4.Kb8!  (an opposition!)  4...Kd7  5.Kb7  Kd6  6.Kc8  +- and  5...Kd8  6.Kc6  (outflanking!)  Kc8  7.Kd5  Kb7  8.Ke5  Kb6  9.Kxf5  Kxb5  10.g4  c5  11.g5  c4  Diagram 16-2   12.Ke4!  (we shall see this method - decoying the hostile king into a check - more than once in this book)  Kb4  13.g6  c3  14.Kd3!  Kb3  15.g7  c2  16.g8=Q+  . }
3. b6 Kb8 4. Kb5 { 4.b7?  c5  5.Kb5  Kxb7= } 4... Kb7 5. bxc7 Kxc7 6. Kc5 Kd7
7. Kd5
{ This time White has seized the opposition, therefore the pawn sacrifice  7...f4  is pointless. }
