{ Mined Squares   Sometimes, it is a single pair of squares that correspond; I refer to such squares as being mined.' Do not be the first to step on a mined square, or you'll be 'blown up' - that is, fall into zugzwang. You must either first allow your opponent to step on the mined square, or move forward, accurately avoiding it.   This and the next diagram are two quite typical examples of mined squares:   Here we have what I call  'untouchable pawns.'  White's king shuttles between b3, c3 and d3, while the black king goes from c7 to b7 to a7, neither of them able to attack the pawn - the squares c4 and b6 are mined. }
1. -- *

