{ And now, let's return to a position we reached while analyzingF. Sackmann's study @@StartBracket@@Diagram 1-11@@EndBracket@@.   The only winning try is to get the king to the d6-square. To keep the opponent from counterattacking successfully on the queenside, it is important to begin the march with the black king as far away as possible. This consideration shows us the first pair of corresponding squares: a6 and b4. }
1... Kb7 2. Kb3 Ka6 3. Kb4 { Black is in zugzwang. } 3... Kb7
{ Now it's time to consider further action. Note the reciprocal zugzwang with the kings at d4 and b5; that means the d4-square is mined, and must be circumvented. }
4. Kc4 Ka6 5. Kd3
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed. A brilliant move. White carefully avoids the d4-square.@@EndSquare@@ }
5... Ka5 6. Ke4 Kb5 7. Kd4 { And Black is in zugzwang again. } 7... Ka4 8. Ke5
Kxa3 9. Kd6 { White wins. } *

