{ Alekhine − Yates, Hamburg 1910 } 1. Kd3
{ A mistake would be  1.Kd4?  Ke6  ⨀  thus, the d4- and e6-squares are mined.  And  1.Kb4?  Ke6  2.Kxb5  Kxe5  3.Kxa4  Ke4  4.b4  Kxe3  leads to a queen-and-rook-pawn vs. queen endgame, which is, according to theory, drawn.   Incidentally, White's moves could also have been transposed:  1.e4  f4  2.Kd3  Ke6  3.Ke2!  ⨀ but if  3.Kd4?!  Ke7  . }
1... Kd7 { 1...Ke6?  2.Kd4  +- } 2. e4 f4 3. Ke2 Ke6 4. Kf2
{ Black resigned. With a white pawn at e4 and a black one at f4, we already know the squares f3 and e5 are mined. White's king avoided entering the f3-square first, while is opposite number had no similar waiting move, since the e5-pawn was in the way. }
