{ The next pair of exercises are rather difficult. In each, you must judge whether Black ought to go into the pawn endgame.   1/6. M. Dvoretsky, 1976 @@StartBracket@@based on the themes of an Estrin-Gusev ending, Moscow 1963@@EndBracket@@. }
1... Rxd7
{ If Black postpones the transition to the pawn ending, playing  1...f4?!  with the idea  2.Ke2  Rxd7  3.Rxd7?  Kxd7  4.Kd3  Ke7!  , Black seizes the opposition when the white king enters the fourth rank.  Black will have serious troubles though in the rook-and-pawn endgame after @@StartFEN@@3r4/3P4/p1k5/1p4p1/1P3p1p/P4P1P/3R1KP1/8 w - - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Rc2+!  Kxd7  3.Rc5  Rg8  4.Ke2  .  He should focus on the task at hand and calculate the forced drawing line. }
2. Rxd7 { 2.Rc2+  Kd6  3.Rc5  Ke6  4.Rc6+  Rd6  is not dangerous for Black. }
2... Kxd7 3. f4 g4
{ After  3...gxf4?  4.Kf3  Ke6  5.Kxf4  Kf6  6.g3  White creates a distant passed pawn that will be decisive. We shall discuss this sort of position later. }
4. g3 { Diagram 16-3 } 4... gxh3
{ 4...hxg3+ ?  loses to  5.Kxg3  gxh3  6.Kxh3  Ke6  7.Kh4  Kd5  the pair of mined squares are g5-e4  8.Kh5 !  Kd4  9.Kg6 !  Ke4  10.Kg5  +- }
5. gxh4 Ke6 6. Kg3 Kf6 7. h5 { 7.Kxh3  Kg6= } 7... Kg7 8. Kxh3 Kh7 9. Kg3 Kg7
{ The h4 and h6 squares are mined. White cannot win because } 10. Kf3 Kh6 11.
Ke3 Kxh5 12. Kd4 Kh4 13. Kd5 Kg3 14. Ke5 Kg4 { is bad. } *

