{ Triangulation refers to a king maneuver which aims to lose a tempo, and leave the opponent with the move.  The d5- and d7-squares are in correspondence. The mobility of Black's king is restricted: he must watch for the c5-c6 break, and also avoid being pressed to the edge of the board. It is not surprising, therefore, that White can easily 'lose' a tempo and place his opponent in zugzwang. }
1. Ke5
{ 1.c6+?  is mistaken here, in view of  1... Kc8$  2.Kd6  Kb8!  3.Kd7  bxc6 =   But not  1.c6+?  bxc6+?  2.Kc5  Kd8  3.Kd6!  Kc8  4.Kxc6  Kb8  5.b7  +- }
1... Kc6 { 1...Ke7  2.c6  +- } 2. Kd4 Kd7 3. Kd5
{ White has achieved his aim, by describing a triangle with his king. The rest is simple. }
3... Kc8 4. Ke6 { Diagonal opposition. } 4... Kd8 5. Kd6 { And now, vertical. }
5... Kc8 6. Ke7 Kb8 7. Kd7 Ka8 8. c6 { White wins. } *

