{ H. Neustadtl, 1898  Find two winning plans.   The author's solution to this study involves the opposition, which White seizes with his very first move. }
1. Kd4 Kc6 2. Kc4 { 2.g5 ?  fxg5 ! =  doesn't work. } 2... Kd6 3. Kb5
{ The opposition can only win if it leads to an outflanking. } 3... Kd5
{ Here the outflanking looks risky, but it turns out to be playable, because of the line  3...Ke5  4.Kc6  Kf4  5.Kd6  Kxg4  6.Ke6  +- Or @@StartFEN@@8/8/2K2p1p/4kP2/6PP/8/8/8 b - - 7 4@@EndFEN@@  4...h5  5.gxh5  Kxf5  6.Kd5  ⨀ }
4. Kb6
{ White will get the opposition again, thanks to his reserve tempo, h4-h5. But first, the enemy king must be decoyed to a bad position - as far as possible from the g4-pawn. }
4... Kd6 5. Kb7 Kd7 6. h5 Kd6 7. Kc8 { Another outflanking. } 7... Ke5 8. Kd7
Kf4 9. Ke6 { White wins. } *

