{ 1/8. N. Grigoriev, 1920 } 1. Kc2
{ Rather than  1.d4?  Ke4  2.Kc3  Kf5!  3.Kd3  Kf4=   The c3- and e3-squares are obviously corresponding.   The white king will break through to e3 in order to set the d-pawn in motion; the black king will confront it from the f3-square. The reciprocal zugzwang arises when the kings are on d2 and f3, so another pair of corresponding squares is defined. The third pair − c2 and f4 − is adjacent to those already known. Finally, we come to the squares b3 and b2, which can be used for ceding the move because the single square, f3, corresponds to them. }
1... Kf4 2. Kb3 { 2.Kb2  Kf3  3.Kb3  works equally well. } 2... Kf3 3. Kb2
{ Black is in zugzwang. } 3... Kf4 4. Kc2 Ke5
{ Diagram 16-5  Now we must discover a new subtlety: there is a reciprocal zugzwang when the kings are on d2 and d4, so the mined square d2 should be avoided.   4...Ke3?  is quite bad in view of  5.Kc3⨀  , while @@StartFEN@@8/8/8/1p6/1P3k2/3P4/2K5/8 b - - 7 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Kf3  5.Kd2⨀  is also inferior. }
5. Kd1 { 5.Kd2?!  Kd4  6.Ke2?  Kc3 = } 5... Kd5 6. Ke2 Kd4 7. Kd2 Ke5 8. Ke3
Kd5 9. d4 Kc4
{ Black's only hope is to attack the b4-pawn. His pawn would promote simultaneously, but unfortunately the new queen is immediately lost. }
10. Ke4 Kxb4 11. d5 Kc5
{ It is worth mentioning that  11...Ka3  12.d6  b4  does not save Black − a queen versus a knight pawn endgame is winning. But if we shift the initial position one file to the right, then Black; with the bishop pawn against the queen, holds: we shall discuss this sort of position later. }
12. Ke5 b4 13. d6 b3 { 13...Kc6  14.Ke6  makes no difference. } 14. d7 b2 15.
d8=Q b1=Q 16. Qc7+ Kb4 17. Qb7+ { White wins. } *

