{ 1/9. B. Neuenschwander, 1985 } 1. Kf4
{ The natural plan is an attack against the d5-pawn, but it should be conducted very carefully. White must take Black's counterplay  (g7-g6)  into account.   However, Black could have had serious difficulties if he was on move when the kings were on f5 and h6. We come to the conclusion that these squares are mined.   1.Kf5?  is wrong in view of  1...Kh6  and White is in zugzwang.  2.Ke5  is met with  2...Kg5  3.Kxd5  Kxg4=  and  2.Kf4  − with  2...g6!  3.hxg6   3.Ke5  gxh5  4.gxh5  Kxh5  5.Kxd5  f5=  3...Kxg6  4.Ke5  Kg5  5.Kxd5  Kxg4=   1.Kh4?  , with the idea of 2.g5, for example  1...Kh6?  2.g5+  Kh7  3.Kg4  +- or @@StartFEN@@8/5ppk/8/3p3P/3P2PK/8/8/8 b - - 1@@EndFEN@@  1...f6?  2.g5!  +-, does not work in view of:   1.Kh4?  g6!  2.Kg5  Kg7!  3.Kf4  f6!=  Rather than  2...gxh5  3.gxh5  and White creates a distant passed pawn. }
1... Kh6 2. Kf5 { Black is in zugzwang. } 2... f6 3. Ke6 Kg5 4. Kf7 Kh6
{ Diagram 16-6   But what should White do now? The answer is rather simple: he uses triangulation in order to pass the move to Black.  4...Kxg4?  5.Kxg7  Kxh5  6.Kxf6  or  5...f5  6.h6  was bad. }
5. Ke7 { Rather than  5.Ke8?  g6= } 5... Kg5 6. Kf8 Kh6 { 6...g6  7.Kg7!  +- }
7. Kf7 Kh7 8. Ke6 Kh6 9. Kxd5 { White wins. } *

