{ 1/10. R. Réti, 1929 } 1. Kd5
{ 1.Ke6?  g5  -+   1.Ke5?  Kf7  ⨀ -+   Let us try  1.Kc6  g5!  and if  2.Kb7  Black wins by means of  2...g4!  because his pawn promotes with check.  Now we notice that if the black king is on f6, White may play Kc6 because he exchanges on g5 with check, avoiding Black's promotion on g1.  And in case of  2.hxg5  h4  -+.   White cannot prevent ...g6-g5, but does this move invariably win? Assume that the black king has just taken the white pawn on g5 and White has replied with Kg3. Now we calculate @@StartFEN@@8/p7/8/1P4kp/8/6K1/8/8 b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Kf5  2.Kh4  Ke5  3.Kxh5  Kd5  4.Kg4  Kc5  5.Kf3  Kxb5  6.Ke2  Kc4  7.Kd2  Kb3  8.Kc1  with a draw. White has made it just in time! This means that he would have lost if his king were slightly further away from the h5-pawn @@StartBracket@@say, on f3@@EndBracket@@.    We know enough to define the corresponding squares. The simplest reciprocal zugzwang is with the kings on f4 and f6: Black, if on move, cannot achieve anything, while otherwise White is lost: 1.Ke4 g5-+ or 1.Kg3 Ke5-+  The correspondence between the e5- and f7-squares is less evident. Actually, if Black is on move, 1...Ke7 is met with 2.Kd5 Kf6, and now 3.Kc6!=, profiting from the fact that the black king is unfortunately placed on f6. But what if White is on move? If 1.Kf4, then 1...Kf6-+ while after 1.Kd5, Black wins by means of 1...g5! 2.hxg5 Kg6 3.Ke4 @@StartBracket@@3.Kc6 h4@@EndBracket@@ 3...Kxg5 4.Kf3 Kf5. @@StartSquare@@Ed. note: for a more in-depth perspective, all the lines above can be trained as well → see the next two exercises.@@EndSquare@@   Using the neighborhood principle, the third pair of corresponding squares is g7-e4. When the black king is on e7, White plays Kd5. }
1... Kf7
{ Or  1...Kg7  2.Ke4!  Kf6  3.Kf4  Ke7!?  4.Ke3!=  rather than  4.Ke5?  Kf7  ⨀ -+ or  4.Kg5?  Kf7  5.Kf4  Kf6  ⨀ -+ }
2. Ke5 Ke7 3. Kd5 Kf6 { 3...Kd7  4.Ke5  Kc7  5.Kd5!= } 4. Kc6 g5 5. hxg5+ Kxg5
6. Kb7
{ Draw.   @@StartSquare@@Ed. After  6...h4  7.Kxa7  h3  8.b6  h2  9.b7  h1=Q  10.b8=Q  both sides have queened and the draw is obvious.@@EndSquare@@ }
