{ The correspondence between the e5- and f7-squares is less evident. Actually, if Black is on move, @@StartFEN@@8/p4k2/6p1/1P2K2p/7P/8/8/8 b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Ke7  is met with  2.Kd5  Kf6  , and now  3.Kc6!=  , profiting from the fact that the black king is unfortunately placed on f6.  But what if White is on move? }
