{ In 1928, Réti offered a different version of this study: move the white king to h5, and instead of the pawn at h5, put three  (!)  black pawns at f6, g7 and h6. The solution is similar. }
1. Kg6 { And after any Black reply } 1... f5 { 1...h5  or  1...Kb6 } 2. Kxg7
{ Followed by the well-known 'chasing two birds at once.'   @@StartSquare@@Ed. note: the line could continue  2...f4  3.Kf6  f3  4.Ke6  Kb6  5.Kd6!  (only move)  f2  6.c7  f1=Q  7.c8=Q  which is a theoretical draw.  Note that @@StartFEN@@8/3K4/1kP4p/8/8/5p2/8/8 w - - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Kd7??  f2  6.c7  f1=Q  7.c8=Q  Qf5+  wins for Black since he will promote after trading queens.   2...Kb6  3.Kf6  f4  4.Ke5  Kxc6  5.Kxf4  is similar to the original study.   2...Kb6  3.Kxh6??  would be a huge mistake in view of  3...f4  4.Kg5  f3  and it's clear Black will promote.@@EndSquare@@ }
