{ A. & K. Sarychev, 1928  The study we shall now examine shows us that Réti's idea can be useful in more than just pawn endings.   1.c8=Q?  Bf5+  2.Kc7  Bxc8  -+  is hopeless.  And @@StartFEN@@8/1pPK3b/8/8/8/5k2/8/8 w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Kd6?  doesn't work either due to  1...Bf5  2.Kc5  Ke4  3.Kb6  Bc8  4.Ka7  b5  -+  The only saving line starts with a paradoxical move that forces the Black pawn to advance. }
1. Kc8 b5 { As in Réti's study, White is short two tempi. } 2. Kd7 b4 3. Kd6
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed.  3.Ke6  Ke4!  loses. The bishop will move decisively to f5.@@EndSquare@@ }
3... Bf5
{ Thanks to the threat of 4.c8=Q, White wins one tempo; now he wins the other tempo by attacking the black bishop. }
4. Ke5 Bc8 5. Kd4 { Draw. } *

