{ 1/18. M. Rauch } 1. Kf1
{ The winning method is not complicated: White should pass the move to his opponent by means of triangulation. Then he will be able to advance his pawns so that they can decide the fight without the king's help.   @@StartSquare@@Ed. Not  1.Ke1?  Ke3!  which  threatens g3-g2 and wins both the b- and the f-pawn.  @@EndSquare@@ }
1... Kd3 2. Kg2 Kd4 3. Kg1 Kd3 4. Kf1 Kd4 5. Ke2 Kd5 6. Ke3 Kd6 7. f4 Kd5 8. b4
{ The pawn square has reached the edge of the board. } *

