{ Three Connected Pawns   It is difficult for the king to fight three connected passed pawns. It has no chance at all if the enemy has any moves in reserve. If not, then a situation of reciprocal zugzwang could arise.  White to move wins. }
1. Kb1 b3
{ 1...a3  2.Ka2  c3  3.Kb3  ⨀ And in case of @@StartFEN@@6k1/8/5P1P/8/ppp5/8/8/1K6 b - - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...c3  2.Kc2  a3  3.Kb3  ⨀. }
2. Kb2 { Any other first move by White leads to the opposite result. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 1 – Pawn Endgames II"]
[Black "Three Connected Pawns 1-58"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/5p2/N1k5/2Pp2pp/P7/2P5/8/6K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Nunn – Friedlander, Islington 1968  On the queenside, we have equality: it would be bad for either side to make the first move there. The question is, who will fall into zugzwang when the kingside pawn moves run out?   White would win by playing  1.Kg2!?  or  1.Kh2!  − the important point is to be able to meet  1...h4  with  2.Kh3!  , for instance:  2...f6  3.Kg4  f5+  4.Kh3  f4  5.Kg4  ⨀ +-   1.Kh2!  h4  2.Kh3!  f5  3.Kh2!  g4   If  3...f4  4.Kg2  +-  4.Kg2  f4  5.Kg1!  ⨀  Kb7  6.Nb4  . @@StartFEN@@8/8/N1k5/2Pp1p2/P5pp/2P5/6K1/8 b - - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...h3+  5.Kg3  f4+  6.Kh2  f3  7.Kg3  ⨀ or  4...g3  5.Kf3  f4  6.Kg2  ⨀   Nothing would be changed by  1.Kh2!  g4  2.Kg3  f6  3.Kf4  f5  4.Kg3  .   1.Kh2!  g4  2.Kg3  and in case of  2...f5  3.Kg2  f4  4.Kf2  or  4.Kh2  .   Or  1.Kh2!  f5  2.Kg2!  − or, with the king at g2 −  2.Kg3  g4  3.Kg2  , etc. The actual game took an immediate wrong turn. }
1. Kf2 h4 2. Kf3 { 2.Kg2  g4  @@StartSquare@@Ed. holds as well.@@EndSquare@@ }
2... h3 3. Kg3 g4 4. a5
{ White has to be the first to upset the queenside equilibrium. He can no longer place his opponent in zugzwang, because the f-pawn retains the right of moving either one or two squares, according to circumstances  (an important technique, to which we shall be returning)  .   4.Kh2  f6!  5.Kg3  f5  ⨀  6.Kh2  f4  ⨀ }
4... f5 5. Nb4+ Kxc5 6. a6 Kb6 7. Nxd5+ Kxa6 8. c4 Kb7
{ The section which follows is devoted to those cases in which both sides queen simultaneously. In such situations, the game sometimes turns into a 'queen versus pawns' endgame − so it makes sense to get to know its theory first. }
*

