{ J. Timman, 1980  Of course, there are exceptions, in which the standard evaluations and techniques are no longer sufficient. }
1. c5
{ In the final position, it's very important that White's king is on  d7  . This is why  1.Bd1?  c5!  would have been a mistake, since the king can't get to d7. @@StartSquare@@Ed. note: White's king will not reach the d7-square in time, after capturing the pawn on c5 - the text moves will bring more clarity.@@EndSquare@@   And  1.Bc2?  f2  2.Bd3  Kf3!  3.Kxc6  e4  4.Bf1  e3  5.c5  e2  -+ is also hopeless. But not @@StartFEN@@8/3K4/2p5/4p3/2P5/3B2k1/5p2/8 b - - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e4?  3.Be2= }
1... e4 { 1...f2  2.Bc4= } 2. Bd1
{ 2.Kxc6?  e3  3.Bc4  e2  4.Bxe2  fxe2  5.Kd7  e1=Q  leaves the black king on g3.   White does no better with  2.Kxc6?  e3  3.Bd5  e2  4.Bxf3  e1=Q  5.Kd7  Black manages to bring up his king by:  5...Qd2+  6.Kc8  Kf4!  7.c6  Ke5  8.c7  Qb4!  9.Bb7  Qf8+  10.Kd7  Qd6+  11.Kc8  Ke6  12.Kb8  Kd7  13.Bc8+  Kc6  14.Bb7+  Kb6  -+   And in case of @@StartFEN@@2K5/2P5/8/4k3/1q6/5B2/8/8 w - - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Kd7  Qd6+  10.Kc8  Qb6!  11.Kd7  Qe6+  12.Kd8  Kd6  -+ }
2... e3 { 2...f2  3.Be2= } 3. Bxf3 Kxf3 4. Kxc6 e2 5. Kd7 e1=Q 6. c6
{ ∆ 7.c7    With the king still on  g3  , Black wins by @@StartFEN@@8/3K4/2P5/8/8/6k1/8/4q3 b KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  6...Qd1+!  7.Kc8  Qg4+  .  In the initial position, after 1.c5! e4, the move 2.Bd1!! solves this problem, since the black king must be drawn to f3. @@StartSquare@@Ed. the author refers to the main line of the study.@@EndSquare@@ }
6... Qd1+ { Or  6...Qd2+ } 7. Kc8 { Black can't prevent 8.c7. } *

