[SetUp "1"]

{ N. Elkies, 1986    When is the right time to break with c4-c5? Right now it would obviously be premature:  1.c5?  Nxh6+  2.Kf8  bxc5  , or  2...Nf5  3.cxb6  Nd6  , and draws.   And on  1.Kg7 ?  Nxh6  2.Kxh6  Ke3!  3.c5  bxc5  4.b6  c4  5.b7  c3  6.b8=Q  c2  7.Kg5!  (threatening the check at f4)  7...Kd2!  the white king is too far from the pawn. The single tempo that White gets when Black's king occupies the c1-square is insufficient to win. }
1. h7 Nf6+ 2. Kg7 Nxh7 3. Kxh7
{ Now we have virtually the same position as in the preceding variation, with the king standing even farther from the queenside. But here, the h6-square is open! }
3... Ke3 4. c5 bxc5 5. b6 c4 6. b7 c3 7. b8=Q c2 8. Qh2 c1=Q
{ 8...Kd3  9.Qf4  +- } 9. Qh6+ { White wins. } *

