{ 1/22. J. Timman, 1988 } 1. a4
{ After  1.Kb3?  Kd5  2.Kb4  Ke5  3.Kb5  Kxf5  4.Ka6  Ke6  5.Kxa7  f5  an endgame of 'queen versus rook pawn' arises. The black king is close enough to the queenside to set up mate:  6.a4  f4  7.a5  f3  8.a6  f2  9.Kb8  f1=Q  10.a7  Qb5+  11.Kc7  Qd7+  12.Kb8  Kd6  13.a8=Q  Qc7# }
1... a5
{ After  1...Kd5  2.Kb4  White has an extra tempo in comparison with the previous annotation. }
2. Kd3 { Black is at the crossroads now.   2.Kb3?  Kd4  is quite bad. } 2...
Kb4
{ The line  2...Kd5  3.Kc3  Ke5  4.Kc4  Kxf5  5.Kb5  leads to a mutual promotion, while after 2...Kb4 the white king will be able to attack the f6-pawn. }
3. Kd4 Kxa4 { Diagram 16-12 } 4. Kc4
{ A necessary subtlety! It is important to push the black king as far away as possible from the f-pawn.   The straightforward continuation  4.Kd5?  loses to  4...Kb5!  5.Ke6  a4  6.Kxf6  a3  7.Ke7  (unfortunately he cannot go to g7 because Black promotes and pins the pawn at f6 and wins.)  7...a2  8.f6  a1=Q  9.f7  Qg7  10.Ke8  Kc6  11.f8=Q  Qd7# }
4... Ka3 5. Kd5 a4 6. Ke6 Kb4 7. Kxf6 a3 8. Ke7 a2 9. f6 a1=Q 10. f7
{ When on b4, the black king is no longer dangerous! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 1 – Pawn Endgames II"]
[Black "Pawn Races"]
[Result "*"]

{ Pawn Races   Let's examine the sort of situation where both players advance simultaneously and queen at the same time, or almost at the same time. Here, the following outcomes are possible:     1. One rook pawn promotes, preventing the other rook pawn from queening;  2. The pawn queens with check, and thereby prevents the enemy pawn from queening; or  3. We get a 'queen vs. pawn @@StartBracket@@or pawns@@EndBracket@@' endgame. 
  Or, if both pawns queen, then:     4. One queen is lost to a 'skewer' check along the file or diagonal;  5. Mate follows;  6. The queens are exchanged, after which we once again have a pawn ending; or  7. We get a queen ending @@StartBracket@@either an elementary one, or one with some play to it@@EndBracket@@. 
  In order to get an idea of all these possibilities  (except perhaps the last one)  , we shall present a fair number of examples. In the previous chapter we have already seen an ending which transposed into a 'queen vs. pawns' endgame; and earlier, we also saw cases where the king fell into check, or the queen was lost to a skewer check @@StartBracket@@see exercises1/4,1/7,1/8,1/10@@EndBracket@@.  Quite often, the chief problem of a position is either to draw the enemy king onto a bad square, or to avoid such a square with one's own king. }
1. -- *

