{ 1/23. Salwe-Flamberg, Petersburg 1914 } 1... Nh4
{ One's first impression might be that Black wins in all lines, but this is far from so. Only the pretty move 1.Nh4!! as was actually played, decides.   Black cannot create a similar situation by means of  1...Kb4?  2.Kxf3  a5  . White plays  3.Ke3  Kb3  4.Kd2  either coming with his king to c1 or forcing the black king to occupy the b2-square and interfering with the a1-h8 diagonal.   1...Ne5+  2.Kf5  Nf3!  3.Kg4  Nh4!  is necessary.   1...Ne5+  2.Kf5  Kb4?  does not win.  3.h4  a5  4.h5  . All lines lead to a drawn endgame of 'queen versus rook pawn'. For example,  4...Nf7  5.Kg6  Nh6  6.Kxh6  a4  7.Kg7!  a3  8.h6  a2  9.h7  a1=Q+  10.Kg8=   1...Ne5+  2.Kf5  Kb4?  3.h4  a5  4.h5  and if now  4...Nd7  5.h6  Nf8  6.Kf6  a4  7.Kf7!  Nh7  8.Kg6!   8.Kg7?  Ng5  -+  8...Nf8+  9.Kf7!=   @@StartFEN@@5n2/8/5K1P/8/pk6/8/8/8 w - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  7.Kg7?  Ne6+  8.Kf6  a3  -+ }
2. Kxh4 Kb4 { Black promotes first and prevents White from promoting. } *

