[SetUp "1"]

{ 1/27. N. Grigoriev, 1931 } 1. h4
{ White should keep the black pawn structure in a compact mass which can be comfortably attacked by the king.   The premature  1.Kf7?  misses the win:  1...g5!  2.Kg7  Kb3  3.Kxh7  Kc4  4.Kg6  g4!  5.Kg5  Kd5  6.Kxg4  Ke6  7.Kg5  Kf7=   Now, however, White arrives in time:  1...Kb3  2.Kf7  Kc4  3.Kxg7  h5  4.Kg6  Kd5  5.Kxh5  Ke6  6.Kg6  with a winning position.   1...h6  2.h5  is also hopeless for Black. But the fight is still not over. }
1... h5
{ With the idea  2.Kf7?  g5  3.hxg5  h4=  However, if the a2-g8 diagonal remains open, the white pawn promotes with check. }
2. Kf8 g6 3. Ke7
{ The only way to attack the g-pawn without fearing 3...g5.   @@StartSquare@@Ed. note: from  f7  , the king interferes with the diagonal, for example:  3.Kf7?  g5  4.hxg5  h4  5.g6  h3  6.g7  h2  7.g8=Q  doesn't come with check, allowing Black to promote as well with  7...h1=Q  .   From  g7  , the king interferes with its own pawn:  3.Kg7?  g5  4.hxg5  h4  5.g6  h3  and White is forced to move the king.@@EndSquare@@ }
*

