[FEN "8/8/2pk4/3p2p1/1p1P2P1/3K4/P1P5/8 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Widening the Beachhead   Hansen − Nimzovitch, Randers simul 1925    Who stands better? White intends to play c2-c3, obtaining an outside passed pawn, which will secure him a decisive advantage. For example:  1...c5?  2.dxc5+  Kxc5  3.c3  .  Nimzovitch hits upon the correct plan − he activates his king, even if it means sacrificing a pawn. }
1... Kc7 2. c3 Kb6 3. cxb4
{ Instead of  3.cxb4  , let's look at  3.c4  .  White will continue by exchanging pawns at d5. It is not hard to see that b5-b3 and a4-b2 are corresponding squares; after that, we can establish a third pair of corresponding squares: a5-c2. Now we understand that Black must inevitably take advantage of this correspondence @@StartBracket@@since he can wait on either of the equivalent squares b6 and a6, while White cannot@@EndBracket@@.    3...Ka6!  4.cxd5  cxd5  5.Kc2  Ka5  ⨀  6.Kb2  Ka4  ⨀  7.Kc2  Ka3  8.Kb1  b3  9.Ka1  Kb4  10.Kb2  bxa2  In order to win, Black cleared a path for his king towards the center. This is, in fact, what 'widening the beachhead' means − trading off pawns, with the idea of clearing a path for the king. }
3... Kb5 4. Kc3 Ka4
{ As Black had foreseen, it's zugzwang. White resigned, since he has to lose all his queenside pawns. }
5. Kc2 Kxb4
{ White still has the outside passed pawn, but the activity of Black's king means far more here. }
6. Kd3 Ka3 7. Kc3 Kxa2 8. Kb4 Kb2 9. Kc5 Kc3 { Black wins. } *

