{ Cohn – Rubinstein, St. Petersburg 1909    Let's examine another classic endgame. With  1.f4!  White would have had an inferior but defensible position. Instead, he decided to exchange rooks, because he had misjudged the pawn endgame. }
1. Rc1 Rxc1 2. Kxc1 Kf6 3. Kd2 Kg5
{ It's not difficult to calculate that White's counterattack with  4.Kd3  Kh4  5.Kc4  comes too late. }
4. Ke2 Kh4 5. Kf1 Kh3 6. Kg1 e5 7. Kh1 b5
{ It is useful to fix the queenside pawns, while Black also leaves himself the reserve tempo a7-a6. White could have prevented this by playing @@StartFEN@@8/pp3ppp/8/4p3/1P6/P3PP1k/5P1P/6K1 w - - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.a4!?  , but it would not have altered the assessment of the position. }
8. Kg1 f5
{ Black's further plan is to 'widen the beachhead' − clear a path for his king to the queenside via pawn exchanges. }
9. Kh1 g5 10. Kg1 h5 11. Kh1 g4
{ 11...h4  12.Kg1  g4  13.fxg4  Kxg4  14.Kg2  h3+  is also strong. } 12. e4
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed. note: for  12.fxg4  → see the nextvariation.@@EndSquare@@ }
12... fxe4 13. fxe4
{ 13.fxg4  hxg4  14.Kg1  e3  15.fxe3  e4  16.Kh1  g3  is no better. } 13... h4
14. Kg1 g3 15. hxg3 hxg3 { White resigned. } *

