{ Cohn − Rubinstein, St. Petersburg 1909  (analysis) } 12. fxg4
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed. Instead of the previously seen,  12.e4  . @@EndSquare@@   @@StartFEN@@8/p7/8/1p2pp1p/1P4P1/P3P2k/5P1P/7K b - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...fxg4!  13.Kg1  e4  14.Kh1  h4  15.Kg1  g3  changes nothing − Black still wins. }
12... hxg4
{ However, taking with the other pawn would have been inaccurate, resulting in a longer win. }
13. Kg1 f4 14. exf4 exf4 15. Kh1
{ Diagram 1-85   Here, widening the beachhead no longer wins:  15...g3?  16.hxg3  fxg3  17.Kg1=  and  17.fxg3  17...Kxg3  18.Kg1  Kf3  19.Kf1  Ke3  20.Ke1  Kd3  21.Kd1  Kc3  22.a4!= }
15... f3 { The right plan was pointed out by Jonathan Mestel. } 16. Kg1 Kh4 17.
Kh1
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed  17.Kf1  can be trained in the next variation → Diagram 1-85 EXTRA.@@EndSquare@@ }
17... Kg5 18. h3 gxh3 19. Kh2 Kg4 20. Kg1 Kf4 21. Kh2 Ke4 22. Kxh3
{ 22.Kg3  h2!  -+ } 22... Kd3 23. Kg4 Ke2 24. Kg3 a6
{ Here is where the reserve tempo comes in handy! } *

