{ 1/29. J. Speelman, 1979 } 1. Kg5
{ With  1.Ke5?  White forces his opponent to open the way to one of the pawns for the king. However, the line  1...Kd7!  2.Kf6  Kc6  3.h4  Kb5  4.h5  Kxa5  5.Kg7  b5  leads only to a draw. @@StartFEN@@8/1p1k3p/8/P3K3/8/7P/8/8 w - - 2 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Kd5  is useless in view of  2...h5=  or  2...Kc7=  Notice that White has missed, by a single tempo, promoting first and then winning the hostile queen. Thus, the same zugzwang position, but with the pawn on h4  (rather than h3)  , would have been winning.   After  1.h4?  Kf7  2.h5  h6  this goal cannot be reached because it is Black who seizes the opposition. White must act more subtly. }
1... Kf7 2. Kh6 Kg8 3. h4 Kh8 4. Kh5
{ After  4.Kg5?  Kg7=  it is Black again who holds the opposition.   Another line that does not work is  4.h5?  Kg8  5.Kg5  Kf7  6.Kf4  Ke6  . Or  6.Kf5  h6=  In case of @@StartFEN@@6k1/1p5p/8/P5KP/8/8/8/8 b - - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Kg7  6.h6+  Kf7  7.Kf5  Ke7  8.Ke5  Kd7  9.Kf6  Kd6!  10.Kg7  Ke7  11.Kxh7  Kf7= }
4... Kg8 { 4...Kg7  5.Kg5  +- } 5. Kg4
{ White seizes the distant opposition and, by means of the usual outflanking procedure, transforms it into the close opposition. }
5... Kf8 6. Kf4 Ke8 7. Kg5
{ Rather than  7.Ke4?  Kd7!  and Black holds:  8.Kf5  8...Kc6=  or  8.Kd5  h5= }
7... Kf7 8. Kf5 Ke7 9. Ke5
{ White has successfully achieved his goal and, as a result of zugzwang, breaks through to one of Black's pawns. }
9... Kd7 10. Kf6 Kc6 11. h5 Kb5 12. Kg7 Kxa5 13. Kxh7 b5 14. h6 b4 15. Kg7
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed.  15.Kg8?  draws as after  15...b3  16.h7  b2  17.h8=Q  b1=Q  there is no 18.Qa8+ − the white king interferes it.@@EndSquare@@ }
15... b3 16. h7 b2 17. h8=Q b1=Q 18. Qa8+ Kb4 19. Qb8+ { White wins. } *

