{ 1/30. Yermolinsky-Komarov, USSR 1986 } 1. f4+
{ It is no easy matter to utilize the extra pawn to win. White found a superb solution: he opened the way for his king to the queenside.   Let us consider another attempt to make progress: triangulation.  1.Kg2  if  1...Ke6?  2.e4  +-, so Black goes instead  1...Kd5  2.Kh3  Ke6!   After  2...Ke5?  3.Kg3  ⨀ White's idea turns out to be successful:  3...Ke6  4.f4  g4  5.f3  gxf3  6.Kxf3  Kd5  7.e4+  fxe4+  8.Ke3  +-  Diagram 16-15   a. 3.f4?! still wins, but takes a long time.   @@StartFEN@@8/8/p3k3/P4pp1/2p5/2P1PP1K/5P2/8 w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.f4?!  gxf4  4.exf4  Kd5!   4...Kf6?  is weaker in view of  5.Kh4!   5.Kg3?  is less accurate. White can achieve only the same queen-and-pawn endgame as above:  5...Kg6!  6.Kh4   6.Kf3  Kh5  7.Ke3?  Kg4  8.Kd4  Kxf4  9.Kxc4  Kf3  10.Kd5  Kxf2  11.Ke5  Ke3=  6...Kh6  7.Kh3  Kg7!  8.Kg2  Kf7  or  8...Kf6!  9.Kf3  Ke6  10.Kg3  Kd5  11.f3  Kc5  12.Kh4  Kb5  13.Kg5  Ka4!?  etc.  5...Kg6  6.f3  ⨀  Kh6  7.Kg3  Kh5  8.Kf2  Kh4  9.Kg2  Kh5  10.Kg3  ⨀  Kg6  11.Kf2  Kh5  12.Ke3  Kh4  13.Kd4  Kg3  14.Ke5  Kxf3  15.Kxf5  Ke3  16.Ke5  +-  5.f3  Kc5  6.Kh4  Kb5  7.Kg5  Ka4!  8.Kxf5  Kb3  9.Kg6  Kxc3  leads to a queen-and-pawn endgame with an extra pawn for White, which is winning.   b. 3.e4? would be a mistake.   3.e4?!  fxe4  4.fxe4  Ke5  5.f3  Kf4  6.e5!   6.Kg2  g4  7.fxg4  Kxg4=  6...Kxf3   6...Kxe5?  7.Kg4  Kf6  8.f4  +-  7.e6  g4+  8.Kh4  or  8.Kh2  Kf2  9.e7  g3+  10.Kh3  g2  11.e8=Q  g1=Q  12.Qf7+  and 13.Qxc4, again with a queen ending a pawn up, but this time it is only drawn.    c. The best option is a return to Yermolinsky's plan.   3.Kg3!  Ke5  4.f4+!!  gxf4+  5.Kf3!  +- }
1... gxf4+ 2. Kf3 fxe3 3. fxe3 Kd5 4. Kf4 Ke6 5. e4 fxe4 6. Kxe4
{ Black resigned. White captures the c4-pawn unimpeded and advances his pawn to c6, achieving the position fromFahrni-Alapin @@StartBracket@@Diagram 1-27@@EndBracket@@. }
*

