{ J. Moravec, 1952  The other form of zigzag occurs when the king has to avoid a check from a newly-promoted queen.   White is outside the square of the a-pawn. His only hope is Réti’s idea. }
1. Kg4 a5 2. Kf5 a4
{ Otherwise, the king gets into the square.   Now White would lose by  3.e6?  Kd8  4.Kf6  Ke8  . And @@StartFEN@@2k5/8/8/4PK2/p7/8/8/8 w - - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Kf6?  a3  4.e6  a2  5.e7  a1=Q+  is also bad. The king must avoid the f6-square. }
3. Kg6 a3 4. e6 a2 5. e7 Kd7 6. Kf7 { Draw. } *

