{ Shouldering   Quite often, one must choose a route for the king that gives a 'shouldering' to the enemy king − that is, it prevents the enemy from arriving in time at an important part of the board. 'Shouldering' is also often called a 'bodycheck'.  Schlage − Ahues, Berlin 1921  White must inevitably win the pawn at a7. Black can save himself only if he can succeed in locking the white king into the corner with ...Kc7.   The game was drawn after  1.Ke6  Kc3  2.Kd6?  Kd4  3.Kc6  Ke5  4.Kb7  Kd6  5.Kxa7  Kc7  . Maizelis demonstrated a win for White by: }
1. Ke6 Kc3 2. Kd5
{ White's king approaches the a7-pawn while simultaneously 'shouldering' the enemy king, keeping it from approaching the c7-square. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 1 – Pawn Endgames II"]
[Black "Shouldering 1-96"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/1p6/8/8/8/8/1P6/K6k w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ J. Moravec, 1940    White only gets a draw out of  1.Ka2?  Kg2  2.Kb3  Kf3  3.Kc4  Ke4  4.b4  Ke5  5.Kc5  (White's king does manage to shoulder the enemy king, but here this is insufficient.)  5...Ke6  6.Kb6  Kd5  7.Kxb7  Kc4=  Or @@StartFEN@@8/1p6/4k3/2K5/1P6/8/8/8 w - - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6.b5  Kd7  7.Kb6  Kc8=  It's important to keep Black's king further away from the pawns; and for this, White needs to meet him halfway. }
1. Kb1 Kg2 2. Kc2 Kf3 3. Kd3 Kf4 4. Kd4 Kf5 5. Kd5 Kf6 6. Kd6 Kf7
{ If  6...Kf5  then  7.b4  Ke4  8.b5  Kd4  9.b6  with the idea of 10.Kc7+-. }
7. b4 Ke8 8. Kc7 b5 9. Kc6 { White wins. } *

