{ 1/35. N. Grigoriev, 1925 } 1. Kf5
{ 1.Kf6?  Kg4  2.Kxf7  Kf5!  is hopeless.  On @@StartFEN@@8/5p2/1p6/1P2K2k/8/8/8/8 w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Kd5?  f5  2.Kc6  f4  we get a lost 'knight pawn vs. queen' endgame. White's only hope is to keep the black king locked on the h-file until Black advances his f-pawn close enough to the white king. }
1... Kh4 2. Kf4 Kh3 3. Kf3 Kh2 4. Kf2 f6 5. Kf3 Kg1 6. Ke4 Kf2
{ The king has blocked the way of his own pawn, so White's attack against the b6-pawn arrives in time.   But  6...Kg2?  would have been even worse: the white king eliminates the f-pawn and has enough time for a return to the queenside:  7.Kf5  Kf3  8.Kxf6  Ke4  9.Ke6  +- }
7. Kd5 { 7.Kf5?  Ke3  -+ } 7... f5 8. Kc6 f4 9. Kxb6 { Draw. } *

