{ 1/37. H. Adamson, 1915 } 1. Kc7
{ The straightforward  1.Kd7?  fails:  1...Kb6  2.Ke6  Kc5  3.Kf5  Kd4  4.Kg6  Ke3  5.Kxh6  Kf4=  White must keep the black king locked on the edge, choose a proper moment for luring the pawns closer, and only then go to the kingside. Very subtle play is required for accomplishing this plan. }
1... Ka6 2. Kc6 Ka5 { 2...Ka7?  3.g4!  Kb8  4.Kd7!  Kb7  5.Ke6  +- } 3. Kc5 Ka4
4. Kc4 Ka3 5. Kc3 Ka2 6. Kc2
{ It is still early for a pawn advance:  6.g4?  Kb1=  Or  6.g3?  Kb1  7.Kd2  Kb2  8.g4  Kb1!  9.Kd3  Kc1!=  , rather than  8...Kb3?  9.Kd3!  +- }
6... Ka3
{ Diagram 16-20   Now, if  6...Ka1  then  7.g4  Ka2  8.Kd3  wins.  And @@StartFEN@@8/8/7p/8/8/8/k1K3P1/8 b - - 11 6@@EndFEN@@  6...h5  is also bad:  7.Kd3  Kb3  8.Ke4  Kc4  9.Kf5  . }
7. g3
{ Rather than a hasty  7.g4?  in view of  7...Kb4  8.Kd3  Kc5  9.Ke4  Kd6  10.Kf5  h5!  11.gxh5  Ke7= }
7... Ka4
{ This continuation is perhaps more clever than the author's solution:   7...Kb4  8.Kd3  Kc5  9.Ke4  ⨀  Kd6  10.Kf5  Kd5  11.g4  +- and  10...Ke7  11.Kg6  .   7...Ka2  8.g4  +-   7...h5  8.Kd3  Kb4  9.Ke4  Kc5  10.Kf5  +- }
8. Kc3
{ After  8.Kd3?  Kb4  9.Ke4  Kc5  a position from the previous variation arises. However strange it may seem, this is a reciprocal zugzwang and, with White on move, the outcome is only a draw:  10.Kf5  Kd4=  or @@StartFEN@@8/8/7p/2k5/4K3/6P1/8/8 w - - 5 10@@EndFEN@@  10.g4  Kd6  11.Kf5  h5!= }
8... Kb5 9. Kd4 Kc6 10. Ke5 { 10.Ke4?  Kc5  ⨀  = } 10... Kc5
{ 10...Kd7  11.Kf6  +- } 11. g4 { White wins. } *

