{ This is the sort of structure we find in the Ruy Lopez Exchange Variation. White to move can stabilize the situation on the queenside. }
1. c4
{ This guarantees White a decisive advantage, thanks to the outside passed pawn he will create on the opposite side of the board.   @@StartSquare@@Ed. In the initial position, Black to move wins → trainable in Diagram 1-103 EXTRA. After  1.c4  White's play is very straightforward since Black no longer has a breakthrough available.  1...a4  (taking on c4 doesn't change the evaluation nor White's plan)  2.Kg3  b4  3.Kf4  Kf6  4.h4  Ke6  5.g5  hxg5+  6.hxg5  a3  7.Ke4  Kf7  8.Ke5  − Black's king will be distracted by the passed pawn, while the white king will start collecting the pawns on the queenside.@@EndSquare@@ }
