{ Tragicomedies: Averbakh − Bebchuk, Moscow 1964  Black has an inferior, but defensible endgame. Bebchuk, however, misjudged the pawn ending. }
1... b5
{ Black had a better defense in  1...h5!?  when White could have tried  2.Rb5!  Black would have to play  2...Re8!  3.gxh5  Rh8  with good drawing chances. Here, too, the exchange of rooks leads to a loss:  2...Rxb5?  3.axb5+  Kxb5  4.e4!  hxg4  5.e5  or @@StartFEN@@8/1p4p1/1p3p2/1k3P1p/4P1PP/3K4/8/8 b - - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Kc6  5.e5  Kd7□  6.e6+  Kd6  7.gxh5  b5  8.Kc3  b6   8...Kc7  9.Kb4  Kc6  10.Ka5  +-  9.Kb4  Kc6  10.h6!  gxh6  11.h5⨀  Kd6  12.Kxb5  Kc7  13.e7  +-. }
2. Rxb5 Rxb5 3. axb5+ Kxb5 4. e4 Kc6 5. e5 fxe5
{ If  5...Kd5  6.e6  Kd6  White brings his king to b6  (or, if Black plays ...b7-b6, to b5)  , and after Black replies Kc8, uses his reserve tempo h4-h5 to win. }
6. g5 hxg5
{ Black finds no relief in  6...Kd6  7.f6  Ke6  8.fxg7  Kf7  9.gxh6  b5  (the floating square for Black's pawns does not reach the last rank, and the distance between the pawns is the unfavorable two files.)  10.Ke4  b4  11.Kd3  and 12.Kc4+-. }
7. f6 { Not, however,  7.h5?  Kd6  8.f6  Ke6  9.fxg7  Kf7  -+ } 7... gxf6 8. h5
{ Black resigned. } *

