{ Tragicomedies: Wade − Korchnoi, Buenos Aires 1960  Korchnoi ignored the possible pawn breakthrough on the queenside. }
1... Kg5
{ He would also have lost after  1...g5?  2.b5  g4+  3.Ke2  Kg5  4.f3  or  4.h3  . Black's king would be tied to the kingside, while White could break through on the queenside at the right moment. And in case of  3...h3  4.a5!   1...g5?  2.b5  g4+  3.Ke3  Kg5  4.f3  g3  5.hxg3  hxg3  6.Ke2!  is also possible.   The only way to ward off White's threat was by  1...b5!  2.axb5  b6  , and we have a draw:  3.h3  g5  4.Kg2  g4?!  5.f4!  g3!=  . And if  3.Ke3  g5!   Just not  3...Kg5?  4.f4+!  exf4+  5.Kf3  +- or  3...Kg4?  4.f3+  Kh3  5.f4  exf4+  6.Kxf4  Kxh2  7.e5  +-  4.h3  g4  5.f4!  gxh3  6.Kf3  exf4  7.e5  , etc. @@StartFEN@@8/2p5/1p6/1P1Pp1pk/1P2P2p/4K3/5P1P/8 w - - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.f3  is weaker in view of  4...g4  5.f4  h3! }
2. b5 Kh5 3. a5 { Black resigned in view of: } 3... bxa5 4. b6 cxb6 5. d6
{ White wins. } *

