{ Martynov − Ulybin, Daugavpils 1986    White had to play  1.Rh1!  intending 2.Rh5. After  1...Kc6!   Neither  1...Re7  2.Rh5  Re2  3.Rxd5+  Kc6  4.Ra5=  nor  1...Rc7  2.b3  is dangerous.  2.Rh5  Rd6  3.f4!?  =+  White's more active king and  (even more important)  rook positions assure him good compensation for the pawn minus. }
1. Re1 Re7
{ In the game, Martynov misjudged the force of Black's reply. Ulybin allowed his opponent to reestablish material equality, because he knew that he would have a decisive positional advantage in the pawn endgame, thanks to his unstoppable threat to create an outside passed pawn. }
2. Rxe7 Kxe7 3. Kxd5 g6 4. c4 h5 5. gxh5 gxh5 6. Ke5 h4 7. Kf4 f5 8. b4 Kd6 9.
Ke3 { Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 1-121 } *

