{ Tragicomedies: Nimzovitch − Tarrasch, San Sebastian 1911 } 1. Kh5
{ The actual move made, 1.Kh5? lost.   White had a draw with  1.Kh7!  Rb5  2.Rxb5!  axb5  3.g4  b4  4.g5=   I suggest the reader establish for himself that White loses after  2.g4?  Rxf5  3.gxf5  a5  4.h5  a4  5.h6  a3  6.Kh8  a2  7.h7  Ke7! }
1... Rb5 2. Kg4 Rxf5 3. Kxf5 a5 4. Ke4
{ The outside passed pawn draws the white king to the queenside − but Nimzovitch probably hoped that his pawns would be able to defend themselves, as in the variation  4...a4?  5.Kd3  f5  6.g3!  However, Tarrasch does not allow his opponent to connect his pawns. }
4... f5+ { White resigned since, after the next moves, his pawns are lost. } 5.
Kd4 { 5.Kxf5  a4 } 5... f4 6. Kc4 Kg6 { Black wins. } *

