[FEN "8/7p/5kp1/p4p2/P2RpP2/3N2PP/6K1/3r4 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Matanovic − Botvinnik, Belgrade 1969    In his notes, Botvinnik analyzed two approaches for White:  1.Rd5  , and  1.Rd6+  Ke7  2.Ra6  . In fact, he had a third try:  1.Kf2!  For example  1...exd3  2.Ke3  Rg1  3.Kf2  and  1...exd3  2.Ke3  Ra1  3.Rxd3  Rxa4  4.Rd6+  followed by 5.Ra6, when White must draw.  But suppose we forget about this possibility, and try to choose the more exact of the two possible rook moves.   First, we must try some short variations, in order to establish the differences between them, to compare their advantages and their shortcomings.   On  1.Rd6+  Ke7  2.Ra6  a clear draw follows  2...Rxd3  3.Rxa5  or @@StartFEN@@8/4k2p/R5p1/p4p2/P3pP2/3N2PP/6K1/3r4 b - - 3 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Rd2+  3.Nf2  e3  4.Kf3!   4.Rxa5  Rxf2+  5.Kg1  is also possible.  4...e2  5.Ra7+  or  4...exf2  5.Kg2  . However, the pawn capture on  d3  is unpleasant:  2...exd3  3.Rxa5  Kd6  .   Now  4.Kf2?  is bad in view of  4...Rg1!  So White must continue with  4.Ra8  , allowing the black king to get closer to his passed d-pawn. Is this rook ending lost or drawn? It is hard to say − which means that it is time to break off the calculation here, and look at the alternative. }
1. Rd5 Rd2+
{ Now this rook endgame, after  1...exd3  2.Rxa5  is harmless for White:  2...d2  3.Rd5  or @@StartFEN@@8/7p/5kp1/R4p2/P4P2/3p2PP/6K1/3r4 b - - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Ke6  3.Re5+  Kd6  4.Kf2  d2   4...Rg1  5.Re3=  5.Ke2  Rg1  6.Kxd2  Rxg3  7.Re3  . But, thanks to the pin of the knight on the d-file, Black has an in-between rook check, securing him a transition into a favorable pawn endgame. }
2. Kf1 Rxd3 3. Rxd3 { A forced exchange − otherwise, the g3-pawn is lost. }
3... exd3 4. Kf2 { Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 1-131 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
