[White "Chapter 1 – Pawn Endgames III"]
[Black "Two Rook Pawns w/an Extra Pawn on the Opposite Wing 1-131"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/7p/5kp1/p4p2/P4P2/3p2PP/5K2/8 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Matanovic − Botvinnik, Belgrade 1969  (continued)   Unfortunately, here too it is not clear whether White can be saved. Nonetheless, pawn endings are generally of a more forcing nature than rook endings are. Here, as a rule, it is possible to obtain an accurate appraisal of the position, if you can take a variation to its conclusion. So it makes sense to concentrate our efforts on the calculation of this pawn endgame.   Black has two plans of action: bringing the king to the center, in the hope of putting his opponent in zugzwang, and the kingside break with g6-g5.    We can easily establish that the first plan is harmless:  4...Ke6  5.Ke3  Kd5  6.Kxd3  h6  7.g4  and if @@StartFEN@@8/7p/4k1p1/p4p2/P4P2/3pK1PP/8/8 b - - 2 2@@EndFEN@@  5...Kd6  6.Kxd3  Kd5  7.g4  h6   on  7...fxg4  8.hxg4  h5  there is  9.f5!  although  9.gxh5  gxh5  10.Ke3  does not lose.  8.g5!  h5  9.h4  and  8...hxg5  9.fxg5  f4  10.h4  Ke5  11.Ke2  with equality. }
1... g5 2. fxg5+
{ 5.Ke3 ?  would be a mistake:  gxf4+  6.gxf4  Ke6  7.h4  Kd5  8.Kxd3  h5  ⨀ }
2... Kxg5 3. Ke3 h5 4. Kxd3 h4
{ We have already seen the situation occurring after  7...f4  8.gxf4+  Kxf4  in the previous example. White's king cannot attack the a-pawn - but this is not necessary: it is enough to squeeze the enemy king onto the h-file. For example:  9.Kd4  or  9.h4  Kg4  10.Ke4  Kxh4  11.Kf4  with a draw. }
5. gxh4+ Kxh4 { Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 1-132 } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 1 – Pawn Endgames III"]
[Black "Two Rook Pawns w/an Extra Pawn on the Opposite Wing 1-132"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/8/8/p4p2/P6k/3K3P/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Matanovic − Botvinnik, Belgrade 1969  (continued)     Which of the two natural moves -  9.Ke3  or  9.Ke2  - should White make? Let's go back to the rule set forth above. After Black wins the h-pawn, our 'arithmetic' shows that he will have one tempo, since the f-pawn is one square above the crucial c1-h6 diagonal. White can only save himself if he can force that pawn forward to f4.   So clearly  9.Ke2?  loses:  9...Kg3  ⨀  10.h4  Kxh4  11.Kf3  Kg5  12.Kg3  Kf6  13.Kf4  Ke6  14.Kf3  Kd5  etc. Or  10.Kf1  Kxh3  11.Kf2  Kg4  and Black now has two tempi. }
1. Ke3 Kg3 2. Ke2
{ Now it is Black who is in zugzwang: he must advance his pawn to f4, since  10...Kg2  11.Ke3  Kg3  12.Ke2  is a useless 'pendulum.' }
2... f4 3. Kf1
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed. White should avoid  11.h4?  with the idea that  11...Kxh4  12.Kf3  is drawn. Instead, Black plays @@StartFEN@@8/8/8/p7/P4p1P/6k1/4K3/8 b - - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  11...Kg2!  and promotes the f-pawn.@@EndSquare@@ }
3... Kxh3 4. Kf2 Kg4 5. Kg2
{ And we have the 'normal' drawn position.   Matanovic was unable to calculate the pawn ending accurately, and so preferred to keep rooks on. Unfortunately for him, the rook ending turned out to be lost.  Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 1-133 }
*

