[SetUp "1"]

{ Matanovic − Botvinnik, Belgrade 1969  (continued)   Let's return to Diagram 1-130. }
1. Rd6+ Ke7 2. Ra6 exd3 3. Rxa5 Kd6 4. Ra8 Kc7
{ Black repeats moves to gain time to think. } 5. Ra5 Kc6 6. Ra8 Kc5 7. Kf2
{ Diagram 1-133 } 7... Ra1
{ 7...Kd4!  8.a5  Ra1  would have won. For example:  9.Rd8+  Kc3  10.Rc8+  Kd2  would lead to approximately the same situation as in the game; or @@StartFEN@@R7/7p/6p1/P4p2/3k1P2/3p2PP/5K2/r7 w - - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.a6  d2  10.a7  d1=N+!  the only way; now wherever the king retreats, it will be checked by the knight, allowing it to get to d5.  11.Kf3  Ra3+  12.Ke2  Nc3+  and  12.Kg2  Ne3+  13.Kf2  Ra2+  14.Kf3  Nd5  15.g4  Nc7  -+   After the text, White manages to save himself by sacrificing several pawns:  8.Ke3!  Rg1  9.g4!  fxg4  10.hxg4  Rg3+  11.Kd2  Rxg4  12.f5!  gxf5  13.Kxd3 =  or  10...Rxg4  11.Rd8!? }
8. Rd8 Kc4 9. Ke3 Re1+ { 9...Rg1?  10.Rd4+= } 10. Kf2 Re2+ 11. Kf3 Re6 12. a5
Kc3 13. Rc8+ Kd2 14. h4
{ According to Botvinnik's analysis,  14.Rc7  would not have saved White either, just not  14...Re1?  15.a6  Ra1  16.a7=  , but @@StartFEN@@8/2R4p/4r1p1/P4p2/5P2/3p1KPP/3k4/8 b - - 4 14@@EndFEN@@  14...h5  15.Kf2  Kd1  16.Kf3  d2  17.Kf2  Re2+!  18.Kf1  Re3  19.a6   19.Kf2  Ra3  followed by ...Ra1-c1.  19...Rxg3  20.a7  Ra3  21.Kf2  h4  22.Kf1  Ra4  23.Kg2  Ke2  24.Re7+  Kd3  25.Rd7+  Ke3  -+ }
14... Re1 15. a6 Ra1
{ Now on  16.Rc6  Ke1  is decisive:  17.Re6+  Kf1  18.Ke3  Re1+  and  18.Rd6  d2  19.Rxd2  Ra3+  White gets mated!   The same thing happens after  16.Ra8  Ke1  17.a7  d2  18.Re8+  Kf1  19.Rd8  Ra3+  . }
16. Rc7 Ke1 17. Kg2 Rxa6 18. Re7+ Kd1 19. Rxh7 Ra2+ 20. Kf1 d2 21. Rc7 Ra1 22.
Kf2 Rc1 { White resigned. } *

