[FEN "8/8/8/8/p1k1P3/P3K3/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ 1/45. M. Zinar, 1982 } 1. Ke2
{ 1.e5?  is wrong; after  1...Kd5  2.Kf4  Ke6  3.Ke4  Ke7=  the count of the reserve tempi is 1:1, therefore the position is drawn. When the pawn is on e4, however, White has two spare tempi instead of one  (his pawn is two squares from e6)  − a favorable situation for him.   1.Kf3?  does not work, either: after  1...Kb3  2.e5  Kxa3  a drawn endgame with queen versus rook pawn arises. However, this endgame is winning when the king is standing on the e-file. From all this, the winning plan can be constructed: White must pass the move to the opponent by means of triangulation. }
1... Kd4 2. Kf3 Kc4 { 2...Ke5  3.Ke3  Ke6  4.Kd4  Kd6  5.Kc4  +- } 3. Ke3 Kb3
4. e5 Kxa3 5. e6 Kb2 6. e7 a3 7. e8=Q a2 8. Kd2 a1=Q 9. Qb5+ Ka3 10. Qa5+ Kb2
11. Qb4+ Ka2 12. Kc2 { White wins. } *

