[FEN "8/8/p1k5/1pPp1pp1/1P6/3K4/P5P1/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Multi-Pawn Endgames   L. Bottlik, 1952  The next example features a typical plan for exploiting the advantage.   Black may have an extra pawn, but his position is difficult. How does he meet the threatened invasion of the white king? }
1. Kd4 f4 2. Ke5 a5 3. a3 a4
{ Black would prefer to exchange a pair of pawns; but after  3...axb4  4.axb4  ,  he is in zugzwang. }
4. Kf5 d4 5. Ke4 d3 6. Kxd3 Kd5 7. g3
{ A necessary undermining of the enemy kingside pawns @@StartBracket@@undermining, by the way, is the theme of our next section@@EndBracket@@.   It is only a draw after  7.Ke2?  g4  8.Kd3  Ke5  9.c6  Kd6  10.Ke4  Kxc6  11.Kxf4  Kd5  12.Kxg4  Kc4  because both pawns will queen. }
7... fxg3
{ No better is  7...Ke5  8.gxf4+  gxf4  9.Ke2  Kd5  10.Kf3  Ke5  11.c6  Kd6  12.Kxf4  Kxc6  13.Ke5  +-  This position would be a draw if Black had exchanged pawns on his 3rd move; but if he had, alas, he would not have gotten this position. }
8. Ke2 { Or  8.Ke3  g4  9.Ke2  . } 8... Ke5 { 8...g4  9.Kf1  changes nothing. }
9. Kf3 Ke6 10. Kxg3 Kf5
{ Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 1-143 } *

