{ 1/46. N. Grigoriev, 1936  Black has the distant opposition and is planning to transform it into the close opposition by means of an outflanking at the appropriate moment. White's only hope is the drawnDedrle position  (Diagram 1-141)  , but how it can be achieved? }
1. Kc2 Kc8 { 1...Kc7?  2.Kc3= } 2. Kd2 { Rather than  2.g5?  hxg5  -+ } 2...
Kd8 3. Ke2
{ It is still too early to push the king ahead:  3.Ke3?  Ke7  4.g5  hxg5  5.Kf3  Ke6  -+ @@StartFEN@@8/4k3/6pp/8/6P1/4K3/8/8 w - - 6 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Kf3  Kd6!  5.g5  h5  -+  as we know, the white king must go to d4 in this position. }
3... Ke8
{ Diagram 16-22   Black is ready to outflank:  4.Kd2?  Kf7!  -+ or  4.Kf2?  Kd7!  , while  5.g5  is still impossible in view of  5...hxg5  . }
4. Kf3 Kd7
{ 4...Kf7  5.Kf4  Kf6  6.g5+!  hxg5+  7.Kg4=  and if @@StartFEN@@4k3/8/6pp/8/6P1/5K2/8/8 b - - 7 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Ke7  5.Ke3!= }
5. g5 h5 6. Ke3 Kc7 { 6...Kd6  7.Kd4=   6...Kc6  7.Ke4  Kc5  8.Ke5= } 7. Kd3
Kb7 8. Ke3 Ka6 9. Ke4 { etc. } *

