{ 1/47. V. Chekhover, 1951 } 1. f5+
{ The king must enter the square of the c-pawn and the d4-pawn must stay protected and passed.  1.fxg5??  c3  -+ and the immediate @@StartFEN@@8/8/4k3/6p1/2pPpP2/4P2P/6K1/8 w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Kf2?  is not correct in view of  1...gxf4  2.exf4  c3  3.Ke3  Kd5  4.f5  Kc4  . The d4-pawn must stay a protected passed pawn. }
1... Kxf5
{ Diagram 16-23   Black's counterplay on the queenside fails now, e.g.,  2.Kf2  Ke6?  3.Ke2  c3  4.Kd1  Kd5  5.Kc1!  (the squares c2/c4 are mined)  5...Kc4  6.Kc2  Kb4  7.d5  Kc5  8.Kxc3  Kxd5  9.Kb4  ,  and the white king controls key squares.  But defensive resources are not exhausted: the black king can enter the fight via the kingside as well after ...g5-g4!   The natural continuation  2.Kf2?  gives only a draw after  2...g4!  3.hxg4+  Kxg4  4.Ke2  c3  ⨀ Notice that Black would have been lost if he had been on move here  5.Kd1  Kf3  6.d5  Kxe3  7.d6  Kf2=  and if  5.d5  Kf5=  In case of @@StartFEN@@8/8/8/8/2pPp1k1/4P3/5K2/8 w - - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Ke1  Kf3  5.Kd2  c3+  or  5.d5  Kxe3  6.d6  c3  7.Kd1  Kf2  8.d7  e3=  As Black would have been lost if he had been on move in the position with the king on e2 and the pawn on c3, we define the corresponding squares and choose the most precise route for the king. }
2. Kf1 c3 { 2...g4  3.hxg4+  Kxg4  4.Kf2!  c3  5.Ke2  ⨀ } 3. Ke1 g4 4. hxg4+
Kxg4 5. Ke2 { Zugzwang. } 5... c2 { 5...Kg3  6.d5  +- and  5...Kf5  6.Kd1  +- }
6. Kd2 Kf3 7. d5 c1=Q+ 8. Kxc1 Kxe3 9. d6 Kf2 10. d7 e3 11. d8=Q
{ White wins. } *

