{ Tragicomedies: Sulipa − Gritsak, Lvov 1995 } 1... g5
{ Far from improving Black's position, this move actually degrades it significantly by giving his opponent the possibility of exchanging a pair of kingside pawns, and creating a passed h-pawn.   White had no answer to the undermining plan with  1...Kd7!  2.Kf3  Kc7  3.h4  and now not  3...Kb7  4.Ke4  a6?  at once, in view of  5.bxa6+  Kxa6  6.c6!  Kb6  7.Kxe5  f3  8.Kd6  f2  9.c7=  , but @@StartFEN@@8/p1k5/6p1/1PP1p3/5p1P/5K2/7P/8 b - - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Kc8  4.Ke4  Kb7  ⨀  5.h3  Kc8  6.Kf3  Kc7  7.Ke4  Kb7  ⨀  8.Kf3  a6!  -+ @@StartSquare@@Ed. Given the instructive value of Black's triangulation, this line can be trained in the next variation → Diagram 1-152 EXTRA.@@EndSquare@@   1...Kd7!  2.Kf3  Ke7  is also good:  3.Ke4  Ke6  ⨀  4.h4   4.Kf3  Kd5  5.c6  Kd6  6.Ke4  a6  -+  4...Kd7!  5.Kf3  Ke7  6.Ke4  Ke6  triangulating again and again with the king, until the opponent runs out of pawn moves. }
2. Kf3
{ The wrong order of moves. After  2.h4!  gxh4  3.Kf3  Kd5  4.c6  Kd6  5.Kg4  a6  6.bxa6  Kxc6  7.Kxh4  Kb6  8.Kg4  Kxa6  9.h4  , it is now White who wins. }
2... Kd5 3. c6 Kd6 { 3...e4+!  was necessary:  4.Kg4  Kd6  -+ } 4. Ke4
{ For the fourth time, the appraisal of the position is reversed. White wins with  4.h4!  gxh4  5.Kg4  . }
4... a6 5. bxa6 Kxc6 6. Kf3 Kb6 7. h4 { Too late! } 7... gxh4 8. Kg4 Kxa6 9.
Kxh4 Kb6 10. Kg4 Kc6 11. h4 Kd6 { White resigned. } *

