{ 1/49. N. Kopaev, 1947 } 1. Kb6
{ Both  1.Rh5?  Kd8  and @@StartFEN@@2k5/3p3r/K3pP1P/4R3/8/8/8/8 w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Rg5?  Kc7!  yield nothing. }
1... Kd8 { 1...Rxh6?  2.Rg5  +- } 2. Rg5 Ke8 3. Rg8+ Kf7 4. Rg7+ Rxg7 5. hxg7
{ We have reached a pawn endgame with White's far-advanced passed pawns by force. }
5... e5 6. Kc5 e4 { Diagram 16-24 } 7. Kc4
{ An important subtlety, the upcoming king assault works only when the black king is standing on g8. At this moment White must plan how to reach the inevitable zugzwang position with Black on move.   7.Kd4?  d5  8.Ke3  Kg8  9.Kf4  Kf7  ⨀  leads only to a draw: we have already seen this position in the previous exercise, in the 1.g7? line. }
7... d6 8. Kc3 { 8.Kd4?  d5= } 8... Kg8 9. Kd4 d5 10. Ke3 Kf7 11. Kf4 Kg8 12.
Kg5 { 12.Kf5?!  Kf7! } 12... Kh7
{ 12...e3  13.Kg6  e2  14.f7#  And if @@StartFEN@@6k1/6P1/5P2/3p2K1/4p3/8/8/8 b - - 5 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Kf7  13.Kh6  e3  14.Kh7  +- }
13. Kf5 e3 14. Ke6 e2 { 14...Kg8  15.f7+  Kxg7  16.Ke7  +- } 15. Kf7 e1=Q 16.
g8=Q+ Kh6 17. Qg6# *

