[White "Chapter 1 – Pawn Endgames III"]
[Black "Diagram 1-159 Exercise 1/50"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/1p4kP/5pP1/3p4/8/4P3/7K/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ 1/50. N. Grigoriev, 1932  White's king is in the square of the b-pawn, but if it approaches the pawn, Black will create another passed pawn on the f-file at cost of his d5-pawn.   For example:  1.Kg3  b5  2.Kf3  b4  3.Ke2  f5  4.Kd3  Diagram 16-25  4...b3!  5.Kc3  d4+!  6.exd4  f4  7.d5  f3  8.d6  f2  9.d7  f1=Q  10.d8=Q  Qc1+  11.Kb4  Qe1+!  12.Ka4  Qa1+!  13.Kxb3  Qb1+  14.Kc3  Qc1+  15.Kb4  Qb1+!  16.Ka5  Qf5+  and  16.Kc5  Qc2+  with a draw.  So the strongest plan is to rush the king over to its own passed pawns. }
1. e4
{ The straightforward  1.Kg3?  b5  , there is already no time for  2.e4  in view of  2...b4  , and @@StartFEN@@8/1p4kP/5pP1/3p4/8/4P1K1/8/8 b - - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  2.Kf4  b4  3.Kf5  leads only to a draw:  3...b3  4.Ke6  b2  5.h8=Q+  Kxh8  6.Kf7  b1=Q  7.g7+  Kh7  8.g8=Q+  Kh6  and the black queen defends the g6-square where White would have liked to give mate. Therefore the b1-h7 diagonal must be closed. }
1... dxe4
{ 1...d4  is even worse in view of  2.Kg3  b5  3.Kf4  d3  4.Ke3  or @@StartFEN@@8/6kP/5pP1/1p6/3pPK2/8/8/8 b - - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...b4  4.Kf5  with mate. }
2. Kg3 b5 3. Kf4 { Diagram 16-26 } 3... e3
{ We already know that Black will be checkmated from  g6  after  3...b4  4.Kf5!  etc. For this reason, he tries to distract the white king from the kingside. }
4. Kxe3 b4
{ After  4...f5  , not  5.Kd4?  f4  , but  5.Kf4!  b4  6.Ke5!  b3  7.Ke6  b2  8.h8=Q+  Kxh8  9.Kf7  the black pawn on f5 is as treacherous as the e4-pawn: it cuts its own queen off from the g6-square. }
5. Kd4 f5
{ Unfortunately, this is forced: after  5...b3  6.Kc3  f5  7.Kxb3  the king remains in the square of the f-pawn. }
6. Ke5 b3 { 6...f4  7.Ke6! } 7. Ke6 b2 8. h8=Q+ Kxh8 9. Kf7 b1=Q 10. g7+ Kh7
11. g8=Q+ Kh6 12. Qg6# *

