[SetUp "1"]

{ The Stalemate Refuge   When there are only a very few pieces left on the board, stalemate becomes one of the most important defensive resources − remember the 'king and pawn vs. king' ending, if nothing else.  Out of the many possible stalemate situations, it is worth noting the diagrammed position. The loss of the c5-pawn appears inevitable; however, Black can still save himself. }
1... Kb6
{ Transposition of moves by  1...a6??  would be a grievous error - White would reply  2.a5!  ,  eliminating the king's stalemate refuge. }
2. Kd5 a6 3. Kd6 Ka5 { And the pawn is untouchable, because of the stalemate. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 1 – Pawn Endgames III"]
[Black "Stalemate 1-161"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/8/p2p3k/2pP3p/1pP1B2n/1P1P4/P7/6K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Nikolaevsky − Taimanov, USSR ch, Tbilisi 1966  In the following endgame, we shall see, besides stalemate, other techniques we saw earlier.  How should this game end? }
1. d4 { Breakthrough. } 1... Ng6
{ Of course not  2...cxd4?  3.c5  ,  and a pawn queens. } 2. dxc5 dxc5 3. Bxg6
{ 3.d6?!  Ne5  and now it is White who must work for the draw. } 3... Kxg6 4.
Kf2
{ Here is a position we know: the protected versus the outside passed pawn. White cannot get a zugzwang position − kings at h4 and g6, with Black to move; therefore, he will have to trade his d-pawn for Black's h-pawn. This exchange would have led to victory, if Black's pawn were at a5  (instead of a6)  , or White's pawn at a4 @@StartBracket@@instead of a2@@EndBracket@@. As it is, the upshot is stalemate. }
4... Kf6 5. Kg3 Kg5 6. Kh3 Kf5 { 6...h4 } 7. Kh4 Kg6 8. d6 Kf6 9. Kxh5 Ke6 10.
Kg5 Kxd6 11. Kf5 Kc6 12. Ke5 Kb6 13. Kd5 Ka5 14. Kxc5 { Stalemate. } *

