{ 1/51. A. Troitsky, 1900 } 1... Kf4
{ ∆ 2...a5.   After  1...Kg4?  the main line of the study arises. White builds a stalemate shelter on the queenside:  2.a5!  Kf4  3.Kf2=  and  2...Kxh5  3.Kd2  Kg4  4.Kc2  h5  5.Kb2  h4  6.Ka3  h3  7.Ka4  h2  8.a3  h1=Q=  and in case of @@StartFEN@@8/6p1/p5Pp/P1p5/2p3k1/2P5/P1K5/8 b - - 3 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Kf3  5.Kb2  Ke3  6.Ka3  Kd3  7.Ka4  Kxc3  8.a3=   But  1...a5??  is even worse because White manages even to win after  2.Ke3  Kg4  3.Ke4  Kxh5  4.Kf5  ⨀  Kh4  5.Ke6  . However, A. Rubenis has refuted the study, Black nevertheless can win. }
2. a5 Ke4 3. Kd2
{ 3.Kf2  Kd3  -+  is hopeless.   After  3.a3  Kf4  Black's king can simply rob the kingside pawns, because the road to the exile does not exist anymore. }
3... Kf3 4. Kc2 Ke3 5. Kb2 Kd3 6. Ka3 Kxc3 7. Ka4 Kd2 8. a3 c3
{ There is no stalemate! } *

