{ Mandler − Prochzka, Czechoslovakia 1976  The next example is considerably more difficult and hence more interesting.   The straightforward  1.b5?  leads to the drawn queen endgame with an extra rook's pawn:  1...Kxg2  2.Kb7  Kxh3  3.Kxa7  Kg4!  4.b6  h3  5.b7  h2  6.b8=Q  h1=Q  .  The other, more promising plan is to squeeze the enemy king into the corner. However, it requires lengthy and accurate calculation. }
1. Kd5 Kxg2 2. Ke4 Kxh3 3. Kf3 Kh2 4. Kf2
{ After  4.b5?  or  4.a4?  , Black's king can use Réti's idea to help him get to the queenside in time:  4...Kg1  5.Kg4  Kg2!  6.Kxh4  Kf3= }
4... h3 { 4...a6  is inferior:  5.a4  h3  6.a5!  Kh1  7.b5  h2  8.Kf1!  ⨀ +- }
5. b5
{ 5.a4?  would be a mistake, in view of  5...a5!  6.bxa5  Kh1  7.a6  h2= } 5...
Kh1 { Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 1-169 } *

