[SetUp "1"]

{ Despotovic − Dvoretsky, Moscow tt 1968 } 1... g4
{ Now Black has the reserve tempo h6-h5. Here, the game was adjourned; White sealed the move  2.Kc3?  but later resigned without continuing, in view of  2...Ke6  3.Kd4  Kd6  4.Kc3  Kd5  5.Kd3  h5  -+  In case of @@StartFEN@@8/8/1p2k2p/1p3p2/1P3Pp1/P1K3P1/7P/8 w - - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Kb3  Kd5  4.a4  bxa4+  5.Kxa4  Kc4  -+ Thanks to his reserve tempo, Black put his opponent into zugzwang, and his king broke through on the wing. }
2. Ke3 { But White could have saved himself by playing 2.Ke3! } 2... Ke6 3. h3
{ Yes!   White loses with either  3.h4?  Kd5  4.Kd3  h5  ⨀ Or  3.Kf2?  Kd5  4.h3  h5!   But now what is Black to do? On @@StartFEN@@8/8/1p2k2p/1p3p2/1P3Pp1/P3K1PP/8/8 b - - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...h5  4.hxg4  or  4.h4  , he loses his reserve tempo, and the position is now drawn:  4...Kd5  5.Kd3  ⨀ }
3... gxh3
{ In this sharp variation, White has time to create kingside counterplay. } 4.
Kf2 { Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 1-172 } *

