{ N. Grigoriev, 1931  White's king has nothing to do on the kingside @@StartBracket@@with the kings on the fourth and sixth ranks, it is easy to establish that the opposition is meaningless, and therefore White cannot create zugzwang@@EndBracket@@. The winning plan will be to feint with the king on the queenside, and then march over to the kingside.  For this plan to succeed, White will need both of his reserve pawn tempi @@StartBracket@@with the pawn at b3, the position would be drawn@@EndBracket@@; so it is important not to lose them on the way. }
1. Ke2 Kd7
{ 1...Kb7  2.Kd3  Ka6  would be senseless, in view of  3.Kc4  +- or  3.b4  Kb5  4.Kc3  Ka6  5.Kc4!  Kb7  6.Kd4  +- }
2. Kd3 Ke7
{ After  2...Ke6  3.Kc4  Black cannot play  2...Ke5  in view of  4.b4  Ke6  5.b5  ; however, if he does not play this, White's king continues on his way to the queenside.   Now on  2...Ke7  3.Kc4?  Ke6  , the line  4.Kb4  or  4.Kb3  4...Kd5=  is bad; and so is −  4.Kd4  Kf6!  5.Kc3  Ke5!  - therefore, White has to play @@StartFEN@@8/8/2p1k3/2P5/2K5/8/1P6/8 w - - 6 4@@EndFEN@@  4.b4  prematurely using up one of his reserve tempi, which renders the win impossible. }
3. Kc3 { Both sides must keep in mind that the e6- and c4-squares are mined. }
3... Ke6 4. Kc4 Kd7 5. Kb4 Kc7 6. Ka5 Kb7 7. b3
{ The first tempo is used up, in order to force the black king away from the kingside. }
7... Ka7 8. Kb4 Kb7 { 8...Ka6  9.Kc3  Ka5  10.Kc4  Ka6  11.b4  ⨀ } 9. Kc4 Kc7
10. Kd4 Kd7 11. Ke5 Ke7 12. b4
{ Zugzwang! That is where we use the second tempo! } *

