{ 1/53. Yermolinsky-I. Ivanov, USA ch, Parsippany 1996 } 1. g5
{ With this move, White not only gets a spare tempo  (h3-h4)  but also deprives the black king of the important f6-square.   The actual game continuation was  1.gxf5?  gxf5  2.Ke2  Ke7  3.Kd3  h5  4.Kxd4  h4  5.Kd3  Draw. }
1... Kf7
{ If Black tries  1...Kg7  (planning 2...h5)  the simplest is  2.e6!  Kf8  3.Ke2  Ke8  4.Kd3  Ke7  5.Kc4!  ⨀  Kxe6  6.Kxd4  ⨀  transposing to the main line. }
2. Ke2 Ke7 { 2...Ke6  3.Kd3  Kd5  4.e6  Kxe6  5.Kxd4  ⨀ } 3. Kd3 Ke6 4. Kxd4
Kd7
{ Diagram 16-29  Now White should sacrifice the e-pawn and occupy the corresponding d4-square when Black captures it; this will put Black in zugzwang. }
5. Kc3 Ke6 6. Kc4 Kd7 7. e6+ Ke7 8. Kd3 Kxe6 9. Kd4 Kf7 10. Ke5 Ke7 11. h4
{ Zugzwang. } *

