[SetUp "1"]

{ 1/54. E. Post, 1941 } 1. Kg5
{ A breakthrough is threatened  1.f4?  b5!  2.cxb5  c4  , therefore the white king must enter the square of the c-pawn.   The move  1.Kg5  seems illogical because it creates no threat @@StartBracket@@2.Kxg6 or 2.f4 will be still met with 2...b5@@EndBracket@@.  1.Kg4  ∆ 2.f4 speaks for itself, the breakthrough fails thereafter and the black king must run to the kingside.   But let us look what can happen:  1.Kg4  Kb8!  2.f4  Kc7  3.f5  gxf5+  4.exf5  Kd7  5.f6!  Ke6  6.Kg5  Kf7  7.Kf5  Black is in zugzwang, but his spare tempo  7...b6!  saves him: the white king must go to an unfavorable square @@StartBracket@@g5@@EndBracket@@.  8.Kg5  d5  9.cxd5  c4  10.d6  c3  11.d7  c2  12.d8=Q  c1=Q+  and the pawn promotes with check.   Looking for an improvement for White, we come back to  1.Kg5  Yes, it creates no threat but still, how should Black react?  1...Kb6  is bad in view of  2.Kxg6!  @@StartBracket@@the black king is an obstacle for ...b7-b5@@EndBracket@@;   The same reply follows after  1.Kg5  Ka6  2.Kxg6!  and if  2...b5  , White takes the pawn with check. What remains is the waiting move @@StartFEN@@8/kp6/3p2p1/p1p3K1/P1P1P3/5P2/8/8 b - - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...b6  , but then Black lacks the highly important spare tempo. If  1...Kb8  then  2.f4!  b5  3.f5  gxf5  4.exf5  and the f-pawn promotes first with check. }
1... b6 2. Kg4 Kb7 3. f4 Kc7 4. f5 gxf5+ 5. exf5
{ White has created a distant passed pawn. } 5... Kd7 { Diagram 16-30 } 6. f6
{ A mistake would be  6.Kg5?  d5  7.cxd5  c4  8.f6=  Not @@StartFEN@@8/3k4/1p6/p2P1PK1/P1p5/8/8/8 w - - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Kf4?  b5!  9.axb5  a4  10.b6  c3!  11.Ke3  a3!  12.b7  Kc7  13.f6  c2!  -+ This technique of decoying the king into a check is already known to us fromKhachaturov's study @@StartBracket@@exercise 1/24@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Ke6 7. Kg5 Kf7 8. Kf5 d5 9. cxd5 c4 10. d6 c3 11. d7 c2 12. d8=Q c1=Q 13.
Qe7+ { with mate. } *

