{ 1/55. Randviir-Keres, Pärnu 1947 } 1... Kb5
{ In case of  1...Kb6?  2.Kc4  a5  3.a4  ⨀  Black is forced to waste his spare tempo before the critical moment arrives:  3...h6  . Thereafter, both  4.d6  Kc6  5.d7  Kxd7  6.Kxc5  and the simpler continuation @@StartFEN@@8/8/1k3p1p/p1pP1Pp1/P1K3P1/8/8/8 w - - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Kd3  Kc7  5.Kc3!  lead to a draw @@StartBracket@@'untouchable pawns'@@EndBracket@@. }
2. a4+ { 2.Kc3  c4  3.Kd4  c3!  4.Kxc3  Kc5  -+ } 2... Kb6 3. Kc4 a5
{ 3...h6?  4.a5+  +- } 4. d6
{ 4.Kd3  loses immediately:  4...Kc7  5.Kc3  Kd6  6.Kc4  h6  ⨀ } 4... Kc6 5. d7
Kxd7 6. Kxc5 Ke7
{ The king goes to the kingside to create the threat ...h7-h5 @@StartBracket@@so that White has no time to attack the a5-pawn@@EndBracket@@   6...Ke8  is also playable; White responds with  7.Kd4!  rather than  7.Kd5?  Ke7!  ⨀ }
7. Kd5 Kf7 { White must avoid  8.Kd6  h5  -+ } 8. Ke4
{ 8...h5?  is premature here:  9.gxh5  Kg7  10.Kf3  Kh7  11.Kg3=  @@StartBracket@@'untouchable pawns'@@EndBracket@@.   But how should White proceed if he is on move? If @@StartFEN@@8/5k1p/5p2/p4Pp1/P3K1P1/8/8/8 w - - 4 8@@EndFEN@@  9.Kf3  or  9.Ke3  then  9...Ke7  10.Ke4  Kd6  11.Kd4  h6  ⨀ @@StartBracket@@this is what the spare tempo is needed for!@@EndBracket@@.   If  9.Kd5  or  9.Kd4  , then  9...h5  10.gxh5  Kg7  -+ or  9...Kg7  ∆ 10...h5 -+. }
8... Kf8
{ Thus, the move is passed to the opponent. The f8-square is equivalent to f7 in all aspects  (two steps to both d6 and h6)  .   8...Kg7  is less precise:  9.Kf3!  Kg8  10.Ke3!  Kf7  11.Ke4! }
9. Ke3 Ke7 10. Ke4 Kd6 11. Kd4 h6 12. Ke4
{ 12.Kc4  Ke5  13.Kb5  h5  14.gxh5  Kxf5  15.Kxa5  g4  -+ } 12... Kc5 13. Ke3
Kd5
{ Almost everything wins now. For example,  13...Kb4  14.Kd4  Kxa4  is good enough. }
14. Kd3 Ke5 15. Ke3 h5 16. gxh5 Kxf5 17. Kf3 Ke6
{ 17...g4+  18.Kg3  Kg5  is also strong:  19.h6  Kxh6  20.Kxg4  Kg6  @@StartBracket@@the f-pawn is standing above the c1-h6 diagonal@@EndBracket@@. }
18. Kg4 Kf7 19. Kf5 Kg7 { White resigned. } *

