[SetUp "1"]

{ Yusupov − Ionov, Podolsk 1977  We can see at once the idea of a pawn breakthrough on the queenside, after a2-a4 and c4-c5. Obviously, it will have no chance of succeeding unless the black king is taken far enough away.   First, it is necessary to put Black on move. It is also important to leave the a-pawn where it is, since from its original square, it has the choice of moving one or two squares forward. }
1. Kf4
{ In playing this, White must be prepared for  1...g6  2.h6  g5+  however, now the pawn breakthrough works:  3.Ke3!  @@StartBracket@@the best square for the king to deal with the black pawns@@EndBracket@@  3...Kg6  4.a4  Kxh6  5.c5!  dxc5  6.a5  bxa5  7.b6  cxb6  8.d6  , and if  5...bxc5  6.a5  c4  7.a6  bxa6  8.bxa6  c3  9.a7  c2  10.Kd2  .   An incautious pawn advance on move one would have let the win slip. Black in response need only be careful which square he picks for his king. For example, after  1.a3?  Kf7?  would be a mistake:  2.Kf5  Ke7  @@StartBracket@@otherwise 3.Ke6@@EndBracket@@  3.Kg6  Kf8  4.a4  ⨀ +-  But Black could play @@StartFEN@@8/1pp3p1/1p1p1k2/1P1P3P/2P3K1/P7/8/8 b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Ke7!  2.Kf5  Kf7!  and if after  1...Ke7!  White goes  2.Kg5  Kf8!  3.Kg6  Kg8  4.a4  Kf8  ⨀, the breakthrough does not work now, and the move-losing maneuver is no longer possible. }
1... Ke7 2. Kg5
{ The king goes inexorably to g6, after which White − thanks to the fact that his pawn is still on a2 − can execute the breakthrough at the ideal moment: when Black's king is on g8. }
2... Kf8 { 2...Kf7  is met by  3.Kf5  Ke7  4.Kg6  Kf8  5.a4!  Kg8  6.c5! } 3.
Kg6 Kg8 { Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 1-179 } *

