{ Tragicomedies: Chiburdanidze − Watson, Brussels 1987  The position is almost the same as theRéti/Mandler study.   White wins with either  1.g4!  Ke6  2.Ke2!  Kf6  3.Kd3  , or  1.Ke3!  Ke5  2.g4  and if @@StartFEN@@8/8/3k3p/8/7P/4K1P1/8/8 b - - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Ke6  2.Kf4!  Kf6  3.g4  . }
1. Kf3 Ke7 2. Kf4 Ke6 3. g4 Kf6 4. Kf3 Ke7
{ An awful blunder in return. As long as the pawn stood on  g3  , Black ceded his opponent the right to control the opposition. But now, with the pawn on  g4  , he cannot give the opposition up!  4...Kf7!=  was necessary. }
5. Ke3 Kf7 6. Kd4 Kf6 7. Kd5 Ke7 8. Ke5 Kf7 9. Kf5 Kg7 10. Ke6 Kg6 11. h5+ Kg5
12. Kf7 Kxg4 13. Kg6 Kf4 14. Kxh6 { Black resigned. } *

