{ N. Grigoriev, 1920  We shall analyze the basic ideas of such positions by using the following study as an example.   If White plays  1.Kh1?  , naively hoping for  1...f2??=  stalemate, then after  1...Kg4  his position is lost. Black's plan is elementary: his king goes to e3, and then he advances ...f3-f2, forcing the advance of White's h-pawn. The fact that Black can choose whether to move his h-pawn one or two squares forward allows him to place his opponent in zugzwang.  For example  2.Kg1  Kf4  3.Kf2  Ke4  4.Kf1  Ke3  5.Ke1  f2+  6.Kf1  Kf3!  7.h3  h5!  8.h4  Kg3  or  7.h4  h6!  8.h5  Kg3  . And in case of @@StartFEN@@8/7p/8/8/4k3/5p2/5K1P/8 w - - 6 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Ke1  Ke3  5.Kf1  f2  6.h4  h5!  -+ }
1. Kf2 Kg4 2. Ke3
{ Thanks to zugzwang, the pawn must leave the h7-square; the position is now a draw. White must only make sure he chooses the right back-rank square for his king @@StartBracket@@corresponding to the position of Black's h-pawn@@EndBracket@@. }
2... h6 3. Kf2 Kf4 4. Ke1 Ke3 { Or  4...h5  5.Kf2  Ke4  6.Kf1= } 5. Kf1 h5
{ 5...f2  6.h3!  Kf3  7.h4  Kg3  8.h5  ⨀  = } 6. Ke1 f2+
{ 6...h4  would be met by  7.Kf1!  f2  8.h3=  But not the hasty  7.h3?  which would be a terrible blunder here, leading to theFahrni-Alapin ending we know so well @@StartBracket@@from Diagram 1-27@@EndBracket@@. Just a reminder: Black wins by triangulating with his king:  7...Ke4  8.Kf1  Ke5  9.Ke1  Kf5!  10.Kf1  Ke4  ⨀ }
7. Kf1 Kf3 8. h3 Kg3 9. h4
{ So the stronger side always wins when the attacker's rook's pawn is also on its starting square. When it has advanced, matters become much more difficult. One major winning position, which is worth knowing, was found by Maizelis in 1955 @@StartBracket@@although it was seen even earlier, in a 1949 study by Valles@@EndBracket@@.  Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 1-185 }
*

