{ Here, everything depends on whose turn it is to move. Black to move wins. }
1... Ke4 2. Ke2 h4
{ An exceptionally important position – reciprocal zugzwang! } 3. Kf2 Kd3
{ Control of the opposition is exploited, as usual, by outflanking – although this time, a paradoxical one. }
4. Kf3 h3 { Zugzwang. } 5. Kf2
{ There is no help in either  5.Kf4  Ke2  6.Kxf5  Kf3!  or  5.Kg3  Ke2  or  5...Ke3  6.Kxh3  f4  . }
5... Kd2 6. Kf3 { 6.Kf1  Ke3  7.Ke1  Kf3  8.Kf1  f4  9.Kg1  Ke2  -+ } 6... Ke1
7. Ke3 Kf1 8. Kf3 Kg1 9. Kg3 f4+ 10. Kf3 { 10.Kxh3  f3  -+ } 10... Kxh2 11. Kf2
f3 { Black wins. } *

