[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/p6p/2k3p1/4Pp2/2K2P1P/6P1/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ The following exceptionally complex example was first given in Fine's book  (1941)  , but unfortunately with completely erroneous analysis. Maizelis  (1956)  did a much better job on the position; and later his conclusions were refined and extended by other authors.   Here we have a protected passed pawn versus an outside passed pawn. Since White cannot win the a-pawn, he will have to trade it for his e-pawn. But what does this leave us with? }
1. Kb4
{ Or  1.Kd4  Kc7  2.Kc5  a6  3.Kc4  and now not  3...Kc6?  4.Kd4  ⨀, but  3...Kc8  4.Kb4  Kb8  5.Ka5  Kb7  . }
1... Kb6
{ Black cannot close up the kingside with  1...h5  ,  since then the trade of pawns will give White an easy win:  2.Ka5  Kb7  3.Kb5  Kc7  4.Ka6  Kb8  5.e6  Kc7  6.Kxa7  Kd6  7.Kb6  Kxe6  8.Kc6  (taking the lateral opposition decides)  8...Ke7  9.Kc7  Ke6  10.Kd8  (outflanking)  10...Kd5  11.Ke7  Ke4  12.Kf6  Kf3  13.Kxg6  Kxg3  14.Kg5!  ⨀ and if @@StartFEN@@3K4/8/4k1p1/5p1p/5P1P/6P1/8/8 b - - 5 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Kf7  11.Kd7  Kf6  12.Ke8  Kg7  13.Ke7  Kh7  14.Kf7  Kh6  15.Kg8  ⨀ }
2. Ka4 a5
{ Equally good is  2...Kc6  3.Ka5  Kc7  4.Ka6  Kb8  .   Fine only examined  2...a6?  3.Kb4  Kc6  4.Kc4  Kb6  5.Kd5!  and White either queens his pawn or wins the pawn on a6.  In case of @@StartFEN@@8/7p/p1k3p1/4Pp2/2K2P1P/6P1/8/8 b - - 3 4@@EndFEN@@  4...a5  5.Kd4! }
3. h5
{ Before exchanging pawns, it is necessary first to weaken the enemy kingside pawn chain. Because it is zugzwang, Black has no choice. }
3... gxh5 4. e6 Kc6 5. Kxa5 Kd6 6. Kb6 Kxe6
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed. note: additional diagram to illustrate the analysis.@@EndSquare@@   The pawn at  f5  must fall. But if Black replies to the capture of the pawn @@StartFEN@@8/5k1p/8/4Kp1p/5P2/6P1/8/8 w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Kxf5  with  1...h4  2.gxh4  Ke7  ,  he will draw, because this will lead to Maizelis' position with White in zugzwang. But if the pawn is captured instead with the king at either e7 or g7, Black is the one in zugzwang, and he loses. So this is what the further course of the struggle will be about.  This conclusion allows us to discover the corresponding squares e5 and f7, d5 and e7 @@StartBracket@@g7@@EndBracket@@. Continuing this analysis, we find more corresponding squares: e6 and g6 @@StartBracket@@e8@@EndBracket@@, f6 and f8. }
7. Kc6
{ But not  7.Kc5?  Kf7!  or  7...Kd7!  8.Kd5  Ke7  9.Ke5  Kf7  10.Kxf5  h4  11.gxh4  Ke7  12.Ke5  Kf7  13.h5  Ke7  ⨀  =   Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 1-188 }
*

