[White "Chapter 1 – Pawn Endgames III"]
[Black "The f- and h-pawns vs. the h-pawn 1-188"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/7p/2K1k3/5p1p/5P2/6P1/8/8 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... Kf7
{ The most stubborn defense, pointed out by Euwe and Hooper @@StartBracket@@1958@@EndBracket@@.   Things are simpler for White after  7...Ke7  8.Kd5  Kf6  9.Kd6  Kf7  10.Ke5  Kg6  11.Ke6  Kg7  12.Kxf5  h4  13.gxh4  Kf7  14.Ke5  Ke7  15.h5  ⨀ +-   But now, since  8.Kd5?  Ke7!  or  8...Kg7!  and @@StartFEN@@8/5k1p/2K5/5p1p/5P2/6P1/8/8 w - - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  8.Kd6  Kf6  9.Kd5  Kg7  or  9...Ke7!  , do not work, there remains but one move. }
2. Kd7 Kf8 3. Kd6
{ 9.Ke6?  would be a mistake:  9...Ke8  10.Kf6  h4  11.gxh4  Kf8  12.h5  Kg8  13.Kxf5  Kf7!=  And if  12.Kxf5  Ke7!  In case of @@StartFEN@@4k3/7p/5K2/5p1p/5P2/6P1/8/8 b - - 6 4@@EndFEN@@  10...Kf8  11.Kg5  h4!  12.gxh4  Kf7!  or  12.Kxh4  h6  is also possible. }
3... Kg7 4. Ke7 Kg8
{ 10...Kg6  11.Ke6  Kg7  12.Kxf5  h4  13.gxh4  Kf7  14.Ke5  Ke7  15.h5  ⨀ +- }
5. Ke6 Kf8 6. Kf6 Kg8 7. Kxf5 h4 8. gxh4
{ White has achieved his aim − the enemy king cannot go to e7 now. } 8... Kf7
9. Ke5 Ke7 10. h5 Kf7 11. Kd6 Kf6 12. h6
{ Etc.  Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 1-189 } *

