{ The only defense left to examine involves Black holding on to both h-pawns. }
1... Kg6 2. Ke6 h6 3. Ke5 Kg7 4. Kxf5 Kf7 5. Ke5 Ke7 6. f5 Kf7 7. f6
{ With the pawn pushed up to h6,  16...h4  17.gxh4  is now useless: at a minimum, White gets the winning position from the gameFahrni-Alapin.  On the other hand, we have practically the same situation on the board now - the only difference being that the e6-square, as is easily seen, corresponds to f8, not e8; and that means the e5-square corresponds to e8. So the familiar triangulation decides. }
7... Ke8 8. Kf4 Kf8 9. Ke4 Ke8 10. Ke5 Kf8 { 19...Kf7  20.Kf5  +- } 11. Ke6 Ke8
12. f7+ Kf8 13. Kf6 h4 14. gxh4 h5 15. Kg6 { White wins. } *

