[SetUp "1"]

{ Tragicomedies: Azmaiparashvili − Eolian, USSR ch tt 1979 } 1. Kg5
{ White wins by  1.Kxf5!  Kf7  2.f4  Ke7  3.Ke5  ⨀  Kf7  4.Kd6!! } 1... Kf8 2.
Kxf5 Kf7 { 2...Ke7!  3.f4  Kf7= } 3. Kg4
{ The comedy of errors continues! Of course, either  3.f4!  or  3.Ke5!  was correct. }
3... Kf6
{ The king steps upon a mined square − one  he should only have gone to after f3-f4.   Black draws after either  3...Kf8!  or  3...Ke6!  4.f4  Kf6!  , and if  4.Kg5  Kf7! }
4. Kf4
{ 4.f4!  ⨀  was simpler: next move, the white king advances, seizing the opposition. For example:  4...Ke7  5.Kg5!  Kf7  6.Kf5  etc., and if  5...Ke6  6.Kh6  . }
4... Kf7
{ 4...Ke6!?  would not have helped, in view of  5.Kg4!  ⨀  Kf6  6.f4!  +- and if @@StartFEN@@8/7p/4k3/7P/6K1/5P2/8/8 b - - 6 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Ke7  6.Kf5!  Just not  5.Kg5?  Kf7= }
5. Kf5
{ And once again, White misses the opportunity:  5.Ke5!  Ke7  6.f4  ⨀ +- } 5...
Ke7 6. Ke5 Kf7 7. Kd6 Kf6 8. Kd7 Kf7
{ Black also draws after  8...Kg5  9.Ke6  h6!  ⨀  10.Ke5  Kxh5  11.f4  Kg6  12.Ke6  Kg7!  13.Ke7  Kg6  (the pendulum.)  Or  8...Kf5  9.Ke7  Kg5! }
9. h6 { 9.f4  Kf6  10.Ke8  Kf5  11.Kf7  Kxf4  12.Kg7  Kf5  13.Kxh7  Kf6= } 9...
Kg6 10. f4 { 10.Ke6  Kxh6  11.f4  Kg7  12.Ke7  Kg6!=  − the pendulum. } 10...
Kf7 { 10...Kxh6?  11.f5  +- } 11. f5 Kf6
{ Draw.  This example demonstrates how senseless the play of both sides can seem when they are unacquainted with the ideas behind a position. }
*

