[SetUp "1"]

{ Šveida − Sika, Brno 1929  Steinitz's rule tells us that, as far as reserve tempi go, White stands better on the queenside, while Black is better on the kingside. The following bit of advice will help you select the optimal strategy for such situations:  Try to equalize, as quickly as possible, the situation on your 'unfavorable' side.  Whoever has the move in the above position will succeed in executing the principle outlined above, and will win.   Let's suppose it is Black to move. }
1... Ke5 2. Kf3 a5
{ The pawns retaining the right to move either one or two squares should be left alone. }
3. h4
{ 3.a4  is met by  3...h6!   The game continued  3.b3  b5!  4.a3  a4  5.bxa4  bxa4  6.h4  h5  and White resigned. And in case of @@StartFEN@@8/7p/8/pp2k3/4Pp2/1P3K1P/P7/8 w - - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.h4  b4  5.h5  h6  -+ }
3... a4 4. h5 h6 5. b4 axb3 { 5...a3  6.b5  b6  -+ } 6. axb3 b6 7. b4 b5
{ Black wins. } *

