[SetUp "1"]

{ Tragicomedies: Laveryd − Wikström, Umeå 1997  With the following difficult, but beautiful example, I wish to close this chapter devoted to pawn endgames. The comments are based on those of Lindgren in Informant 74.   On the queenside, the two kings have already occupied the mined squares b3 and c5. It would seem that the side  (let's say, Black)  that first runs out of pawn moves will lose. So the correct answer - that the position is a draw - appears paradoxical.   The first question is: How is Black to avoid losing immediately? For  1...f6?  or  1...f5?  is completely hopeless in view of  2.exf6  gxf6  3.g4! }
1... h5
{ It turns out that, after the natural  1...h5  2.h4?  it is not White who places his opponent in zugzwang - he falls into it himself:  2...g5!  3.hxg5  h4  ⨀   By the way, this example fully deserves to be placed in 'Tragicomedies, ' since the actual continuation was  1...h6??  2.h3??  h5!  -+  3.h4  g5!  4.g3  g4  , and White resigned. In case of @@StartFEN@@8/5pp1/4p2p/2k1P3/1pP1p3/1K2P3/5PPP/8 w - - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.g4!  f5  3.exf6  gxf6  4.h4  +- or  2...g6  3.h4  +- }
2. h3
{ But now, Black once again faces a tough defensive task.  2...g5?  loses at once to  3.g3  . And @@StartFEN@@8/5pp1/4p3/2k1P2p/1pP1p3/1K2P2P/5PP1/8 b - - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...f5?  to  3.h4  . No better is  2...h4?  3.g3!  g5  4.g4  or  3...hxg3  4.fxg3  f5  5.exf6  gxf6  6.h4  .   2...g6?  is elegantly refuted by  3.g4!  hxg4  4.h4!  But not  3.h4?  g5!  So there is only one move left. }
2... f6 3. h4
{ Of course not  3.exf6?  gxf6  and it is not difficult to see that White is the one in zugzwang. But now what does Black do?   Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 1-194 }
*

