{ Drawn Positions   Knight and pawn win easily against a lone king @@StartBracket@@that is, of course, so long as the pawn is not lost@@EndBracket@@. But there are exceptions.  Black saves himself by squeezing the opposing king in the corner. He must only be careful to choose the correct square for his king.   1...Kf8?  loses after  2.Nc7  Kf7  3.Ne6  ⨀ }
1... Kf7 2. Nc7 Kf8 3. Ne6+ Kf7
{ It is useful to note that  the knight @@StartBracket@@unlike the other pieces@@EndBracket@@ cannot lose a move in order to give the move to the opponent  − the knight cannot triangulate. }
