[SetUp "1"]

{ 2/3. P. Faragó, 1943 } 1. Kg7
{ 1.h7?  Rg5  2.h6  Nc6  3.a7  Ne5  or  3...Nd8  loses immediately, hence White's initial move is forced. }
1... Rg5+ 2. Kf6
{ 2.Kf7?  is incorrect:  2...Rf5+  3.Kg7  Ke7  4.h7  Rf7+  5.Kg6  Rf8  6.Kg7  Rh8!  7.h6  Nc6  8.a7  Ne5  9.a8=Q  Rxa8  10.h8=Q  Rxh8  11.Kxh8  Kf7  12.Kh7  Nd7  13.Kh8  Nf8  14.h7  Ng6#  Checkmating the white king in the corner with the knight is Black's goal in all cases, while White has to find a way to avoid this sorrowful outcome. }
2... Rg8
{ 2...Rxh5  3.Kg7  Ke7  4.h7  leads to nothing, for example:  4...Rh3!?  5.h8=Q  Rg3+  6.Kh6!=  , rather than  6.Kh7?  Kf7  -+ }
3. h7
{ The king prefers to stay on f6 where it deprives the black knight of the important e5-square.   After  3.Kf7?  White can no longer hold the game:  3...Re8!  (the rook will be sacrificed in the corner only when the white pawn comes to h7)  4.h7  Rh8  5.h6  Nc6  6.a7  Ne5+!  7.Kf6  Kd6!  8.Kg7  Ke7  and we have already seen what follows.   By the way, another winning method exists:  8...Ke6  9.a8=Q  Rxa8  10.h8=Q  Ra7+!?  11.Kg8  Ng4  12.Kf8  Nf6  and White has no satisfactory defense against the threat 13...Rf7#.  And in case of @@StartFEN@@6KQ/r7/4k2P/8/6n1/8/8/8 w - - 3 12@@EndFEN@@  12.h7  Nh6+  13.Kf8  Ra8+  14.Kg7  Nf5+  and 15...Rxh8. }
3... Rh8 { 3...Ra8  4.Kg7= } 4. h6
{ Rather than  4.Kg7?  Ke7  5.h6  Nc6  -+  again. } 4... Nc6 { Diagram 16-32 }
5. a7
{ Before White sends his king to the corner he wants to get rid of the a-pawn.  5...Nxa7  6.Kg7=  Of course, Black does not take the pawn but his knight cannot go to e5; it must occupy a less favorable square. }
5... Ne7 6. Kg7 { 6.a8=Q?  is premature:  6...Rxa8  7.Kg7  Nf5+ } 6... Ke6 7.
a8=Q Rxa8 8. h8=Q Rxh8
{ White's last opportunity for a mistake:  9.Kxh8?  Kf7  10.Kh7  @@StartBracket@@we know this position fromexercise 2/1@@EndBracket@@  10...Nc6  11.Kh8  Ne5  12.Kh7  Nd7  13.Kh8  Nf8  14.h7  Ng6# }
9. h7 { Draw. } *

