{ I should also point out that even with the knight in the corner, the position is certainly not always hopeless. True, the knight can no longer deal with the pawn by itself; but sometimes the king can come to its rescue in time.     In the starting position @@StartSquare@@Ed. note: based on the previous example.@@EndSquare@@, let's move the black king to d3. Now the knight cannot get to h2 following  1.Nh6?  h2  2.Ng4  h1=Q+  , the pawn queens with check. }
1. Ng3 { This is what White has to play, threatening 2. Nf1. } 1... h2 2. Kb7
{ Diagram 2-11  The knight has set up a  barrier  against the enemy king, which not only cannot cross the e2- and e4-squares, but also is denied e3 and d2 @@StartBracket@@because of the forking Nf1+@@EndBracket@@.  Knight forks are a vital technique in knight endgames.   In order to attack the knight, the king will have to lose time with the outflanking ...Kc2-d1-e1-f2, or ...Kd4-e5-f4. }
2... Kd4
{ 2...Kc2  3.Kc6  Kd1  4.Kd5  Ke1  5.Ke4  Kf2  6.Kf4=  Or  6.Nh1+  Kg2  7.Ke3= }
3. Kc6 Ke5 4. Kc5 Kf4 5. Nh1 Kf3 6. Kd4 Kg2 7. Ke3 Kxh1 8. Kf2 { Draw. } *

