{ N. Grigoriev, 1932  The knight goes after the h-pawn, while the black king stands athwart his path. Which side will win out? }
1. Nb4 h5 2. Nc6 { 2.Nd5+?  Kf3!  3.Nc7  h4  4.Ne6  Kg4!  loses for White. }
2... Ke4
{ This generalization may be illustrated by the variation @@StartFEN@@8/8/K1N5/7p/4k3/8/8/8 w - - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nd8?  h4  4.Ne6  Kf5!  5.Nd4+  Kg4  -+ }
3. Na5 h4 4. Nc4 { 4.Nb3?  Ke3  -+ } 4... Kf3
{ 4...h3  5.Nd2+  Ke3  6.Nf1+=   Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 2-13 }
