[White "Chapter 2 – Knight versus Pawns"]
[Black "Knight vs. Rook Pawn 2-13"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/8/K7/8/2N4p/5k2/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ N. Grigoriev, 1932  (continued)     One last little task: to choose between  5.Nd2+  and  5.Ne5+  . }
1. Ne5+
{ On  5.Nd2+?  Black responds  5...Ke2!  6.Ne4  h3  7.Ng3+  Kf2  and since the knight cannot reach the h2-square, White loses.  Black should avoid @@StartFEN@@8/8/K7/8/7p/5k2/3N4/8 b - - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  5...Kg2??  6.Nc4!  h3  7.Ne3+= }
1... Kg3
{ On  5...Kf4  White plays  6.Ng6+  while other retreats allow the knight to get to g4. }
2. Nc4 h3 3. Ne3
{ It is interesting that the only way to refute @@StartFEN@@8/8/K7/7p/1N6/4k3/8/8 w - - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nc2+?  instead of 2.Nc6! is by  2...Kf2!  The natural reply  2...Ke4?  allows White the same sort of saving maneuver as in the main variation  3.Na3!  Kd3  4.Kb5!  h4  5.Nc4  h3  6.Ne5+=  And if  3...h4  4.Nc4=   Let's think about the strategic basis for White's saving plan. His knight goes to the h2-square via g4 or f1. Each of those routes individually might be interdicted by the king. The c4-square is key, because both routes intersect here: c4-e5-g4 and c4-d2-f1. Black cannot prevent the double threat.    Double attack is one of the most effective methods of struggle in chess. Along with tactical double attacks @@StartBracket@@such as knight forks@@EndBracket@@, it is important to learn the use of strategic double attacks as well − moves which further two @@StartBracket@@or more@@EndBracket@@ goals simultaneously.   In addition to the study we have just examined, this strategy might also be illustrated by some of the pawn endgames examined earlier, such asWeenink's position @@StartBracket@@Diagram 1-15@@EndBracket@@ orB. Neuenschwander's position @@StartBracket@@Diagram 1-31@@EndBracket@@. }
*

