{ 2/5. N. Grigoriev, 1932  The knight cannot arrive at h2 in time − at most, it can only prevent a promotion by taking the h1-square under control. Then White's only hope is to create a barrier that will make it difficult for the black king to approach. }
1. Nf7 { 1.Ng6?  h3  2.Nf4  h2  3.Ne2+  Kd2!  4.Ng3  Ke1  -+  does not work. }
1... h3 2. Ng5 { 2.Nd6?  fails to  2...Kd3  3.Nf5  Ke2!  4.Ng3+  Kf2  -+ } 2...
h2 3. Ne4+
{ Diagram 16-33   Where should the black king go? After  3...Kd3?!  4.Ng3!  ,  a barrier arises, as we already know.   If  3...Kd4  then  4.Ng3?  is bad:  4...Ke5!  5.Kc6  Kf4  6.Nh1  Kf3  and the white king fails to get to f2. But White has @@StartFEN@@8/2K5/8/8/3kN3/8/7p/8 w - - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf2!  Now both  4...Ke3  and  4...Ke5  are met with  5.Ng4+  . And after  4...Kc3  5.Kd6  Kd2  6.Ke5  Ke2  7.Nh1  Kf3  8.Kd4  Kg2  9.Ke3  Kxh1  10.Kf2= }
3... Kc2 4. Ng3
{ 4.Nf2?  Kd2  leads to the line from the previous annotation, but with an extra tempo for Black. }
4... Kd1 5. Kd6 Ke1 6. Ke5 Kf2 7. Kf4 { Draw. } *

