{ 2/6. D. Gurgenidze, 1970  (after N. Grigoriev, 1934) } 1. Ka3
{ Only here, to keep the b3-square free. Both  1.Kb3?  Ke6!  and @@StartFEN@@8/4k2N/7p/1p6/8/8/K7/8 w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Kb2?  Kf7!  are losing.   White can easily parry the threat to the h7-knight by approaching the b5-pawn with his king, e.g.,  1.Ka3  or  1.Kb3  Kf7  2.Kb4  Kg7  3.Kxb5  Kxh7  4.Kc4  =. However, Black has a more dangerous plan, namely  1...Ke6  and if  2.Kb4  then  2...Kf5  3.Kxb5  h5  -+   Since the white king fails to enter the square of the h-pawn after  1...Ke6  , the task of fighting against it must be taken up by the knight:  2.Nf8+  . It is highly important to foresee its entire route, because the correct first move can only be discovered in this way. }
1... Ke6 2. Nf8+ Kf5 3. Nd7 h5 4. Nc5 h4 5. Nb3
{ 5.Nd3?  h3  6.Nf2  h2  7.Kb4  Kf4  -+ } 5... h3 6. Nd2 h2 { 6...Kf4  7.Nf1= }
7. Nf1 h1=Q 8. Ng3+ { Draw. } *

