{ 2/7. Stangl-Schneider, Berlin 1992 } 1. c5
{ In the actual game, White played  1.Ng7?  The position after  1...Bf6  2.Nxh5  Bd4!  (∆ 3...Kd3)  is definitely lost: White cannot prevent Black's king march to the queenside pawns.  3.c5  Bxc5  @@StartBracket@@Diagram 16-34@@EndBracket@@  4.Nf6  Kd4  5.Nd7  Kd5  6.Ke1  Bd4  7.Kd2  Kc4  8.Nb8  Kc5  9.Nd7+  Kb4  10.Nb8  Kxa4  11.Nc6  Bb6  12.Ne5  f2  13.Ke2  Kb3  14.Nf3  a4  15.Nd2+  Kb4  White resigned.   On the more stubborn  4.Ng7!?  Kd3  5.Ne6  , both  5...Be3  6.Nd8  Kc4  7.Nc6=  and  5...Kc4  6.Ng5  Kb4  7.Nxf3  Kxa4  8.Nd2  Kb4  9.Ke2=  are useless. Also, in case of  6...f2  7.Ne4  .   As Müller has demonstrated, Black wins after @@StartFEN@@8/8/4N3/p1b5/P7/3k1p2/8/5K2 b - - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Be7!  6.Kf2  Ke4  7.Nc7  Bh4+  8.Kf1  Kd4  9.Nb5+  Kc4  10.Nd6+  Kb4  11.Nf5  Bf6  12.Kf2  Kxa4  13.Kxf3  Kb3  -+  White can advance his c-pawn in order to win the bishop for it. It looks highly risky but should be checked, because the alternative is completely hopeless. }
1... Bg3 2. c6 h4 3. c7 Bxc7 4. Nxc7 h3 5. Nd5+ Kd4
{ 5...Ke4  6.Nf6+  Kf5  7.Nh5= } 6. Ne7 { Diagram 16-35 } 6... h2
{ 6...Ke4  7.Kg1!= } 7. Nf5+ Kc4 8. Ng3 Kb4 9. Kf2 Kxa4 10. Kxf3 Kb3 11. Kg2 a4
12. Ne2 Kb2 { 12...a3  13.Nc1+ } 13. Nf4
{ We know this drawing position fromGrigoriev's study. } 13... Kc3
{ 13...a3  14.Nd3+ } 14. Nd5+ { 14.Ne2+?  Kd2!  -+ } 14... Kb3 15. Nf4 a3 16.
Nd3 { Dvoretsky. } *

