{ M. Dvoretsky, 2000  (analysis)     Let's move the pawn to  c3  . White's task is now more complex. He only gets a draw out of  1.Kg2?  Ke4  2.Kg3  Kd3  3.Nd5  or  3.Nb5  Kc4=   In case of  1.Nb5?  , now not  1...Ke4 ?  2.c4  , but  1...Kd5  2.Na3  Ke4  3.Kg2  Kd3  4.c4  Kc3  5.Kf3  Kb3  6.Ke4  Kxa3  Here, if the king were on e5, White would win with 7.Kd6. But there is a solution. }
1. Na8 Kd5 { 1...Ke4  2.c4  +- } 2. Nb6+ Kc6 3. Nc4 Kd5
{ And now the simplest is: the barrier. } 4. Nd2
{ Understandably, if we moved the starting position one file to the left, there would be no win. }
*

