{ If White must defend the knight with his king, then the wins come far less often. Sometimes, we get a position of reciprocal zugzwang.  Ebralidze − Bondarevsky, USSR ch, Tbilisi 1937 }
1. Ke5
{ Seizing the opposition is important when the black pawn is at h5 − consequently, it follows that with the pawn at h7, White needs the anti-opposition.   In the actual game, White erred, missing the win:  1.Ke6?  Kg5!  2.Ke5  h5  3.Ke4  Kg4  , and if  3.Ke6  Kg6!  4.Ne3  Kg5  .  Draw, in view of  5.Ke5  h4  6.g4  h3  . }
1... Kg5
{ Other moves don't help either:  1...h5  2.Kf6  or  2.Ke4  +- And if  1...h6  2.Kf6!  Kh5  3.Nxh6!  Kxh6  4.g4  +-   1...Kf3  2.Ke6!  Kg4  3.Kf6  ⨀  (the king triangulates)  3...h5  4.Kg6  and  3...Kh5  3.Ne3  . }
2. Ne3 h5 3. Ke4 { 3.Nf5  +- } 3... h4 4. g4 h3 5. Kf3 { White wins. } *

