[FEN "8/8/8/4p2k/4Pp2/8/2N5/1K6 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ D. Blundell, 1995  (continued)     Let's try  1.Na3?  f3  2.Nc4  . Now the natural  2...Kg4?  leads to a loss  3.Kc2  Kg3  4.Kc3!  ⨀  f2  5.Nd2  Kf4  6.Kd3  ⨀ +- and  4...Kf4  5.Kd3  f2  6.Nd2  ⨀ +- Black can try instead @@StartFEN@@8/8/8/4p3/2N1P3/2K2pk1/8/8 b - - 5 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Kg4  5.Nxe5+!  Kf4  6.Kd4  . White won here only because with his king at  c3  the e5-pawn could be captured with check.   That can be avoided by playing after  1.Na3?  f3  2.Nc4  Kh4!!  or  2...Kg5!!  3.Kc2  Kg4!  4.Kc3!?  Here there is also  4...Kg5!?  for example  5.Kd2!?  f2  6.Ne3  Kf4  7.Kd3  Kg3!  8.Nf1+  Kf3!  9.Nd2+  Kf4  . Or  4...Kg3!  We have reached another reciprocal zugzwang position, this time with White to move.  5.Nd2  runs into  5...Kf4  6.Kd3  f2=  (the main zugzwang.)   An equivalent line is  5.Kd2  f2  6.Ke2  Kf4  7.Nd6  Kg3  , and if  7.Nd2  f1=Q+!  or  5.Kd3  f2  6.Nd2  Kf4!  ⨀  Incidentally, looking at this variation leads us to the astonishing conclusion that both sides should maneuver so as not to be the first to approach the other. As soon as White plays either Nd2 or Kd3, he falls into zugzwang; and if Black is too hasty with either ...f2 or ...Kf4, the zugzwang position occurs with him to move instead. Thus, we have a case known to us from pawn endings: mined squares. However, this is the only case I know of where the squares are mined for four different pieces at once, and not for the usual two.  And now, for the solution. White must play much as in the last variation, except that he must place his knight, not on c4, but on b3, leaving the c4-square open for his king. }
1. Na1 f3 2. Nb3 Kg4 3. Kc2 Kg3 4. Kc3 Kg4 5. Kc4
{ Diagram 2-23    The point! Black can wait no longer: on  5...Kg3  6.Kd5  f2  7.Nd2  Kf4  8.Nf1  +-  decides. He must go to the mined square first, which of course puts him into zugzwang. }
5... Kf4 6. Kd3
{ 6.Kd5?  Ke3  and if @@StartFEN@@8/8/8/4p3/2K1Pk2/1N3p2/8/8 w - - 8 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Nd2?  Ke3  . }
6... f2 7. Nd2 Kg3 8. Ke2
{ 8.Kc4  Kf4  9.Kd5?  is mistaken, in view of  9...Ke3  10.Nf1+  Kf4  ⨀  = }
8... Kg2 9. Nf1 Kg1 10. Ne3 { Zugzwang. } *

