{ Tragicomedies: Nimzovitch − Rubinstein, Karlsbad 1911    The best square for the knight would have been  d7  , from where it defends the e5-pawn and prevents the exchange ...f7-f6. This could easily have been achieved by  1.Kb3  ,  1.Kb5  or  1.Kb4!  Kf4  2.Nd3+  Ke4  3.Kc4  , and after  2...Kxg4  3.Nc5!  Kf5  4.Nd7  +- Unfortunately, Nimzovitch was too hasty. }
1. Nd3 f6 2. exf6 Kxf6 3. Nf2 Kg5
{ White's king is too far from the center of the action − Black has enough time to drive the knight from f2 by advancing his e-pawn. }
4. Kb4 e5 5. Kc4 e4 6. Kd4 Kf4 { Draw, in view of  7.--  e3  . } *

