{ Tragicomedies: Keres − Lengyel, Luhacovice 1969  The game was adjourned here, and Lengyel resigned without continuing. Evidently, he assumed that his e- and g-pawns were doomed, and White must inevitably wind up two pawns ahead.   But this is not the case. As Keres pointed out, Black has a simple plan of defense which guarantees him the draw. First, he must force g2-g3, after which he can defend the g4-pawn from h2 with his knight. White cannot break down this defensive setup: Bg1 is met by ...Nf3 with tempo. And there is no possible zugzwang, either. }
1... Ne1
{ Simplest is to attack the pawn at once.   1...Nf4  2.g3  Ne6  is also possible:  3.Bxe5  Ng5  4.Kf4  Nf3  5.Bd6  Nh2=  But not  2...Nd5+  3.Ke4  Nf6+  4.Kf5!  +- }
2. g3
{ And  2.Kf2  is met by  2...Nd3+  3.Kf1  Kc8  4.g3  Kd7  5.Ke2  e4  6.Ke3  Ne1 =  And if  3.Kg3  e4  4.Kxg4  e3  5.Kf3  Ne1+  6.Kg3  e2  7.Kf2  Nxg2= }
2... Nf3 { We already have the indicated defensive position. } *

