{ 2/8. I. Horowitz, I. Kashdan, 1928    White's barrier is not effective: Black plans 1...Kb4 followed with ...a5-a4-a3. For example,  1.Ke7?  Kb4  2.Kd6  a5  3.Kd5  a4  4.Nc4  Kb5!  ⨀  5.Kd4  Kb4  6.Kd3  Kb3=  A better place for the knight should be investigated. }
1. Nb3 Kb4
{ We should also explore the attempt of overcoming the barrier from the side. As we shall see it takes too much time.   1...Kc4!?  2.Na1!  Kd3  3.Ke7  Kd2  4.Kd6  a5  5.Kc5  a4  6.Kb4  Kc1  7.Kc3  or  7.Ka3  Kb1  8.Nb3!  +- In case of  5...Kc1  6.b3  Kb2  7.Kb5  +- And if @@StartFEN@@8/8/p2K4/8/8/8/1P1k4/N7 b - - 7 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Kc1  5.b4!  Kb2  6.Kc6!  , rather than  6.Kc5?  Kc3!  ⨀  = }
2. Na1
{ This barrier is solid enough. An advance of the a-pawn gives Black nothing now: if ...a4-a3, then Nc2+ with bxa3 to follow. }
*

