{ 2/9. Tal-Böök, Stockholm 1960 } 1... a4
{ Black's king must go to the hostile pawns but  1...Kd4  is met with the fork  2.Ne6+  . An advance of the g-pawn enables White to fix the kingside:  1...g6?  2.g5!  hxg5  3.hxg5  a4  4.Kc1!  Kd4  5.Ne6+  Ke5  6.Nf8  Kf5  7.Nh7  +-   In case of  1...g5?  2.hxg5  hxg5  3.Kc1  Kd4  4.Nd7!  Ke4  5.Kb2  Kf4  6.Nf6  Ke5  7.Nh5  +- But  3.Ne4+  Kb2  4.Nxg5  a4  5.Nf3  a3  6.Nd4  a2  7.Nc2  is also strong.   Let's study  1...Kd4?  more attentively. We can see that Black loses here, too:  2.Ne6+  Ke5  3.Nxg7  Kf4  4.g5  hxg5  5.h5  Ke5  6.Ne8!  ∆ 7.h6  6...Kf5  7.Nd6+  Kf6  8.Ne4+  and 9.Ng3+-. Or  5...g4  6.h6  g3  7.Ke2!  +-   However, the last line gives us a tip to the correct solution: 1...a4!! First the white king should be diverted to the queenside. }
2. Kc1
{ After  2.Nxa4+  Kd4  neither the knight nor the king can help the pawns in time. }
2... a3 { 2...Kd4  is also possible already. } 3. Kb1 Kd4 4. Ne6+ Ke5 5. Nxg7
Kf4 6. g5 hxg5 7. h5 { Diagram 16-36 } 7... g4 8. h6 g3 9. Ne6+
{ 9.Nh5+  Kg5= } 9... Kf5 10. h7 g2 11. Nd4+ Kg6 { Draw. } *

