[White "Chapter 3 – Knight Endgames"]
[Black "Diagram 3-6 Exercise 3/2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/K5p1/1p5k/1P5p/P1n5/5N2/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ 3/2. Szabó − Grószpéter, Kecskemet 1984 } 1. Nd2 Nxd2
{ He must accept the knight sacrifice because both  1...h4  2.Nxc4  h3  3.Ne3  @@StartBracket@@∆ 4.Nf1@@EndBracket@@  3...h2  4.Ng4+  and  1...Ne5  2.Kxb6  are quite bad. }
2. a5
{ 2.Kxb6?  h4  In this position, the game  (it was played in a team competition)  was adjudicated and White was awarded a win. The main line is instructive and nice. }
2... bxa5
{ 2...h4  3.axb6  h3  4.b7  h2  5.b8=Q  h1=Q  6.Qh8+  +-   2...Nc4  3.a6  h4  4.Kb8  and if @@StartFEN@@8/K5p1/Pp5k/1P5p/2n5/8/8/8 b - - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nd6  4.Kxb6  h4  , now White should avoid  5.Kc6?  h3  ,  5.Ka5?  Nc4+  ,  5.a7?  Nc8+  6.Kc5  Nxa7  7.b6  Nc6!  , and play  5.Kc5!  Nc8  6.b6  +- }
3. b6 Nc4 4. b7 Ne5 { Diagram 16-37 } 5. Kb8
{ An unusual move: the king interferes with its own pawn!   The natural looking  5.Kb6?  is wrong:  5...Nd7+  6.Kc7  Nc5  . And after @@StartFEN@@8/1P1n2p1/1K5k/p6p/8/8/8/8 w - - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Kc6  Nb8+  7.Kc7  , it makes no sense for Black to repeat moves with  7...Na6+  8.Kb6  Nb8  , so  7...a4!  8.Kxb8  a3  , and Black wins the queen ending with two extra pawns. }
5... Nc6+
{ 5...a4  6.Kc7  +- and if @@StartFEN@@1K6/1P4p1/7k/p3n2p/8/8/8/8 b - - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nd7+  6.Kc8!  +- }
6. Kc7 Nb4 7. Kb6 { White wins. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 3 – Knight Endgames"]
[Black "Botvinnik's Formula"]
[Result "*"]

{ Botvinnik's Formula    'Knight endgames are pawn endgames' : that is something Botvinnik once said. What he had in mind, is that many of the laws of pawn endings apply equally to knight endings. The same high value is given, for instance, to the active position of the king or the outside passed pawn.  Such techniques as the pawn breakthrough, shouldering, the various methods of playing for zugzwang, and so forth, are seen constantly, not just in pawn endgames, but also in knight endgames. And we shall be convinced of this after studying a few practical examples. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 3 – Knight Endgames"]
[Black "Botvinnik's Formula 3-7"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/1p6/6n1/p3k1Np/4P3/P3K3/1P6/8 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Lasker − Nimzovitch, Zürich 1934  Let's begin with a classic endgame.   In the diagram, the pawn endgame would be an easy win for Black with the outside passed pawn. In the knight ending, Black has considerably more problems to solve. The canonical text is that Black played flawlessly to win a better ending, but Karsten Müller put this ending under the microscope in 2019 and found some amazing resources for both sides. We present his analysis here. }
1... Kf6
{ Always watch out for knight checks. The overhasty  1...h4?!  would allow the white knight to attack the queenside pawns by  2.Nf7+  Kf6  3.Nd6  b6  4.Nc4  h3  5.Kf2! }
2. Nh7+ Kg7 3. Ng5 Kf6 4. Nh7+ Ke7
{ The king retreats, but only briefly; now the e5-square will be occupied by the knight. On  5.Kd4  ,  Black forces a won pawn endgame with  5...Nf8!  6.Ng5  Ne6+! }
5. Ng5 Ne5 6. Kd4 Kd6 7. Nh3
{ A careless move which allows Black to fix White's queenside pawns. The prophylactic  7.b3=  was called for; now White is losing, although it is very complicated. }
7... a4 8. Nf4 h4 9. Nh3
{ Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 3-8 } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 3 – Knight Endgames"]
[Black "Botvinnik's Formula 3-8"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/1p6/3k4/4n3/p2KP2p/P6N/1P6/8 b - - 0 9"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Lasker − Nimzovitch, Zürich 1934  (continued) } 9... b6
{ Nimzovitch’s only error in this ending, violating the “Steinitz rule” that says that pawns are best placed on the second rank. It turns out that Black needs all the tempi he can keep in reserve.   The win is very deep as Black must lose a tempo by triangulation with the king:  9...Nc6+  10.Kd3  Kc5  11.Kc3  Nd4  12.Ng1  Ne6  (from this important square, the knight threatens to go to g5 and so White must move back to h3)  13.Nh3  Kb5  14.Kd3  Kb6!  15.Kd2  (trying to be stubborn, but the king will run out of squares)  15...Kc6  16.Kc2  Nc5!  17.Nf2  Kb5  (the king wants to go to d3 now to maintain the correspondence of squares, but the knight stops that)  18.Kc3  Ne6  19.Nh3  Kc5!  (finally achieving the desired zugzwang)  20.Kd3  Nd8!  21.Kc3  Nf7  22.Kd3  Ne5+  23.Kc3  Nf3  24.Kd3  b6!  (only now can the pawn advance, and only very carefully!)  25.Kc3  b5  26.Kd3  b4  -+ and Black wins similar to the game. }
10. Nf4 b5 11. Nh3
{ Not yet a losing move, but it makes the task very hard.   After  11.Kc3!  Kc5  12.Ne6+  Kb6  13.Ng5!=  Black will not be able to make progress.  12.b3  also draws. }
11... Nc6+ 12. Ke3
{ The decisive error, allowing Black to apply another technique borrowed from the arsenal of pawn endgames: widening the beachhead.  Ed. note: analyzed in the next variation → Diagram 3-8a }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 3 – Knight Endgames"]
[Black "Botvinnik's Formula 3-8 a"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/8/2nk4/1p6/p2KP2p/P6N/1P6/8 w - - 0 12"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Lasker − Nimzovitch, Zürich 1934  (analysis)   Emanuel Lasker probably rejected 12.Kc3 because of the following moves. }
12. Kc3 Ke5 13. Kd3 Na5 { Let's look at what could happen. } 14. Ng1 Kf4 15. e5
Nc6 16. e6 Kf5
{ Diagram 3-8a   After  17.Kc3?  Kf6  -+ White is in zugzwang. If  18.Kd3  Kxe6  19.Nf3  Ne5+!  and in case of  18.b3  18...axb3  19.Kxb3  Nd4+  20.Kc3  Nxe6  21.Kb4  Nd4  22.Kc5  Ke5!  defending the knight and Black wins. }
17. Kd2 { This remarkable move changes everything. } 17... Kf6 18. Kc3
{ Now Black is in zugzwang. } 18... Ke7
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed.  18....Kxe6  19.Nf3  h3  20.Ng5  Kd5  21.Nxh3  =@@EndSquare@@ }
19. b3 axb3 20. Kxb3 Nd4+ 21. Kc3 Nxe6 22. Kb4 Nd4 23. Kc5
{ And the black king is too far away to help. Draw.  Ed. note: the game continuation is illustrated in the next variation → Diagram 3-8b }
