axb4+ Kxb4 15. Kc2 { Diagram 3-8b } 15... Nd4+
{ Nimzovitch displays good technique. The point of widening the beachhead is to clear the king’s path to the opposite wing, but the grandmaster is in no hurry to execute this plan. First, it is useful to reposition the knight on e6 from where it hobbles the enemy knight.   The direct  15...Kc4  wins as well, e.g.,  16.Ng5  Ne5  17.Nh3  Kd4  18.b3  axb3+  19.Kxb3  Kxe4  20.Kc2  Kf3  21.Kd1  Kg3  22.Ng1  Nf3  23.Ne2+  Kg4  -+ }
16. Kb1 Ne6 17. Ka2 Kc4 18. Ka3 Kd4 19. Kxa4 Kxe4 20. b4 Kf3 21. b5 Kg2
{ White resigned. On  22.b6  there follows  22...Kxh3  23.Kb5  Nd8  , and if @@StartFEN@@8/8/1P2n3/8/K6p/7k/8/8 w - - 0 23@@EndFEN@@  23.b7  23...Nc5+  . Nimzovitch evidently calculated this variation when he played 15...Nd4+.   Diagrams 3-9 and 3-10 have been intentionally omitted. }
