{ Botvinnik − Kholmov, Moscow ch tt 1969  White's king is considerably more active than his opponent's, and that factor defines his great, and probably winning, advantage. Still, many subtleties remain. }
1. Ng5
{ It is important to induce Black's pawns to advance, as then they will be easier to attack. }
1... f6 2. Nh7
{ But this is a mistake which allows Black to draw with precise defense.   The correct method was found by Müller, 2019:  2.Ne6+!  Kd7  3.Nf4  h4  4.Nd5  , and either the pawn ending is winning for White or White dominates in the knight ending. }
2... f5 3. h4
{ If White played  3.f4?!  , then after  3...b6+  4.Kd4  Kd6  5.Nf8  Nc6+  6.Ke3  Ne7  , Black would hold easily, as the white king does not have the f4-square. }
3... f4
{ Waiting tactics would eventually result in zugzwang for Black, so he initiates a kingside counterattack. }
4. Nf8 b6+
{ It is not yet time for desperation with  4...f3?  , just not  5.gxf3?  b6+  6.Kd4  Nf5+=  , but  5.g3  Nf5  6.Nxg6  Nxg3  7.Kd4  and Black will lose, as shown by Müller, 2019. }
5. Kd4 Nf5+ 6. Ke4
{ 6.Kd5!?  must now be met with  6...f3!  (which does not work in other variations, but here the white king is too far)  7.g3  Nxg3  8.Nxg6  Nh1= }
6... Nxh4 { Not  6...f3?  7.g3  Nxg3+  8.Kxf3  Nf5  9.Nxg6  with an easy win. }
7. Ne6+ Kc6 8. Nxf4 Kb5
{ 8...g5?  loses to  9.g3!  gxf4  10.gxh4  .   8...a5!  draws, however:  9.g3  Nf5  10.Nxg6  Nd6+  11.Kd3  Kb5= }
9. g3 Nf5 10. Nxg6 Nh6
{ It is only here that Black commits the fatal mistake. As Müller discovered in 2019,  10...Nd6+  11.Kd5  Nc4  12.f4  Ne3+  13.Ke4  Nf1  gives Black enough counterplay to still hold the game.   Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 3-12 }
