{ R. Réti, 1929  The following is an example of zugzwang.   On  1.Kb8?  Kb5!  2.Nb4  Nc6+  3.Kb7  , Black forces the draw with  3...Na5+!  4.Kc7  Nc6  . In case of  1...Nc6+?  2.Kb7  Kc5  3.Nd4!  or  3.Nb4!  − a standard deflecting knight sacrifice.  Before moving his king to b8, White must lose a move so as to force the enemy king, through zugzwang, to occupy the a5-square. }
1. Ka7 Kb5
{ Black loses immediately with  1...Kc5  2.Nd4!  zugzwang  2...Kxd4  3.Kb6  +- − but not  2.Nb4?  Kb5  3.Kb8  Nc6+  with the drawing position we know already. }
2. Nb4 Ka5
{ The goal is achieved! Black's king stands badly here − it deprives the knight of this square, and also fails to control c6. }
3. Kb8 Nc6+ 4. Kb7 { 4.Kc7??  Nxb4  5.a7  Nd5+= } 4... Nd8+ 5. Kc7 Ne6+ 6. Kb8
{ Or  6.Kc6  +- } *

