{ Alburt − Lerner, Kiev 1978  (continued)   The queen ending is a win. White only has to get his queen to the d-file, where it will safeguard the king against checks and support the advance of his passed pawn. }
1. Qg5+ Kh3 { 9...Kf3  10.Qd5+  Kg3  11.Qd3+  Kh4  12.d7  +- } 2. Qd2 Qa1
{ 10...Qe4+  11.Qd3+  +-   10...b3+  11.Kc3  Qa1+  12.Kxb3  Qb1+  13.Ka4  +- }
3. d7 Qa4+ 4. Kb1 Qb3+ 5. Kc1 Qa3+ { 13...Qxc4+  14.Kb2  +- } 6. Kd1 Qb3+ 7.
Ke2 Kg4
{ The final trap: on  16.d8=Q??  Black has a perpetual:  16...Qf3+  17.Ke1  Qh1+  18.Kf2  Qh2+  19.Ke3  Qf4+  20.Kd3  Qf5+=  White replies with a typical trick for queen endgames: he utilizes the enemy king position to meet Black's check with a check of his own. }
8. Qd1 Qxc4+ 9. Ke3+ { Black resigned. } *

