{ 3/5. Timman − Ree, Amsterdam 1984 } 1. a4
{ 1.Nf5?!  suggests itself, but after  1...Ng2  , what should White do? If  2.g6?  Nf4  3.g7  Nh5+  4.Kf7  Nxg7  5.Kxg7  Kc4  , the knight cannot arrive in time to prevent an exchange of queenside pawns. The tempting knight sacrifice deflection @@StartFEN@@8/8/pp3K2/3k1NP1/1P6/P7/6n1/8 w - - 2 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Ne3+?  Nxe3  3.g6  is refuted by  3...Kd6!  4.g7  Nd5+  5.Kf7  Ne7  .  As Müller has discovered, White still wins after  2.Ne7+!  Kc4  3.Ke5  Nh4  4.Kf4  +- and if  2...Kd6  3.g6  Nf4  4.a4  Nxg6  5.Nxg6  a5  6.b5  Kc5  7.Ke5  Kb4  8.Kd4  Kxa4  9.Kc4  . But playing for zugzwang wins much more simply. }
1... b5 2. a5 Kc4 3. Nf5 Ng2 4. Ke5 { Black resigned. } *

