{ 3/6. V. Halberstadt, 1949  To achieve success, one must remember the triangulation technique. }
1. Kg5
{ 1.Kf5?  misses the win: after  1...Ka7!  ,  it is White who is in zugzwang.  2.Nd7  does not win here in view of  2...Nxd7  3.e6  Nb6!  4.e7  Nc8  , while @@StartFEN@@5n2/k7/8/2N1PK2/8/8/8/8 w - - 2 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Kf6  is met with  2...Kb6  . }
1... Ka7
{ If  1...Kb8  then  2.Kf6  Kc8  3.Kg7  Nd7  4.Nxd7  Kxd7  5.Kf7  +- and in case of @@StartFEN@@1k3n2/8/5K2/2N1P3/8/8/8/8 b - - 3 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Kc7  3.Ne6+  . }
2. Kf5 { The tempo is lost, and Black is in zugzwang. } 2... Kb6 3. Nd7+ Nxd7
4. e6 { White wins. } *

