{ 3/7. Cvetkovic-Stefanovic, Porec 1987  Thanks to the distant passed a-pawn, the white king is placed closer to the kingside than its counterpart. But how does it save the pawns from annihilation by the black knight ? This mission is far from simple. }
1. h3
{ 1.Nxh7?  Nxh2  ∆  2.--  Nf1=   1.Kd4?  Nxh2  2.Ke3  Ng4+  3.Kf3  Nf6=   1.h4?  Nxg3  2.Kd4  Ne2+  3.Ke5  Ng1  ∆ 4...Nf3+=  and if  3.Ke3  Nc3  4.Nxh7  Nd5+  5.Kf3  Kxa4  6.Nf8  Ne7  and White cannot activate his king in time:  7.Ke2  Kb4  8.Kd3  Kc5  .  In case of @@StartFEN@@5N2/4n3/6p1/5p2/k4P1P/5K2/8/8 w - - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Ke3  Nd5+  8.Ke2!?  Nxf4+  9.Kf3  Nh5  10.Nxg6  Kb5  11.Ne7  Kc5  12.Nxf5  Kd5  13.Kg4  Ke5=  The last line can be improved if White takes a single step with his h-pawn instead of a double. In that case, the king gets an additional route, via h4. }
1... Nxg3 2. Kd4 { 2.Kd5?  Ne2  3.Ke5  Ng1= } 2... Ne2+
{ If  2...Kxa4  then  3.Nxh7  ∆ 4. Nf8+-  . After @@StartFEN@@5N2/7p/6p1/k4p2/P2K1P2/6nP/8/8 b - - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nh5  3.Ke5  decides, rather than  3.Ke3?  Nf6  . }
3. Ke3 Nc3 4. Nxh7 Nd5+ 5. Kf3 Kxa4 6. Nf8
{ Diagram 16-38   6...Ne7  is hopeless now:  7.Kg3!  Kb4  8.Kh4  Kc4  9.Kg5  Kd5  10.Nxg6  . }
6... Kb5 { This is how the game continued. } 7. Nxg6 Kc5 8. Kg3
{ The king must be activated. } 8... Kd6 9. Kh4 Ke6 10. Kg5 Nc3 11. Nf8+ Kf7
12. Nd7 Ne4+ 13. Kxf5 { And White had two extra pawns. } *

