[Black "Pawns on the Same Side"]
[Result "*"]

{ Pawns on the Same Side   Is it possible to convert an extra pawn, if all the pawns are on the same side? Practice in such positions has shown, that with the exception of pawn endgames, a player's chances of success are greatest in knight endgames. The “four vs. three” knight endgame was considered a win for a long time, going back to analysis by Reuben Fine in 1941.  Taking into account today's state of the art in endgame theory and practice, we revise this evaluation to “good winning chances.” There are many drawn positions, and many positions which for the moment defy a clear verdict. In this section, we show both the theory and practical examples and illustrate some ideas for both sides. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 3 – Knight Endgames"]
[Black "Pawns on the Same Side 3-21"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/5pkp/3n2p1/8/3NP3/5P2/4K1PP/8 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ R. Fine, 1941  Let's start with Fine's position, which has been reprinted in many endgame manuals. }
1... Kf6
{ Reuben Fine's analysis focused on forcing lines where Black tries to trade pawns and achieve a draw quickly. We shall also see what can happen if Black tries a passive defense. }
2. g3 Ke5
{ The move  2...h5  should be mentioned. The f7-g6-h5 pawn configuration is often recommended in rook endings, as White may have to trade some pawns to make progress. But in a knight ending, this can also create weaknesses in Black's camp:   3.Nb3  Ke5  4.Kd3  Nc8  5.f4+  Ke6  6.Nd4+  Kd6  7.Nf3  f6  8.Kd4  Ke6  9.Nh4  Kf7  @@StartBracket@@as the black king has to attend to its pawn on  g6  , the white king can go around@@EndBracket@@  10.Kc5  Ne7  11.Kd6  g5  12.fxg5  fxg5  13.Nf3  +- or @@StartFEN@@2n5/5p2/3k2p1/7p/4PP2/3K1NP1/7P/8 b - - 4 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nb6  8.e5+  Ke6  9.Ke4  f6  10.Nh4  Kf7  11.Kd4  Na4  12.Kd5  , which will win. }
3. Nc6+ Ke6 4. Ke3 Kd7
{ Trying to avoid weakening anything for now. Immediately forcing the action is fraught with danger for Black.  Ed. note: analyzed in the next variation → Diagram 3-21a }
*

