[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 3 – Knight Endgames"]
[Black "Pawns on the Same Side 3-21 a"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/5p1p/2Nnk1p1/8/4P3/4KPP1/7P/8 b - - 0 4"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ R. Fine, 1941  (analysis) } 4... f5
{ Fine's main line, but now after White's move all king retreats lose.   Instead of  4...f5  , insufficient is  4...g5  5.Nd4+  Kf6  6.f4  gxf4+  7.gxf4  Nc4+  8.Kd3  Nb2+  9.Kc2  Nc4  10.e5+  Ke7  11.Kd3  +-, and Black will have trouble with his weak h-pawn. }
5. Nd4+ { Diagram 3-21a } 5... Kf6
{ a.  5...Ke7  6.e5  Nc4+  7.Kf4  h6  8.g4  fxg4  9.fxg4  is similar to positions we shall look at later in our main line, but Black's pawn is already on  h6  where it is placed worse than on  h7  , as we shall see. Now if  9...Nb2  ,  10.g5!  hxg5+  11.Kxg5  Nd3  12.e6  +-   b.  5...Kf7  6.Kf4  fxe4  7.fxe4  Nc4  8.Nf3  Kg7  9.e5  +- and if @@StartFEN@@8/5k1p/3n2p1/8/3NPK2/6P1/7P/8 b - - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...g5+  8.Ke5  Nc4+  9.Kd5  Ne3+  10.Kd6  Nc4+  11.Kc5  Ne3  12.e5  Ke7  13.Nf3!  g4  14.Nd2  +- }
6. exf5 gxf5 7. Kf4 { Black is in zugzwang and must give way. } 7... Kg6 8. Ke5
Nf7+ 9. Ke6 Nd8+ 10. Ke7 Nb7
{ Ed. note: analyzed in the next variation → Diagram 3-21b } *

