{ R. Fine, 1941  (continued from Diagram 3-21) } 5. Nd4 f6
{ We are still following in Fine’s footsteps, but here is an important point of uncertainty.   Karsten Müller suggested  5...Nc4+!?  with the idea of holding back the f7-f6 advance for now, which allows White in some variations to advantageously create a passed e-pawn. While it is hard to say for sure if it will make a difference, 5...Nc4+ may offer additional defensive resources. }
6. Kd3 Nf7 7. f4 Ke7 8. Nf3
{ The white knight needs to keep an eye on the g5- and e5-squares. The immediate  8.g4?!  is countered by  8...g5!  and if  9.fxg5?  Ne5+= }
8... Nd6 9. g4
{ White strengthens his position by advancing his kingside pawns. } 9... Kd7
10. h4 Ke7
{ Diagram 3-21c  This position, which can be arrived at by different move orders, became the starting point for grandmaster Alex Fishbein's research in 2019. We believe that White wins in all lines. Here is his analysis: }
11. e5 Nc8
{ Black is trying to keep the tension in the hope that White will be forced to either trade on f6, remaining without a passed pawn, or push it through to e6, where, surprisingly, it will tie down his own pieces.  Ed. note: analyzed in the next variation → Diagram 3-21d }
*

