{ R. Fine, 1941  (analysis)     The main line starts with  11...Nc8  but other options are not better. }
11... fxe5
{ This direct attempt loses, although it is by no means easy.   11...Nb5  12.Nd4  Nc7  13.Kc4  Na6  14.Kb5  Nc7+  15.Kc6  Na6  16.Kb6  forces Black to trade on e5, which will transpose to the previous line, as  16...Nb4?  loses immediately to  17.Nc6+!  Nxc6  18.exf6+  intermediate check!  18...Kxf6  19.Kxc6  +-   11...Nb7  12.Kc4!  @@StartBracket@@the d4-square needs to be saved for the knight@@EndBracket@@  12...fxe5  13.fxe5  Ke6  14.Kd4  h6  15.h5!  +- and if @@StartFEN@@8/1n2k2p/5pp1/4P3/2K2PPP/5N2/8/8 b - - 2 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Nd8  13.Nd4  Nb7  14.Kd5  fxe5  15.Nc6+  Kd7  16.fxe5  +-  actually trapping the knight. }
12. fxe5 Nb5 13. Nd4 Nc7 14. Ke4 Na6 15. Nf3
{ 15.h5?  is premature and leads to a draw after  15...Nc5+  16.Kd5  Nd3= }
15... Nc5+ 16. Kd5 Nd3 17. Nd4
{ Diagram 3-21d  The first step is to push away the black knight to some distant squares on the queenside, and in some lines even threaten to trap it. White can only later convert into a simpler ending with h4-h5. }
17... Nb4+ 18. Kc4 Na6 19. Ne2 { 19.h5?  Nc7  is still a draw. } 19... Ke6 20.
Kd4 Nc7 21. Nf4+ Kd7 22. Kc5
{ 22.h5  also wins, but after  22...gxh5  White must take with the knight. }
22... Na6+ 23. Kc4 Ke7 24. Nd5+ Ke6 25. Kd4 Nb8 26. Nf4+ Ke7 27. Ke4 Na6 28. h5
gxh5 29. gxh5 Nc5+ 30. Kf5
{ Reaching the key zugzwang position which we shall see in the main line.   Ed. note: the main line is presented next → Diagram 3-21e & 3-21f }
