[White "Chapter 3 – Knight Endgames"]
[Black "Pawns on the Same Side 3-21 g & h"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/4k2p/6p1/2n1P3/5NPP/4K3/8/8 w - - 0 20"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ R. Fine, 1941  (continued)   Knight + e-, g-, and h-pawns vs. knight +g- and h-pawns positions are often drawn, as we shall see later in this section. Here, however, White's knight occupies a good square on f4, keeping the black king from attacking the e-pawn, and also keeping an eye on g6 and h5. Still, a win for White is very tricky. }
20. Kd4
{ 20.h5?  leads to a drawn position after  20...gxh5  21.Nxh5  Ke6  22.Kd4  Nb3+=  and if  21.gxh5  Kf7!  22.Kd4  Na4  23.Ke4  Ke7!  24.Kf5  Nc5  @@StartBracket@@Diagram 3-21h@@EndBracket@@. We have here a position of mutual zugzwang. With Black to move, he would have to allow e6 with check and it is an easy win.  But with White to move, he cannot win!  25.e6  Kd6!  and now in order to make progress, White has to push the h-pawn, but then it is a stalemate fortress in the corner.  26.Kf6  Ne4+  is just a perpetual.  So  26.h6  Ke7  27.Nd5+  Kf8  28.Kf6  Nxe6  29.Kxe6  Kg8= }
20... Nb3+ 21. Kd3
{ 21.Kd5?  does not win because of  21...Nd2  22.h5  gxh5  23.gxh5  Nf1= }
21... Nc5+ 22. Ke3
{ Having triangulated, White is preparing that zugzwang position for the opponent. }
22... Nb3
{ A tougher defense.   22...Kd7  23.h5  gxh5  24.gxh5  Ke7  25.Kd4  Na4  26.Ke4  Nc5+  27.Kf5  Zugzwang for Black.  27...Kf7  28.e6+  Ke7  29.Ke5  +-  and now the win is easy. }
23. h5
{ The black knight is far away, and White can convert into the N+2P vs N+1P ending. }
23... gxh5 24. gxh5 Kf7
{ 24...Nc5  25.Kd4  Nb3+  26.Ke4  Nc5+  27.Kf5  +-  Zugzwang again. } 25. Ke4
Ke7 { 25...Nc5+  26.Kd5  And 27.e6+ wins. } 26. Kd5
{ Only not  26.Kf5??  Nc5  and it is White who is in zugzwang. } 26... Nd2
{ Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 3-21i & 3-21j } *

