{ Grischuk – Moiseenko, Russia  (ch)  Sochi, 2006  As we mentioned, the position with the e-pawn blocked on e4 and the pawns on g3-h4/g6-h5 is drawn. It is because of the abundance of such drawn positions that we can no longer state that the knight four vs. three ending is winning in general. }
1. Nf3 Nd3+
{ Also good is  1...Ng4  2.e5+  Ke6  3.Kg5  Kf7  4.e6+  Kg7!  5.e7  Nf6  6.Ne5  Nh7+  7.Kf4  Nf6  8.Kf3  Ne8  , and if @@StartFEN@@8/8/5kp1/7p/4PKnP/5NP1/8/8 w - - 2 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nd2  Ne5  3.Ke3  Ng4+  4.Kd4  g5  5.Nc4  gxh4  6.gxh4  Nh2  7.e5+  Ke6  8.Ke4  Ng4  , etc. }
2. Ke3 Nb4 3. Kd4 Ke6
{ An instructive mistake: the knight needs to harass the white king with  3...Nc2+!  4.Kd3  Nb4+  5.Kc4  Nc2  6.Kd5  Ne3+  7.Kd6  Nc4+  8.Kc5  Ne3  or  8...Ne5  . }
4. Ng5+ Kd6 5. e5+
{ Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 3-25b } *

