{ Grischuk – Moiseenko, Russia  (ch)  Sochi, 2006  (continued)   Whereas the position with the pawn stuck on e4 was drawn, the position with the pawn on e5 can be winning, especially if the knight can reach the key f4-square. }
5... Ke7 6. Nh3 Ke6
{ 6...Kf7  7.Nf4  Nc6+  8.Kd5  Ne7+  9.Kd6  is hopeless, so Black tries to counterattack. }
7. Nf4+ Kf5 8. e6 Nc6+ { 8...Kf6  9.Nd5+  +- } 9. Kc5 Ne7 10. Kd6 Ng8 11. e7
{ Alexander Grischuk finishes in fine style. } 11... Nxe7 12. Kxe7 g5 13. Ng2
Kg4 14. Kf6 gxh4 15. gxh4 Kg3 16. Kg5 Kxg2 17. Kxh5 Kg3 18. Kg5
{ Black resigned. } *

