[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 4 – Bishop versus Pawns"]
[Black "Bishop and Rook Pawn 4-1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "5k2/8/6BP/8/8/8/2K5/8 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Bishop and Rook Pawn   If the bishop does not control the rook pawn’s queening square, then the weaker side has only to get his king into the corner @@StartBracket@@we call that the “safe” corner@@EndBracket@@. }
1... Kg8 { With an obvious draw. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 4 – Bishop versus Pawns"]
[Black "Bishop and Rook Pawn 4-1 EXTRA 1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "5k2/8/6BP/8/8/8/2K5/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Let's learn the techniques of cutting the king off from the safe corner. Let's suppose that it is White's move instead.   If the bishop were on  f5  , he would win after @@StartFEN@@5k2/8/7P/5B2/8/8/2K5/8 w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Be6!  With Black's king on f6, a different standard cutoff maneuver − 1.Bh5@@StartBracket@@e8@@EndBracket@@! − works instead.  But in the diagrammed position, there is only one way to play for the win. }
1. Bh7 Kf7 2. Kd3 Kf6 { ∆  3.--  Kg5  . } 3. Bf5 Kf7 { ∆  4.--  Kg8  . } 4. Bh7
{ 4.Be6+  Kg6= } 4... Kf6 { Draw. } *

