[White "Chapter 4 – Bishop versus Pawns"]
[Black "Bishop and Rook Pawn 4-2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2k5/8/2K5/8/pB6/P7/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Now let's look at a position with paired rook pawns @@StartBracket@@with the king cut off from the corner@@EndBracket@@. The famous theoretician Vsevolod Rauzer did considerable analysis on this situation.  V. Rauzer, 1928  White cuts off and then drives the king away from the corner, yet he still cannot win. Rauzer found a key drawing zone for this ending: a7-d4-e5-f4-h6. If the black king finds itself outside the zone and cannot get back in, the game is lost. If the king is being chased by the white king but stays inside the zone, the game is often drawn, but if the king is on the border @@StartBracket@@for example, on d4@@EndBracket@@, then the situation can be more complicated. If you are defending this position, try to stay inside the border.  Let’s see how this works in practice: }
1. Bd6 Kd8 2. Kb7 Kd7 3. Bc7 Ke6 4. Kc6 Ke7 5. Bb6 Ke6 6. Bc5 Ke5 7. Bf8 Ke6
{ Staying well inside the drawing zone.  Ed. note: analyzed in the next variation → Diagram 4-2a }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 4 – Bishop versus Pawns"]
[Black "Bishop and Rook Pawn 4-2 a"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "5B2/8/2K5/4k3/p7/P7/8/8 b - - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ V. Rauzer, 1928  (analysis) } 7... Kd4
{ By contrast to  7...Ke6!  ,  7...Kd4?  is an instructive mistake. Now we have a border case. }
8. Bd6
{ The precise winning move, forcing the king to immediately abandon the drawing zone.   Averbakh only examined  8.Bg7+  , allowing Black to gain the half-point with  8...Ke4!  9.Kd6  Kf5  back in the zone, and the white king is close, so this should be a draw!  10.Be5  Kg6  draws as we shall see in the main line, but not the “active”  10...Ke4?  11.Ke6  Kf3  12.Kf5  Ke3  13.Bb2  and with his wayward king, Black loses, although the win is still quite complicated.  After  8...Kc4?  9.Bb2  Kb3  10.Kb5!  is the quickest win. }
8... Ke4 { 8...Kc4  9.Bc5  Kd3  10.Kb5  +- } 9. Kb5 Kd5 10. Bh2 Ke6 11. Kxa4
Kd7 12. Kb5 Kc8 13. Kb6
{ From this variation we can see how vital the h2-b8 diagonal is to the bishop. However, the only way the bishop can occupy it is if the black king gets too frisky. Usually when the black king is in the drawing zone, the bishop cannot occupy the h2-b8 diagonal because then the king can come nearer the safe a8-corner. So the inner part near the a8-corner of the drawing zone is safer than the outer part.  Ed. note: the drawing line is presented in the next variation → Diagram 4-2a EXTRA. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 4 – Bishop versus Pawns"]
[Black "Bishop and Rook Pawn 4-2 a EXTRA"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "5B2/8/2K1k3/8/p7/P7/8/8 w - - 0 8"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ V. Rauzer, 1928  (continued) } 8. Bd6 Kf7 9. Kd7 Kf6 10. Bh2 Kf7
{ 10...Kf5  11.Ke7  Kg5  12.Ke6  Kg6  is also possible. But again, not outside the zone with  11...Ke4?  12.Ke6! }
11. Be5 Kg6
{ 11...Kg8?  is stepping too far away:  12.Kc6  Kf7  13.Kb5  Ke6  14.Kxa4!  +-;  11...Kf8  is fine, however. }
12. Ke6
{ 12.Kc6  Kf5!  An important theme, attacking the bishop on that critical diagonal; we shall see this theme again. }
12... Kg5 13. Bb2 Kg6 14. Bf6 Kh6 15. Kf5 Kh7
{ But not  15...Kh5?  which steps outside the zone. White then wins with  16.Bg7  , although the win is very complicated. }
16. Ke6 Kh6 17. Kf7 Kh7 18. Be5 Kh6 19. Bg7+ Kh7 20. Kf8 Kg6 21. Kg8 Kf5 22.
Kf7 Kg5 23. Bf8 Kf5 24. Be7
{ White has managed to drive the king closer to the center; but now he has to keep it from returning to a8. As a result, Black can stay well within the drawing zone. }
24... Ke5 25. Ke8 Ke6 26. Bf8 Kf6 27. Bb4 Kg7 { etc. } *

