[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 4 – Bishop versus Pawns"]
[Black "Bishop and Rook Pawn 4-2 b & c"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/2K5/3B4/2k5/p7/P7/8/8 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ After Rauzer, 2019  The zone is a7-b6-c5-d4-e5-f4-g5-h6. And a8, etc., are inside the zone. Where should the king go? There are four moves, but only one draws. It is the one that stays well inside our zone. }
1... Kd5
{ 1...Kb5?  is tempting because it seems close to the corner which is where we need to get, but it is outside the Rauzer zone and loses:  2.Kb7  Ka5  3.Bc5  Kb5  4.Bb4  Kc4  5.Kc6  Kd4  6.Bd6!  , reaching the winning position we saw in the previous example. }
2. Kd7 Ke4
{ 2...Kd4?  only temporarily gets in the zone:  3.Kc6!  wins, as previously seen. }
3. Kc6
{ 3.Ke6  Kd4  , with the white king on  e6  , the d4-square @@StartBracket@@still in the zone@@EndBracket@@ is not as dangerous.  4.Bb4  Kc4  5.Kd6  Kd4!  6.Ke6  Kc4=  and if  6.Kc6  Ke5=  Just not  6...Kc4?  7.Bc5  +-  Note that  5...Kb5?  loses again:  6.Kc7  Ka6  7.Bc5  Kb5  8.Be3  Ka6  9.Kc6  Ka5  10.Kb7  Kb5  11.Bb6  Kc4  12.Kc6  Kb3  13.Bc5  Kc4  14.Bd6  +- as previously noted. }
3... Kf5 { We cross the frontier.  3...Kd4?  4.Kb5  Kd5  5.Bh2  +- ⨀ } 4. Kb5
Ke6
{ Diagram 4-2c  The only way to draw, but a theme we have seen. The bishop needed to be on the h2-b8 diagonal, but to keep some key squares away from the black king, it had to be on a square where it gets attacked at the critical moment. The position is drawn. }
5. Bh2 Kd7 6. Kxa4 Kc8 7. Kb5 Kb7
{ And Black has arrived in time.  I might add  (without giving the full proof, which is pretty weighty)  that if, in Rauzer’s starting position, we move the pawn on a3 back to a2, the evaluation changes.   White will try to stalemate the enemy king  (while still keeping him away from the corner, of course)  , in order to force the move a4-a3, after which the bishop can pick off the pawn. If Black tries to avoid this scenario, then he must move his king into the center, which will allow White, by playing a2-a3 at the right moment, to obtain the “bad” black king situation we have already seen.  Diagrams 4-3 and 4-4 have been intentionally omitted. }
*

