[SetUp "1"]

{ Now for one more variation @@StartBracket@@analyzed by Horwitz and Averbakh@@EndBracket@@ on Rauzer's position @@StartBracket@@seeDiagram 4-2@@EndBracket@@. Let's add a black pawn at b5.   The king's arrival in that upper left-hand corner is mortally dangerous. It will be stalemated, and be forced to play  ...b5-b4  , when the a3-pawn goes to the b-file. White to move wins quickly by @@StartFEN@@2k5/8/2K5/1p6/pB6/P7/8/8 w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Ba5  Kb8  2.Bb6  Kc8  3.Bc7  ⨀ and if  2...Ka8  3.Kc7  ⨀  b4  4.axb4  +-.  But Black to move renders the position drawn, since White can no longer stalemate the king. The move ...b5-b4 is no longer even fatal; in fact, at the right moment it will be Blacks salvation. }
1... Kd8 2. Kd6 Ke8 3. Ke6 Kd8 4. Bd6 { 4.Ba5+  Ke8!= } 4... Kc8
{ 4...Ke8?  5.Be7  ⨀ } 5. Be5
{ 5.Ke7  Kb7  6.Kd7  b4!  7.axb4  Kb6=  But not  7...a3?  8.Bc5!  a2  9.Bd4  +- }
5... Kd8
{ Black loses after  5...Kb7?  6.Kd6  b4  7.axb4  Kb6  8.Bb2!  Kb5  9.Ba3  Kc4  10.Kc6  Kb3  11.b5  , and after  6...Kb6  7.Bd4+  Kb7  8.Kd7  .  The position is lost also after  6...Kc8  7.Bf6  Kb7  8.Bd8  Kc8  9.Bb6  Kb7  10.Kc5  Kc8  11.Kc6  Kb8  12.Ba5  Ka7  13.Bc7  or  13.Bb4  . In case of @@StartFEN@@1k6/8/2K5/Bp6/p7/P7/8/8 b - - 22 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Kc8  13.Bc7  +- or  12...Ka8  13.Kc7  Ka7  14.Bb6+  Ka6  15.Kc6  . }
6. Bf6+ Kc7 7. Be7 Kc6 8. Bd6 b4
{ White can drive the enemy king to the kingside and try to stalemate it there. In order to avoid stalemate, the king will have to retreat to the lower half of the board; but that is less dangerous now than it was without the b5-pawn, in view of ...b5-b4! at the right moment, which now becomes a resource for Black. }
