{ 4/5. H. Weenink, 1922 } 1. Bb1
{ A brilliant move!   Black hoped to build an elementary fortress, e.g.  1.Bh7?  Kc3  2.Kb5  Kd4  3.Kc6  Ke5  4.g6  Ke6  5.Bg8+  Ke7=  and if  4.Kd7  g6!=   White can get the missing tempo by means of a bishop sacrifice followed by shouldering in the arising pawn endgame, but the straightforward attempt  1.Kb4?  Kxc2  2.Kc4  does not win:  2...Kd2  3.Kd4  Ke2  4.Ke4  Kf2  5.Kf4  Kg2  6.Kg4  g6  7.Kf4  Kh3=  , or  5.Kf5  Kg3  6.Kg6  Kg4=  . }
1... Kxb1
{ Also loses.   After  1...Kc3  the bishop is better placed on b1 than on h7:  2.Kb5  Kd4  3.Kc6  Ke5  4.Kd7  Kf4  5.g6  +- or  4...g6  5.Ke7  and the black king cannot step to f5. }
2. Kb3 Kc1 3. Kc3 Kd1 { 3...Kb1  4.g6  +- } 4. Kd3 Ke1 5. Ke3 Kf1 6. Kf3
{ White wins. } *

