{ 4/6. E. Somov-Nasimovich, 1935  The rook must go back from g8, but where? Only deep, precise calculation can tell. }
1. Rh8
{ If  1.Rf8+?  then  1...Bf5  2.g8=Q  h1=Q+  3.Ka2  Qd5+!  4.Qxd5  cxd5  The d-pawn can be stopped by means of  5.Kb1  d2+  6.Rxf5+  Kxf5  7.Kc2  but the pawn ending turns out to be losing:  7...Ke5  8.Kxd2  Kd4  and if  9.b3  then  9...a3  -+ rather than  9...axb3?  10.b5=  . }
1... d2 2. g8=Q d1=Q+ 3. Ka2 Qb3+ 4. Qxb3 axb3+ { Diagram 16-40 } 5. Ka3
{ In case of  5.Kxb3?  Kg3  6.Rxh2  (Forced - otherwise 6... Bh3-+)  6...Kxh2  7.Kc4  Kg3?  8.Kc5  Bd7  9.Kd6  Be8  10.Ke7  Bh5  11.Kd6  Bf3  12.Kc5  and 13.b5=, so  7...Ba6+!  8.Kc5  Bb5  White is lost.   5.Ka1?  Kg3  6.Rxh2  Kxh2  7.b5  c5 !  is also useless. }
5... Kg3 { ∆ 6...Bh3 } 6. Rxh2 Kxh2 7. b5 cxb5
{ 7...c5  makes no sense in view of  8.Kxb3=  . Now the drawing pawn structure has been built, and all that remains to do is a king retreat homewards. }
8. Kb4 Kg3 9. Kc3 Kf2 10. Kd2 { Draw. } *

