{ 4/8. P. Kiriakov, 1997 } 1. c4
{ Otherwise @@StartFEN@@8/8/3k4/1p6/8/2P1P3/2P1K3/1b6 b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Ba2  -+ }
1... b4 { 1...bxc4?  2.Kd2= } 2. Kd1
{ White must 'lose' a tempo. After  2.Kd2?  Kc5  he is put in zugzwang.  3.Kc1  Ba2  4.c3  bxc3  is hopeless, while @@StartFEN@@8/8/8/2k5/1pP5/4P3/2PK4/1b6 w - - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e4  loses to  3...Kd4!  rather than  3...Ba2?  4.c3! }
2... Kc5 3. Kd2
{ Now it is Black who is in zugzwang and it may seem that the fight is over:  3...Kxc4  4.Kc1  or @@StartFEN@@8/8/8/2k5/1pP5/4P3/2P5/1b1K4 w - - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Ba2  4.c3!  b3  5.Kc1=  However Black still has resources. }
3... Kxc4 4. Kc1 Ba2 { Diagram 16-41 } 5. Kd2
{ The 'obvious'  5.Kb2?  is met with  5...Bb3!!  6.cxb3+  Kd3  with a winning pawn endgame. Now, however, Black cannot avoid the Ponziani position. }
5... Kb5 6. c3 b3 7. Kc1 { Draw. } *

