[SetUp "1"]

1. c5 Bxc5 2. Bb3 e5 3. Be6 Kc7 4. Ke4
{ The draw is obvious White need only run his bishop up and down the h3-c8 diagonal.  Thus, White was able to save himself − three  (!)  pawns down  @@StartBracket@@drawing tendency@@EndBracket@@. The final position is a fortress, in which the weaker side's only pawn is properly placed on the same color square as its own bishop. The bishop defends its pawn at h3 and holds the enemy pawns at g5 and f6 on the same diagonal. White sacrificed a pawn, so that by attacking the enemys sole, well-placed pawn at e6, he could force it to advance to a dark square, after which the pawns could be easily blockaded.   Analyzing almost any endgame in this chapter, you will see some or all of our just-formulated rules in action. }
*

