[SetUp "1"]

{ Bishop and Two Connected Pawns vs. Bishop   Careful analysis of the following basic theoretical position will familiarize us with the characteristic ideas of such endgames.   White threatens to continue e5-e6, followed by Ke5 and f5-f6. To stop this plan, Black must take the e6-square under control with his bishop. But from d7 or from b3? Let's examine both choices.   On  1...Bb3?  the position is lost. First, White gives a  probing check,   to see which way the enemy king goes.  It is important to have the bishop prevent it from getting between the pawns after e5-e6.  Therefore,  2.Bg5+!  Then,  the white king goes to help the e-pawn from the side opposite the one the enemy king went to . For example:  2...Kd7  3.Kf4  Ba2  4.Bh4  Bf7  5.Kg5  Ke7  6.Kh6+  Kd7  7.Kg7  Bc4  8.Kf6  and 9.e6+, winning.   Or  1...Bb3?  2.Bg5+!  Kf7  3.Kd4  Ba2  4.Kc5  Bb1  5.e6+  and 6.f6  ; if  4...Bb3  5.Kd6  and 6.e6+.   Note that the bishop check from the other side is ineffective: @@StartFEN@@8/4k3/8/4PP2/4K3/1b6/3B4/8 w - - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Bb4+  Kf7!  3.Kd4?  Bc2!  4.e6+  Kf6  5.e7  Ba4  and draws.  As soon as the pawns are blocked on the same color squares as their bishop, the draw becomes obvious.   So with his bishop on b3, Black loses. But he gets an easy draw after the text move. }
1... Bd7 2. Bg5+ Kf7
{ Now Black merely waits, shuttling the bishop back and forth between c8 and d7. In order to prepare e5-e6, White needs to maneuver his king to d5 or d6. But this is impossible, as long as the king is tied to the defense of the f5-pawn. Which suggests a rule:  The bishop must be placed where it prevents the advance of one of the pawns while simultaneously attacking the other. }
*

