{ Tragicomedies: Walther – Fischer, Zürich 1959  Black dreams of giving up his bishop for the queenside pawns. Then his king would go to h8, and even if it cannot, we haveRauzer’s drawing position @@StartBracket@@Diagram 4-2@@EndBracket@@. White’s goal is to put his king at a6 and his pawn at b5. This situation  (“autopilot”)  is known to us from the section on bishop vs. connected passed pawns from Chapter 4. }
1... Kd7
{ Black had to employ the “pawns in the crosshairs” technique:  1...Bf4!  2.b4  Bd2  3.a3  Bc1!  4.a4  Bd2!  5.Kc5  Kd7  @@StartBracket@@pointed out by Solomon@@EndBracket@@.  6.b5  Be3+  7.Kc4  Kd6  8.a5  Bd2  9.a6  Be3=  .  After  6.a5  Kc7  7.Kb5  Be1  8.Ka4  Bd2  9.b5  , Black defends himself similarly todiagram 5-5:  9...Kd6!  10.b6  Kc5=  . }
2. a4
{ White errs in return. The winning line was  2.b4!  Kc7  3.Ka5!  Bg3  4.b5  Bf2  5.Ka6  ∆ a4-a5, while after @@StartFEN@@8/2k5/3b4/K7/1P5p/5B1P/P7/8 b - - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Kb8  4.b5  @@StartBracket@@Black does not have time to prevent b5-b6@@EndBracket@@  4...Ba3!?  5.b6  Kc8  6.Ka6  Kb8  7.Be4  ⨀  Kc8  8.Ka7  Bc5  9.a4  +- @@StartBracket@@pointed out by the Swiss problemist Fontana@@EndBracket@@. And if  7...Bc5  8.a4  +-. }
2... Kc7
{ A simpler draw could probably have been obtained by  2...Bg3!?  3.b4  Be1  , and if @@StartFEN@@8/3k4/8/1K6/P6p/5BbP/1P6/8 w - - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Kb6  Bf2+!  4.Kb7  Be1  . }
3. b4 Kb8
{ By tucking his king at a7, Fischer gains control of a6, which prevents his opponent from going on autopilot. }
4. a5 Ka7 5. Kc4 Bg3 { 5...Bc7  . } 6. Kb3
{ If  6.b5  , then  6...Be1  7.b6+  Ka6= } 6... Be1 7. Ka4 Bd2 8. Bh5 Be1 9. b5
Bf2 10. Be2
{ On  10.b6+  Bxb6  11.axb6+  Kxb6  , the king goes to h8. Also useless is @@StartFEN@@8/k7/8/PP5B/K6p/7P/5b2/8 w - - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Bf3  Be3  11.Kb3  Bd2  . }
10... Be3 11. Kb3 Bd2
{ Black allows his opponent to advance the pawn to b6, so as to reach the defensive position ofDiagram 5-5. }
12. b6+ Kb7 13. Ka4 Kc6 14. Bb5+ Kc5 15. Be8 Be1 { Draw. } *

