{ 5/2. Schöneberg-Starck, DDR ch, Weimar 1968  Black's intentions are obvious: ...Ke5-f6 followed with ...e5-e4. This plan can be parried only by a king assault on d5 @@StartBracket@@similar toDiagram 5-5@@EndBracket@@. }
1. b6
{ But prior to the idea mentioned above, White should get rid of his own b5-pawn, which only snarls his plans @@StartBracket@@positional factors are more important than pawns!@@EndBracket@@.   In the game, however, White failed to tackle the problem he was faced with.  1.Kf3?  Now Black was winning with  1...Bb6!  , but went for  1...Ke5?  White could have saved the game with  2.b6!  again, but  2.Bd7?  was played instead.  2...Bb6!  -+  3.Ke2  Kf6  . @@StartBracket@@Diagram 16-46@@EndBracket@@  The pawn is stopped on  b5  where it blocks the important a6-f1 diagonal, so the king's march is not possible anymore:  4.Kd3  e5  5.Kc4  e4  6.Kd5  e3  -+. In case of  4.Kf3  e5  5.Bc6  Ke6  6.Bb7  e4+  This win of the bishop leads to a quick finish.   Black could also have won another way:  6...Kd6!?  followed by ...Kc5-d4, as in the theoretical positions we have studied.  7.Bxe4  fxe4+  8.Kxe4  Bf2  9.b6  Kd6  10.Kf5  Bh4  White resigned. @@StartFEN@@8/8/1b2k3/1P4p1/4K3/7P/8/8 b - - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Bc7  also leads to the goal:  9.b6  if now  9...Bxb6??  10.h4!=  , so  9...Bb8  10.h4  g4  , while after  10.Kf3  Kf5  11.Ke3  Kg6  -+. }
1... Bxb6
{ Attempting to save a tempo by ignoring the b6-pawn fails: if  1...Ke5!?  then the simplest is  2.Kf3  Kf6  3.Ke2  e5  4.Kd3  Bxb6  5.Kc4  . But  2.b7  Ba7  3.Kf3  Kf6  4.Ke2  e5  5.b8=Q!!  Bxb8  6.Kd3  e4+  7.Kd4  is also playable. }
2. Kf3 Ke5 3. Ke2 Kf6 4. Kd3 e5 5. Kc4 e4 6. Kd5 { Diagram 16-45 } 6... e3
{ On  6...Kg6  with the idea  7.--  e3  8.Ba6  Kh5  , both @@StartFEN@@2B5/8/1b4k1/3K1pp1/4p3/7P/8/8 w - - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Ke5  Bc7+  8.Kd4=  and  7.Kc4  f4  8.Kd5!  e3  9.Bg4=  are good. }
7. Ba6
{ The draw is obvious now, e.g.,  7...g4  8.hxg4  fxg4  , just not  9.Bf1??  g3  , but @@StartFEN@@8/8/Bb3k2/3K4/6p1/4p3/8/8 w - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Ke4  Kg5  10.Kd3!  Kh4  11.Ke2  Kg3  and now either  12.Bc8  or  12.Kf1  Kh2  13.Bb7  . And if  7...Kg6  8.Be2  .   Ed.note: analyzed in the next variation → Diagram 16-46 EXTRA. }
