{ Y. Averbakh, 1954  The ideas we have examined thus far will help you orient yourself in the most varied kinds of situations with disconnected pawns − even with a large number of pawns on the board. }
1... Kd7 2. Kc3 Ke6 3. Kd4 Be2 { 3...Bb7  4.Kc5  Kd7  is equivalent. } 4. Kc5
{ ∆ Kc6-c7+- } 4... Bf3
{ 4...Kd7?  would be a mistake: after  5.Kd5  Bf1  6.Ke5  Be2  , when the white king gets into the kingside. Now, White will get nothing out of  7.Kf6  Bd3  8.a6?  Bxa6  9.Kxg6  Ke8  − with the same drawing position as in the game Berger-Kotlerman @@StartBracket@@with opposite colors and reversed flanks@@EndBracket@@.   The correct idea is to play for zugzwang. From  d3  , the bishop defends the g6-pawn on one diagonal, while on the other, it restrains the advance of the a-pawn; ergo, it has no moves. White's king cannot be allowed to get to  e7  − that means that, in addition to d7, the black king has just two other squares:  e8  and  d8  . We can take away the first one by putting the king on f7; the second, by moving the bishop to  c7  . @@StartFEN@@8/3k4/3P2p1/P3K1P1/8/B7/4b3/8 w - - 11 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bc5  Bf1  8.Bb6  Be2  9.Bc7  Bd3  10.Kf6  Ke8  11.Kg7  ⨀  Kd7  12.Kf7  ⨀ +- }
5. a6 Kd7 6. Kb6 Kc8
{ The king maintains the zone: White threatened @@StartFEN@@8/3k4/PK1P2p1/6P1/8/B4b2/8/8 w - - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  7.Ka7  Kc8  8.d7+!  Kxd7  9.Kb8  +-. }
7. Ka7 { Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 5-14 EXTRA } *

