{ Topalov – Shirov, Linares 1998    “Normal” play would bring White the draw without too much trouble, for instance:  1...Kd6?  2.Kf2!  Kc5  3.Ke3=  simplest – although White also does not lose after  2.Bxf6  Kc5  3.Kf2  d4  4.Ke2  Kc4  5.Be7  Kc3  6.Kd1  . }
1... Bh3
{ Shirov found a fantastic resolution of the position. The bishop is sacrificed for a single tempo – the one needed for the king to get to e4. }
2. gxh3
{ 2.Kf2  Kf5  3.Kf3  would not help in view of  3...Bxg2+!  4.Kxg2  Ke4  -+. }
2... Kf5 3. Kf2 Ke4 4. Bxf6
{ After  4.Ke2  f5  , Black has too many passed pawns. } 4... d4
{ ∆  5.--  a3  . } 5. Be7 Kd3 { Threatening  6.--  Kc2  and  7.--  d3  . } 6.
Bc5 Kc4 { But not  6...Kc3?  7.Ke2  . } 7. Be7 Kb3
{ 7...Kc3  is just as good. Now the king must reach  c2  , which gives us the“pants” situation we spoke of in Chapter  4. White resigned. }
