{ 5/4. A. Norlin, 1922  White's king wants to go to f8, to help its pawn that is stopped by the black bishop, but Black then advances his pawn, deflecting the white bishop from the c7-pawn. }
1. Kc3
{ The principle of the 'single diagonal' is helpful here. White should transfer his bishop to a5, where it will protect the c7-pawn and hold back the black one. For this purpose, he must first protect the c7-pawn with the king, without allowing ...a7-a5-a4.   With the pawn on  a4  it is a draw:  1.Kc5?  a5!  2.Kb5  a4  3.Kb4  Kc8= }
1... Bf7 2. Kb4 Be6 3. Be5
{ The bishop should now clear the d6-square.  3.Kc5?!  is inaccurate in view of  3...Bb3!  with the threat  4.--  a5  . }
3... Kc8
{ In case of @@StartFEN@@8/pkP2bP1/8/2K1B3/8/8/8/8 b - - 7 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Kc8  5.Kc6!  @@StartBracket@@6.Bc3 is threatened.@@EndBracket@@  5...Be8  6.Kd6  Bf7  7.Bc3!  and 8.Ba5.  , while after  4...Kc8  5.Kc6!  if Black goes  5...a5  then  6.Kb5  +- }
4. Kb5
{ The author's line  4.Kc5  Bb3!  5.Kb5!  Kb7  6.Kb4!  and 7.Kc5 is a little bit slower than this. }
4... Kb7 { 5.Ka6 was threatening. } 5. Kc5 Bb3 6. Kd6 { ∆ 7.Kd7 } 6... Kc8 7.
Bc3
{ White has carried out his plan. With his next move, he places the bishop on a5 and then advances his king to f8. }
