{ Kotov − Botvinnik, USSR ch, Moscow 1955  (continued) } 4. Ba3
{ Note the black bishop’s excellent position in the variation  4.Be7  Kxh4  5.g6+  Kg4  . It protects the b3-pawn and restrains both enemy pawns along the single diagonal a2-g8. White has no counterplay, so Black just advances his h-pawn and wins the bishop for it. }
4... Kxh4 5. Kd3 Kxg5
{ Another strong line is  5...Kg3  6.Ke4  h4  7.d5  h3  8.dxe6  h2  9.Bd6+  Kg4  10.Bxh2  b2  11.e7  b1=Q+  . }
6. Ke4 h4 7. Kf3 { 7.d5  Bxd5+  -+ } 7... Bd5+
{ White resigned. After  8.Kf2  , Black’s king goes toward the b3-pawn. The bishop, meanwhile, defends the h-pawn, while restraining the d-pawn along the diagonal c8-h3. }
