{ Tragicomedies: Bellón – Minic, Siegen ol 1970    This was the adjourned position in which White sealed his 41st move. After analyzing in their rooms, the players agreed to a draw without resumption. Black’s positional advantage appeared insufficient for victory to Minic.  Judging from his comments in the Informant, he was convinced by the following line:  1.Bd8  Bc6  2.Bc7  Kf5  3.Bd8  Kg4  4.Be7  a5  5.bxa5  Kf5  6.a6  Ke4  7.a7  Kd4  8.a8=Q  Bxa8  9.c6  Bxc6  10.Bd6  , when the a3-pawn is securely protected, and the draw is obvious. }
1. c6
{ The only saving line. In fact, Bellón probably sealed the other move instead. Otherwise, after the game ended, this line would have been revealed in the annotations. }
1... Bxc6 2. Bd8 Kd3 3. Bc7
{ “Pawn in the crosshairs” – it is important to force it to move onto the same color square as its bishop. }
3... f3 4. Bd8 Kc2 5. Bc7 Kb3 6. Bd8 Kxa3 7. Ba5 Kb3 8. Ke3 Kc4 9. Kf2 Kd3 10.
Bc7 Ke4 11. Bb6 Bd5 12. Bc7 Kf5 13. Bd8
{ This is the same position as in the last diagram – except that there is no pawn at  c5  . Here Black gets nothing from  13...a5  14.Bxa5  Kxg5  , since the connected passed pawns are easily blockaded on the dark squares. If White had not forced the timely advance of the f-pawn, with the pawn at  f4  this position would be lost, of course. }
13... Kf4 14. Kf1
{ Now on  14...Ke3  , White has  15.Bb6+  , this check was the reason behind the pawn sacrifice. }
14... Bc4+ 15. Kf2
{ On  15...Bd3  , White cannot play either  16.Ke1?  Kg3!  17.Bc7+  Kg2  or  16.Kg1?  Ke3!  17.Bb6+  Ke2  , followed by 18...a5. However, he does have @@StartFEN@@3B4/8/p5p1/1p4P1/1P3k2/3b1p2/5K2/8 w - - 18 16@@EndFEN@@  16.Bc7+  exploiting the fact that the f3-pawn is not protected by the bishop  16...Kxg5  17.Kxf3  . }
15... Be2 16. Kg1 Ke3 17. Bb6+
{ The e2-square is occupied. And if the bishop goes to g2, White plays Ke1! @@StartBracket@@analysis by Dvoretsky@@EndBracket@@. }
*

