{ Tragicomedies: Bellón − Minic, Siegen ol 1970  (analysis)   It is surprising that even after home analysis, neither the players themselves nor their teammates were able to solve this rather simple position. In point of fact, its evaluation hinges on the sealed move. }
1. Bd8 Bc6
{ Black wins. To begin with, he must simply capture the a3-pawn @@StartBracket@@since the bishop cannot protect it@@EndBracket@@, and then the threat of the ...a6-a5 breakthrough will become more serious. Taking the pawn at a5 would give Black his second passed pawn. }
2. Bc7 f3 3. Bd8 Kd3 4. Bc7 Kc2 5. Bd8 Kb3 6. Ke3 Kxa3 7. Ba5 Ka2 8. Kd2
{ 8.Kd3  Kb3  -+ } 8... Kb2 9. Ke3 Kc3
{ Having done its job, the king returns to the other side. } 10. Kf2 Kd3 11.
Bd8 Ke4 12. Bc7 Kf5 13. Bd8 { Diagram 5-31 } 13... Kf4
{ Zugzwang! White’s bishop is torn apart: on one diagonal, it protects the g5-pawn; on the other, it controls the a5-square. }
14. Bc7+
{ After  14.Be7  a5!  15.bxa5  b4  , the king goes to the queenside once again, to win the bishop for the b-pawn. White has no counterplay, since the black bishop does everything on the one diagonal a8-h1, defending the f3-pawn and stopping both enemy passers.   The king retreat is no help either.  14.Kf1  Ke3  15.Bc7  a5!  16.bxa5  b4  , or  16.Bxa5  Bd5  , followed by  17.--  Bc4+  and  18.--  f2+  . After giving some thought to the final position of this variation, we come to understand that White’s own pawn at  c5  is in his way, because it blocks the important a7-g1 diagonal. So White must rid himself of it. @@StartSquare@@Ed. note: seen in the previous variation → Diagram 5-30@@EndSquare@@ }
14... Kxg5
{ Black moves his king to d3 and plays ...g6-g5-g4-g3+ when Bxg3 loses to ...a6-a5, and Kxg3 to ...Ke2.    @@StartSquare@@Ed. note: to illustrate the line → @@StartFEN@@8/2B5/p1b5/1pP5/1P4p1/3k1p2/5K2/8 b - - 0 20@@EndFEN@@  20...g3+  21.Bxg3  a5  and if  21.Kxg3  Ke2  -+@@EndSquare@@ }
*

