{ Ljubojevic – Karpov, Milan 1975    Of course, the position is drawn. All White needs do is to take the kingside pawns off the light squares, and his bishop can defend them. This frees the king to counter Black’s play on the queenside, where he wants to create a passed pawn. The simplest solution to the problem is  1.g5!  fxg5  2.hxg5  ∆ f4=, and if  1...f5  2.f4  Kd5  3.Bg7  .   Another reasonable line would be  1.h5!?  gxh5  2.gxh5  Kd5  3.Bg7  f5  4.h6  Kc4  5.f4  Kb3  6.Kd2=  Matanovic, and in case of  1...g5  2.Ke4  Bc2+  3.Ke3  f5  4.gxf5+  Kxf5  5.h6=  . }
1. Ke4 a4 2. h5
{ White is doing all he possibly can to complicate his life. Here again,  2.g5!  f5+  3.Ke3  would have secured an elementary draw. }
2... gxh5 3. gxh5 f5+ 4. Ke3 Kd5 5. h6 Kc4 6. f4 Kb3
{ Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 5-33 } *

