{ Ljubojevic − Karpov, Milan 1975  (continued)     White might still have saved the game by playing  7.Kd2!  Bf3  8.Kc1  or  8.Bg7  . Evidently, Ljubojevic did not feel like calculating the consequences of  7.Kd2!  Kxb2  .  However, as Villeneuve has shown, the bishop sacrifice is insufficient:  8.Kxd1  Kxa3  9.Kc2  Kb4  10.Kb2=  , and after  8...c4  9.Bg7+  c3  10.Ke2!   10.Be5?  b5  11.Bd4  b4  -+  10...Kc2  11.Ke3  b5  12.Kd4!  Kd2  13.Kc5!  and if  10...Kxa3  11.Kd3  b5  12.Kc2!  or  11.Bxc3  b5  12.Be5  b4  @@StartBracket@@∆ 13...Ka2-+@@EndBracket@@  13.Bd6!  +- }
7. Bg7 Kc2
{ Only now, when the white king is cut off from the queenside, does his position become lost. Black’s pawn advance will reach its goal – but only with the black bishop on b3, which is where Karpov is sending it now. }
8. Be5 Bh5 9. Bf6
{ 9.Bc7  would not help:  9...Kxb2  10.Bxb6  c4  11.Bd4+  Kxa3  12.Kd2  Kb3  13.Bf6  a3  . Then Black will place his bishop at  b1  , pawn at  a2  , transfer his king to  g6  and @@StartBracket@@with the white bishop at g7@@EndBracket@@, trade the c4-pawn for the h6-pawn by means of  ...c4-c3  . And in case of @@StartFEN@@8/7p/1B5P/5p1b/p1p2P2/P3K3/1k6/8 w - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Bc5  c3  12.Bd4  Kc2  13.Bf6  Be8  followed by  14.--  Bb5  and  15.--  Kb3  . }
9... Bf7 10. Be5 { Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 5-34 } *

