{ 5/5. Berezhnoy-Gusev, Rostov-Don 1972  
How should the game end? } 1... Ke6
{ The king runs to the h-pawn, reaching the first defensive position. But can the bishop prevent the creation of another passed pawn on the queenside?  It is worth mentioning that reaching the first defensive position is the only correct plan for Black. Yes, after  1...Be2  , the immediate  2.d5  cxd5  3.Kxd5  does not succeed in view of  3...Bd1!  4.Bd6   4.Kc5  Ba4=  4...Ke8  5.Ke6  Bb3+  6.Kf6  Bd1=  . But White plays @@StartFEN@@8/3k4/2p5/1pK5/1P1P3P/P5B1/4b3/8 w - - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Bf4  Bf3  3.Be5  , and  3...Ke6!  is quite necessary here, because the prolonged passive policy  3...Be2?  loses to  4.d5  cxd5  5.Kxd5  Bd1   5...Ke7  6.Kc5  , planning Kb6-a5 and a3-a4 +-  6.Kc5  Ba4  7.h5  Ke6  8.h6  , and if  6...Ke6  7.Kxb5!  Kxe5  8.Kc6!  @@StartBracket@@shouldering in the most precise way@@EndBracket@@  8...Bf3+  9.Kc7  Be2  10.a4  +-. }
2. h5 Kf7 3. h6 Kg6 4. Bf4 Kh7 5. Kb6 { Diagram 16-48 } 5... Bd5
{ The game continued  5...Be4??  6.Ka5  Kg6  7.a4  bxa4  8.Kxa4  Kf7  9.b5  , and Black resigned. @@StartFEN@@8/7k/2p4P/Kp6/1P1PbB2/P7/8/8 b - - 6 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bc2  wouldn't have worked either:  7.d5!  +- }
6. Ka5 Bb3 7. a4 bxa4 8. b5 cxb5 9. Kxb5 a3
{ Is useless – the a-pawn will deflect the bishop from protecting its own pawn. }
