{ Euwe – Yanofsky, Groningen 1946 } 1... h5
{ A typical move, ensuring the safety of the kingside pawns. On  1...Ke6?!  , Black would have had to reckon not only with  2.g4!?  but also with  2.Kf2  Kd7?  3.Bf8  g6  4.Bh6!  , when the h7-pawn becomes an attractive target for the white king. }
2. Kf2 Bd3
{ A technique we have already seen more than once: the a-pawn is forced onto a square of the same color as its bishop. However, now was not the time to attack the pawn. Necessary was  2...Ke6  , bringing the king closer to the important f5-square. }
3. a7 Be4 { Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 5-37 } *

