{ Euwe − Yanofsky, Groningen 1946  (continued) } 4. g3
{ His opponent’s inaccuracy remains unpunished. As John Nunn has correctly noted,  4.g4!!  hxg4  5.Kg3  won. For example,  5...Bf3  @@StartBracket@@with the king on  e6  ,  Kf5  holds@@EndBracket@@  6.Kf4  Ke6  7.Bd4  g6  8.h3  ⨀  g5+  9.Kg3  +- and if @@StartFEN@@8/P7/4k1p1/8/3B1Kp1/5b1P/1P6/8 b - - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Bg2  9.Kxg4!  +- but not  9.hxg4  Bh1=  with a situation as soon arose in the game.   Also sufficient for victory is  4.h4!  g6  5.g4!  hxg4  6.Kg3  Bf3  7.Kf4  Ke6  8.Kg5  Be4  9.Kxg4  Kd7  @@StartBracket@@the attempt to transfer the king to  b7  is hopelessly late@@EndBracket@@  10.Kf4  Bg2  11.Kg5  Be4  12.a8=Q  Bxa8  13.Kxg6  +- @@StartBracket@@shown by Burkhard Treiber@@EndBracket@@. }
4... Ke6 5. Ke3 { Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 5-38 } *

