{ Kaidanov – Antoshin, RSFSR ch 1984    What plan should White select?  1.Bf4?  hoping to induce the reply  1...h5  , giving his king invasion squares on the kingside, would be a gross blunder in view of the pawn sacrifice  1...g5!  2.hxg5  hxg5  3.Bxg5  Ke8  . Black’s king arrives at  b7  @@StartBracket@@the “first defensive system”@@EndBracket@@, and White is unable to create a second passed pawn on the kingside.  By the way, ...g6-g5 is not yet a threat – White replies h4-h5, fixing the h6-pawn. @@StartBracket@@With a lightsquare bishop, for the weaker side to have his pawns on dark squares renders them weak, and is generally a serious positional defect.@@EndBracket@@ But without exchanging off these pawns, it makes no sense to go into the first defensive position, because the bishop will be unable to defend its kingside. }
1. Kf1 Ba8 2. Kg1 Bd5 3. Kh2 Ba8 4. Kg3
{ Now let’s examine  4.Kh3  Bd5  5.g4?  fxg4+  6.Kxg4  Ba8  7.Kg3  Bd5  8.Kg2  Ba8  9.Kf1  Bd5  10.Ke2  Ba8  11.Kd2  Bd5  12.Kc3  Ba8  13.Kb4  . Now, the defensive plan of marching the black king down to  e2  ,  13...Ke7  14.Bg7  h5  15.Kc3  Kd6  16.Kd2  Kd5?  does not work, because his opponent will advance through the now open g2-square.  But there is another idea: Black can return to the first defensive position:  13...Bd5!  14.Kc5  Ke7  15.Bg7  h5  16.Kb4  Kd6  17.Kc3  Kc7!  18.Be5+  Kb7  19.Bb8  Kb6!  20.Kd2  Kb7  21.Ke1  Bc4!=  , and White’s king will not get to the kingside. }
4... Bd5 5. Bc7
{ Ed. note: analyzed next → Diagram 5-44 and continued in the variation → Diagram 5-45. }
