{ Kaidanov – Antoshin, RSFSR ch 1984  (analysis)   White will not be able to get to the a-pawn through the queenside: the enemy king will “maintain the zone.” But by doing so, he will be diverted from the f7-square, and then White can play Bg7, induce ...h6-h5, and return with his king to the kingside. Let’s try it. }
1. Kd2 Ba8 2. Kc3 Bb7 3. Kb4 Ke7 4. Bg7 h5 5. Kc3
{ Diagram 5-44   Is there a way to prevent the king march via h2 to e5? Kaidanov suggests a counterattack by Black’s king:  5...Kd6  6.Kd2  Kd5  7.Ke1  Kc4  8.Kf1  Kd3  9.Kg1  Ke2=  . However, he must also consider  7.Ke2!  @@StartBracket@@instead of 7.Ke1@@EndBracket@@  7...Kc4  8.f3  . It would be safer to exploit the absence of White’s king from the kingside by switching, at precisely this moment, to the first defensive position. }
5... Kd7 6. Kd2 Bd5 7. Ke1 Kc8 8. Bf8
{ 8.Be5  Kb7  9.Bb8  changes nothing, while  8.Kf1  Kb7  loses the pawn at  a7  . }
8... Kb7 9. Bc5 Bc4 10. f3 Bd5
{ At first it seemed to me that the same objective could be achieved through the immediate  10...f4?  , but Stephan Neurohr has proven that White wins here by continuing  11.fxe4  fxe3  12.d5  exd5  13.e5  , while  12...e5  is also no better. }
11. Kf2 f4 12. fxe4 { 12.exf4  exf3  13.gxf3  Kc8  14.Ke3  Kd7= } 12... Bxe4
13. exf4 Bf5
{ With an obvious draw.  Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 5-45 }
