{ Both of the following exercises are rather difficult. In the first, you must calculate variations accurately; in the second, you must find a far from obvious plan of action.  5/6. Tringov-Smyslov, Reykjavik 1974 }
1. f3
{ The f2-pawn must go forward, but where?   The game continued  1.f4?  Bg1!  2.Kd3  Bh2  3.Ke3  Kf6  . Black has chained his opponent to the defense of the f4-pawn and now directs his king to  b2  . White has no answer to this simple plan. By the way, the bishop has gone to  h2  (rather than c7)  in order not to interfere with the king when it steps to  d6  .  4.Ba2  Ke7  5.Bg8  Kd6  6.Bf7  Kc5  7.Ba2   7.Be6  Kb4  8.Kd3  Bxf4  9.Kc2  Be5!  10.Bxf5  a2  -+  7...Kb4  8.Kd4  Bxf4  9.Kd5  Bg3  10.Kd4  f4  White resigned.   In endings with opposite-color bishops, the defender should keep his pawns on the squares of his bishop's color. Therefore, the text move  1.f3!  suggests itself, having in mind the first defensive position. The bishop can protect kingside pawns easily when the king stands on b3 @@StartBracket@@if ...Kf4, then Be6!, and if ...f5-f4, then the bishop goes to g4@@EndBracket@@. The question is whether White can build this setup in time.   At the training session for young Russian players I led in the spring of 2001, my apprentices suggested another defensive plan for White:  1.Kf3  Kf6  2.Ba2  Ke5  3.Bg8  Bc5  4.Ba2  @@StartSquare@@Diagram 16-51@@EndSquare@@  The king cannot now go to  d4  in view of  5.Kf4  , therefore Black plays  4...Bf8!  with the idea of  5.--  Bh6  and only then, finally,  6.--  Kd4  . White responds with  5.Ke3!  Bh6+  6.Kd3  closing the way to the black king. However after  6...Kf4  (7...Kf3 is threatened)  7.Bd5  Bf8  (the bishop wants to go to c5 in order to attack the f2-pawn)  8.Kc2  Bc5  9.Kb3  Bxf2  10.Kxa3  , Black wins by the familiar shouldering' technique:  10...Ke3!!  11.Kb3  Kd2! }
1... Kf6 2. Kd3 Ke5
{ But the position is drawn after all! White should make a waiting move. } 3.
Bg8
{ If the bishop retreats from  d4  , White can transpose to the first defensive position: @@StartSquare@@Ed. note: to illustrate the line @@StartFEN@@6B1/8/8/4kp2/3b3p/p2K1P1P/8/8 b - - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bb6  4.Kc2  Kf4  5.Be6!  Kxf3  6.Bxf5  , and  6...a2  7.Kb2  is not dangerous for him anymore.@@EndSquare@@ }
3... Kf4 4. Kxd4 Kxf3
{ The king is placed worse on f3 than on g3 @@StartBracket@@see the line 3.f4+?@@EndBracket@@, and this circumstance allows White to save the game. }
5. Bd5+ Kg3 6. Ke3 f4+ { 6...Kxh3  7.Kf3  locking the king on the h-file. } 7.
Ke2 f3+ 8. Kf1 Kxh3 9. Kf2 Kg4 10. Bxf3+ { Analysis by M. Dvoretsky. } *

