{ 5/7. Simagin-Janssen, wchsf cr 1967  The second defensive position is present. According to the rules, a road for the king to the h5-pawn should be paved, but how does one do so? }
1. Bf7
{ The straightforward attempt  1.Kb2  Kb6  2.Ka3  Bg5  3.Ka4  Bh6  4.a3  Bg5  5.b4  axb4  6.axb4  cxb4  7.Kxb4  allows Black to build an unassailable fortress by means of  7...Bd2+!  8.Kb3  Kc5  . The breakthrough a2-a3 and b3-b4 @@StartBracket@@followed by c4-c5@@EndBracket@@ should be carried out when the king is on  d3  . The bishop belongs on  a4  where it deprives the black king of important squares and restrains Black’s eventual passed b-pawn that soon appears. }
1... Bf8 2. Be8 Bh6 3. a3 { ∆ 4.b4 } 3... Bf8
{ If  3...Kb6  , then  4.Kd3  @@StartBracket@@∆ Ke4-d5@@EndBracket@@  4...Kc7  5.b4!  axb4  6.axb4  cxb4  7.c5  Bf8  8.Kc4  b3  9.Ba4  b2  10.Bc2!  and if  7...b3  8.Ba4  b2  9.Bc2  +- or  8.Kc3  Bf8  9.c6  +- }
4. Ba4 { Zuzgwang. } 4... Kb6
{ On  4...Bh6  or  4...Kd6  ,  5.b4  is decisive. } 5. Kd3 { ∆ Ke4-d5 } 5...
Kc7 { Diagram 16-52 } 6. b4
{ There are other ways to win, but this is the simplest. } 6... axb4 7. axb4
cxb4 8. c5 { Black resigned because of: } 8... Bxc5
{ 8...b3  9.Kc4  b2  10.Bc2  +- } 9. Kc4 Bf8 { 9...Kd6  10.h6  +- } 10. Kd5 Kd8
11. Ke6 { Diagram 16-53 has been intentionally omitted. } *

