{ Capablanca − Janowsky, New York 1916  (continued)   In this position, Janowsky resigned. And wrongly so – as Averbakh has shown. Black could get a draw by employing the basic defensive plan of “king behind king.” Since White is going to put his king on c6, Black must hurry his king over to c4. }
11... Kf4 12. Bd4 { 12.Be5+  Ke3  13.b5  Kd3  14.Kc6  Kc4= } 12... Kf3 13. b5
{ 13.Bc5  Ke2  14.Kc6  Kd3  15.Kd7  Bg5  16.b5  Kc4= } 13... Ke2 14. Kc6 Kd3
15. Bb6 Bg5 16. Bc7 Be3
{ After  17.Bd6  Kc4  , Black prevents the interference along the diagonal at  c5  just in time. But the struggle is not over yet. }
17. Kd5 { Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 6-7 } *

