{ Capablanca − Janowsky, New York 1916  (continued) } 17... Bd2
{ On  18.b6  , the pin  18...Ba5  saves him. } 18. Bd8
{ Now the threat of @@StartFEN@@3B4/8/8/1P1K4/8/3k4/3b4/8 w - - 2 18@@EndFEN@@  19.b6  Ba5  20.b7  forces Black to retreat. That is fine – White’s bishop stands worse on  d8  than it did on  c7  . }
18... Be3
{ There is no longer any danger in  19.Be7  @@StartBracket@@∆ 20.Bc5@@EndBracket@@  19...Bb6!  20.Kc6  Ba5!  @@StartBracket@@White no longer has 21.Bc7@@EndBracket@@  21.Bd6  Kc4=  . White has just one final trap. }
19. Bc7 Bd2 20. Kc6 Be3 21. Kb7 { 21.Bd6  Kc4= } 21... Kc4 22. Ka6 Kb3
{ Once again, the same technique of “king behind king”: the black king heads for  a4  . He would lose after  22...Bf2?  23.Bb6  Bh4  24.Be3  Bd8  25.Bd2  ∆ Ba5+-. And  22...Kb4?  23.Bb6  Bg5  24.Ba5+  and 25.b6+- is wrong too. }
23. Bb6 Bg5 24. Bf2 Bd8 25. Be1 Ka4
