{ We have already seen the tragicomedies that occurred in the gamesBotvinnik-Model andCapablanca-Janowsky. I will add one more example.  Tragicomedies: Savchenko − Krivonosov, USSR 1989 }
1... Be5
{ Black should have carried out his interference in a more primitive form, by preparing ...Be5. This could have been achieved either by  1...Kd5  2.Kd3!?  Ke6!  3.Bd4  a2  4.c4  Be5  . Just not  2...a2?  3.c4+=   Or by  1...Kd6  2.c4  2...a2  ,  2...Ke6  , or  2...Be5  3.c5+  Ke6!  -+.  3...Kd5?  is a mistake, because of  4.c6= }
2. Bxe5 Kd5 3. Bg7
{ After  3.Kd3!  not  3...a2?  because of  4.Bg7  +-, but  3...Kxe5  4.Kc2  the king is in the square of the a-pawn. }
3... Kc4
{ And Black won.   The same tactical idea of interference as in theHeuäcker study brought Black success here. However, this occurred only as a result of his opponent's gross blunder. }
