{ 6/1. L. Centurini, 1847 } 1. Bh4
{ The bishop wants to go to b8; if it manages to get there, the fight will be over immediately. So Black tries to prevent it. }
1... Kb5 2. Bf2 Ka6
{ Diagram 16-54    If White now directs the bishop to  c7  then the black king returns to  c6  in time. After  3.Be3  Bd6!  4.Bg5  Kb5  5.Bd8  Kc6  there is no sense in  6.Be7  Bh2  because the white bishop cannot enter the g1-a7 diagonal immediately. But if the black bishop occupies some other position, White could win the decisive tempo by means of deflection. }
3. Bc5 { Zugzwang. } 3... Be5 4. Be7 Kb5 5. Bd8 Kc6 6. Bf6
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed. Had Black played 3...Bf4 or 3...Bg3, instead of 3...Be5, White would have had now available 6.Bg5 or @@StartFEN@@2KB4/1P6/2k5/8/8/6b1/8/8 w - - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bh4  , respectively.@@EndSquare@@ }
6... Bh2 7. Bd4 { ∆ Ba7-b8+-. } *

