{ 6/2. Zviagintsev-Chernin, Portoroz 1997  White wins if he manages to advance the pawn to b6 and to penetrate to a7 with his king. As Zviagintsev has demonstrated, Black could have held the game. }
1... Be2
{ Black’s initial move  1...Kf6?  allowed White to carry out this plan unhindered.  2.b5  Ke7  3.b6  Be2  4.Bc6!  Kd6  5.Bb5  Bf3  6.Ka6  Kc5  7.Bf1  Black resigned. The king transfer to the rear of the white king  7...Kb4  8.Ka7  Ka5  cannot help here because the a6-c8 diagonal, where the bishop will be forced, is too short. And in case of  4...Kd8  5.Bb5  Bxb5  6.Kxb5  +- }
2. Ba6 Bf3 { Diagram 16-55 } 3. b5
{ If  3.Bf1  , then  3...Bc6!  4.Kb6  Be8  5.Kc7  Kf6  6.Kd6  Ba4  7.Bc4  Be8  8.Bd5  Bb5  9.Kc5  Be8  10.Bc6  Bh5  11.b5  Ke7  12.b6  Kd8=  , rather than  3...Kf6?  4.b5  Ke7  5.Ka6  +- }
3... Kf6 4. b6 Ke7 5. Bf1
{ 5.Bc8  Kd8  6.Bf5  Bb7  or  6...Be2  gives nothing - the king cannot get to  a7  . }
5... Bb7 6. Kb5 Kd8
{ 6...Kd6  is also playable, but after  7.Bh3  he must retreat anyway:  7...Ke7  □. }
7. Bh3 Ke7 8. Kc5 Kd8 9. Kd6 Bf3 10. Be6 Bb7
{ A position of reciprocal zugzwang has arisen, with White on move @@StartBracket@@seediagram 6-3@@EndBracket@@. }
