{ 6/3. Y. Hoch, 1977  The initial moves are easy to find. } 1. Kd8 Bb7 2. c7+
Ka7 3. Bc6 Ba6 4. Bxb5 Bb7 { Diagram 16-56 } 5. Bc6
{ But here precise calculation is required to the end. Only then will the reason for this zwischenzug be clear.   If White had not found the correct continuation on the fifth move, Black could have gotten rid of the pawn:  5.Bd7?  Kb6  6.Bc8  Bd5  or  6...Bg2  7.Ba6  Bh3  8.Bf1  Be6 !  9.Bc4  d5 !  10.Bxd5  Bh3  11.Bf7  Kc5  12.Be8  Kd6= }
5... Ba6 6. Bd7 Kb6 { 6...d5  7.Bc8  Bf1  8.Bb7  Bh3  9.Bc6  d4  10.Bd7  +- }
7. Bc8 Bf1 8. Bb7 Bh3
{ Now White should bring his bishop to d7 as soon as possible @@StartBracket@@before the black king comes to d6@@EndBracket@@. }
9. Bg2 Be6 { 9...Bg4  10.Bf3!  and  9...Bf5  10.Be4! } 10. Bd5 Bh3 11. Bf7 Kc5
12. Be8
{ ∆ Bd7+-. Black's d6-pawn caused his downfall because it stood in the way of his own king. }
