{ 6/4. J. Sulz, 1948 } 1. Be1
{ A subtle zwischenzug that provides the important b4-square to the bishop in the future.  White has a clear plan: to drive the black bishop off the a3-f8 diagonal and create an interference on f6. Black's only hope is the advance of his h-pawn because his king cannot get to f5 in time.   The hope is not completely groundless, as can be seen from the line  1.Bh4?  h5!  2.Be7  Ba5!  3.Bf8  Bd8  4.Bg7  h4  5.Bf6  h3!  6.Bxd8  h2  7.e7  h1=Q = }
1... Bc5 2. Bh4 h5 { 2...Kd5  3.Be7  Bb6  4.Bf8  Bd8  5.Bg7  Ke4  6.Bf6  +- }
3. Be7 Bb6 4. Bb4 Bd8 5. Ba5
{ This is the point ! The black bishop is forced out from the comfortable d8-square. }
5... Bg5 6. Bc3 h4 7. Bf6 Bxf6 { 7...h3  8.e7  +- } 8. Kxf6 h3 9. e7
{ White wins. } *

