{ 6/5. I. Agapov, 1981 } 1. g3
{ Now 2.c7+- is threatened. Black prevents the pawn advance with a pinning technique, similar to theCapablanca-Janowsky ending we have seen already.  The task of utilizing the material advantage is rather difficult here because the white king is out of play forever.   For example, the straightforward attempt  1.c7?  Kh4  2.c8=Q  Bxc8  3.Bxc8  Kg3  leads to a draw.  Connected passed pawns are often impotent when they are fixed on squares of their bishop's color. }
1... Bd5 2. Ba8
{ ∆  2...--  3.c7  Be6  4.Bb7+-  .  2.f4?  is wrong in view of  2...Kg4  3.Bc8+  Kxg3= }
2... Be6 { 2...Bxf3?  3.c7  Bg4  4.Bf3  +- } 3. c7 Bc8
{ Diagram 16-57  What to do now?   In case of  4.f4?  Kg4  5.Be4  Bd7  White cannot make any progress.  We might consider the idea of a bishop sacrifice on h3 with the interference g3-g4 to follow. But this plan is difficult to carry out, because Black can respond with a king march to the c7-pawn.   For example,  4.Be4?  Kg5  5.Bd3  Kf6!  6.f4  Ke7=  or @@StartFEN@@2b5/2P5/5k2/8/8/2pB1PP1/1pP5/1K6 w - - 5 6@@EndFEN@@  6.g4  Kg5  7.Bf5  Ba6=  . In case of  6.Bf1  Ke7  7.Bh3?  Bxh3  8.g4  Kd7  -+  The bishop should therefore be transferred to e8 first, so that Black will be forced to defend the h5-square in order to avoid the bishop exchange Bh5-g4. Only when the black king is farthest from the queenside can the main plan be successful. }
4. Bc6 Kg6 5. Be8+ Kg5 6. Bf7 { Zugzwang. } 6... Kh6
{ 6...Bd7  7.Bc4  Kf6  8.Ba6 } 7. Bc4
{ There is no other way to win:  7.f4?  Kg7  8.Bh5  Kf6  9.g4  Ke7= } 7... Kg6
8. Bf1 Kf6 9. Bh3 Bxh3 10. g4 { White wins. } *

