{ Fixing Pawns   Averbakh − Veresov, Moscow 1947 } 1. h4
{ The experienced player makes such moves − fixing the enemy pawns on the same color squares as his bishop − without thinking.   White has a great positional advantage. After the necessary preparations, he will create an outside passed pawn on the queenside, which will divert the enemy forces, allowing White to fall upon the kingside pawns. }
1... Bd7 2. Bf1 a5 3. Bg2 Bc6 { 3...Bf5  4.Bh1  ⨀ } 4. Bh3 b5 5. cxb5 Bxb5 6.
Bc8 Bc6 7. b4 axb4 8. axb4 Bb5 9. Bb7 g5
{ On  9...Bd3  10.Bc6  Kf5  11.Bd7+  or  11.b5  Bxb5  12.Bxb5  Kg4  13.Kf2  e3+  14.Kg2  +-, and if @@StartFEN@@8/8/2B3p1/1P3k1p/4p2P/3bK1P1/8/8 b - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Kg4  12.b6  Ba6  13.Kf2  e3+  14.Kg2  +-  is decisive. }
10. Bxe4 gxh4 11. gxh4 Ba4
{ 11...Be8  loses also:  12.Bf3  Kf5  13.Be2!   But not  13.Kd4?  Kf4  and  14.--  Kg3  .  13...Ke5  14.Bd3!  ⨀  14...Bd7  15.Bg6  Kd5  16.Bxh5  Kc4  17.Be2+  Kxb4  18.h5  Bf5  19.Bd3  Be6  20.h6  Bg8  21.Kd4  +-. And in case of @@StartFEN@@4b3/8/8/4k2p/1P5P/3BK3/8/8 b - - 6 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Kd5  15.Kf4  Kd4  16.Be2  +- }
12. Bg6 Bd1 13. b5 Kd5 14. Kf4 Kc5 15. Kg5 Be2
{ 15...Kxb5  16.Bxh5  Bc2  17.Be8+  Kc5  18.h5  Kd6  19.Kf6!  +-   Ed. note: analyzed in the next variation → Diagram 6-17 and the game continuation → Diagram 6-18 }
