{ Zugzwang   With a bad bishop, the weaker side's defensive hopes often are destroyed through zugzwang. Here is the simplest example:   Y. Averbakh, 1954   The correspondence between the f3- and f7-squares is obvious to win, it is necessary only to give Black the move. If you like, you can also find other pairs of corresponding squares  (for example, the f1- and b3-squares also correspond to f7)  , but there is no real need. }
1. Be2 Be8
{ If  1...Bg6  then  2.Bd3  Bh7  3.Bf1!  Bg8  4.Be2  Bf7  5.Bf3  ⨀, and if @@StartFEN@@8/7b/p2k4/1p1p1p1p/1P1K1P1P/2P1P3/8/5B2 b - - 5 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bg6  4.Bg2  Bf7  5.Bf3  ⨀ }
2. Bd3 Bg6 { 2...Bd7  3.Bc2  Be6  4.Bd1  Bf7  5.Bf3  ⨀ } 3. Bc2 Bh7 4. Bb3 Bg8
5. Bd1 Bf7 6. Bf3 { White wins. } *

