{ Shabalov − Varavin, Moscow 1986  (continued) } 1. Bh2 Bg7 2. g5
{ White 'breaks the rule', by moving a pawn onto a square the same color as his own bishop − in order to restrict the enemy bishops mobility still further. There is no other way to make any progress. }
2... Bf8 { 9...Bh8  10.Bg3  Bg7  11.Be1  is hopeless. } 3. Bxe5 Be7 4. Bf6 Bb4
{ The decisive error.   After the accurate  11...Bc5  12.Bd8  Bb4  13.Kd4  Kd6  and if  12.Bc3  Bb6  (shown by Aczel)  realizing the extra pawn is evidently not possible. }
5. Bc3
{ Advancing the e-pawn does nothing for White:  12.e5  Bd2  13.e6  Kd6  14.e7  Kd7  So he takes the a5-pawn in exchange for the g5-pawn. }
5... Be7 6. Bxa5 Bxg5 7. b4 Bf4 8. b5+ Kd6 9. Bc3 g5 10. e5+ Kc7
{ 17...Bxe5  18.Bxe5+  Kxe5  and now not  19.Kc5?  Ke6  , but @@StartFEN@@8/8/8/1P2k1p1/2K5/8/8/8 w - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  19.b6!  Kd6  20.Kb5  g4  21.Ka6  +- }
11. Ba5+ Kc8 12. Kd5 g4 13. e6 g3 14. Kc6 Bg5 { 22.e7  was threatened. } 15. b6
{ Black resigned. } *

