{ Pawns Which Do Not 'Play by the Rules'   In chess, there are no absolute laws. Even so important and generally useful an axiom as the unprofitability of placing one's pawns on the same color squares as one's bishop must occasionally be broken. Here are the possible reasons for doing so:   To restrict the mobility of the enemy bishop using ones own pawns @@StartBracket@@as occurred in the preceding example@@EndBracket@@;  The need to undermine the enemy pawn chain;  The attempt to create an impregnable fortress around a 'bad bishop'.  The first and third points are illustrated in the next variation → Diagram 6-22. }
1. -- *

