{ Sveshnikov – Kasparov, USSR ch, Minsk 1979  First, let’s evaluate what actually happened in the game. }
1... g6
{ If instead of 4.a3 White goes @@StartFEN@@8/5pp1/4p3/ppk1P2p/5P1P/1PK3P1/P7/8 w - - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.b4+  then  4...axb4+  5.Kb3  f6  and if  4.Kd3  Kb4  5.Kc2  Ka3  6.Kb1  a4  -+ }
2. Ke2 { The bishop cannot retreat, owing to 2...Be1. } 2... Bc5 3. Bxc5
{ The pawn ending is lost. White could have drawn by avoiding the exchange of bishops. After  3.Be1!  Ke4  4.Ba5  , I cannot see how Black can improve his position.   And if  3...b4  , hoping for  4.Bd2?  Ke4  5.Be1  a5  6.Bd2  Bd4  7.Be1  Be3  , with zugzwang, or  7.Bc1  Bc3  8.Be3  Be1!  then simply @@StartFEN@@8/5p2/p3p1p1/2bkP2p/1p3P1P/1P4P1/P3K3/4B3 w - - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Kf3!= }
3... Kxc5 4. Kd3 Kb4 5. Kc2 Ka3 6. Kb1 a5 7. Ka1 a4 { Widening the beachhead. }
8. bxa4 Kxa4 9. Kb1 { 9.Kb2  b4  -+ } 9... Ka3 10. Ka1 b4 11. Kb1 b3
{ White resigned. } *

