{ Tragicomedies: Teichmann – Marshall, San Sebastian 1911  Even though Black has an overwhelming positional advantage, the endgame is not as simple as it seems. Both sides made many errors; nor did grandmaster Averbakh avoid errors in his commentaries. }
1... Bf7+
{ An unfortunate move, allowing the king to return to the defense of the kingside through the d3-square. Now the position becomes drawn. }
2. Kd3 Kf4 3. Bf1 Kg3 4. Ke3 Bd5 5. Ke2 f5 6. Ke3 Be6
{ The bishop sacrifice is insufficient:  6...f4+  7.Ke2  Bb7  8.Ke1  Bxf3  9.gxf3  Kxf3  10.Be2+  Kg2  11.Bf1+  Kg3  12.Ke2=  . And if Black goes @@StartFEN@@8/8/8/6p1/5p1p/5k1P/4B3/4K3 b - - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Kg3  , instead of 10...Kg2, then  11.Bg4  Kg2  12.Ke2=  .  The only remaining try at making progress is ...g5-g4, but this leads to the exchange of too many pawns. }
7. Ke2 g4 { Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 6-26 } *

