hxg4
{ Or with @@StartFEN@@8/3b4/8/8/6pp/4K1kP/6P1/5B2 w - - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10.hxg4!  Bxg4  11.Bb5!  @@StartBracket@@pointed out by Chéron@@EndBracket@@, giving up the g2-pawn right away, but activating his bishop. For example,  11...Be6  12.Bc6  Bc4  13.Be4  Bf1  14.Bd5  Bxg2  15.Be6=  @@StartBracket@@the attempted interference leads to a drawn pawn ending@@EndBracket@@, or  11...Kxg2  12.Kf4!   12.Bc6+?  Kg3  ∆ h3-h2, Bh3-g2  12...Be6  13.Bc6+  Kf2   After  13...Kh2  14.Bb7  h3  15.Be4  Kg1  16.Kg3  h2  the interference on  g2  is impossible.  14.Bd5!  Bxd5  15.Kg4  , and if  14...Bd7  15.Bc6!  Bh3  16.Bd5  Bg2  17.Be6=  Averbakh considers the text move the decisive error, but he is wrong. }
8... fxg4 9. Ke3
{ 9.fxg4!  Bxg4+  here Averbakh only considers  10.Ke3  Bd7  -+, but  10.Ke1!  was necessary leading to a curious position of reciprocal zugzwang. @@StartSquare@@1@@EndSquare@@ But it is Black to move here, and after  10...Bd7   10...Bh5  11.Bb5  Kxg2  12.Bd7  , or  12.Bc6+  first.  11.Ba6  Bc6  12.Bc8  Bxg2  13.Bd7=  and if  11...Kxg2  12.Bb7+  Kg1  , White has time to get his king to g3:  13.Ke2!  h3  14.Kf3  h2  15.Kg3=   @@StartSquare@@1@@EndSquare@@ White to move loses: @@StartFEN@@8/8/8/8/6bp/6k1/6P1/4KB2 w - - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Bb5  Kxg2  12.Bc6+  Kg1  -+   Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 6-27 }
