Bd7
{ Black blunders in turn, allowing his opponent to force the draw by the same means indicated in the notes to move 8. @@StartSquare@@Ed. see the previous variation.@@EndSquare@@   The win was  9...gxf3!  10.gxf3  Bd7  ⨀  11.f4  Bg4!  ⨀  12.Ke4  Kf2  -+ and if  11.Ke2  Bb5+  12.Ke1  Bc6  13.f4  Be4!  14.Ke2  Bf5!  15.Ke1  Bg4  ⨀ Black has to avoid @@StartFEN@@8/8/2b5/8/5P1p/6k1/8/4KB2 b - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Bg2?  due to  14.f5  h3  15.f6= }
10. fxg4 Bxg4 11. Ke4
{ The loser is always the one who makes the last mistake! We already know that  11.Bb5!  would draw. But with the bishop on  f1  , White is helpless. }
11... Bc8 12. Ke3 Bd7 { White resigned. } 13. Ke4
{ Or 13.Ke2, Black is winning.   13.Kd2  Kf2!  14.Bc4  Kxg2  15.Ke1  Kg1!  16.Bf1  Be6  ⨀  17.Bb5  h3  18.Bc6  h2  19.Be4  Bh3  ∆ Bg2. }
13... Bc6+ 14. Ke3 Bxg2
{ Ed. note: the initial position, Diagram 6-25, is analyzed in the next variation → Diagram 6-28. }
