{ Euwe - Menchik, Hastings 1930/31  (continued)     Comparing this position to the analogous position after 2...Bxg4?! @@StartSquare@@Ed. seen in Diagram 6-29@@EndSquare@@ here Black has a passed h-pawn. For this reason  7.Kc4?  Be6!  does not win.   On  7.Kc3?  Ke7  8.Kb4  , advancing the h-pawn gives Black serious counterplay:  8...h5!  9.Kb5  h4  10.Kb6  h3  11.Kc7  Be6  12.Bxb7  Bc4  ∆ Bf1-g2.   However White wins by  7.e4!  Ke7  8.Ke3!  f6  9.f5!  , followed by Kf4, and then either e4-e5 or Kg4-h5. }
7. Bf3
{ White restrains the passed pawn, but now Black’s king is able to get to c7. }
7... Ke7 8. Kc4 Kd8 { 9.Kb5  allows  9...Kc7  . } 9. Kd5 b6 10. c6
{ Euwe fails to sense the danger. He had to resign himself to a draw after  10.Bh5  . }
10... Kc7 11. Ke5 Be6 12. f5 Bb3 { 12...Bc4 } 13. Kf6 b5
{ Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 6-32 } *

