{ 6/6. Lasker-Bogatyrchuk, Moscow 1935 } 1. Kg5
{ White cannot do without e3-e4. The game continued  1.e4?  d4!  2.Bc4  Bb7  3.Kg5  Bc8  4.Kf4  Kd7  5.Kf3  Bb7  6.Ke2  Bc8  7.Kd3  Bb7  8.Kxd4  Bc8  9.Ke3  Bb7  and a draw was agreed. In the final position, White’s own e4-pawn only causes him trouble because it closes the important h1-a8 diagonal. Without this pawn, White would have had the upper hand. So the correct plan is a king transfer to  d4  prior to the advance e3-e4. }
1... Kf7 2. Kf4
{ As Grigoriev demonstrated,  2.Bg6+!  Ke7  3.Kf4  would be even more precise. However, even with an active king, Black is faced with severe problems. }
2... Kg7 3. Kf3 Kh6 4. Ke2 Kg5 5. Kd2 Kg4 6. Kc3 Kg5 7. Kd4 Bb7 8. e4
{ Diagram 16-58 } 8... dxe4
{ If now  8...Bc8  , then  9.exd5  exd5  10.Bf1  Kg6  11.Kd3  Kg5  12.Ke3  ⨀  Kg4  13.e6  +-. And if  12...Kg6  13.Kf4  or @@StartFEN@@2b5/8/p1p3k1/P1PpP3/1P6/3K4/8/5B2 b - - 3 11@@EndFEN@@  12...Bb7  13.Bh3  . }
9. Bxe4 Kh5 10. Kd3 Kg5 11. Ke3 Kh6
{ 11...Ba8  12.b5!  axb5  13.a6  b4  14.Bc2  ∆ Bb3 +-   11...Kg4  12.Bg6  Kg5  13.Bf7!  Kf5  14.Kd4  Bc8  15.Be8  Bb7  16.Bd7  ⨀ +- }
12. Kf4 Kg7 13. Kg5 Kf7 14. Kh6 Ke7 15. Kg7 Ba8 16. b5 axb5 17. a6
{ White wins. } *

