{ It is not uncommon in such situations for Black to have a passed pawn too. The stronger sides strategy remains unchanged: White must still play for zugzwang. The defender, however, now has a new resource:  deflection.  Sometimes, the pawn distracts the bishop from controlling an important square, which the knight then immediately occupies. Or the reverse can happen: sometimes the knight is sacrificed to allow the pawn to queen.   Lisitsyn − Zagorovsky    1.Be8?  would be a mistake in view of  1...h5!  (deflection)  2.Bxh5  Nd7+  3.Ke6  Nb6  The knight stands far away from the king, and the position would be drawn. }
1. Bf5 h5 2. Ke6 h4 3. Kf6 { Zugzwang. } 3... Nc6
{ 3...h3  is no better:  4.Bxh3  Ke4  5.Ke6  Kd4  6.Bf5  ⨀ } 4. d7 Nd8 5. Be6
{ ∆ Bd5, Ke7 } 5... Ke4 6. Bh3
{ The most accurate move, threatening 7.Bg2+ and 8.Ke7. But the immediate  6.Ke7  Nb7  7.Bc4  h3  8.Ba6  +-  was also possible. }
6... Kf3 7. Ke7 Nb7 { 7...Nc6+  8.Kd6  Nd8  9.Kc7  Nf7  10.Be6  +- } 8. Bf1 Kg3
9. Ba6 Nc5 10. d8=Q { Black resigned. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 7 – Bishop versus Knight"]
[Black "Bishop and Pawns vs. Knight 7-4"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/8/6b1/3k4/7P/4K3/1p1N4/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Now, here is a more complex example.  Nazarevsky − Simonenko, Kiev 1939 } 1.
h5
{ Exploiting the fact that the pawn is temporarily poisoned, to advance it further.  1...Bxh5?  2.Kd3=  On@@StartFEN@@8/8/6b1/3k4/7P/4K3/1p1N4/8 w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Ke2?  Kd4  the position is lost. }
1... Bh7 2. h6 Kc5 3. Ke2 Kd4 4. Kd1 Kc3
{ Let's examine the other attempts to play for zugzwang:   4...Bd3  5.Ke1  Ke3  works well if White plays  6.Kd1?  Kf2  ⨀ -+ But White saves himself if he sacrifices a pawn to deflect the bishop:@@StartFEN@@8/8/7P/8/8/3bk3/1p1N4/4K3 w - - 7 6@@EndFEN@@  6.h7!  Bxh7  7.Nc4+   4...Kd3  5.Ke1  Kc3  Now not  6.Kd1?  Bd3  7.Ke1  Kc2  ⨀, but  6.Ke2!  Now  6...Bg6  is met by   And if  6...Kc2  then, White saves himself with the knight sacrifice indicated by Konstantinopolsky:  7.Nc4!!   Counting on  7.Ke1?  Bd3  ⨀ Or  7.Ke3?  Kd1  ⨀  7...Bd3+  8.Ke3  Bxc4  9.h7  b1=Q  10.h8=Q=  7.Ke1!  leading back to the game line.   7.Ke3?  Bd3  ⨀ Or  7.Kd1?  Bd3  8.Ke1  Kc2  ⨀  would be a mistake. }
5. Ke1 Kc2 6. Ke2 Bd3+ 7. Ke1 { 7.Ke3?  Kc3  ⨀  is a mistake. } 7... Kc1 8.
Nb3+ Kb1 9. Kd1
{ The final touch.   9.Nd2+?  Kc2  ⨀ Or  9.Kd2?  Ka2  10.Nc1+  Ka3  both lose. }
9... Bc2+ 10. Ke2 Bh7 11. Kd1 Bc2+ 12. Ke2 Bg6 13. Kd1 Bh5+ 14. Kd2 Ka2 15. h7
b1=Q 16. Nc1+ Ka3 17. h8=Q { Draw. } *

