{ 7/2. L. Katsnelson, 1979 } 1. Kb1
{ The line  1.g4?  Kc2  2.Nb2  Bg7  or  2.Nf2  Be3  3.Ne4  Kd3  is hopeless. But if White had no pawns in the latter case, he could have saved the game because of stalemate, @@StartFEN@@8/6b1/8/8/2p5/8/1Nk5/K7 w - - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Ka2  . This tactical idea can serve as an anchor, because White cannot avoid zugzwang anyway. }
1... Bg5 { 1...Bd2  2.g4  Bg5  3.g3 } 2. g4 Bd2 3. g5 Bxg5 4. g4
{ After  4.g3?  Bh6  5.g4  Bg5!  ⨀  6.Ka1  Kc2  White is lost because he has failed to get rid of his own pawn in time. }
4... Bh6 5. g5 Bxg5 6. Ka1 Kc2 7. Nb2 Bf6 { 7...c3  8.Na4= } 8. Ka2
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed. Taking the knight leads to stalemate and other moves allow White to capture the c-pawn. The draw is obvious.@@EndSquare@@ }
