{ If the bishop cannot handle the job on its own  (which is what happens most often)  , then the outcome depends upon the position of the defending king: can it prevent the bishop from being interfered with or driven off?  Y. Averbakh, 1958  With the king at a1 or b1, White would win by Kd5-c4-b5-a6-b7. But here  (or with the king at c1, also)  , Black's king is in time to help the bishop. }
1. Kd5
{ The other plan  1.Ke7  Kb3  or  1...Kc3  2.Nd8  Kc4  3.Ne6  Ba5  4.Kd6  Bb4+!  does not win for White either. It is important that White does not have the  5.Nc5  interference – the king covers that square. }
1... Kc3
{ Note Black's accurate first move.   1...Ka3?  would be refuted by  2.Kc4!  Ka4  3.Kc5  ⨀ +-  @@StartBracket@@this is how White wins if the king is on a2 in the starting position@@EndBracket@@.   And if  1...Kb3?  hoping for  2.Kc5?  Ka4  , when White is the one in zugzwang, then @@StartFEN@@8/2bP4/2N5/3K4/8/1k6/8/8 w - - 2 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nd4+  Kb4  3.Ne6  Ba5  4.Kc6  , with the unstoppable threat of interference by 5.Nc7. }
2. Kc5 Kd3 3. Kb5 Ke4 4. Ka6 Kd5 5. Kb7 Kd6
{ Draw.  Ed. note: analyzed in the next variation → Diagram 7-9 EXTRA } *

