{ Tragicomedies: Stein − Dorfman, USSR 1970  The bishop has a hard time with a rook's pawn, since it has only one diagonal to work with. However, Dorfman played too straightforwardly and was unable to garner the full point. }
1... Nd3 2. Ba1 { Black threatened the interference  2...Nb2  . } 2... Nb2 3.
Ke1
{ 3.Ke3  must be answered by  3...Na4!  4.Ke2  Kc1!  (see below)  ,  or  4.Kd4  Kb1  5.Kd3  Nc5+  6.Kc3  Kxa1  -+ Whereas, in the game Sakaev-Sunye Neto  (Sao Paulo 1991)  , after  3...Kb1?  4.Kd2!  the win was gone. }
3... Kb1
{ The road to victory was noted as far back as the 19th century by Horwitz. Black should have played  3...Na4!  instead of 3...Kb1?  4.Ke2  Kc1  . Possible variations are:  a.  5.Kd3  Kb1  6.Kd2  Nb2  ⨀  7.Kc3  Kxa1  8.Kc2  Nd3  ⨀ -+   b.  5.Ke3  Kb1  6.Kd2  Nb2  ⨀ and if  6.Kd3  Nc5+!   Of course not  6...Kxa1?  7.Kc2=  7.Kd2  Nb3+  or @@StartFEN@@8/8/8/2n5/8/3K4/p7/Bk6 w - - 11 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Kc3  Kxa1  8.Kc2  Nb3  or  8...Nd3  ⨀ -+   c.  5.Ke1  Nc5!  6.Ke2  Kb1  7.Kd1  Nd3  8.Kd2  Nb2  ⨀ +- Trying to get the bishop out on move 6 or 7, doesn't help:  6.Bg7  Nd3+  and 7...Nb2 or  7.Bg7  Na4  . }
4. Kd2 Kxa1 5. Kc1 Nc4 6. Kc2
{ Draw. We know the concluding position from the chapter 'Knight vs. Pawns' @@StartBracket@@seeDiagram 2-2@@EndBracket@@. }
