{ 7/4. A.Kalinin, 1974  The bishop is ready to hold the pawn from either diagonal. If it occupies the a3-f8 diagonal, then White must interfere by means of Ne7 before the black king can prevent this. From g7, the bishop can only be driven away by the knight from f5. There is a single  (and unusual)  way to solve both these problems in time. }
1. Ng2 Bb4+
{ If  1...Bg7  , then  2.Nh4!  , and 3. Nf5 cannot be prevented.  1...Kg6  also loses:  2.Nh4+  Kg5  3.Nf5!  Bb4+  4.Nd6  . Finally, @@StartFEN@@8/4KP1k/8/8/8/2b5/6N1/8 b - - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Bb2  2.Ke8  Ba3  transposes to the main line of the solution. }
2. Ke8 Ba3 { Or  2...Kg7  3.Nf4  Kf6  and Black loses the bishop:  4.Nd5+  . }
3. Nf4 { Or  3.Ne3 } 3... Kg7 4. Nd5 { ∆ 5.Ne7. } *

