{ Miles – Dzhindzhikhashvili, Tilburg 1978  Whereas in the preceding example Black’s king was forced to defend its pawns, here this role is played by the knight. In order to let his king break into the enemy camp, White uses the standard techniques of widening the beachhead and zugzwang. }
1. g4 hxg4 2. fxg4 Kg6 3. Kg3 Kg5
{ On  3...f5  4.gxf5+  exf5  5.Kf4!  decides. } 4. Kf3 Kh6
{ Nor does  4...e5  help, in view of  5.Kg3  Kg6  6.Kh4  Kh6  7.Bd8  Kg6  8.g5!  fxg5+  9.Bxg5  Nb8  10.Bd8  Nd7  11.Kg4  ⨀ +- And if @@StartFEN@@3B4/3n4/1p3pk1/p1p1p1P1/P1P1P2K/1P6/8/8 b - - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...f5  9.exf5+  Kxf5  10.Kh5  e4  11.g6  +- }
5. Kf4 Kg6 6. e5 fxe5+ { 6...f5  7.gxf5+  exf5  8.e6  +- } 7. Bxe5 Kf7 8. Bc7
Kf6 9. g5+ Kf7 10. Kg4 Kg6 11. Bd6
{ Black resigned. He is in zugzwang, and will find himself in zugzwang over and over again, since his knight is tied to the defense of the b6-pawn, and cannot budge.   For example:  11...e5  12.Bc7  ⨀  e4  13.Kf4  @@StartBracket@@13.Bd8@@EndBracket@@  13...e3  14.Kxe3  Kxg5  15.Ke4  +-, or  11...Kf7  12.Kh5  Kg7  13.Bc7  ⨀  Kh7  14.g6+  Kg7  15.Kg5  ⨀ +- And in case of @@StartFEN@@8/2Bn2k1/1p2p3/p1p3PK/P1P5/1P6/8/8 b - - 8 13@@EndFEN@@  13...e5  14.Kg4  +- }
