{ Spassky – Fischer, Santa Monica 1966  White would certainly love to play g2-g4  (for instance, in reply to 1...Nd6)  , tying one of the enemy pieces to the kingside. Then the king would move over to the queenside, and attack Black’s pawns. Fischer’s choice makes things considerably easier for White, since it gives him a passed pawn without even having to exchange pawns for it. }
1... g5 2. h5 Nh6 3. Kd3 Ke5 4. Ba8 Kd6 5. Kc4 g4 6. a4
{ Black’s king can only defend one of the two queenside pawns. Seeing that the a7-pawn is doomed, Spassky does not hurry to attack it, preferring to strengthen his position maximally first. }
6... Ng8 7. a5 Nh6 8. Be4 g3 9. Kb5 Ng8 10. Bb1 Nh6 11. Ka6 Kc6 12. Ba2
{ Black resigned.  Ed. note: analyzed in the next variation → Diagram 7-23 } *

