{ 7/7. L. Katsnelson, L. Mitrofanov, 1977  The bishop clearly dominates the knight. White's hopes are based on the reduced material on the board and on theRéti idea that we have discussed in the chapter on pawn endgames. }
1. Kc7
{ Both  1.c7?  Bd6  2.Kb7  Bxc7  3.Kxc7  Kh3  and @@StartFEN@@1K6/8/2P5/8/6pk/bp6/7P/3N4 w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Kb7?  Bd6  2.Kb6  Kh3  or  2...Bxh2  3.Kb5  Bc7  4.Kc4  g3  lose. }
1... b2
{ An immediate draw results from  1...Bb4  2.Kb6  Bd6  3.Kb5  Bxh2  4.Kc4  and if @@StartFEN@@8/8/2Pb4/1K6/6pk/1p6/7P/3N4 b - - 5 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Kh3  4.Kc4  Kxh2  5.Kxb3  g3  6.Ne3=   The consequences of  1...Bc5!?  are less obvious:  2.Kd7  Bb6  3.Ke6  Kh3   3...Bc7  4.Kd5  ∆ Kc4=  4.Kf5  , the king must move away from the b3-pawn because the threat 4...Kxh2 should be prevented,  4...Bc7  5.Nf2+   A safer alternative is  5.Ke4!  Kxh2  6.Kd3  followed with 7.Ne3.  Diagram 16-62  a.  5...Kxh2  6.Nxg4+  Kg1  7.Ne5!  b2  8.Nf3+  Kf2  9.Nd2  Ke2  10.Nb1=   b.  5...Kh4  6.Nd1!  Bxh2  7.Ke4!  Bc7  8.Kd3  g3  9.Ne3  Kg5  10.Kc3=   c.  5...Kg2  6.Nd3!  Kf3  7.Ne5+!  Ke3  8.Nc4+  Kd4  9.Nb2  Bxh2  10.Kxg4= }
2. Nxb2 { 2.Nc3?  Bb4  -+ } 2... Bxb2 3. Kd6 Bc1 4. Ke5 Kg5
{ The only way to stop the c-pawn.  Diagram 16-63 } 5. Ke4 Bf4 6. h4+ gxh3 7.
Kf3 Kf5 8. Kf2 Bh2 9. c7 { Draw. } *

