[SetUp "1"]

{ Stoltz − Kashdan, The Hague ol 1928  (continued) } 1. Nf3
{ 6.f3  Ba6+  7.Ke3  Kc5  8.Nc2  should have been preferred.  Here is Averbakh's suggested continuation:  8...Bf1  9.g3  Ba6  10.Nd4  Kb4  runs into  11.Nc6+  and if @@StartFEN@@8/p4ppp/b7/2k5/3N3P/1P2KPP1/8/8 b - - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  10...Bb7  11.Kd3  Kb4  12.Kc2  Bd5  13.Kb2  g6  14.Kc2  a6  15.Kb2  and it is still not clear how Black will break down his opponent's resistance. }
1... Ba6+ 2. Kc3
{ On  7.Ke3  Kc5  8.Ng5?  Kb4  9.Nxf7  Kxb3  the a-pawn decides.  8.Nd4  is called for. }
2... h6 3. Nd4 { 8.g3  is necessary. } 3... g6
{ 8...Ke4  gives good winning chances. } 4. Nc2
{ 9.f3  is stronger, taking the important e4-square under control. } 4... Ke4
5. Ne3 f5
{ Black has deployed his king to maximum effect. He intends to drive the knight from e3, and then to attack the g2-pawn with his bishop. }
6. Kd2 f4 7. Ng4
{ Hopeless is  12.Nc2  Bf1!  13.Ne1  Kf5  ∆ 14...Kg4,  14.f3  g5  15.hxg5  Kxg5!  and the king reaches g3. }
7... h5 8. Nf6+ Kf5
