{ Stoltz − Kashdan, The Hague ol 1928  (continued) } 1. Nd7
{ Once again Stoltz fails to show defensive grit. As Müller and Lamprecht indicate, Black's task would have been considerably more difficult after  14.Nh7!  Kg4   14...Bf1  15.f3  and if  15...Bxg2  then  16.Ke2  .  15.Nf8  Kxh4  16.Nxg6+  Kg5  17.Ne5  Kf5  18.Nf3   The pawn endgame after  18.Nd3  Bxd3  19.Kxd3  Kg4  20.Ke2  h4!  21.b4  a6  22.Kf1  Kf5  23.Ke1  Ke5!  is lost.  18...Bb7  19.Ke2  , but Black still wins with  19...a5  20.Nd4+  Ke4  21.Nc2  f3+  22.gxf3  Kf4  -+ @@StartBracket@@Burkhard Treiber@@EndBracket@@. }
1... Bc8
{ Excellent technique.   On  15.Nc5  Kg4  decides; however, the text is no improvement. }
2. Nf8 g5 3. g3 { Forced, after  16.hxg5  Kxg5  the knight is lost. } 3... gxh4
4. gxh4 Kg4 5. Ng6 Bf5 6. Ne7 Be6 7. b4 Kxh4 8. Kd3 Kg4 9. Ke4 h4 10. Nc6 Bf5+
11. Kd5 f3 { Of course not  24...h3?  25.Ne5+  and 26.Nf3. } 12. b5 h3 13. Nxa7
h2 14. b6 h1=Q 15. Nc6 Qb1 16. Kc5 Be4 { White resigned. } *

