{ Karpov – A. Sokolov, Linares cmf  (2)  1987  Which pawn should Black take?  In principle, when you have a knight against a bishop, the task is made easier, the narrower the battlefield: all the pawns should be on the same side.    From this point of view, the logical move is  1...Nxa4!  And in fact, this would have led to a draw:  2.Bd4  Kd6  3.Kb5   3.e5+  Ke6  4.h4  h6  5.Kb5  Nc5  6.Bxc5  bxc5  7.Kxc5  g5=  and if @@StartFEN@@8/7p/1p1k2p1/8/n1KBPP2/8/7P/8 w - - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Kb4  Nc5  4.Bxc5+  bxc5+  5.Kb5  g5=  3...Nc5  4.Bxc5+  bxc5  (∆ 5...g5)  5.h4  h6  6.Kc4  Kc6  7.e5  h5  ⨀= }
1... Nxe4 2. Kb5 Nc5 3. Bf8
{ Sokolov probably counted on  3.Bd4?  Nxa4!  4.Kxa4  Kf5  5.Be3  Kg4  6.Kb5  Kh3= }
3... Nd7 { Now  3...Nxa4  4.Kxa4  Kf5  5.Bd6  +- no longer helps. } 4. Ba3 Kd5
5. Be7 Kd4 6. Bd8 { Black resigned. } *

