{ Tragicomedies: Krnic − Flear, Wijk aan Zee 1988  (analysis) } 3. Kh6
{ It is odd that Flear recommends  3.Kh6  , instead of  3.a4  . The grandmaster even awards this move an exclamation point, although in point of fact it deserves a question mark, and, according to analysis by Zviagintsev and Dvoretsky, it probably lets the win slip. }
3... a5 { Flear examines only the weaker  3...Nb6  and  3...a6  . } 4. Bc5
{ 4.a4  Nd6  5.Kg5  Nc4 } 4... a4 5. h3
{ 5.Kh7  Kf6  6.Kg8  g5  is not better. } 5... Kf6 6. h4 Kf5 7. Kg7 Kg4
{ Diagram 7-34  In order to understand what follows, we must recall the conclusions we reached when studying Rauzer’s positions with bishop and pawn vs. bishop @@StartBracket@@diagrams4-2 and4-2 b & c@@EndBracket@@. }
8. Kf6
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed.  6.Kxg6  is analyzed in the next variation → Diagram 7-35@@EndSquare@@ }
8... Kxh4 9. Ke6 Kg4 10. Kd7 Kf5 11. Kxc8 Ke6
{ Black has no trouble drawing with the white pawn on a3. Here, the pawn is on a2, which would give White a win @@StartBracket@@although a rather complicated one@@EndBracket@@, if there were not a black g-pawn on the board. That of course changes the evaluation. }
