{ 7/8. Chekhover-Lasker, Moscow 1935  Black stands better  (his bishop is obviously better than the knight)  but he must play accurately. }
1... b5
{ After  1...Bb2?  2.a4  Kb6  3.Ke1  Ka5  4.Kd2  Kb4  5.Kc2  , White manages to defend his queenside in time. If  1...Kc6?!  2.Ke1  b5  3.Kd2  Bb2  , Black must take into account  4.b4!  Bxa3  5.Kc3  a5  @@StartBracket@@he has nothing else@@EndBracket@@  6.bxa5  . }
2. Ke1 Bb2 3. a4 bxa4 4. bxa4 Kc6
{ Black cannot eliminate the a4-pawn  4...Kb6  5.Kd2  Ka5?  6.Kc2  Be5  7.f4  Bd6  8.Kb3=  , therefore the king goes to the center. }
5. Kd2 Kc5 { Diagram 16-64 } 6. Kc2
{ As Müller indicates, White could have answered the text with @@StartFEN@@8/5p1p/4pp2/pN6/Pk2P3/8/1b1K1PPP/8 w - - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Kd3!  because  8...Kxa4  9.Kc4  traps the king on the edge of the board, making it extremely difficult for his opponent to make the most of his advantage. }
6... Bd4 7. f3 Kc4 8. Nxd4 Kxd4 9. Kb3 a5 { Black wins. } *

