{ Pirrot – Yusupov, Germany tt 1992    1...Bxa2  2.Kf2  ∆ Ke3 would lead to a roughly equal position. Yusupov finds the best practical chance. }
1... f5 2. Nc3
{ His opponent gets greedy: by maintaining the balance of material, he loses the game.  2.Nd2!  was necessary @@StartBracket@@blockading the passed pawn@@EndBracket@@  2...Bxa2  3.f4  @@StartBracket@@fixing the enemy pawn on the same color square as the bishop@@EndBracket@@,  3...Ke7  4.Kf2  Bd5  5.g3  Kd6  6.Ke3  Be4  7.Kd4  , and there appears to be no way to break into the fortress White has constructed. On the other hand, @@StartFEN@@5k2/6pp/8/5p2/p7/3p1P2/bP1N2PP/6K1 w - - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Kf2  f4  4.Ne4  Ke7  5.Ke1  or  5.g3  was good, too. }
2... d2 { Threatening  3.--  Be2  . } 3. Kf2 f4
{ White’s position has become hopeless, since his king is cut off forever from the passed pawn. }
4. b3 axb3 5. axb3 Bd3 6. g3 g5 7. h4 h6
{ There is no need to calculate the variation  7...fxg3+  8.Kxg3  gxh4+  9.Kxh4  Be2  , since the text provides a much simpler resolution. }
8. hxg5 hxg5 9. gxf4 gxf4 { White resigned in view of } 10. Nd1
{ 10.Kg2  Be2  11.Kh3  Bxf3  -+ } 10... Ke7 11. Nb2 Kd6 12. Nd1 Kc5 13. Nb2 Kb5
14. Nd1 Kb4 { Black wins. } *

