{ 7/9. Spassky-Botvinnik, USSR ch tt, Moscow, 1966  What can White do against a march of the black king to the a2-pawn? Botvinnik indicated the correct defensive plan: White should hold the enemy king on the edge by posting his own king on c2, while the knight must block the passed pawn from e2. }
1. Nf1
{ In the game, however,  1.Nc4?  was played. Here the knight is placed too far from  e2  , thus the defensive plan that we have discussed does not work, and no other plan exists.  1...Kc3  2.Kd1  Bd4  @@StartBracket@@∆ 3...Kd3@@EndBracket@@  3.Ke2  e3  4.Na5   The pawn ending after  4.Nxe3  Bxe3  is lost.  4...Kb2  5.Nc6  Bc5  6.Ne5  Kxa2  7.Nd3  Be7  White resigned. }
1... Kc3
{ Instead of  1...Kc3  , Black has a more poisonous possibility:  1...Bc7!?  creating difficulties for a knight march to  e2  . But White manages to hold in this case, too:  2.Ne3  Bf4  now not  3.Nc4?!  Kc5  , but  3.Ng4  Bg5   3...Kc3  4.Nf6  Kb2  5.Nd5!  Bd6  6.Kd1  Kxa2  7.Kc2  Ka3  8.Ne3  Bf4  9.Nf5  e3  10.Nd4=  4.Nf2  Ke5  5.Ng4+  Kf5  6.Nf2  Bc1  7.Nh3  Bb2  8.Ke3!  Ke5  9.Ke2  Bd4  10.Ng5  Kf5  11.Nf7  @@StartBracket@@analysis by Averbakh@@EndBracket@@. }
2. Ng3 e3 3. Kd1 Kb2 4. Ne2 Kxa2 5. Kc2
{ And White has built an indestructible fortress. } *

