{ 7/10. Petrosian-Fischer, Buenos Aires  (m/6)  , 1971  (variation) } 1. Nh1
{ 1.Nd1?  loses to  1...Kb3  2.Nxe3  dxe3  3.Kxe3  Kc3  , and the opposition is decisive, and  1.Nh3?  of course is totally hopeless. }
1... Bf4 2. Kc2
{ Forming a barrier can sometimes be even more important than material. After  2.h3?  Kb3  3.Ke2   3.Nf2  Be3  is similar.  3...Be3!  4.Kd3  Kb2  5.Ng3  Kc1  6.Nh5  Kd1  7.Nxf6  Ke1  8.Nxh7  Kf2  ,  the black king penetrates, takes the h3- and f3-pawns, and wins the g4-pawn by zugzwang. }
2... Bxh2 3. Nf2 Bg3 4. Nd3 Kb5 { 4...Ka3  5.Nc5  Kb4  6.Nd7  Kc4  7.Nb6+ } 5.
Kb3
{ Surprisingly, the white knight and king imprison the black bishop. Black does have one more plan: the king can walk to the kingside and prepare ...h5, but for this, the bishop will need to come back to d8, and White can prevent that. }
5... Kc6 6. Kc2 Kd6 7. Kd1 Ke7 8. Nb4
{ Having taken away the e1-square from the bishop, the knight can move to a more active post. }
8... Kf7 9. Nd5 Kg6 { 9...Bf4  10.Kc2!  , stopping the threat of  ...d3+  . }
10. Ne7+ { And Black cannot make progress. } *

