{ The Knight is Superior to the Bishop    Domination and Knight Forks   Nepomniaschy − Polovodin, Leningrad ch 1988 }
1... Nc3
{ The key to the position is that on  2.a3  Ne2!!  decides:  3.Kxe2  bxa3  and if  3.axb4  Nf4+  . Without this little combination, based upon a knight fork, there would be no win @@StartBracket@@with the bishop at  f3  , let’s say, the position is drawn@@EndBracket@@. }
2. Bf3 Nxa2 3. Bd1 b3
{ Once again, Black has recourse to a fork, in order to advance his passed pawn  4.Bxb3  Nc1+  5.Kc3  Nxb3  6.Kxb3  Kb5  ⨀ loses at once. On the other hand, @@StartFEN@@8/6p1/2k2p2/3p1P2/1p1P2P1/3K4/n7/3B4 b - - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Kb5  4.Bc2  Nc1+  5.Kd2  b3  is strong, too. }
4. Kd2 b2 5. Bc2 { 5.Kc2  Nc3  -+ } 5... Nb4 6. Bb1 Kb6
{ An outstanding loss of tempo!   The straightforward  6...Kb5?  7.Kc3  ⨀  Ka4  8.Kxb2=  and if @@StartFEN@@8/6p1/5p2/1k1p1P2/1n1P2P1/2K5/1p6/1B6 b - - 5 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nc6  8.Ba2  Ne7  9.Kb3  leads to a draw. }
7. Kc3 Kb5 8. Kb3 { 8.Kxb2  Kc4  -+ } 8... Nc6 9. Kc3
{ 9.Bd3+  Ka5  10.Kxb2  Kb4  -+  is no better. } 9... Ka4 10. Kxb2
{ 10.Ba2  Ka3  -+ } 10... Nb4
{ Zugzwang. But not  10...Nxd4?  11.Ba2=   Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 7-45 }
*

