{ Nepomniaschy − Polovodin, Leningrad ch 1988  (continued)   A picturesque domination of the knight over the bishop! Note that the knight takes away only three of the bishop’s squares. Another is controlled by the d5-pawn @@StartBracket@@the pawns’ placement on the squares of the same color as the opposing bishop is one of the means of restricting its mobility@@EndBracket@@. But the chief blame for White’s helplessness lies with his own kingside pawns, placed on squares the same color as his bishop, and turning it “bad.” }
