{ Fixing The Pawns   We have already pointed out more than once how important it is to fix the enemy pawns on the same color squares as his bishop. Thus, we limit ourselves here to looking at two new examples.  Osnos − Bukhman, Leningrad ch tt 1968  The advantage, of course, is White's, since all his opponent's pawns are isolated and weak. But this might not have been enough to win, had White not found the following maneuver, forcing the d-pawn to advance onto a square the same color as his bishop. }
1. Nd5 Kg7 2. Nb6 Bb3 3. Nc8 d5 4. Ne7 h5 5. h4
{ One more pawn fixed on a light square. } 5... Kf8 6. Nf5 Bc2 7. Ne3 Bb3 8.
Kh2 Ke7 9. Nf5+ Ke6 { A terrible blunder in a hopeless position. } 10. Nd4+
{ Black resigned.  Diagram 7-50 has been intentionally omitted. } *

