{ Karpov – Kasparov, Moscow wm  (9)  1984/85  White’s task here is considerably more complicated. For the time being, the king has no route into the enemy camp; he must continue by “widening the beachhead.” The interfering kingside pawns can be removed in two ways: by g3-g4, or by exchanging on g5, followed by f3-f4. }
1... gxh4
{ The best defense was  1...Ke6!  On  2.hxg5  fxg5  3.f4  , Black can draw either by  3...gxf4  4.gxf4  Bg6  , or by  3...g4!?=   And after  1...Ke6!  2.g4  hxg4  3.hxg5  , as John Nunn points out, Black must play  3...gxf3!   3...fxg5  4.Nxg4  , followed by Kg3 and f3-f4, would be weaker.  4.gxf6  would be met by  4...Be4  . And in case of  4.Kxf3  fxg5  5.Kg4  Kf6  6.Nxd5+  Kg6=   White keeps more practical chances by refraining from @@StartFEN@@8/8/p3kp2/1p1p2p1/1P1P2pP/P3NP2/5K2/1b6 w - - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.hxg5  in favor of  3.Nxg4!?  gxh4  4.Kg2  . And  2.Kg2!?  gxh4  3.g4!  is also worth looking into.   After home analysis, Kasparov decided to alter the pawn structure, judging @@StartBracket@@correctly@@EndBracket@@ that after  2.gxh4  Bg6  White could no longer break through. Alas, neither he nor his trainers could foresee White’s tremendous retort, securing his king a road into the enemy camp. }
2. Ng2 hxg3+ { 2...h3  3.Nf4  +- } 3. Kxg3 Ke6 4. Nf4+ Kf5 5. Nxh5
{ Threatening Ng7-e8-c7. } 5... Ke6 6. Nf4+ Kd6 7. Kg4 Bc2 8. Kh5 Bd1 9. Kg6
{ Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 7-54 } *

