{ Karpov − Kasparov, Moscow wm  (9)  1984/85  (analysis) } 9... Ke7
{ 9...Bxf3  10.Kxf6  is absolutely hopeless. In such situations, we employ the  steady driving off of the enemy king:  the knight goes to  f5  , and after the king’s forced retreat @@StartBracket@@since the pawn endgame is lost@@EndBracket@@, White’s king goes to  e5  or  e7  . Then the knight gives check again, etc. }
10. Nxd5+
{ Unjustified greed – now Black gets the chance to activate his king, via the newly-opened d5-square.  Ed. note: analyzed in the next two variations → Diagram 7-55 & 7-56 and the game continuation is given in Diagram 7-57. }
