{ Karpov − Kasparov, Moscow wm  (9)  1984/85  (analysis) } 10. Nh5 Bxf3 11.
Nxf6 { Was far stronger. } 11... Be4+
{ The best defense.   11...Ke6?  12.Ne8  @@StartBracket@@∆ 13.Nc7+@@EndBracket@@  12...Be4+  13.Kg5  Kd7  14.Nf6+  Ke6  15.Nxe4  dxe4  16.Kf4  Kd5  17.Ke3  ⨀ +- In case of @@StartFEN@@*4N3/8/p3k1K1/1p1p4/1P1P4/P4b2/8/8 b - - 2 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Kd7  13.Ng7  Ke7  @@StartBracket@@otherwise 14.Kf6@@EndBracket@@  14.Kf5  , and White wins. }
12. Kg5 Bd3
{ Diagram 7-55 White cannot gain control of the f6- or e5- squares with his king.   Capturing the pawn is also unconvincing:  13.Nxd5+  Kd6  14.Ne3  or  14.Nf4  does not change anything, so  14.Nc3  Bf1!  15.Kf4  Bg2  16.Ke3  @@StartBracket@@intending Ne4-c5@@EndBracket@@  16...Bh3!  17.Ne4+  Kd5  18.Nc5  Bc8  19.Kd3  Bf5+  20.Kc3  Bc8  , and Black is apparently out of danger.  I thought that the variations I had found were sufficient to demonstrate that the position was drawn. However, grandmaster Mihail Marin suggested an extremely dangerous plan: }
13. Ng4
{ With the idea of continuing Ne5-c6-b8. I attempted to hold the line by }
13... Bf1 14. Ne5 Bh3
{ And now  15.Nc6+  Kd6  16.Na5   16.Nb8??  Bc8  and  17.--  Kc7  .  16...Ke7!  17.Nb3  Kf7  18.Nc5  Bc8  is useless, while winning the d-pawn by  15.Ng6+  Kf7!  16.Nf4  Bc8  17.Nxd5  Ke6  would lead to the drawn position we already know. But Marin showed that White could play for zugzwang: }
15. Kg6 Ke6 16. Nc6 Kd6 { 16...Bf5+  17.Kg5  and 18.Nb8. } 17. Na5 Ke7 18. Nb3
Bd7 19. Nc5 Bc8 20. Kg7 { Black loses the a6-pawn. But not  20.Kg5  Kf7  . }
20... Bf5
{ On the other hand, Black’s resistance is not yet broken – he can lock the king in at g7 for a while. }
21. Nxa6 Bd3 { Ed. note: analyzed in the next variation → Diagram 7-56 } *

