{ Karpov − Kasparov, Moscow wm  (9)  1984/85  (continued) } 10... Ke6
{ 10...Kd6!?  was more precise, leading, after  11.Nxf6  Bxf3  or  11.Nc3  Bxf3  12.Kxf6  Bg2  , to a position examined in the last note. @@StartSquare@@Ed. see the previous variation → Diagram 7-56@@EndSquare@@ }
11. Nc7+ { Diagram 7-57 } 11... Kd7
{ Now Black will be two pawns down.  11...Kd6  was stronger. If  12.Ne8+  then  12...Ke7   12...Kd5  13.f4  is inferior.  13.Nxf6  Bxf3  14.Kf5  Kd6  15.Kf4  Bg2  16.Ke3  Bh3  , leading to roughly the same positions as after 10...Kd6. And on @@StartFEN@@8/2N5/p2k1pK1/1p6/1P1P4/P4P2/8/3b4 w - - 3 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Nxa6  there follows  12...Bxf3  13.Kxf6  Kd5  . }
12. Nxa6 Bxf3 13. Kxf6 Kd6 14. Kf5 Kd5 15. Kf4 Bh1 16. Ke3 Kc4 17. Nc5 Bc6 18.
Nd3 Bg2
{ 18...Be8!?  19.Ne5+  Kd5  was worth considering. Even with two extra pawns, the outcome is still far from clear – Black’s king is too active. He must only be careful not to go after the a3-pawn @@StartBracket@@when White will lock him in by putting his own king at c3@@EndBracket@@. }
19. Ne5+ Kc3 { 19...Kd5!? } 20. Ng6 Kc4 21. Ne7
