{ Karpov − Kasparov, Moscow wm  (9)  1984/85  (continued) } 21... Bb7
{ 21...Kb3?  would not have worked in view of  22.d5  Kxa3  23.d6  Bh3  24.Nd5  .   However, it would be safer to keep the bishop in the lower half of the board:  21...Bh1!  22.d5?  Bxd5=  and if @@StartFEN@@8/4N3/8/1p6/1PkP4/P3K3/8/7b w - - 1 22@@EndFEN@@  22.Nf5  Kd5  . In this position, White’s advantage is insufficient to win. The move Black actually played is a decisive mistake. }
22. Nf5 Bg2
{ As Speelman and Tisdall indicated, neither  22...Kc3?  23.Kf4!  Kb3  24.Ne7  Kxa3  25.d5  , nor @@StartFEN@@8/1b6/8/1p3N2/1PkP4/P3K3/8/8 b - - 2 22@@EndFEN@@  22...Bc6?  23.Kf4  Kb3  24.Ke5  Kxa3  25.Kd6  Be4  26.Ng3  would save Black. @@StartSquare@@Ed. note: a better defense for Black is given next → Diagram 7-59@@EndSquare@@ }
23. Nd6+ Kb3 24. Nxb5 Ka4 25. Nd6 { Black resigned. } *

