{ Karpov − Kasparov, Moscow wm  (9)  1984/85  (analysis) } 22... Kd5
{ This is what Black should have played. } 23. Kd3 Ke6 24. Ne3
{ 24.Ng3  Bg2  25.Ne4  Bf1+  26.Ke3  Kd5  27.Nc3+  Kc4= } 24... Bf3
{ Diagram 7-59 It is important to prevent White’s knight from reaching c3. }
25. Kc3
{ An interesting try.   On  25.Kd2  , intending to march the king into the enemy camp, Black does not respond with  25...Kf6?  26.Nd1!  and 27. Nc3 @@StartBracket@@since Black no longer has 26...Kd5@@EndBracket@@, but simply waits – when White’s king reaches the eighth rank, the bishop will cut off its path to the queenside along the h3-c8 diagonal.   25.d5+  Ke5!  Leads to nothing. But not  25...Bxd5?  26.Kd4  ∆ 27.Kc5. }
25... Kd6
{ Otherwise @@StartFEN@@8/8/4k3/1p6/1P1P4/P1K1Nb2/8/8 w - - 6 25@@EndFEN@@  26.Kb3  followed by 27.a4 – Black cannot reply  26...Bc6  , because of  27.d5+! }
26. a4 { 26.Kb3  Bc6  27.d5  Be8  28.Kc3  Ke5= } 26... bxa4 27. Nc4+ Kd5
{ 27...Kc7?  28.b5  +- } 28. Nb6+
{ 28.b5  Be2  29.b6  Kc6  30.d5+  Kb7  31.d6  Kc6= } 28... Kc6 29. Nxa4 Kb5
{ Or  29...Bh5  . Paradoxically, two extra pawns are insufficient to win here – White has no way to strengthen his position.   Ed. note: White's winning continuation is presented in the next variation → Diagram 7-59 EXTRA. }
