{ Karpov − Kasparov, Moscow wm  (9)  1984/85  (analysis)   And nevertheless, Karsten Müller has found a subtle means of getting the knight to the key c3-square. After }
22... Kd5 23. Kd3 Ke6 { White plays } 24. Ng7+ Kd7 { 24...Kd6  25.Ne8+ } 25.
Nh5 Bg2
{ Hoping for  26.Ng3?  Ke6!  27.Ne4  Bf1+  and  28.--  Kd5  .   On  25...Kd6  there follows, not  26.Nf4?  Bc8!  and  27.--  Bf5+  but instead,  26.Nf6!  or  26.Ng3!  , and then 27.Ne4+ and 28.Nc3. }
26. Nf4 Bf1+ 27. Ke4 Kd6 28. Ke3 { Zugzwang. } 28... Bc4
{ 28...Kc6  29.d5+  Kd6  30.Kd4  Bc4  31.a4  +- } 29. Ne2 Kd5 30. Nc3+
{ When the c4-square, which is needed by the king, is occupied by the bishop. }
