{ 7/14. Popa-Galic, Bucharest 1938 } 1. Kd3
{ White would have gladly brought his knight to e6, but there is no way to get to that square. If he attacks the c7-pawn, the bishop will protect it. Black is not afraid of zugzwang because he has two squares for his king: f6 and g6.  White cannot do without a king transfer to the queenside. The black king can only reach c8; White places his king on a8 and drives Black away with a knight check from a7. }
1... Kf7 2. Kc4 Ke8 3. Kb5 Kd8 4. Ka6 Kc8 5. Ka7 Bf6 6. Ne4 Be7 7. Ka8 Bd8 8.
Nc3 Bf6 9. Nb5 { The remainder of the game was: } 9... e4 10. fxe4 Be5 11. Na7+
Kd8 12. Kb7 Bc3 13. Nb5 Ba5 14. Nxd6
{ The simple  14.Nd4  ∆ Ne6+, was good enough, too. } 14... cxd6 15. e5 Bc7 16.
e6 Ba5 17. e7+ Kxe7 18. c7 Bxc7 19. Kxc7 { Black resigned. } *

