{ 7/15. Botvinnik-Eliskases, Moscow 1936  After the game, Botvinnik found the correct solution: }
1. Kc3
{ The advance c5-c6 is prepared.   Generally, it is useful to press Black even more by advancing the pawn to c6. However the immediate  1.c6?  was met with  1...Bd3  2.Kc3  b5!  , and White had to accept the draw because the line  3.Nd4  Bc4  4.Ne6  Bxd5  5.Nxc7?  Bxc6  is senseless. Instead of 5.Nxc7?, White has  5.Nd4=  . }
1... Bb7
{ 1...Bd3  2.Nd4  b5  3.Ne6  +- and if  2...bxc5  3.bxc5  dxc5  4.Nb3  c4  . The pawn ending that results after  5.Na5  Bf1  6.Nxc4?  Bxc4  7.Kxc4  Ke7  ⨀ is drawn @@StartBracket@@the corresponding squares are c5/d7, d4/d6, c4/e7; the correspondence is favorable for Black now, and White cannot cede the move to him@@EndBracket@@.  However @@StartFEN@@bxc5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nd4!  Bf1  6.Nb5  Ke7  7.Nxc7  Kd6  8.Nb5+  Kxd5  9.Nd4  wins. }
2. c6 Bc8 { 2...Ba6  3.Nd4  ∆ Ne6. } 3. Nd4 Ke7
{ Diagram 16-66   A try for zugzwang seems attractive now:  4.Nb5  Kd8  5.Na7?  Black responds with  5...Ba6!  6.b5  Bc8  7.Kd4  ⨀  Ke7  8.Nxc8+  Kd8  9.Na7  Ke7=  , and it suddenly becomes clear that Black has built a fortress, so the extra knight cannot be utilized. }
4. Kb3
{ Planning a king transfer to b5 followed by a knight sacrifice on b6.   Another winning method was suggested by Inarkiev:  4.b5!  Kd8  5.Nc2  Ke8  6.Nb4  Ke7  7.Na6  Kd8  8.Kc4  and Black is in zugzwang. }
4... Kd8 5. Ka4 Ke7 6. Kb5 { ∆ Nc2-a3, c4xb6 } *

