{ I. Maizelis, 1950  Let us look at a slightly more complicated case in the following diagram. }
1... Kc5
{ Only this move holds. Black does not allow the white king to approach his pawn.   1...a5?  is bad because of  2.Rh5!  cutting the king off. However  1...Kb5?  2.Kf7  a5  3.Ke6  a4  4.Kd5  is no better.  @@StartSquare@@Ed. In the book, the line ends here, but for completeness' sake, we will continue it a bit longer. }
2. Kf7 a5 3. Ke6 a4 4. Ke5 a3 5. Ra8 Kb4 6. Kd4 Kb3 7. Kd3 Kb2
{ We have transposed to known territory →Diagram 8-6@@EndSquare@@ } *

