[SetUp "1"]

{ Alekhine – Bogoljubow, Germany/The Netherlands wm  (19)  1929 } 1... Kg4
{ The world championship challenger resigned shortly after playing this move. He should have applied the shouldering method:  1...Ke4!  It is easy to see that in this case the position would have been drawish: the black king prevents his opponent from getting to the black pawn in time. }
2. b7 f5 3. b8=Q Rxb8 4. Rxb8 f4 5. Kd5
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed. It is important to start with the text move. Instead  5.Rf8?  allows Black to repair his mistake with  5...Kf3  6.Kd5  Ke3!  , reapplying the shouldering method and making a draw.@@EndSquare@@ }
5... f3 6. Ke4 f2 7. Rf8 Kg3 8. Ke3 { White wins. } *

