{ 8/1. A. Troitsky, 1912 } 1. dxe6 Rc1+ 2. Kf2
{ Not  2.Kg2?  Rxh1  3.Kxh1  Kc6  ,  and the knight is unable to protect the e-pawn. }
2... Rxh1 3. e7 Rh2+ 4. Kf3
{ 4.Ke3?  is wrong in view of  4...Rh5!=  First of all, White should eliminate the f6-pawn. }
4... Rh3+ 5. Kf4 Rh4+ 6. Kf5 Rh5+ 7. Kxf6 Rh6+ 8. Kf5
{ Rather than  8.Ke5?  Rh1  9.Nf6  Rh8  10.Nd7+  Kc7  11.Nf8  Rh1= } 8... Rh5+
9. Kf4 Rh4+ 10. Kf3 Rh3+ 11. Ke2 Rh2+ 12. Kd3 Rh3+ 13. Kd4 Rh4+ 14. Kd5 Rh5+
15. Kd6 { Diagram 16-67 } 15... Rh6+
{ If  15...Rh1  then  16.Nf6  Re1  17.Nd7+  and 18.Ne5+- } 16. Nf6 Rxf6+
{ 16...Rh8  17.Nd7+  and 18.Nf8+- } 17. Kd5 Rf5+ 18. Kd4 Rf4+ 19. Kd3 Rf3+ 20.
Ke2 { The king had to take two tours − up-and downstairs! } *

