{ 8/3. P. Benko, 1980 } 1. Rh1+
{ The line  1.Kc3?  a1=Q+  2.Kb3  Qa8 !  -+  is clearly unacceptable.   By analogy with the previous exercise  1.d5  exd5  2.Kc3  a1=Q?  3.Kb3  +- seems attractive, inasmuch as after  2...a1=N?  3.Rh4  the knight is lost:  3...Ka2  4.Rd4  Ka3  5.Rxd5  Nb3  6.Rb5  +- But Black manages to hold after @@StartFEN@@8/8/8/3p4/8/2K5/p6R/1k6 b - - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d4+!  3.Kb3  a1=N+!=  The winning method is known from pawn endgame theory − a 'half-stalemate'. }
1... Kb2 2. Ra1 Kxa1 3. Kc2 e5 4. d5 e4 5. d6 e3 6. d7 e2 7. d8=Q e1=N+
{ 7...e1=Q  8.Qd4+  # } 8. Kb3 { 8.Kc3  Nd3  9.Qb6  +- } 8... Nd3 9. Qd4+
{ White wins. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
