[SetUp "1"]

{ 8/6. N. Kopaev, 1954  Being well-armed with the experience of previous examples, we can find White's initial move, perhaps almost automatically. }
1. Rf7+ Kg3
{ If  1...Ke3  then  2.Rg7!  Kf4  3.Kf7  g4  4.Kg6!  g3  5.Kh5  +- } 2. Ke7 g4
{ Diagram 16-69 } 3. Ke6
{ 3.Kf6?  is bad in view of  3...Kf4!!  (shouldering)  4.Kg6+  Ke3!= } 3... Kh2
4. Kf5
{ 4.Ke5  is also playable, while the check  4.Rh7+?!  is premature in view of  4...Kg2  5.Kf5?  Kf3!  6.Ra7  g3  7.Ra3+  Kf2  8.Kf4  g2=  . The only winning method is @@StartFEN@@8/7R/4K3/8/6p1/8/6k1/8 w - - 4 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Rf7!!  g3  6.Ke5  here. }
4... g3 5. Kg4 { 5.Rh7+  and  5.Kf4  are equivalent. } 5... g2 6. Rh7+ Kg1 7.
Kg3 Kf1 8. Rf7+ Kg1 9. Rf8
{ Almost every move is good here, for example,  9.Ra7  or  9.Rg7  , but by no means  9.Rf2??  Kh1!  and a stalemate saves Black. }
9... Kh1 10. Rh8+ Kg1 11. Rh2 { White wins. } *

