{ The following simple example demonstrates several very important practical ideas.  Topalov – Beliavsky, Linares 1995    After  1.b6?  Rxa6?  2.b7  Ra5+  3.Kc4  etc., loses @@StartBracket@@moving downstairs@@EndBracket@@. Black holds with the intermediate check prior to the capture of the pawn:  1...Ra5+!= }
1. Kb6 Kd2
{ If  2.a7?  now, then  2...Kc3  3.Kb7  Kb4  4.b6  Kb5=  Here we observe “the tail-hook”  again; the technique that we know from bishop versus pawn endings @@StartBracket@@diagram 4-30@@EndBracket@@. }
2. Ka7 { Black resigned in view of } 2... Kc3 3. b6 Kc4 4. b7 Rb1 5. b8=Q Rxb8
6. Kxb8
{ We call this method  a change of the leader.  Why does White push the less advanced b-pawn ? First of all, because the rook, being placed on another file, does not prevent its advance. In addition, the a-pawn that remains on the board after the win of the rook is more remote from the black king, so its tail holding will be more difficult. }
*

