{ Alekhine – Tartakower, Vienna 1922    Alekhine analyzes the natural continuations  1.Kc2  ,  1.Kc4  ,  1.g5  ,  1.Rh2  and shows that all of them are good enough at best for a draw. But his beautiful concept wins: }
1. Rd5
{ “The variations springing from this rather unlikely move @@StartBracket@@it attacks one solidly defended pawn and allows the immediate advance of the other@@EndBracket@@ are quite simple when we have described the basic idea – the black pawns are inoffensive:  1. When they occupy squares of the same color as their bishop, for in that case White’s king can hold them back without difficulty by occupying the appropriate white squares, e.g.,  1...f2  2.Rd1  e4  3.Kc2  Bf4  4.Rf1  followed by 5.Kd1.  2. When the rook can be posted behind them, but without loss of time, e.g. }
1... e4 2. Rf5 Bg3 3. g5 e3 4. Rxf3 e2 5. Re3 { Alekhine. } *

