{ A.Petrosian – Tseshkovsky, USSR ch  (1)  , Minsk 1976    Black has an elementary win:  1...Kd7!  , threatening with  2.--  c2  or @@StartFEN@@R7/3k4/6K1/8/1p6/2p5/8/8 b - - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.--  b3  ,  2.Ra7+  Kd6  3.Ra6+  Kd5  , etc. He played less precisely. }
1... Kd5 2. Kf5
{ In this position, the game was adjourned. Later in a hotel room, Petrosian demonstrated the following continuation to his rival: }
2... b3 { 2...c2  3.Rd8+  Kc4  4.Ke4= } 3. Rd8+ Kc4 4. Ke4
{ and showed him a volume of Chess Endings edited by Averbakh where the final position is evaluated as drawn in connection with the line: }
4... b2 5. Rc8+ Kb3 6. Rb8+ Kc2 7. Kd4
{ The opponent’s arguments and the authority of the book convinced Tseshkovsky, and he accepted the proposed draw. It was however an unfounded decision!  Black’s play can be improved by means of @@StartFEN@@3R4/8/8/3k1K2/8/1pp5/8/8 b - - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Kc5!  @@StartBracket@@instead of 3...Kc4?@@EndBracket@@  4.Rc8+   4.Ke4  b2  5.Rc8+  Kd6  -+  4...Kd4  5.Rd8+  Ke3  6.Rb8  b2  . Curiously enough, the resulting position is examined on the same page of the same book and, as Tarrasch proved in 1912, it is won!  7.Ke5  and now not  7...c2?  8.Rb3+  , but  7...Kf3!  8.Rb3  Kg4  -+ and if  8.Kf5  Ke2!  9.Ke4  Kd1  10.Kd3  c2  11.Rh8  c1=N+!  and 12...b1=Q. }
*

