[Black "Pawn on the Seventh Rank: The Rules"]
[Result "*"]

{ Hence we can conclude:  1. If the pawn is on the seventh rank, multiple winning methods exist. The most important ones are  building a bridge  for protection from checks along files and  a rook maneuver for protection from side checks along ranks.  If the attacker has a knight pawn, then only building a bridge wins.   2. When the king of the weaker side is cut off from the pawn, the only defensive technique consists in  side checks .  3. A rook pursuit of the enemy king can only be successful when  the rook and the pawn are separated at minimum by three lines.  As we shall see later, this rule does not only pertain to side checks.  4. A central or a bishop pawn divides the chessboard into two unequal parts: one is long, another is short.  The correct positioning of forces for the weaker side is to keep the king on the short side, and the rook on the long side. }
1. -- *

