{ With Black on move, the evaluation changes. } 1... Ra7+ 2. Rd7
{ 2.Ke8  Kf6  3.Re1  Re7+=  and if  2.Kd6  Kf8= } 2... Ra8
{ The simplest defensive method: Black prevents the position with the pawn on the 7th rank.   2...Ra6??  would have been a grave error in view of  3.Ke8+  Kf6  4.e7  and if  4...Ke6  then  5.Kf8!  +-   However any other rook retreat along the a-file, for example  2...Ra1  ,  does not give up the draw because after  3.Ke8+   The only correct reply to  3.Rd6!?  is  3...Ra8!  3...Kf6!  4.e7  Ke6!  5.Kf8  Black has  5...Rf1+!  Here he manages to hold only because of the fact that the white rook is misplaced at d7. }
3. Rd8
{ 3.Kd6+  is useless:  3...Kf8  or  3...Kf6  4.Rf7+  Kg6=   The waiting attempt  3.Rb7  can be met either with  3...Kg6  4.Kd6  Kf6  5.e7  Kf7=  Or with @@StartFEN@@r7/1R2K1k1/4P3/8/8/8/8/8 b - - 4 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Ra1  4.Kd7  Ra8  5.e7  Kf7=  But not  3...Kg8??  4.Kf6  Rf8+  5.Rf7  +-   In case of  3.Rd6!?  the only correct reply is  3...Kg6!   3...Ra1?  is bad because after  4.Ke8  Kf6  the pawn steps ahead with a check. And  3...Rb8?  loses to  4.Rd8!  Rb7+  5.Kd6  Rb6+  6.Kd7  . }
3... Ra7+ 4. Kd6 Ra6+ { 4...Kf6??  5.Rf8+  Kg7  6.e7  +- } 5. Ke5 Ra5+ 6. Rd5
Ra8 { 6...Ra7??  7.Rd7+  ;  6...Ra1!? } 7. Rd7+ { 7.e7  Kf7  8.Rd8  Ra5+= }
7... Kg6
{ Rather than  7...Kf8??  8.Kf6  +-  because passive defense does not help against a central pawn.  The reason for the drawn finale was the position of the black rook: it was placed on the long side.  Let us shift all the pieces except for the black rook one file to the left. @@StartFEN@@8/3K1k2/3P4/8/8/8/r7/3R4 b - - 0 8@@EndFEN@@ Now when the rook is on the short side, Black, as one can see easily, is lost. }
