{ Let us examine another position, not an elementary one, but quite an important one. Only two files separate the black rook from the pawn, and this circumstance offers White winning chances.   However a straightforward attempt  1.Ra1?  ∆ 2.Rg1+ misses the win:  1...Rb7+  2.Kd8  Rb8+  3.Kc7  Rb2  ∆ 4...Kf8 or 4... Kf6  4.Rf1  Ra2!  5.e7  Ra7+  with a draw, because the rook managed to deliver long side checks in time.   For a win, White should yield the move to his opponent. As a matter of fact, @@StartFEN@@1r6/R3K1k1/4P3/8/8/8/8/8 b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Rc8  loses to  2.Ra1  . In case of  1...Rb1  , the white rook occupies the important a8-square;  1...Kg8  2.Kf6  Rf8+  3.Rf7  is also bad. Only  1...Kg6  remains for Black but, as we shall see, this move also worsens his position. }
1. Kd6+ { But not  1.Kd7?  Kf6  ⨀  2.e7  Kf7= } 1... Kf6 2. Kd7 { Zugzwang. }
2... Kg7
{ 2...Rb1  3.e7  +- and if @@StartFEN@@1r6/R2K4/4Pk2/8/8/8/8/8 b - - 3 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Kg6  3.Ra1  +- }
3. Ke7 { Zugzwang. White has achieved his goal by means of triangulation. }
3... Kg6
{ After  3...Rb1  4.Ra8!  wins:  4...Rb2  5.Ke8  Rh2  6.Ra7+  Kf6  7.e7  Rh8+  8.Kd7  . And if  4...Rb7+  5.Kd6  Rb6+  6.Kd7  Rb7+  7.Kc6  Re7  8.Kd6  Rb7  9.e7  +-. And in case of @@StartFEN@@R7/1r4k1/3KP3/8/8/8/8/8 b - - 9 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Kf6  6.Rf8+  Kg7  7.e7  +- }
4. Ra1 Rb7+ 5. Kd8 { 5.Kd6  is also good. } 5... Rb8+
{ After  5...Kf6  White's winning method is instructive:  6.e7!  Rxe7  runs into  7.Rf1+  . And if  6...Rb8+  7.Kc7  Re8  8.Kd6!  Rb8  9.Rf1+  Kg7  10.Kc7  Ra8  11.Ra1 !  +- }
6. Kc7 Rb2 { Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 9-9 } *

