{ Tragicomedies: Alburt – Dlugy, USA ch, Los Angeles 1991 } 1... Kg5
{ Black could have had an easy draw after  1...Ra4!  , occupying the long side with his rook. }
2. Ra6 Rb4
{ The game was adjourned in this position. Grandmaster Dlugy, assisted during home analysis by two experienced colleagues, Wolff and Ivanov, failed to understand the essence of the position, and his first move after the resumption of play was a decisive error.  What is even more striking is that Dlugy had the classic work by Levenfish and Smyslov on rook endings at his disposal. In that book, naturally, the position indiagram 9-8 is examined. Black had to avoid that position but, after a short while, it arose on the board anyway. }
3. Ke6 { If  3.Kd6  then  3...Kf5!=  Of course not  3...Kg6??  4.Kc5+  . } 3...
Kg6
{ After  3...Rb7  , we have the above mentioned basic position but shifted one line down, and this circumstance could enable Black to hold. Both  3...Rb8  and  3...Rb1  were also playable. }
4. Ke7+ Kg7 5. Ra7
{ Black had obviously expected only  5.e6?  Rb7+  6.Kd8  Rb8+  7.Kc7  Rb1= }
5... Rb8
{ 5...Rb6!?  6.e6  Rb8  was more persistent; White had then to employ the triangular maneuver:  7.Kd6+!  Kf6  8.Kd7  ⨀  Kg7  9.Ke7!  ⨀ }
6. e6 Kg6 7. Ra1 Rb7+ 8. Kd6 Rb6+ 9. Kd7 Rb7+ 10. Kc6 Rb8 11. Kc7 Rh8
{ 11...Rb2  12.Re1! } 12. e7 { Black resigned. } *

