{ 9/3. Hector-Krasenkov, Ostende 1990 } 1... Ra1
{ Black would have gladly abandoned the corner with his king but  1...Kh7?  loses by force:  2.Kf8+  Kh6  3.Re6+!  Kg5  4.f6  Kf5  5.Rb6  Ra8+  6.Kg7  +- and if  3...Kh7  4.f6  +- So he should follow a waiting policy. }
2. Re2
{ The game continued  2.f6?!  Kh7!  with a drawn position we already know  3.Kf8+  Kg6  4.f7  Kf6!  5.Kg8  Rg1+  . White could have set his opponent much more difficult problems. }
2... Ra7+ 3. Kg6 Rg7+ { A passive defense  3...Ra8  loses. } 4. Kf6 Rg1
{ The rook dares not to come back to the long side:  4...Ra7??  5.Re8+  Kh7  6.Re7+  +- }
5. Ke7 Rg7+ { Diagram 16-74 } 6. Ke8 Ra7 7. Kf8
{ If  7.f6  , then  7...Kg8!  8.Rg2+  Kh7  9.f7  Ra8+  and the checks from the long side save Black. Of course not @@StartFEN@@4K2k/r7/5P2/8/8/8/4R3/8 b - - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Ra8+?  8.Kf7  Ra7+  9.Kg6  +- }
7... Ra8+ 8. Kf7 Ra7+ 9. Re7 Ra1 { The initial position has arisen again. } 10.
Re2 Ra7+ 11. Kg6 Rg7+ 12. Kf6 Rg1 13. Ke7 Rg7+
{ Having returned to the diagrammed position, White tries another possibility. }
14. Kd6 Rf7
{ This subtle defense saves the game. After  14...Ra7?  15.Re8+  Kh7  16.Re7+  or  14...Rg1?  15.f6  Kg8  16.Ke7  , Black was lost. }
15. Re8+ { 15.Ke6  Ra7= } 15... Kg7 16. Re7 Kf6 { Draw. } *

