{ If White is to move in the initial position, it was once thought that the text move leads to a win. }
1. Kf6
{ For example  1...Rf1+  2.Ke6  Kf8  3.Ra8+  Kg7  4.Ke7  Rb1  5.e6  @@StartBracket@@we know this position already: seeDiagram 9-8@@EndBracket@@  5...Rb7+  6.Kd6  Rb6+  7.Kd7  Rb7+  8.Kc6  +-  But in 1897 Max Karstedt discovered “Karstedt’s draw.” We call it the second defensive method in the Philidor position: an attack from the rear allows Black to hold. }
1... Re1 2. Ke6 Kf8
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed. note:  2...Kd8  draws as well and will be analyzed in the next variation →Diagram 9-18. But as a rule of thumb, we always aim for the short side with the king, so that the rook will have more checking distance on the long side.@@EndSquare@@ }
3. Ra8+ Kg7
{ Now we can evaluate the position of the black rook. It prevents both  4.Ke7  and  4.Kd7  . }
4. Kd6 Kf7 { And White must retrace his steps: } 5. Ra7+ Ke8 6. Ke6 Kf8 7. Ra8+
Kg7 8. Re8 Ra1 { The black rook occupies the long side. } *

