White is in a precarious situation: 1...Kd3 is threatened. Dreev tries his last chance. }
1. h4 Rxh4
{ Black should have given a rook check and moved his pawn to  g4  . Later on, he could either trade kingside pawns, under more favorable circumstances than has actually happened, or move his king to the g-pawn. The eventual consequences of  1...Rg1+!  were:  2.Kd2  Rg2+  3.Ke1  g4  4.Kf1   4.h5  Kc3  5.h6  Rh2  6.Rh8  d3  7.Rc8+  Kd4  8.Rd8+  Ke3  9.Re8+  Kf3  -+  4...Rh2  5.Rxg4  Kc3  6.Kg1  Rc2!  7.h5  d3  -+ And if @@StartFEN@@8/8/8/8/3p2RP/2k5/2r5/6K1 w - - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Rg8  d3  8.Rc8+  Kb2  -+   If after  1...Rg1+!  2.Ke2  , then  2...d3+  3.Kf2  d2  , or  3.Kd2  Rg2+  4.Kd1  g4  5.h5  Rh2  6.Rxg4+  Kc3  -+. And  6.Rc8+  doesn't help either due to  6...Kd4  , etc. }
2. Rxg5 Kc3 3. Rd5 Rh1+ 4. Ke2 Rh2+ 5. Kd1 Kd3 6. Kc1 Rh1+ 7. Kb2 Re1 8. Rd8
Re4 9. Kc1 Ke2 10. Kc2 { Draw. } *

