{ 9/5. Rohde-Cramling, Innsbruck wch jr 1977  This position was deeply analyzed by Kopaev in 1955. White wins, although with some hard work. When playing it, one should beware of slipping into theoretically drawn endings. Rohde was probably ill-prepared theoretically and failed to avoid an error. }
1. Ke6 { Of course not  1.Kf6?  Re1!= } 1... Kf8
{ 1...Kd8?  2.Rh8+  Kc7  3.Ke7  +- } 2. Rf7+
{ An important zwischenschach to impair Black’s king position. Both  2.Ra7?  Re1!  and  2.Rh8+?  Kg7  3.Ra8  Re1!  draw immediately. }
2... Kg8
{ 2...Ke8  3.Ra7  Kf8  4.Ra8+  Kg7  5.Ke7  Rb1  6.e6  is hopeless for Black. When we were discussingDiagram 9-8, we stated that the white rook is ideally placed on  a8  . This is the position White wants in this ending, and he can achieve it – provided that he plays correctly. }
3. Rd7
{ Rather than  3.Ra7?  Re1!   3...Kf8?  4.Ra8+  Kg7  5.Ke7  +-  4.Kd6  Kf8!  and if  4.Kf6  Rf1+  5.Ke6  Re1=  Unfortunately there is no @@StartFEN@@6k1/R7/4K3/4P3/8/8/8/5r2 b - - 9 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Ke7??  Rf7+  – this is why the white rook should be placed near the king.   The move  3.Rc7?!  is much less precise, however it does not miss the win after  3...Re1  4.Kf6!  Rf1+  5.Ke7  Ra1  6.Rc2  Ra7+  7.Kf6  Rf7+  8.Ke6  Ra7  9.Rd2! }
3... Re1 4. Kf6 Rf1+ 5. Ke7
{ The drawbacks of the disadvantageous position of the black king on g8 tell for the first, but not for the last time in this ending. }
5... Ra1
{ Diagram 16-75   The occupation of the long side is the most stubborn defensive method. White’s task would have been much easier after  5...Rf7+  6.Kd6  Rf8  7.e6  Ra8  8.Ke5!   8.Ke7?  Kg7=  8...Kf8  9.Kf6  +- And after  6...Rf1  7.e6  Rd1+  8.Ke7  Ra1  9.Rd2  +- }
6. Rd2
{ The game continued  6.e6?  Kg7  @@StartBracket@@seeDiagram 9-7, the line 2...Ra1@@EndBracket@@  7.Rd6  @@StartBracket@@∆ Ke8 +-@@EndBracket@@  7...Ra8!  with a drawn position. }
6... Ra7+ { The threat was 7.Rg2+. } 7. Kf6 Rf7+ { Forced. } 8. Ke6 Rf1
{ Unfortunately for Black, the rook must leave the long side because  8...Ra7  9.Rd8+  Kg7  10.Rd7+  is bad. White immediately occupies the a-file. }
9. Ra2 Kg7
{ 9...Re1  10.Kf6!  Rf1+  11.Ke7  Rf7+  12.Kd6  +-. In case of @@StartFEN@@6k1/8/4K3/4P3/8/8/R7/5r2 b - - 17 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Kf8  10.Ra8+  Kg7  11.Kd6  +- }
10. Ra7+
{ It is still not too late for a mistake:  10.Ke7?  Rf7+  11.Kd6  Rb7  12.e6  Rb6+  13.Kd7  Rb7+  14.Kc6  Rb1  15.Rf2  Ra1!=  , and if  12.Ra6  Kf7=  or  12...Rb8=  . }
10... Kg6 { 10...Kf8  11.Ra8+  Kg7  12.Kd6  +- } 11. Ra8 Kg7 12. Ke7
{ 12.Kd6  is equivalent. } 12... Rf7+ { 12...Rb1  13.e6  Rb7+  14.Kd6  +- } 13.
Kd6 Rb7 14. e6 Rb6+ 15. Kd7 Rb7+ 16. Kc6 Re7 17. Kd6 { White wins. } *

