{ The Pawn Has Not Crossed the Mid-line    In this section, we shall learn one more defensive method, the one that is called  "the frontal attack."      If, for example, the white pawn stands on b5, it makes no sense for Black to keep his rook on b8 because it is too close to the pawn. However when the pawn has not crossed the middle line, such a rook position is justified, because the rook and the pawn are separated by no less than three rows, and therefore pursuing the king by the rook gives chances for a draw. }
1. -- *

