{ Kochiev – Smyslov, L’vov zt 1978    Both  1.Ke4  and  1.Rh1  might lead to a draw. However White carelessly moved the king away from a safe place. }
1. Ke2 Kb5 2. Rb1+ Ka4 3. Rc1 Kb4 4. Rb1+ Ka3 5. Rc1 Rd5
{ First of all, Smyslov has optimally activated his king @@StartBracket@@an ideal place for the king is two squares diagonally from the pawn@@EndBracket@@, and now he protects the pawn with the rook. Were the white king at e3, he could attack the rook immediately, while now White cannot do it in time. }
6. Ke3 Kb2 7. Rc4 { 7.Ke4  Rd4+  -+ } 7... Kb3
{ White resigned. The pawn crosses the middle of the board and, with the white king on the long side, the position is lost. }
