{ Now let us discuss situations with the black king being cut off from the pawn by more than one file.  A. Chéron, 1923 }
1. Kc4 Rc8+ 2. Kb5 Rd8 3. Kc5 Rc8+ 4. Kb6 Rd8
{ White has placed his king at its most active position. Now it is time to protect the pawn with the rook. Unlike theKochiev-Smyslov endgame, he cannot do it horizontally. However the rook can be placed behind the pawn here, because the black king fails to help his rook in time. }
5. Rd1 Kf6 6. Kc7 Rd5 7. Kc6 Ra5 { 7...Rd8  8.d5  is also hopeless. } 8. Re1
{ It is important to cut off the king from the pawn again. Now Black loses in view of the unlucky distribution of his pieces: the king stands at the long side while the rook is at the short one. }
8... Ra6+ 9. Kb5 Rd6 10. Kc5 Rd8 { Or  10...Ra6 } 11. d5 { etc. } *

