{ A. Chéron, 1926    The method that was applied in the previous example does not work here. After  1.Kd4  Rd8+  2.Kc5  Re8  3.Kd5  Rd8+  4.Kc6  Re8  5.Re1?  Kg6  6.Kd7  Ra8  Or  6...Re5  7.Kd6  Ra5  . Black's rook occupies the long side with an obvious draw.  The winning idea is to create mate threats against the black king which is pressed to the edge of the board. Its current position on h5 is optimally suited for defense. Therefore White, utilizing zugzwang, must drive it away from h5. }
1. Rg2 Kh4 2. Rg7
{ 2.e5?  Rxe5+  3.Kf4  is premature in view of  3...Kh3!=   2.Rg6  Kh5  3.Rd6?  Kg5  4.Kd4  Ra8=  also brings nothing. }
2... Kh5 3. Rg1 { Zugzwang. } 3... Kh6
{ Now  3...Kh4  loses to  4.e5!  Rxe5+  5.Kf4  .   The idea of cutting off the white king along the rank also does not help:  3...Ra8  4.e5  Ra4  5.e6  Ra6  6.Kf4  Rxe6  7.Kf5  +- And if @@StartFEN@@8/8/4P3/7k/r7/4K3/8/6R1 b - - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Kh6  6.e7  Ra8  7.Kf4  Re8  8.Kf5  Rxe7  9.Kf6  +- }
4. Kd4 Rd8+ 5. Kc5 Re8 6. Kd5 Rd8+ 7. Ke6 Re8+ 8. Kf6 { White wins. } *

