{ We have seen a tragicomedy in a game byKochiev in which his grave error had fatal consequences. A draw would have maintained excellent chances for his qualifying for the Interzonal tournament. After losing, he failed to qualify, and the whole career of this young talented grandmaster declined steeply thereafter.  Many have erred in similar situations, even the greats of this world.  Tragicomedies: Tal − I.Zaitsev, USSR ch tt, Riga 1968  White should play Kd3 and Rb1, but which order of moves is correct?   A theoretical draw can be achieved after  1.Rb1!  g5  2.Kd3  Re5  3.Kd4  Re8  4.Rg1  Kg6  5.Kd3  @@StartBracket@@see the previous diagram@@EndBracket@@. }
1. Kd3 Re1 { Here are the eventual consequences if the game were continued: }
2. Kd2 Re6 3. Rb1 g5 4. Rg1
{ 4.Kd3  g4  5.Rb5  g3  6.Kd2  g2  7.Rb1  Rg6  8.Rg1  Kh5  9.Ke3  Kh4  -+ }
4... Kh5
{ ∆ 5...g4   It is useful to improve the king's position by bringing it from  h6  to  g6  . A premature  4...Re5?  misses the win:  5.Kd3  Kh5  6.Kd4  Re2  7.Kd3  Rh2  8.Ke3= }
5. Rh1+ Kg6 6. Rg1
{ 6.Re1  Rxe1  7.Kxe1  Kh5  8.Kf1  Kh4!  -+   Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 9-35 }
*

