{ 9/6. Arencibia-Vladimirov, Leon 1991 } 1. Ke3
{ The game continued  1.Rc5?  Kb4  2.Rc1  c5  3.Rb1+  Ka3  4.Rc1  Rd5  , and White resigned. The reason for the defeat is the same as in the Kochiev-Smyslov and the Tal-I.Zaitsev endings:  the poor position of the king on e2.   Another inaccurate possibility is  1.Ra6?  expecting  1...Kb4?  2.Ke3!  Kb5  3.Ra1=  But Black plays  1...Kc3!  putting White into zugzwang. On  2.Ke3  Re6+  the white king is driven one more file farther from the pawn.  After @@StartFEN@@8/8/R1pr4/8/8/2k5/4K3/8 w - - 2 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Ke1  Kb4  3.Ke2  Kb5  4.Ra1  c5  , the king fails to leave the second rank in time. All that remains is  2.Rb6  , but then  2...Rd2+  3.Ke3  c5  -+ follows. If the rook were on  a6  , a check from  a3  would have saved the game. }
1... Kb4 2. Ra1 c5 3. Rb1+ Ka3 4. Rc1 Rd5 5. Ke4 { Draw. } *

