{ Let us move the black king and the white rook one file away, as in this diagram.  White wins, because the black king fails to reach c7 in time. }
1. Rh2 Ke7 2. Rh8 Kd6
{ If  2...Kd7  then  3.Rb8  Ra1  4.Kb7  Rb1+  5.Ka6  Ra1+  6.Kb6  Rb1+  7.Kc5  With Blacks king on d6, the c5-square is not available for escaping, so White must find another itinerary. }
3. Rb8 Ra1 4. Kb7 Rb1+ 5. Kc8 Rc1+ 6. Kd8 Rh1 7. Rb6+ Kc5
{ Both  8.Re6?  Ra1  and @@StartFEN@@3K4/P7/1R6/2k5/8/8/8/7r w - - 14 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Ra6?  Rh8+  9.Kd7  Rh7+  10.Ke8  Rh8+  11.Kf7  Ra8  are useless now. }
8. Rc6+ Kb5 { 8...Kd5  9.Ra6  Rh8+  10.Kc7  Rh7+  11.Kb6  +- } 9. Rc8 Rh8+ 10.
Kc7 Rh7+ 11. Kb8
{ Black to play in the initial position should opt for @@StartFEN@@K7/P4k2/8/8/8/8/4R3/1r6 b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Rb3!?  as then White must win the queen vs. rook ending which arises after  2.Rh2  Ke7  3.Rh8  Kd6  4.Rb8  Ra3  5.Kb7  Rb3+  6.Kc8  Rc3+  7.Kd8  Rh3  8.Rb6+  Kc5  9.Rc6+  Kxc6  10.a8=Q+  Kd6  . }
