{ Tragicomedies: Vladimirov – Rashkovsky, USSR chsf, Chelyabinsk 1975    To achieve a draw, White should simply force Black’s king to the h-file:  1.Rg8+!  Kf5  2.Rf8+  Kg4  3.Rg8+  Kh3  4.Rg5  h4  5.Rg8=  And  1.Rc1!  ∆ 2. Re1= is also good. }
1. Rc3 h4 2. Re3
{ The decisive error! It was still not too late to return to the correct plan by playing  2.Rc6+!  Kg5  3.Rc8  Rh7  4.Rg8+  , and if @@StartFEN@@2R5/4r3/8/6k1/7p/8/3K4/8 b - - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...h3  4.Rg8+  or  4.Rh8  Kg4  5.Rg8+  Kf3  6.Rf8+  Kg2  7.Rg8+  Kh1  8.Rg6  h2  9.Rg8= }
2... Rh7 3. Re1 { 3.Rh3  Kg5  4.Ke2  Kg4  is also bad. } 3... h3 4. Rh1 Kg5 5.
Ke3 Kh4 6. Kf2 Rf7+ 7. Kg1 { 7.Ke2  Ra7  , planning  8.--  Ra2+  and 9...h2. }
7... Ra7 { White resigned. } 8. Rh2 Ra1+ { Of course not  8...Kg3??  9.Rg2+! }
9. Kf2 Kg4
{ is decisive.   A similar position  (like diagram 9-39, but with the white rook on d4 plus reversed wings and colors)  occurred in Dvoiris-Kovalev, USSR ch  (1)  , Simferopol 1988.   Curiously enough, Kovalev lost precisely in the same way as Vladimirov: @@StartFEN@@8/4r3/6k1/7p/3R4/8/3K4/8 w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Rd3?  h4  2.Re3? }
