[SetUp "1"]

{ The Rook Is in Front of the Pawn and the Pawn Is on the Sixth Rank   J. Vancura, 1924  The main difference between this position and those discussed above, is the fact that here White's king has a refuge from vertical checks: the a7-square. The king hides there in order to free his rook from the job of protecting the pawn.   The black king, in contrast, fails to reach the queenside:  1...Kf7?  and now  2.a7?  Kg7  would have been premature. Therefore @@StartFEN@@R7/5k2/P7/8/8/5K2/8/r7 w - - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Ke4  Ke7   2...Ra5  instead of 2...Ke7 is also hopeless:  3.Kd4  Kg7  4.Kc4  Kf7  5.Kb4  Ra1  6.Kb5  Rb1+  7.Kc6  Ra1  8.Kb7  Rb1+  9.Ka7  Ke7  10.Rb8  Rc1!?  11.Kb7   Rather than  11.Rb6?  Kd7  11...Rb1+  12.Ka8  Ra1  13.a7  +- Black's king fails to reach  c7  in time @@StartBracket@@seediagram 9-38@@EndBracket@@.  3.a7!  Kf7  or  3...Kd7  4.Rh8  +-  Because of this analysis, the diagrammed position had been considered winning for a long time. However a saving plan was finally discovered. This plan is based on the fact that the a6-pawn gives the king a refuge from vertical checks, but cannot hide him from side checks. Therefore Black should bring his rook to f6. }
1... Rf1+ 2. Ke4 Rf6
{ This is the so-called  'Vancura position'.  Black follows the same 'pawn in the crosshairs' method found in endings with bishops of opposite colors. The rook attacks the pawn in order to prevent the enemy's rook from leaving a8. What can White do?  If a6-a7, Black always has Ra6 @@StartBracket@@his king will obviously never leave the g7- and h7-squares@@EndBracket@@.If White defends the pawn with his king, a series of checks follows, and then the rook returns to f6. }
3. Kd5 Rb6 4. Kc5 Rf6 { The best place for the rook! } 5. Kb5 Rf5+ { etc. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 9 – Rook Endgames I"]
[Black "The Rook Is in Front of the Pawn and the Pawn Is on the 6th Rank 9-44"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "R7/6k1/P7/8/5K2/8/8/r7 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Now let us move the white king to f4.  P. Romanovsky, 1950    1...Rf1+??  2.Ke5  Rf6  is bad here on account of  3.Rg8+  However, Black has no other defensive plan than the rook transfer to the sixth rank. }
1... Rc1
{ If  1...Rc1  2.Ke5  then  2...Rc6=  follows, achieving the Vancura position. White may use the opportunity for removing his rook from the corner.   It is worth mentioning that  1...Rb1?  instead of 1...Rc1 would lose:  2.Ra7+!  Kg6  3.Rb7  Ra1  4.Rb6+  Kf7  5.Ke5  +-   If after  1...Rb1?  2.Ra7+!  Black tries  2...Kf6  then  3.Ke4  Rb6  4.Rh7!  Kg6  5.a7  Ra6  6.Rb7  +-   However the first moves might have been transposed:  1...Ra5!?  2.Ke4  Rb5!  or  2...Rc5!  3.Ra7+  Kg6  4.Rb7  Ra5=  and after @@StartFEN@@8/R7/P5k1/2r5/4K3/8/8/8 w - - 5 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Kd4  Rc6! }
2. Rb8 Ra1 3. Rb6
{ 3.Rb7+  Kf6  4.a7  Ke6  is weaker.   When the rook stood on  a8  , the black king was riveted to the kingside; but now the time comes for a march to the pawn. But this should be done carefully: the premature  3...Kf7?  4.Ke5  Ke7  5.Rb7+  Kd8  6.a7  loses for Black. }
3... Ra5 4. Ke4 Kf7 5. Kd4
{ If  5.Rh6  then  5...Kg7!  But not  5...Ke7?  6.a7  Kd7  7.Rh8! } 5... Ke7 6.
Kc4 Kd7 7. Kb4 Ra1
{ And the draw is clear.  In many lines, the kings compete in a race to the queenside. If the white king stood closer to the pawn, then the black one would eventually arrive too late. This means that Black cannot delay the rook transfer to the sixth rank; this plan should be executed as soon as possible. }
*

