{ Tragicomedies: Brodsky − Khmelnitsky, Kherson 1989     1.Ra4+!  Kf5  2.Rc4  Ra2+  3.Kg3  Rb2  4.Ra4  would have led to a draw. }
1. Rg6+ Kf4 { 1...Kf5??  2.Rg3=  is the Vancura position. } 2. Ra6
{ White does not have  2.Rg3  on account of  2...Rg1+!  And  2.Rf6+  can be met by  2...Ke4!  , while @@StartFEN@@8/8/6R1/8/5k2/p7/6K1/r7 w - - 2 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Rc6  by  2...Ra2+! }
2... Ke4 3. Ra4+ Ke3
{ An absurd move!   If the king is going to move ahead, then why not to  d3?  But  3...Kd5  4.Rf4  Ra2+  5.Kg3  Rb2  would have been a much simpler win.  Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 9-48 }
