[SetUp "1"]

{ Tragicomedies: Brodsky − Khmelnitsky, Kherson 1989  (continued)     Now we have @@StartBracket@@with reversed wings and colors@@EndBracket@@ the Romanovsky position, 1950. Its solution is  4.Rh4!!  Ra2+  5.Kg1!  Rf2  6.Ra4  Ra2  7.Rh4=  And in case of @@StartFEN@@8/8/8/8/7R/p3k3/6K1/r7 b - - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  4...Kd2  5.Rh3!  Kc2  6.Rf3!  a2  and now not  7.Ra3??  Kb2  , but  7.Rf2+!  Kd3  8.Rf3+  Ke4  9.Ra3= }
1. Rg4 { A decisive error. } 1... Ra2+ 2. Kh3
{ After  5.Kg1  Kf3!  6.Rc4  Re2  -+ In case of @@StartFEN@@8/8/8/8/6R1/p4k2/r7/6K1 w - - 4 3@@EndFEN@@  6.Ra4  Black has a pleasant choice between  6...Ra1+  7.Kh2  Ke2  , and  6...Kg3  7.Kf1  Ra1+  8.Ke2  a2  ∆ 9.Rh1. }
2... Rf2 3. Ra4 a2 4. Ra3+ Kd4 5. Kg3 Rb2 6. Kf4 Rf2+
{ White resigned. The aim of the last check was probably to improve the rook position after 10. Kg3, bringing it to  c2  first, and to push the king thereafter. However, the immediate  9...Kc4  10.Ke4  Kb4  11.Ra8  Kc3  -+  was sufficient for a win. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
