{ Szabó – Tukmakov, Buenos Aires 1970    White may simply wait and maintain the a-pawn in the crosshairs. For example,  1.Rb5  Kd6  2.Rf5  Ra1  3.Kh2!  a4  4.Rf4!  a3  5.Rf3!  a2  6.Ra3  . And if @@StartFEN@@8/8/3k4/8/7p/p4R2/7K/r7 b - - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Kc5  6.Rb3  Kc4  7.Rf3  Kb4  8.Rf4+!  , etc. Szabó, an experienced grandmaster, did not know this defensive system. }
1. Kg2 Kd6 2. Kf2 Ra2+ 3. Ke1
{ After  3.Kg1  Kc6  4.Rf5!  the position was still drawn. } 3... Ra1+ 4. Ke2
{ There is no salvation anymore:  4.Kf2  a4  5.Rxh4  a3  6.Ra4  Kc5  -+ and if @@StartFEN@@8/8/3k4/8/7R/p7/5K2/r7 w - - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Rh3  a2  7.Ra3  Rh1  -+   Or  4.Kd2  Rh1!  5.Rxa5  h3  6.Rh5  h2  ∆ 7...Ra1-+ }
4... a4 5. Rh6+ Ke5 6. Rh5+ Kf6 7. Kf2 a3 8. Kg2 Rc1 9. Ra5 Rc3
{ White resigned. } *

