{ Twenty-three years later, precisely the same position occurred in Emms-Riemersma, Gausdal 1993. And again, White did not know the theory of this ending. }
1. Rh6+ Kd5 2. Rh5+ Kc4 3. Rxh4+
{ 3.Rf5!  Ra1  4.Kh2  a4  5.Rf4+  with a draw. } 3... Kb3 4. Rh5
{ Diagram 9-52 } 4... Ra1
{ White’s rook is misplaced, and it is important to keep it on the h-file. Emms demonstrated that this could have been achieved by the subtle move  4...Ra3!  , for example,  5.Kh2  a4!  6.Rh3+  Kb2  7.Rh4  Ra2!  8.Rg4  Kb3+  9.Kh3  Rc2  -+ In case of @@StartFEN@@8/8/8/8/p6R/8/rk5K/8 w - - 4 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Kh1  Ra1+  9.Kg2  a3  10.Rh3  a2  -+   If after  4...Ra3!  5.Rg5  , then  5...Kb4+  6.Kg2  Rc3  7.Rg8  a4  8.Rb8+  Kc4  9.Kf2  a3  10.Ra8  Kb3  11.Ke2  a2  12.Kd2  Rc4  Black is winning. }
5. Kg2
{ An error in return. A draw was possible through  5.Rg5!  a4  6.Rg3+  Kb4   6...Kc2  7.Rg2+  Kd3  8.Rg4  a3  9.Rg3+  Kc2  10.Kh2=  7.Rg4+  Kb5  8.Rg5+  Kc6  9.Rg6+!  the king should be driven as far away as possible.   Premature is  9.Rg4?  a3  10.Kh2  Rb1  11.Ra4  Rb3  12.Kg2  Kb5  13.Ra8  Kb4  14.Kf2  Kc3  15.Ke2  Kb2  -+, or  10.Kg2  Kb5!  11.Rg3  Kb4  12.Rg4+  Kb3  13.Rg3+  Kb2  -+  9...Kd5  10.Rg5+  Ke6  11.Kg2  a3  12.Rg3  ∆ Rf3= And if @@StartFEN@@8/8/4k3/6R1/p7/8/6K1/r7 b - - 11 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Rb1  , then  12.Ra5  Rb4  13.Kf2  Kd6  14.Ke2= }
5... a4 6. Kf2 { 6.Rh3+  Kb2  7.Rh4  a3  -+ } 6... a3 7. Rb5+ Ka2 8. Ke2 Rb1 9.
Rd5 { 9.Ra5  Kb2  10.Rb5+  Ka1  11.Ra5  a2  -+ } 9... Kb2 10. Rd2+ Kb3 11. Rd3+
Ka4 12. Rd4+ Rb4 13. Rd8 a2 14. Kd3 Kb3 { White resigned. } *

