{ Doubled Pawns   If the king of the weaker side stands in front of the pawns, a draw can usually be easily achieved @@StartBracket@@except for those cases when the rook must stay on the back rank in view of mate threats@@EndBracket@@. The applicable ideas here are familiar to us from the Philidor position →Diagram 9-17. }
1. Rb7 Rg6
{ 1...Kc8!?  @@StartSquare@@Ed. holds as well, but the text move is a clearer illustration of Black's defensive setup.@@EndSquare@@ }
2. Rb6 Rg4
{ Black goes over to the second defensive method in the Philidor position after  3.Kc6  Rxd4  4.Rb8+  Ke7= }
3. d6 Rg1
{ The rook prepares itself for giving rear checks because the white king has no refuge at d6 anymore. }
4. Kc6 Rc1+ 5. Kd5 Rh1 6. Rb8+ Kd7 7. Rb7+ Kd8 8. d7 Rh5+ { 8...Ke7 } 9. Kc6
Rh6+ 10. Kc5 Rh5+ 11. d5 Rh6
{ And again, Black returns to the defensive method suggested by Philidor. } *

