{ The best chances for a successful defense exist when the king blocks the pawns. This is perhaps the most important drawn position:  J. Kling, B. Horwitz, 1851 }
1. Rd4 Rb6 2. Rd8 Rb4+ 3. Ke5 Rb7
{ The most precise: Black protects the seventh rank and threatens to take the g-pawn. He cannot of course do it immediately:  3...Kxg5??  4.h7  +-   Erroneous is  3...Rg4?  4.Rg8+  Kh7  5.Kf5!  +- Rather than  5.Rg7+?!  Kh8  6.Kf5?  Rf4+  - a 'desperado' rook.   The Encyclopaedia of Chess Endings claims that  3...Rb5+  4.Rd5  Rb7  5.Ke6  also loses for Black. But I do not see how White can make any progress after  5...Ra7   5...Rb6+  6.Ke7  Rb7+  7.Rd7  Rb8  or  7...Rb5  8.h7  Rb8!=  is also good.  6.Rd7  Ra6+  7.Rd6  Ra7  and if @@StartFEN@@8/3R4/r3K1kP/6P1/8/8/8/8 w - - 12 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Ke7  Kxg5  8.h7  Ra8  9.Kf7  Kh6= }
4. Rg8+ Kh7 5. Re8 Kg6
{ Black returns to the initial position of this ending. But he can now force a draw with  5...Rb5+  6.Kf6  Rxg5!=  or  6...Rf5+! }
6. Kf4 Rb4+ 7. Re4 Rb6 { Draw. } *

