{ Let us look at a more complicated but quite useful situation that can occur in a practical game.  G. Kasparian, 1946    For the time being, let us accept that White wins if he succeeds in transferring his rook to the fifth rank. This means that Black dare not play either  1.--  Kf8  2.Rf7+  ∆ Rf5 or  1.--  Rd3  2.Rc7  Rh3   2...Rd5  3.h6  3.Rc5  . Therefore his rook must stay on  g3  and  h3  . But what can Black do when the white king comes to the kingside?   It turns out to be difficult for White. If his king comes to  g2  when the black rook is on  h3  , then @@StartFEN@@6k1/7R/6P1/7P/8/7r/6K1/8 b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Ra3  is playable, because  2.Rb7  Ra5!  3.h6  Rg5+  loses a pawn.   The same happens after  2.Kh2  Rb3  3.Ra7  Rb5!  . If White plays  2.Kf2  the rook goes back to  h3  . By the way here, as in all similar positions,  2...Rh3  3.h6  Rh5  4.Kf3  Rg5  5.Rg7+  Kh8  6.Kf4  Rg4+!  or  6...Rf5!  leads nowhere.  However if, with the white king on f2 and the black rook on h3, Black is on move, he comes to be in zugzwang.  His rook must leave its comfortable position behind the pawns, and then the white rook has the opportunity to leave h7.  We have come to the conclusion that f2 and h3 are the squares of the reciprocal zugzwang. Obviously enough, another pair of such squares is e2 and g3. Furthermore, when the white king stands on any dark square of the second rank the black rook must be on h3 while, when the king stands on a light square, the rook must move to g3 in order to draw. }
1. Ka2
{ A paradoxical move that contradicts the standard approach @@StartBracket@@'first we move our king to the kingside, and only think thereafter'@@EndBracket@@. It turns out that one should be thinking immediately because any other initial move misses the win.   After  1.Kb2?  Rh3  2.Kc2  Rg3  3.Kd2  Rh3  4.Ke2  Rg3  5.Kf2  Rh3  White is in zugzwang:  6.Kg2  Ra3  7.Rb7  Ra5=   If  1.Rb7?  then  1...Rg5  2.Rh7  Rg2!  3.Kb1  Rh2  4.Kc1  Rg2  5.Kd1  Rh2  6.Ke1  Rg2  7.Kf1  Rh2  (the same zugzwang position, only a rank lower)  8.Kg1  Ra2  9.Rb7  Ra5=   In case of  1.Kb1?  the correct method is  1...Rb3+!  The rook gives checks until the king steps on the second rank and then goes to a corresponding square.   1...Rg2?  is erroneous:  2.Kc1  Rh2  3.Kd1  Rg2  4.Ke1  Rh2  5.Kf1  and Black is in zugzwang:  5...Ra2  6.Rb7  +-  For example,  2.Kc2  Rg3!  Or @@StartFEN@@6k1/7R/6P1/7P/8/1r6/8/1K6 w - - 2 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Kc1  Rc3+!  3.Kd1  Rd3+!  and if  3.Kd2  Rh3!  4.Ke2  Rg3  5.Kf2  Rh3  ⨀  = }
1... Rh3 2. Kb2 Rg3 3. Kc2 Rh3 4. Kd2 Rg3 5. Ke2 Rh3 6. Kf2 { Zugzwang. } 6...
Ra3 7. Rd7 Rh3 8. Rd5 Kg7 9. Kg2 Rh4 10. Kg3
{ Ed. note: analyzed in the next variation → Diagram 9-57 } *

