{ G. Kasparian, 1946  (analysis)   It remains for us to prove that White wins if he succeeds in bringing his rook to the fifth rank. This fact is not quite obvious because Black blocks the pawns with his king. However his blockade is less efficient than in the Kling and Horwitzposition. }
1. Ka2 Rd3 2. Rb7 { But, of course, not  2.Kb2?  Rh3!  ⨀ = } 2... Rh3
{ 2...Rg3  can be met by  3.Kb2  Rg5  4.Rh7  Rg3  5.Kc2  and it is Black who turns out to be in zugzwang again. This is the simplest way.   But another, more universal way also exists:  3.Rb3!?  Rg5  4.Rh3  Kg7  (otherwise the white king goes ahead)  5.h6+  Kg8  6.g7!   Rather than  6.h7+?  Kh8  7.Rh6  Rg1  and White's king will not have a refuge from rook checks from the rear.  6...Kh7  7.Kb3  White activates his king and gradually wins @@StartBracket@@a similar position was analyzed by Kling and Horwitz as long ago as in 1851@@EndBracket@@. }
3. Rb5 Kg7 { 3...Rg3  4.Rb3  +- } 4. Rg5
{ Now Black has neither  4...Kh6  5.g7!  nor @@StartFEN@@8/6k1/6P1/6RP/8/7r/K7/8 b - - 7 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Rc3  5.h6+!  Kxh6  6.g7  But this position is winning for White even without this move @@StartBracket@@when the black king stands on h6@@EndBracket@@. }
4... Rh4
{ In case of  4...Kg8  5.Kb2  Re3  White plays  6.Kc2!  Ra3  7.Kd2  Rb3  8.Ke2  Ra3  9.Kf2  Rb3  10.Rd5  +- A hasty @@StartFEN@@6k1/8/6P1/6RP/8/4r3/1K6/8 w - - 10 6@@EndFEN@@  6.h6?  Rh3  7.h7+  Kg7  on the contrary, leads to a theoretical draw. }
5. Kb3 Rh1 6. Kc4 Rc1+ 7. Kd5
{ The king must go ahead.   Nothing can be achieved by  7.Kd3  Rh1  8.Ke3  Rh3+  9.Kf2  and now not  9...Rh4?  10.Kg2  ⨀ +-, but @@StartFEN@@8/6k1/6P1/6RP/8/7r/5K2/8 b - - 17 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Rh1  10.Kg2  Rh4  ⨀  and the rook cannot be forced away from the h-file. }
7... Rd1+ 8. Kc6 Rc1+ 9. Kd6 Rd1+ 10. Rd5 Ra1 11. Ke7 Ra6
{ Therefore, after 12...Kg8 White has to play @@StartFEN@@3K2k1/8/6P1/3R3P/8/8/8/4r3 w - - 24 13@@EndFEN@@  13.h6!  Re6   13...Rg1  14.Rd6   13...Rh1  14.Ke7!  14.h7+!  Kh8  15.Rg5  Kg7  16.Rh5  +- But not  14.Rg5?  Ra6  15.Ke7  Rb6  16.h7+  Kg7  17.Rh5  Rb7+  18.Ke6  Rb6+  with a draw. }
12. Rd7 { Diagram 9-57 } 12... Rb6
{ 12...Ra5  13.Ke6+  Kg8  14.h6  +-  is quite bad.   After  12...Rc6  Kasparian gives  13.Kd8+  Kg8  14.Re7  Rd6+  15.Kc7  Ra6  16.Kd7  ∆ 17.Re6  And if @@StartFEN@@3K2k1/4R3/2r3P1/7P/8/8/8/8 b - - 27 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Kf8  15.Kd7  Ra6  16.Re6  Ra7+  17.Kd6  Ra6+  18.Ke5  Ra5+  19.Kf6  +- }
13. Kd8+ Kg8
{ 13...Kf8  is met with  14.Kc7!  Ra6  15.Rd6  or  15.h6  Rxg6  16.Rd8+  and 17.h7 -+. }
14. Kc7
{ But this recommendation is incorrect: instead of 18... Ra6+?, Black plays @@StartFEN@@6k1/r7/4KRP1/7P/8/8/8/8 b - - 35 18@@EndFEN@@  18...Kg7!  because after  19.Rf7+?  Rxf7  20.gxf7  Kf8  ⨀  he holds a pawn ending despite being two pawns down. }
14... Ra6 15. Rd6
{ ∆ h6+-  This complicated analysis can hardly be  (and certainly should not be)  remembered in all its details. To know that the rook transfer to the fifth rank wins is quite enough, yet the proof of this fact turns out to be rather complicated. }
*

