{ 9/8. G.Kasparian, 1948 } 1... Kc4
{ ∆ 2...Kb3. Black must redirect his king to the opposite wing in order to utilize the unfavorable position of the white king on the edge.   If  1...Ke6?  2.h4  Kf6  3.h5  Kg7  4.Rh7+  Kg8  @@StartBracket@@seeDiagram 9-56@@EndBracket@@  5.Ka2!!  , White wins.   The tempting  1...Rg2?!  2.h4  Kc4  is also losing after  3.Kb1!  Kb3  4.Kc1  Kc3  5.Kd1  Kd3  6.Ke1  Ke3  7.Kf1  Rf2+  8.Kg1  Kf3  9.h5  Rg2+  if now  10.Kf1  Rh2  , so  10.Kh1!  Diagram 16-77.  For example,  10...Kf2  11.Rh7  Kg3  now not  12.g7?  Kf2  ∆ 13...Rg4, but  12.Rf7!  Rh2+   12...Ra2  13.Kg1  Ra1+  14.Rf1  Ra2  15.Rb1  +-  13.Kg1  Rxh5  14.g7  Rg5  15.Rf2!  Kh3+  16.Kh1  +- If @@StartFEN@@8/8/6PR/7P/8/5k2/6r1/7K b - - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Rg4  , then White does not play  11.Rh7?!  Rg5!  and he is in zugzwang:  12.g7?  @@StartBracket@@12. Rh6@@EndBracket@@  12...Rg4  13.Kh2  Rg2+  with perpetual check, but  11.Rh8!  Rg5   11...Kf2  12.Rf8+  +-  12.Rh7!  instead, and it is Black who is in zugzwang:  12...Rg4  13.Rf7+  winning @@StartBracket@@analysis by Leitao and P.H. Nielsen@@EndBracket@@. }
2. Kb2 Rg2+ { Diagram 16-78 } 3. Ka3
{ 3.Kc1  Kc3  4.Kd1  Kd3  5.Ke1  Ke3  6.Kf1  Kf3  7.h4  Rh2  8.Kg1  Rg2+   8...Ra2  9.h5  Ra1+  10.Kh2  Ra2+  11.Kh3  Ra1=  9.Kh1  Kf2=  or  9...Rg4= }
3... Rg3+ 4. Ka4 Rg1 5. Ka5 { 5.Rh4+  Kd5  6.Rg4  Rxg4+  7.hxg4  Ke6= } 5...
Kc5 6. Ka6 Kc6 7. Ka7 Kc7 8. Ka6 { 8.Rh7+  Kd6  9.Rb7  Ke6= } 8... Kc6
