{ Gligoric − Smyslov, Moscow 1947  (analysis)   The following attempt is interesting: }
1. Rg7+ Kf6 2. Rc7 Kg6 { Black can also play  5...Rg1+  6.Kf3  Rh1  . } 3. h7
{ Instead of 6... Rg1+? Black must play the text move immediately. } 3... Rh1
{ If White tries the waiting move  7.Rb7  Black can wait too:  7...Rh2  with no fear of  8.Rb5  Kg7!  9.Rg5+  Kh8!   Another good line is  7...Rg1+  8.Kf3  Rh1  9.Ke4  Re1+  because, when the white rook stands on b7, the king's route around it is too long:  10.Kd5  Rd1+  11.Kc6  Rc1+!  12.Kb6  Rh1!  with a draw. }
4. Kf3 Kf5
{ Or  7...Kf6!?  8.Ke4  Re1+  9.Kd5  Rd1+  10.Kc6  Rh1!  When the black king stands on  f6  , White has no important move  11.Re7  , while after  11.Rd7  or  11.Kb7  then  11...Kf5  the black king abolishes the f4-pawn and returns to g6 in time. }
*

