[Black "f- and h-Pawns 9-63"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/2R4P/6k1/7r/4KP2/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Gligoric − Smyslov, Moscow 1947  (analysis)     The continuation  9.f5+?  Kf6  10.Rc6+  Kg7  11.Ke5  Kxh7  12.Rc7+  Kh6!  13.Kf6  Rh1  14.Rc2  Rh3!=  does not promise White any success @@StartBracket@@see the ending, Polugaevsky-Ree@@EndBracket@@. @@StartFEN@@8/6kP/2R5/4KP1r/8/8/8/8 b - - 4 3@@EndFEN@@  11...Rh1!?  is even simpler.  White should cede the right to move to his adversary, with the idea of forcing the black rook away from h5, and then advancing his king, when his rook stands precisely on c7. All this can be achieved in the following way: }
1. Rd7 { Or  9.Re7 } 1... Kf6 2. Ra7 { 10.Rd8?  Rxh7  11.Rd6+  Ke7= } 2... Kg6
{ 10...Rh1?  11.Ra8!  Rxh7  12.Ra6+ } 3. Rc7 { Zugzwang. } 3... Rh1
{ 11...Kf6?  12.Rc8!  +- } 4. Ke5 Re1+ 5. Kd6 Rd1+
{ 13...Rh1  14.Re7!  ∆ 15.Kd7. } 6. Kc6
{ Later, I discovered the possibility of a more stubborn defense. Instead of 14...Rh1, Black should play the text move. }
6... Rd8
{ In order for White to win, he need only get his king back to the f-pawn, while keeping the black rook tied to the eighth rank. But how is this to be accomplished? }
7. Kc5 Ra8
{ After which  16.Kd4  is useless:  16...Ra4+  17.Ke5  Ra5+  18.Ke4  Rh5  , and if @@StartFEN@@8/2R4P/6k1/8/r2K1P2/8/8/8 w - - 16 9@@EndFEN@@  17.Ke3  Ra3+  18.Ke4  Rh3  (∆ 19...Rh5)  19.Ke5  Re3+  20.Kd5  Rd3+  21.Kc6  Rd8!  etc.   Before bringing the king back, it is important to bring the rook to d7 first. Then Black's rook maneuver to h3  (as in the variation we just examined)  has no point − once again, White brings his king forward, and now the Black rook cannot get to d8. }
8. Ra7
{ The most exact line.   Not  16.Rd7  at once:  16...Ra5+  17.Kd4?!  Rh5  and White must start all over again. }
8... Rb8 9. Rd7 Kf6 { 17...Ra8  18.Kd4 } 10. Kd4 { Threatening Ke4-f3-g4. }
10... Rb4+ 11. Ke3 Rb3+ 12. Ke4 Rh3 13. Kd5 Rd3+ 14. Kc6 Rc3+ 15. Kb7 Rh3 16.
Kc8 { White wins. } *

