{ Gligoric − Smyslov, Moscow 1947  (continued)   @@StartSquare@@Ed. note: the defensive method against the f- and h-Pawns presented in this example is marked as important in the printed book. Due to its length, on Chessable Diagram 9-64 is given first as Informational and then the moves can be trained as well in the next three excerpts → Diagram 9-64 #1, #2, #3.@@EndSquare@@ }
1... Kf6 2. Rc6+ Kg7
{ The main danger for Black is for his king to be forced to the back rank. This could have happened after  4...Kf7?  5.Kg5  Rg1+  6.Kf5  Rh1  7.Rc7+  +- }
3. Kg5 Rg1+ 4. Kf5 Ra1 5. Rc7+ { 7.Rg6+  Kf7= } 5... Kh6 6. Re7 Rb1 7. Re8 Kg7
8. Re5 Ra1 9. Rd5 Rf1
{ Not a bad move, but holding the rook in the corner was quite enough. } 10.
Rd4 Ra1 11. Rd6 Ra5+ 12. Kg4 Ra1
{ 14...Rb5  is also playable: it leads back to the initial position. } 13. Re6
Rg1+ 14. Kf5 Ra1 { Diagram 9-64 } 15. h6+ Kh7 16. Rd6 Ra2 17. Kg5 Rg2+ 18. Kf6
Kxh6 19. Ke7+ Kh7 20. f5 Re2+ 21. Re6 Ra2 22. f6 Ra8
{ We have discussed this sort of position in the section dedicated to the pawn on sixth rank. The black rook is placed on the long side, so a draw is inevitable. }
23. Kf7 Kh6 24. Re1 Ra7+ 25. Re7 Ra8 26. Rd7 Kh7 27. Rd1 Ra7+ 28. Ke6 Ra6+ 29.
Rd6 Ra8 30. Rd4 Kg8 31. Rg4+ Kf8
{ Draw.  In this example, Black kept his king on f7 until the danger of its being driven to the back rank arose. Thereafter the king went to g7 and later on - to h6, attacking the white pawn. But, strictly speaking, Kopaev's recommendation was to place the king in front of the more advanced pawn.  The best position for the rook is on a1; it is ideally suited for giving checks along files as well as ranks. However, if the pawns are not advanced too far, the rook stands quite well on the fifth rank, and sometimes on f1. }
*

