{ It goes without saying that not all positions with f- and h-pawns are drawn. The most important exception was already mentioned above:  Black usually loses if his king is cut off on the back rank.   Capablanca − Kostic, Havana m  (1)  1919  One does not need to keep the solution in mind because White has many winning ways to choose from. }
1. f6
{ Kopaev suggests  1.Rb8+  Kf7  2.h6  ∆ 3.h7;  and if  1...Kg7  2.f6+!  Rxf6  3.h6+  . In case of @@StartFEN@@1R4k1/8/2r5/5PKP/8/8/8/8 b - - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Kh7  2.f6  Rc5+  3.Kg4  Rc4+  4.Kf5  Rc5+  5.Ke6  Rc6+  6.Ke7  Rc7+  7.Kf8  Kh6  8.f7  +-   If after  1...Kh7  2.f6  Black tries  2...Rc7  , then  3.Re8  +- }
1... Rc1 2. Rg7+
{ Belavenets's suggestion is also good:  2.h6  Rg1+  3.Kf5  Rf1+  4.Ke6  The king is striving for the 8th rank. If  4...Re1+  then  5.Kd6!  rather than  5.Kd7?  Kf7  6.h7  Rh1= }
2... Kf8
{ This loses at once.   But  2...Kh8  could postpone the loss only for a little while:  3.Kg6  Rg1+  4.Kf7  Ra1  5.Rg8+  Kh7  6.Re8  Ra7+  7.Kf8  White's next move will be 8.f7 @@StartBracket@@the h5-pawn deprives the black king of the important g6-square@@EndBracket@@. }
3. h6 { Black resigned; he cannot prevent h6-h7. } *

