{ 9/9. Beliavsky-Azmaiparashvili, Portoroz 1997  Of the six possible king retreats, only one is correct, but which one? }
1... Kd3
{ The correct solution!   1...Kd4?  is quite bad:  2.Rf1  followed by 3.Kxh3. Or  1...Kf3  and  1...Kf4?  2.Ra1  Ra6  3.f6  @@StartBracket@@the f-pawn cannot be captured because, after the rook exchange, the king is beyond the square of the a5-pawn@@EndBracket@@.   The game continued  1...Kd2?  2.Re5  Kd3  hoping for  3.Kxh3?  Kd4  4.Rb5  Kc4=  . However, Beliavsky responded with @@StartFEN@@8/8/5r2/P3RP2/8/3k3p/7K/8 w - - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3.a6!  Rxa6  4.Kxh3  , and Black was lost: the king is on the long side, and can be cut off from the pawn not only vertically, but horizontally as well. The remainder was  4...Kd4   4...Ra4  5.Kg3  5.Re6  Ra8  6.Kg4  Rg8+  7.Kf4  Kd5  8.Ra6   8.Re1  was also good here – a frontal attack does not help because the pawn has crossed the middle line.  8...Rg1  9.f6  Rf1+  10.Kg5  Ke5  11.Kg6  Rg1+  12.Kf7  Rb1  13.Kg7  Rg1+  14.Kf8  Kf5  15.f7  Re1  16.Kg7  Rg1+  17.Kh7  Black resigned.   Let’s look at  1...Kf2?  Here  2.Re5?  is no longer good, because after  2...Kf3  3.Rb5  Kg4  , the h3-pawn is protected and White cannot strengthen his position. Therefore, he plays  2.Ra1!  Rxf5   2...Ra6  3.Kxh3  +-  3.a6  Rf8  4.a7  Ra8  and cuts the black king off horizontally by  5.Ra3!  in order to slow its march to the a7-pawn. The following line shows what happens then:  5...Ke2  6.Kxh3  Kd2  7.Kg4  Kc2  8.Kf5  Kb2  9.Ra6!  Kb3  10.Ke6  Kb4  11.Kd6!  Kb5  12.Ra1  Kb6  13.Rb1+  Ka6  14.Kc7!  Rxa7+  15.Kc6  +- }
2. Rf1
{ If  2.Rd1+  ,  2...Ke4?  is bad in view of  3.Rf1  +-. The simplest is @@StartFEN@@8/8/5r2/P4P2/8/3k3p/7K/3R4 b - - 2 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Ke3  , but  2...Ke2  is also playable:  3.Rd5  Kf3=  or  3.Ra1  Rxf5  4.a6  Rf8  5.a7  Ra8  6.Ra3  Kd2=  @@StartBracket@@here Black has an extra tempo in comparison with 2...Kf2@@EndBracket@@. }
2... Ke2 3. Rf4 Ke3 4. Ra4 Rxf5 5. a6 Rf8 6. a7 Ra8 7. Kxh3 Kd3 8. Kg4 Kc3 9.
Kf5 Kb3 10. Ra1 Kb4 11. Ke6 { Diagram 16-79 } 11... Kc5
{ This case of shouldering is familiar to us from the analysis of theKasparov-Short ending.  11...Kb5?  is bad:  12.Kd6!  Kb6  13.Rb1+  – this is precisely what results from 1...Kf2? }
12. Kd7 Kb6 13. Rb1+ Kc5 14. Rb7 Rh8 { Draw. } *

