{ Black’s actions in the following endgame were based on two typical methods: shouldering and cutting off the king.  Yusupov − Tseshkovsky, Moscow tt 1981    In case of the straightforward  1...hxg3?  2.Kxg3  Kd3  3.Ra2  c3  4.h4  c2  5.Rxc2  Kxc2  It is shouldering that helps here:  6.Kf4!   White, of course, cannot play  6.h5??  Rd4!  -+   But  6.Kg4?  Kd3  7.h5  Ke4  8.Kg5  Ke5  9.Kg6  Ke6  10.h6  Rg1+  also loses.  6...Kd3  7.h5  Rh1  8.Kg5  Ke4  9.h6  Ke5  10.Kg6  Ke6  11.Kg7!   Rather than  11.h7?  Rg1+  12.Kh6  Kf7  13.h8=N+  Kf6  14.Kh7  Rg2  ⨀ -+  11...Rg1+  12.Kf8!  and if  11...Ke7  12.h7  Rg1+  13.Kh8!=   1...Kd3?  2.Rf2!  or  2.Rg2  has the same consequences.  Deliberating over his next move, Tseshkovsky recognized White's defensive plan and found how to prevent its realization. }
1... Rf1+ 2. Kg4 hxg3
{ Now, after  3.Kxg3  Kd3  4.Ra2  c3  5.h4  c2  6.Rxc2  Kxc2  the white king cannot go to f4, and White loses. }
3. Rd2+ Ke3 4. Rg2 { 4.Rc2  Rf4+!  5.Kxg3  Rd4  6.h4  Kd3  changes nothing. }
4... Rf4+
{ White could hold after  4...c3?  5.Rxg3+  Kd4  6.Rg2  Kd3  7.h4  @@StartBracket@@compared with the line 3. Kxg3 Kd3 he would have an extra tempo@@EndBracket@@. Alas, Black wins easily by means of cutting the king off along the fourth rank. }
5. Kxg3 c3 6. h4 Rc4 7. Rc2 Kd3 8. Rc1 c2 9. h5 Kd2 10. Rh1 c1=Q 11. Rxc1 Kxc1
{ White resigned. } *

