{ The most important method in sharp endings with a far-advanced passed pawn is  interference  @@StartBracket@@'building a bridge'@@EndBracket@@. It occurs, together with other useful techniques, in this example.  Balashov − Dvoretsky, USSR ch tt, Moscow 1967    The main threat is by no means Kc5-b6-b7 in that case the king will certainly be late when coming back to fight against the black pawn. White is planning 2.Kb5! followed by the interference: Rc6+ and Ra6. If  1...Kf5?  then again  2.Kb5!  Ra1   2...Rxa7  3.Rxa7  g4  4.Kc4  Ke4  5.Rg7  Kf3  6.Kd3  g3  7.Rf7+  and 8.Ke2.  3.Rc5+!  Kf4  4.Rc4+  and 5.Ra4.  Or @@StartFEN@@8/P7/8/1KR2kp1/8/8/8/r7 b - - 4 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Kf6  4.Rc6+  and 5.Ra6.  Every tempo counts in such situations. Black holds by means of  driving the king away by vertical checks.  The king should be driven as far as possible from the g-pawn. }
1... Ra1 2. Kb6 Rb1+ 3. Kc6 Ra1 4. Kb7 Rb1+
{ The immediate  4...Kf5  is also sufficient for a draw. } 5. Kc8 Ra1 6. Kb8
Kf5 { Draw.  Ed. note: analyzed in the next variation → Diagram 9-75 } *

