{ Balashov − Dvoretsky, USSR ch tt, Moscow 1967  (analysis)   Another method of preventing the threat of interference looks less attractive: }
1... Kh5
{ The king on the h-file will be unable to shoulder his counterpart. In reality, this move loses, and its eventual consequences are quite instructive. }
2. Kb6 { ∆ 3.Rc8 Diagram 9-75 } 2... Ra1
{ 2...g4  is very bad in view of  3.Rc5+  and 4.Ra5 @@StartBracket@@a bridge again@@EndBracket@@.   The same method decides in case of  2...Rb4+  3.Ka5  Rb1  4.Rc4!   After  2...Kh4  White can apply another typical method:  deflection  of the rook, namely  3.Rc4+  Rxc4  4.a8=Q  . However, after  4...Rf4=  a theoretically drawn position arises @@StartBracket@@we will study this sort of ending later in the book@@EndBracket@@.  Therefore the interference method should also be applied here: @@StartFEN@@8/P1R5/1K6/6p1/r6k/8/8/8 w - - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Kb5!  Ra1  4.Rc4+  and 5.Ra4. }
3. Rc8
{ 3.Rc5?  Rxa7  is erroneous: the rook is placed badly on the fifth rank, and even more, it stands in the way of the white king. }
3... Rxa7 { Equivalent is  3...Kg4  or  3...g4  4.a8=Q  Rxa8  5.Rxa8  . } 4.
Kxa7 Kg4
{ Or  4...g4  5.Kb6  g3  and here  6.Kc5?  would be wrong in view of  6...Kg4=  White should play @@StartFEN@@2R5/8/1K6/7k/8/6p1/8/8 w - - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Rg8!  Kh4  7.Kc5  Kh3  8.Kd4  g2  9.Ke3  Kh2  10.Kf2  +- }
5. Kb6 Kf3 6. Rf8+ { A familiar method: zwischenschach for gaining a tempo. }
6... Ke3 7. Rg8 Kf4 8. Kc5 g4 9. Kd4 Kf3 10. Kd3 g3 11. Rf8+ Kg2 12. Ke2
{ White wins. } *

