{ 9/10. Beliavsky-Radulov, Leningrad 1977 } 1... Rf5
{ It is important to chain the white rook to defense of the pawn. If  2.Kb3  g3  3.Kb4  g2  4.Rg6  the bridge technique is decisive:  4...Rf4+  ∆  5.--  Rg4  .   1...g3?  2.Rg6  g2  3.Kb3  Kf2  4.Kb4=  and if @@StartFEN@@8/5r2/6R1/P7/8/1K3k2/6p1/8 b - - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Rf4  4.a6  leads to a draw.  The white pawn is advanced far enough, so Black has no time either for interfering by  4...Rg4  or for utilizing the fact that the white king is cut off along the fourth rank  4...Kf2  5.a7  . }
2. Ra8 g3 3. a6 Rf6 4. a7 Rf7 { White resigned. } *

