{ 9/11. D. Gurgenidze, 1987 } 1. c3
{ As soon becomes clear,  1.c4?  loses. In the upcoming rook-versus-pawn endgame, White plays for stalemate, and therefore the c-pawn should be left to be captured by the black king.  And  1.Re1?  is very bad in view of  1...Rf8+!   However, after Inarkiev's suggestion  1.Re7!?  , with the idea of  1...Rf8+  2.Ke6  , Black seems to have no win, for example, @@StartFEN@@7r/4R3/8/5K2/8/8/kpP3P1/8 b - - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Rb8  2.Ra7+  Kb1  3.g4  Kxc2  4.Ra2  . }
1... Rf8+ 2. Kg6 Kb3 3. Rxb2+ { 3.Re1?  Rg8+  ∆ ...Rxg2-+ } 3... Kxb2 4. g4
Kxc3 5. g5 Kd4 6. Kh7 Rf7+ { The last trap. Diagram 16-80 } 7. Kh8
{ 7.Kh6?  is a mistake:  7...Ke5  8.g6  Rf1  9.g7  Kf6  -+ } 7... Ke5 8. g6
Rf8+ 9. Kh7 Kf6 10. g7 Rf7 11. Kh8 Rxg7 { Stalemate. } *

