{ 9/12. V. & M. Platov, 1923 } 1. e6
{ After  1.Rb7+?  Ka6  2.e6  Black holds by means of  2...c5+!  3.Kd3  or  3.Kc3  Rf5!?  Of course not  3.Ke5?  due to  3...d6+  -+ }
1... Rf6
{ @@StartFEN@@8/4PR2/k1K5/8/8/5p2/4r3/8 b - - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Rc2+  also doesn't help  8.Kd7  Rd2+  9.Ke8  f2  10.Kf8  +- }
2. Rb7+
{ This zwischenschach is necessary.   The gain of a rook for a pawn in the line  2.exd7?  Rd6+  3.Ke5  Rxd2  4.Ke6  f3  5.Rc8  Re2+  6.Kd6  Rd2+  7.Kc7  c5=  only draws. }
2... Ka6
{ After  2...Ka4  3.exd7  Rd6+  4.Kc5  Rxd2  an interference on the d-file decides:  5.Rb4+  ∆ 6.Rd4. }
3. exd7 Rd6+
{ 3...Rf8  4.Rc7  Rd8  5.Kc5  f3  6.Kd6  f2  7.Rxc6+  and 8.Rc1+- } 4. Kc5 Rxd2
{ Diagram 16-81 } 5. Rb2
{ White improves the position of the rook with tempo, utilizing the fact that  5...Rxd7  is impossible in view of  6.Kxc6   5.Rb3?  is wrong:  5...f3!  6.Rxf3  Kb7=  And if @@StartFEN@@8/3P4/k1p5/2K5/8/1R3p2/3r4/8 w - - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Kxc6  Rc2+  with a draw. }
5... Rd3
{ Black cannot create a fortress with a rook against a queen:  5...Rxb2  6.d8=Q  Rc2+  7.Kb4  Rb2+  8.Kc4  Rb5  9.Qc7  +-   5...Rd1  is also bad:  6.Kxc6  Rc1+  7.Kd6  Rd1+  8.Kc7  Rc1+  9.Kd8  f3  10.Rd2!  +- }
6. Rb3
{ The rook occupies the 3rd rank in order to prevent the advance of the f-pawn.   6.Kxc6?  is premature:  6...Rc3+  7.Kd6  Rd3+  8.Kc7  Rc3+  9.Kd8  and now not  9...f3?  10.Rd2!  +-, but @@StartFEN@@3K4/3P4/k7/8/5p2/2r5/1R6/8 b - - 6 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Re3!  10.Rd2  Kb7= }
6... Rd2 7. Kxc6 Rc2+ 8. Kd6 Rd2+ 9. Kc7 Rc2+ 10. Kd8 Re2
{ With the idea  11.Rd3?  Kb7= } 11. Rf3
{ Black must protect the pawn, but his rook will be too close to the white king. }
11... Re4 12. Kc7 Rc4+ 13. Kd6 Rd4+ 14. Kc6 Rc4+ 15. Kd5 { White wins. } *

