{ Lasker’s Idea   Books on chess endings contain many interesting and instructive rook-and-pawn endings with a single pawn on each side. We have already studied some typical methods that are characteristic for this material in the previous section of the book. Now we shall discuss one more idea. The second world champion introduced it.  Em. Lasker, 1890    Were Black on move, he could hold the game by playing @@StartFEN@@2K5/2P4R/k7/8/8/8/2r4p/8 b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Ka7!  or  1...Rb2!  But it is White who is on move, and he sets into motion a mechanism that gradually drives the black king as far away as the second rank. }
1. Kb8 Rb2+ 2. Ka8 Rc2 3. Rh6+ Ka5 4. Kb7 Rb2+ 5. Ka7 Rc2 6. Rh5+ Ka4 7. Kb7
Rb2+ 8. Ka6 Rc2 9. Rh4+ Ka3 10. Kb6 Rb2+ 11. Ka5 Rc2 12. Rh3+ Ka2 13. Rxh2
{ White wins. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 9 – Rook Endgames II"]
[Black "Lasker's Idea 9-82"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "4K3/R3P3/8/7k/8/8/p7/r7 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ A slightly more complicated version of the same idea is demonstrated in the following example.  P. Keres, 1947 }
1. Ra3
{ It is worth mentioning that the diagrammed position occurred, with reversed colors, in the game I. Zaitsev-Dvoretsky, Moscow ch 1973. I did not know the endgame study by Keres and, having discovered the same idea, executed it in a slightly different way:  1.Ra5+  Kh4!  2.Ra3!  ⨀ The game continued  2...Kg5   In case of  2...Kg4  3.Kf7  we transpose into the main line of the Keres' study.  3.Rg3+  Kf4  4.Rg2  Kf3  5.Rh2   Keres suggests  5.Rb2  Ke3  6.Kd7  Rd1+  7.Kc7  Rc1+  8.Kb7  a1=Q  9.e8=Q+  5...Ke3  6.Rb2  ⨀  Ke4  7.Re2+  Kd3  8.Kd8  Kxe2  9.e8=Q+  and my opponent resigned after a few more moves. }
1... Kh4
{ Black prevents the rook transfer to the second rank: 2.Rh3+ and 3.Rh2. } 2.
Ra5
{ Zugzwang.   When the black king is placed on  h4  ,  2.Kf7?  has no point − after  2...Rf1+  3.Kg6  Rg1+  4.Kh6  Re1  White's king has traveled too far away from the e7-pawn and cannot protect it. Therefore White waits; he realizes that Black's king is placed worse on any square other than h4. }
2... Kg4 3. Kf7 Rf1+ 4. Kg6 Re1 5. Ra4+ Kh3 6. Kf6 Rf1+ 7. Kg5 Rg1+ 8. Kh5 Re1
9. Ra3+ Kg2 10. Rxa2+
{ In the study by Lasker, this was the termination point; but here the fight goes on. }
10... Kf3 11. Ra7 { Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 9-83 }
*

