{ 9/13. Petrosian-Karpov, USSR ch, Moscow, 1976 } 1... Kh8
{ On  1...Kh6?  White wins similarly to Lasker’s study:  2.f7  Ra1  3.Kg8  , and if  2...Kh7  3.h6  Kxh6   3...Ra1  4.Rxc2  +-  4.Kg8  Rg1+  5.Kh8  Rf1  6.Rc6+  Kh5  7.Kg7  Rg1+  8.Kh7  Rf1  9.Rc5+  Kh4  10.Kg7  Rg1+  11.Kh6  Rf1  12.Rc4+  Kh3  13.Kg6  Rg1+  14.Kh5  Rf1  15.Rc3+  Kg2  16.Rxc2+  +- }
2. f7 Ra1
{ Diagram 16-82   He must begin the counterattack immediately! Otherwise White plays @@StartFEN@@5K1k/2R2P2/8/7P/8/8/2p5/2r5 w - - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.h6  , and the black king is denied the important g7-square. }
3. Ke7
{ The king has a refuge from vertical checks: h6. However, Black manages to hold because of a stalemate!   In the actual game,  3.Rxc2  was played instead. Black forced the white king far from the pawns with a series of side checks:  3...Ra8+  4.Ke7  Ra7+  5.Kf6   5.Ke6  Ra6+  6.Kd7  Ra7+  7.Rc7  Rxc7+  8.Kxc7  Kg7=  5...Ra6+  6.Kg5  Ra5+  7.Kg4  Ra4+  8.Kg3  Ra3+  9.Kg2  Kg7  10.Rf2  Kf8  11.Rf5  Ra6!   11...Ra7?  loses to  12.h6  Rxf7  13.h7  +- And if  12...Ra6  13.Rh5  +-  12.Kg3  Rh6  13.Kg4  Draw, in view of  13...Rh7  . }
3... Re1+ 4. Kf6 Rf1+ 5. Kg6 Rg1+ 6. Kh6 c1=Q+ 7. Rxc1 Rg6+ { Draw. } *

