{ A Rook and Two Pawns vs. a Rook and Pawn    All Pawns Are on the Same Wing   If all the pawns are grouped on the same wing, then a draw is the most probable outcome. Even when there is a passed pawn, the defense is, as a rule, not too difficult.  Smyslov – Keres, USSR ch, Moscow 1949 }
1. Rb8 f4+ 2. Kg2 Rc2+ 3. Kf3
{ 3.Kg1?  loses to  3...Kh4  4.Rb3  Re2  ∆  5.--  Re3  . } 3... Rc3+
{ There is no danger for White in  3...Rh2  4.Rh8+  Kg6  5.Rg8+  Kf6  6.Rh8  Kg7  7.Rh5  Kg6  8.Rh8  Kf6  9.Kg4!   9.Rh5?  Kf5  10.Rh8  Rxh3+!  9...Rg2+  10.Kf3  Rg3+  11.Kf2  , and  11...Kg6  can be met, besides the waiting  12.Kf1  , even with  12.h4  g4  13.Rg8+  or  13.Rf8  Rf3+  14.Kg2  . }
4. Kg2 Rg3+ 5. Kh2 Re3 6. Kg2
{ 6.Rh8+  Kg6  7.h4!  g4  8.Rg8+  Kh5  9.Rh8+  and if  8...Kf5  9.Rg5+  Ke4  10.Rxg4= }
6... Kg6 7. Rf8
{ The simplest solution: White cuts the enemy king off from the center of the board.  Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 9-86 }
*

