{ Smyslov − Keres, USSR ch, Moscow 1949  (analysis)   Cutting the king off along the f-file is not obligatory @@StartBracket@@even more so because Black can overcome it@@EndBracket@@. Instead of 7.Rf8, the text move is also possible. }
7. Ra8 Kf5 8. Ra5+ Re5 9. Ra8
{ The game Timman-Radulov, Wijk aan Zee 1974 @@StartBracket@@with reversed colors and wings@@EndBracket@@ went  9...Rd5  10.Rf8+  Ke4  11.Re8+  Kd3  12.Kf3  Kd2  13.Kf2  Kd1  14.Rf8  Rd2+  15.Kf1  Rh2  16.Rf5  Kd2  17.Rxg5  Ke3  18.Ra5  Draw. }
9... Re2+
{ White should play  10.Kf3  Rh2  11.Rf8+!  followed with Rh8 And if  10...Re3+  11.Kg2=  It is worth mentioning that here again, as on move three, a retreat of the king to the back rank loses. }
10. Kg1 f3 11. Ra4 Rg2+
{ 11...Re4?  12.Ra2  Kf4  13.Kf2  Re2+  14.Rxe2  fxe2  15.h4!= } 12. Kh1
{ Diagram 9-87 This position occurred in Schmidt-Plachetka, Decin 1976, with a single unimportant difference: the white rook stood on b4.   12.Kf1  Rh2  13.Ra5+  Kg6  -+ }
12... g4 13. hxg4+ { 13.Rxg4  Rxg4  14.hxg4+  Kxg4  -+ } 13... Kg5
{ Now Black threatens  14.--  Re2  followed by ...Kh4-g3. As we know, a passive defense with the rook on the first rank does not help against an f-pawn. As for checks from the rear, Black will use the g-pawn as an umbrella against them.   If  13...Rxg4?  14.Ra2  Kf4  15.Kh2  Rh4+  16.Kg1  Kg3  , White holds the endgame because of a stalemate:  17.Rg2+= }
14. Ra1 Re2
{ In the game, Plachetka choose a mistaken continuation  14...Kh4?  and White managed to hold the game by means of  15.Rf1!  Rg3   if  15...Kg3  16.Rg1  Kf2  17.Ra1  Rxg4  , a stalemate saves White again:  18.Ra2+  Kg3  19.Kg1  Rb4  20.Rg2+!  16.g5!  Kxg5  17.Ra1  . However a step by the king to the opposite direction would have led to a win:  14...Kf4!  15.g5   15.Rf1  Re2  16.g5  Kg3  17.Rg1+  Kh3  18.Rf1  f2  , or  15.Rg1  Re2  -+  15...Kg3  16.--  Rh2+  17.Kg1  f2+  is threatened. Therefore  16.Rg1  Kf2  17.Ra1  Rg4!  18.Ra2+  Kg3  19.Kg1  Rb4  @@StartBracket@@the g-pawn is still on the board, so there is no stalemate possibility@@EndBracket@@  20.Ra1  Rb2  21.g6  Rg2+  22.Kf1  Rh2  -+ }
15. Rg1 Kh4 16. g5 Kh3 { 16...f2 } 17. Ra1 Rh2+ 18. Kg1 f2+ { Black wins. } *

