{ Vaisser − Djuric, Szirak 1985  In comparison with the previous ending, the black pawns are less advanced. This circumstance seems to be in White's favor, but actually he is faced with severe problems. His rook cannot reach h8, as with Smyslov's defensive method against a king penetration via the h-file.   For example, if  1.Rb6?  then  1...f5+  2.Kf4  Ra8  3.Rb7  Ra4+  4.Kg3  Ra3+  5.Kf4  Rh3  , and if  5.Kg2  Kh5  6.Rh7+  Kg4  7.Rh6  Ra6  -+   In Gliksman-Novak, Stary Smokovec 1976, the same position with reversed colors arose. The game continued  1.h5?  gxh5+  leads to a drawn endgame with f- and h-pawns. Therefore  1...g5!  2.Rb6  Rf7  3.Ra6  Kg7  4.Kf5  Rb7  5.h6+   5.Ra5  Kh6!  6.Kxf6  Rb1  7.Kf5  Kxh5  -+  5...Kxh6  6.Rxf6+  Kh5  7.Ke5  Rb3  8.Rf1  Kh4  9.Rh1+  Rh3  -+  and Black won.  Vaisser discovered a new defensive method for this sort of ending, and thus a highly important one: }
1. Kh3
{ The immediate  1.Ra3  Rb8  2.Rf3  Rb6  ⨀  3.Kg3   3.Rf1?  f5+  4.Kh3  Rb3+  5.Kh2  Rb4  -+  3...Kh5  4.Kh3  Ra6!?  and now  5.Kg3?  is wrong in view of  5...f5  ∆  6.--  Ra4  -+. But @@StartFEN@@8/8/r4pp1/7k/7P/5R1K/8/8 w - - 8 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Rf1!  Ra3+  6.Kh2  f5  7.Rg1=  was good enough, too. }
1... f5 2. Ra3 Rf7
{ 2...Rb8  was more sensible, because here White, if he wished, could have played 3.Ra8 transposing to the plan we already know. }
3. Rb3 Re7 4. Rg3 Re8 5. Rg1 Re3+ 6. Kh2
{ It becomes clear that the black king cannot go ahead when the white rook is placed on the g-file:  6...Kh5  7.Rg5+  . }
6... Rd3 7. Rg2 Rd6
{ If  7...f4  then  8.Rg4  Rd2+  9.Kh3  or  9.Kg1  f3  10.Rf4  Rd3  11.Rg4  ∆ Kf2=  But @@StartFEN@@8/8/6pk/8/5p1P/3r4/6RK/8 w - - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Rf2  Rd4  9.Kh3  Kh5  10.Rd2!=  is also good. }
8. Kh3 Rf6 9. Rg5
{ Draw in view of  9...f4  10.Kg2  f3+  11.Kf2  Rf4  12.Rg3  Kh5  13.Rg5+! } *

