{ Chigorin - Tarrasch, Budapest 1896  (analysis)   The rook had to watch the fifth rank. The a6-pawn is not necessary for Black: its existence is not essential for a draw. }
1... Kg8 2. h5 Rb5
{ The most solid defense, suggested by Fridstein.   In the line  2...Kf8  3.h6  Kg8  4.Rg7+  Kf8  5.Rg6  Kf7  6.h7  Ra4+  7.Kg3  Ra3+  8.Kh4  Ra1  9.h8=N+  Kf8  10.Rxf6+  Kg7  11.Kg5  Kxh8   11...Ra5+?  12.Rf5  Rxf5+  13.gxf5  Kxh8  14.Kf6!  +-  12.Kg6  White, according to the Encyclopedia of Chess Endings, should win. However it is a mystery to me how he can do it after  12...Kg8  13.Rb6  Kf8  14.g5  a5  , and if  13.g5  Rb1  14.Rxa6  Rb8= }
3. Rxa6 Kg7 4. Ra7+ { Diagram 9-92 } 4... Kg8
{ Moreover, as noted by Vardan Pogosyan, the king is not obliged to retreat to the eighth rank: after  4...Kh6!?  5.Rf7  Rb4+  or  5...Rb6  6.Kf5  Rb5+  7.Kxf6  Rb4!  , a drawn position has arisen on the board, familiar to us through the analysis of thePolgar-Short ending @@StartBracket@@9-89@@EndBracket@@. }
5. h6 Rc5 6. Rg7+ Kf8 { 6...Kh8?  7.Rf7  Rc6  8.Kf5  +- } 7. Rg6
{ 7.Kg3  Rc1= } 7... Kf7 8. h7 Rc8 9. Rh6 Kg7
{ 9...Rh8?  10.Kf5  Kg7  11.Rh1  Kf7  12.Ra1  +- } 10. Rh1 Ra8
{ And White cannot strengthen his position. } 11. Kf5 Ra5+
{ Ed. note: analyzed in the next variation → Diagram 9-93 } *

