{ Chigorin - Tarrasch, Budapest 1896  (analysis) } 2... Rg5
{ Is also playable. } 3. Rxa6 Kg7 4. Ra7+
{ 4.h6+  Kg6=  But not  4...Kxh6?  5.Rxf6+  Rg6  6.Kf5  +- } 4... Kg8 5. h6 Rg6
6. h7+ Kh8 7. Rf7
{ Diagram 9-93  Black should not cling to the f6-pawn. He achieves a draw by means of }
7... Rg5
{ The other way Black can save himself was shown by David Navara:  7...f5!  8.gxf5  Rg4+!  or  8.g5  Ra6=   After  7...Rh6?  8.Kf5!  Black loses. The game Malisauskas-Sandler @@StartBracket@@USSR 1977@@EndBracket@@ continued  8...Rh4   8...Rh5+  9.Kg6!  Rg5+  10.Kh6  +-  Now  9.g5?  would be a mistake in view of  9...fxg5  10.Kg6  Rf4=  and if  9.Rxf6?  Rxh7!=  In the game @@StartFEN@@7k/5R1P/5p2/5K2/6Pr/8/8/8 w - - 5 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Rd7  was played,  9...Rh6  10.Re7   A simpler way is  10.Ra7  ⨀  Rh4  11.g5!  fxg5  12.Kg6  +-  10...Rh4  11.g5  Rh5  12.Kg6??  A gross error just when a step away from a win.  12...Rxg5+  13.Kh6  Re5!  14.Rf7  Re8  15.Kg6  Rd8  Draw. Instead,  12.Re8+!  Kxh7  13.Kxf6  was decisive. }
8. Rxf6 Ra5 { 8...Rg7  9.Rh6  Ra7= } 9. Rh6 { 9.Rf7  Ra4+  10.Kg5  Rxg4+= }
9... Ra4+ 10. Kg5 Ra5+ 11. Kh4 Ra7
{ Or  11...Ra1=   Diagram 9-94 has been intentionally omitted. } *

