{ The rook’s placement is extremely important.  If the rook of the stronger side is placed passively  (in front of the enemy’s pawn)  a draw can be achieved simply by placing the king in front of the connected pair of pawns.    Some time ago I was quite impressed by a discovery that the former world champion produced during our joint analytical work.  Diagram 9-96 has been intentionally omitted.  Adapted from V.Smyslov 1976  White has three finely placed connected pawns, but the position is drawn! }
1... Ra3+ 2. Kd4 { 2.Kd2  Ra4  3.f5  Ra5=  is no better. } 2... Ra4+ 3. Kc3
Rxf4 4. Rxa2 Rh4 { 4...Rf5  also draws. } 5. Ra7+ Kg8 6. Ra8+ { 6.h6  Rg4= }
6... Kg7
{ But not  6...Kh7?  7.g6+  , coming to a winning Kasparian position, seeDiagram 9-56. }
7. h6+ Kg6 8. Rg8+ Kh7 9. Rg7+ Kh8 10. Re7 Rg4 11. Re5 Kh7 12. Kd3 Kg6
{ The most White could achieve is the drawnKling and Horwitz position @@StartBracket@@Diagram 9-55@@EndBracket@@. Smyslov and I actually analyzed the position with the b-pawn rather than the a-pawn. In that position, Karsten Müller, many years later, showed a complicated path to victory.  Ed. note: see the next variation → Diagram 9-96b }
*

