[SetUp "1"]

{ K.Müller 2014, Smyslov 1976 } 1... Rb3+ 2. Ke4 Rb4+ 3. Kf5 Rb5+ 4. Ke6
{ 4.Kg4?!  Rb4  is useless. } 4... Rb6+ 5. Kd5 Rb5+ 6. Kc6 Rb4 7. f5
{ Ed. note: analyzed in the next variation → Diagram 9-96c } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 9 – Rook Endgames II"]
[Black "Pawns on Opposite Wings 9-96 c"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/6k1/2K5/5PPP/1r6/8/1p6/1R6 b - - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ K.Müller 2014, Smyslov 1976  (analysis) } 7... Rg4
{ If Black temporizes,  7...Rb8  8.h6+  Kh7  , then the most exact way is  9.Kd5!   But not  9.Kc5?  Rg8  @@StartSquare@@  9...Rf8  also draws.@@EndSquare@@ @@StartFEN@@6r1/7k/7P/2K2PP1/8/8/1p6/1R6 w - - 3 10@@EndFEN@@  10.g6+  Kxh6  11.Rxb2  Kg5  12.Rf2  Kf6=  9...Rb4  10.Ke5  @@StartBracket@@and now, thanks to zugzwang, Black must allow the king back to the lower half of the board@@EndBracket@@  10...Rb5+  11.Kf4  Rb4+  12.Kg3  Rb5  13.Kg4  Rb3  14.Kh4  ⨀ +- }
8. h6+ Kh7 9. Rxb2 Rxg5 10. Rf2
{ White’s king is close enough to the f-pawn, which would not be the case if Black had an a-pawn like in the previous position.  Clearly, the problems with the realization of White’s material advantage were obviously caused by the poor position of White’s rook. Tarrasch’s famous rule is perfectly on point here:  Place your rook behind the passed pawn, whether it is yours or your adversary’s.  Thereby the rook can retain utmost activity.  Tarrasch’s rule is valid for the overwhelming majority of rook-and-pawn endings but, as it goes without saying, not for absolutely all of them. Generally speaking, there is no rule in chess which does not have an exception.  An amateur followed Tarrasch’s rule in a correspondence game and had to resign immediately after receiving his opponent’s reply. He wrote an irritated letter to the grandmaster: “I relied upon your authority but lost because of you, with your stupid rule...”  Tarrasch published it in his chess column with the final position of that game, adding the following annotation: “Especially for this reader and a few similar to him @@StartBracket@@the majority, as I am sure, do not need it@@EndBracket@@, I supplement my rule. You should always place your rook behind a pawn. Except for the cases when this is unfavorable!”  Diagram 9-97 has been intentionally omitted. }
*

