[FEN "8/8/6k1/R7/7P/p5PK/2r5/8 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In some cases, the weaker side holds when his rook protects his pawn from the side.  Tarrasch – Chigorin, St. Petersburg m  (9)  1893 }
1... a2
{ As Maizelis proved, the diagrammed position is drawn @@StartBracket@@however against a more favorable setup of White’s pawns @@StartFEN@@8/8/6k1/R7/6P1/6KP/p1r5/8 b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ at h3 and g4, Black has no chances@@EndBracket@@. }
2. h5+
{ If the pawn stepped ahead without giving a check @@StartBracket@@e.g., with the black king on f6@@EndBracket@@, the move @@StartFEN@@8/8/5k2/R6P/8/6PK/p1r5/8 b - - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Rc5!  would have led to an immediate draw. Well, let us make use of this idea later, when the white pawns reach a higher rank. }
2... Kf6 3. Kh4 { 3.g4  Rc5!  4.Rxa2  Kg5= } 3... Rh2+ 4. Kg4 Rb2 5. Ra6+ Kg7
6. Kg5 Rb5+ 7. Kh4 Rb2 8. g4
{ @@StartFEN@@8/6k1/R7/7P/6PK/8/pr6/8 w - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.h6+  is threatened. }
8... Kf7 9. Ra4 { 9.h6  Rb6!  10.Ra7+  Kg6=  is nonsensical. } 9... Kg7
{ Rather than  9...Rc2?  10.h6  Kg6  11.Ra6+  Kh7  12.Kh5  +- } 10. Ra7+
{ 10.Ra6  Kf7= } 10... Kf6 11. g5+ Kf5 12. h6 Rh2+ 13. Kg3 Rh1 14. Rxa2 Kxg5
{ Draw. } *

