{ Sometimes the weaker side employs another, more active defensive method: the king is advanced to support the passed pawn. As a consequence, this pawn will cost a whole rook for the stronger side, but in the meantime his own pawns, together with the king, will be advanced too far, and the endgame “two connected passed pawn against a rook” turns out to be winning.  Therefore this tactic has practical chances only against less advanced pawns and misplaced pieces of the stronger side. As, for example, in the following case:  Reshevsky – Alekhine, AVRO 1938    It would have been an easy draw for Black with the white rook on a1: @@StartFEN@@8/8/3k4/8/6P1/7K/pr5P/R7 b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Ke6  2.Kg3  Kf6  . }
1... Kc6
{ In our case, however, a passive defense is hopeless:  1...Ke6?  2.Kg3  Kf6  3.h3  Kg6  4.Kh4  Rh2  5.Ra6+  Kg7  6.g5  Kh7  7.Kg4  followed by h4, Kh5 etc.  Or @@StartFEN@@8/8/5k2/R7/6P1/6KP/pr6/8 b - - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Rc2  4.Kh4  Rh2  5.Ra6+  Ke5  6.Kg5!  Rxh3  7.Rxa2  Rh8  8.Re2+  Kd6  9.Kf6  +- }
2. Kg3
{ If  2.g5  , then  2...Rb5!  3.Ra6+  Kb7  4.Rxa2  Rxg5  5.Rc2  Rg8=  The evaluation of the final position of this line is not quite obvious because we have not studied defense by frontal attack against a rook pawn. I think it is pertinent to say here that, with an h2-pawn, White has winning chances only when the black king is cut off on the a-file. }
2... Kb6 3. Ra8 Kb5 4. h3
{ After  4.g5  , both  4...Kb4  @@StartBracket@@∆ Rb3+@@EndBracket@@ and the immediate  4...Rb3+  are good. }
4... Kb4 5. Kf4
{ The consequences of  5.Kh4  are harder to calculate, but its result is still a draw:  5...Kb3  6.g5   6.Kg5  Rb1  7.h4  a1=Q  8.Rxa1  Rxa1  9.h5  Kc4  10.h6  Kd5  11.Kg6  Ke5=  6...Rb1  7.Kh5  a1=Q  8.Rxa1  Rxa1  9.g6  Kc4  10.g7  Rg1  11.Kh6  Kd5  12.Kh7  Ke6  13.g8=Q  Rxg8  14.Kxg8  Kf5= }
5... Rc2
{ As is presumed in endgames with a far advanced passed pawn, Black speculates on the threat of interference, namely  6.--  Rc4+  7...Rc5@@StartBracket@@c3@@EndBracket@@+ and 8...Ra5@@StartBracket@@a3@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Rb8+ Kc3 7. Ra8 Kb4
{ Draw.   Of course, there is no reason for Black to play  7...Kb2  , but he seems not to be losing even after that move:  8.h4  a1=Q  9.Rxa1  Kxa1  10.h5  Rh2  11.Kg5  Kb2  12.Kh6  Kc3  13.g5  Kd4  14.g6  Ke5  15.g7  Rg2  16.Kh7  Kf6= }
*

