{ Tragicomedies: Dreev – Ehlvest, USSR chsf, Tallinn 1986    As we know, when the white rook is passive, the black king should be placed on the queenside. However, after  1...Kd5?  2.a5  ∆ Kc3-b3-a4, Black is lost. At the proper moment, the rook abandons the blockade square  g4  in order to create threats to the king. Vulfson analyzed a similar endgame in detail in the book by Dvoretsky and Yusupov, Technique for the Tournament Player.  It is important to push the g-pawn at least a single step forward in order to reduce the active possibilities of the white rook. }
1... Kf5 2. Rg1 g4 3. Kc4 g3
{ But now the king fails to come back to the queenside in time. Black had to play  3...Ke6!  4.Kc5  , he could resort to frontal checks:  4...Rc8+!?  And on @@StartFEN@@6r1/8/4k3/8/PPK3p1/8/8/6R1 w - - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Rg3  Kd6  5.b5  Kc7  6.a5  Kb7= }
4. Kd5 { Shouldering! } 4... Rd8+ 5. Kc6 Rc8+ 6. Kb7 Rg8 7. a5 Rg7+ 8. Kb6 Ke5
9. a6 Rg6+ 10. Kc5 { Black resigned. } *

