{ Tragicomedies: Ostermeyer – Dueball, BRD ch, Mannheim 1975 } 1. Kg2
{ An odd move: in endgames, the king should go forward, not backward.  1.f3  suggested itself, for example,  1...b3   1...Rc4  2.f4  or  2.Rb6+  ∆ 3.f4  2.Kf4  @@StartBracket@@∆ Rb6+@@EndBracket@@  2...Rc4+  @@StartBracket@@side checks are not efficient because the rook and the f3-pawn are only separated by two files@@EndBracket@@  3.Ke3  Rc3+  4.Ke4  Rc4+  5.Kd3  Rf4  6.Ke3  +-  And in case of @@StartFEN@@8/8/6k1/1R6/4K1P1/1pr2P2/8/8 b - - 5 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Kf6  5.f4  Rc4+  6.Ke3  Rc3+  7.Kd4  Rg3  8.Rb6+  and 9.g5 +- White is playing in accordance with a principle that, in Nimzovitch’s opinion, is a cornerstone of correct endgame strategy:  the collective advance! }
1... b3 2. f4
{ A severe positional error: the king will be cut off from the pawns forever. It was still not too late for  2.f3!  ∆ 3.Kg3 +- }
2... Kf6 3. Rb6+ Kf7 4. g5 Kg7 5. f5 Rc5 6. Rb7+ Kg8 7. Rb8+ Kg7 8. f6+ Kf7
{ Draw.   Or  8...Kg6  9.Rg8+  Kf7  10.Rg7+  Kf8= } *

