{ 9/16. Bernstein-Zuckerman, Paris 1929  The main question is which pawn should be advanced first? }
1. h6
{ Bernstein played  1.g6?  a2  2.Kg2  Rb1!  3.Rxa2  Rb5  4.Ra8+  Kg7  5.Ra7+  Kg8  6.Rh7  and now  6...Rb3!  could have led to a draw à la Kasparian, seeDiagram 9-56. Instead of this, Black played  6...Rg5+??  and lost. }
1... a2
{ Both  1...Kf8  2.Ra8+  Kf7  3.h7  and  1...Kh8  2.Kg2  Ra2+  3.Kf3  Ra1  4.g6  are quite bad. }
2. Kh2 { 2.Kg2?  Rb1  3.Rxa2  Rb5= } 2... Rb1 3. Rxa2 Rb5 4. Rg2 Kh7
{ Diagram 16-83 } 5. g6+
{ But surely not  5.Kh3?  Kg6  arriving at theKling and Horwitz drawn position. }
5... Kg8 6. Rg3 Ra5 7. Rb3 Rh5+ 8. Rh3 Rg5 9. h7+
{ 9.g7  Kh7  10.Rg3  is equivalent. } 9... Kh8 10. Rg3 Rh5+ 11. Kg2 Kg7 12. Rh3
Rg5+ 13. Kf3 Rf5+ 14. Kg4 Rf8 15. Kg5 { White wins. } *

