{ If the rook protects pawns from the side and the enemy king blocks the passed pawn, then the pieces of the stronger side attack the opponent's pawn on the other wing, while the passed pawn, if necessary, can be sacrificed.   An interesting example of this strategy follows in the next diagram. Studying it, we should refresh our memories about the theory of rook and pawn versus rook endgames, particularly the case of frontal attack.   Rigan − Yandemirov, Budapest 1993    According to the above-mentioned rule, Black must attack the g4-pawn. But how is he to do this? His king is cut off along the sixth rank, while  1...Rc4?  will be met by  2.Rxb5  Rxg4  3.Kc3  Kg6  4.Kd3  Rf4  5.Ke3=  or  5.Rb1  g4   5...Kh5  6.Ke3=  6.Ke3!  Rf5  7.Ke2!  ∆ 8.Rf1=, rather than @@StartFEN@@8/8/6k1/8/5rp1/3K4/8/1R6 w - - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Ke2?  Kg5  7.Rf1  g3! }
1... Kg7
{ A superb waiting move that puts White in zugzwang. His rook is placed optimally and cannot abandon its post. In case of  2.Kb4  Rc4+  3.Kxb5  Rxg4  4.Kc5  Rh4!  (the only method of crossing the sixth rank with the king)  5.Kd5  Rh6  6.Rb1  Kg6  7.Ke4  Rh3!  the king is cut off along the rank, and this fact is decisive. }
2. Kb2 Rc4 3. Rxb5 Kf6
{ This is why the white king should have been pushed back! The rook is not hanging now, and Black manages to improve his king's position without letting White do the same. If  4.Rf5+  Kg6  5.Rf1  then  5...Rxg4  6.Kc3  Rg2!  7.Kd3  Kh5  8.Ke3  Kg4  -+ }
4. Kb3 Rxg4 5. Kc3 Re4 6. Kd3 Re8
{ In a very similar position from the gameTal-I. Zaitsev, Diagram 9-34,  6...Re1!?  7.Kd2  Re8  was played, but in our current case Black can even do without it. }
7. Kd2
{ 7.Rb1  is met by  7...g4!  8.Kd2  Kg5!  9.Re1  Rxe1  10.Kxe1  Kh4  -+ And in case of @@StartFEN@@4r3/8/5k2/8/6p1/3K4/8/1R6 w - - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Rb5  g3  9.Kd2  Re4!  10.Rb3  Rg4  11.Rb1  g2  12.Rg1  Kg5  13.Ke2  Kh4  14.Kf2  Kh3  -+ }
7... Kg6 { 7...g4  is also good. } 8. Rb1 Re5 { 8...g4??  9.Re1= } 9. Rg1 Kh5
{ White resigned.   9...Kf5!? } *

