{ As was said earlier, only an active defense gives the weaker side chances of salvation. We would like to emphasize two of the most important defensive methods:    1. The king's attack against a pawn.  Sometimes one succeeds in giving the rook up for a pawn, eating another pawn with the king and saving the game with a pawn against a rook.    2. Exchange of rooks.  If the eventual pawn endgame is drawn, the weaker side drives away the hostile rook, from the rank where it is protecting both pawns, by means of the exchange threat. These methods are often combined.
  Marshall − Capablanca, New York  (9)  1909 }
1... Rc7+ 2. Kg6
{ Had Frank Marshall been able to divine his opponent’s intent, he could have neutralized it by playing  2.Ke6  or  2.Kf6!  Rb7  3.Ke5!  Here Black is in a bad way, as the exchange of rooks does not work:  3...Rb4  4.Rxb4+  axb4  5.a5  Kc3  6.a6  b3  7.a7  b2  8.a8=Q  b1=Q  9.Qf3+  Kc4  10.Qc6+  or  9...Kd2  10.Qf2+  Kc3  11.Qd4+  and the queens come off. }
2... Rb7 3. h4 Rb4 4. Kg5
{ After  4.Rxb4+  axb4!  5.a5  Kc4  6.a6  b3  7.a7  b2  8.a8=Q  b1=Q+  a drawn queen-and-pawn endgame arises. }
4... Kxa4 5. h5 Ka3
{ But, of course, not  5...Kb3  or  5...Kb5??  6.Rxb4+  axb4  7.h6  +- } 6. h6
Rb8 7. h7 a4 8. Rh4 Rh8 9. Kg6 Kb3 10. Kg7 Rxh7+ 11. Kxh7 a3
{ Draw.  Ed. note: analyzed in the next variation → Diagram 9-109 } *

