[SetUp "1"]

{ The following example, as well as the exercises in this section, show how difficult precise calculation can be in this sort of position.   Taimanov − Averbakh, Leningrad 1947    Deliberating over the natural continuation  1...Kc4!  over the board, Black decided that he could get no more than a draw on account of  2.Kg6  Kb4  3.Rg3  a3  4.Rg2  a2  5.Rxa2  Rxa2  6.Kxg7=   Later on, Averbakh found an improvement: instead of  4...a2?  ,  4...Rc7!  5.Rg4+  Kb3  6.Rg3+  Kb2  -+ And if @@StartFEN@@8/2r3p1/6K1/7P/1k6/p7/6R1/8 w - - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Kh7  Rc5!  6.Kg6   6.Rh2  Rg5  7.Rh4+  Kb5  -+  6...Kb3  7.Rg3+  Kb2  8.Rg2+  Rc2  @@StartBracket@@this is why the zwischenzug 5...Rc5! was necessary – the king prevents a rook capture on g7.@@EndBracket@@  9.Rg1  Rh2!  @@StartBracket@@from here, the rook defends the g7-pawn indirectly and, at the same time, protects the king from checks along files and ranks@@EndBracket@@  10.Rg5  a2  11.Rb5+  Kc1  12.Ra5  Rg2+  13.Kh7  Kb1  14.Rb5+  Rb2  15.Ra5  Rb7  -+   The move  4.Rg2  is not forced, but  4.Rg1  a2  5.Ra1  Kb3  6.Rg1  is even worse. Curiously enough, Minev, in the Encyclopedia of Chess Endings, annotating a similar endgame from Marshall-Duras, San Sebastian 1912, evaluated this position as drawn, although  6...Rc7!  is quite a simple win. @@StartSquare@@Ed. detailed analysis → Diagram 9-111@@EndSquare@@ }
1... Ra6
{ The attempt to cut the king off from the g7-pawn does not work, although it does not spoil anything either. }
2. Kf5 Kc4 3. Rg3
{ This is the point!   The line  3...a3?  4.Rxg7  a2  5.Rg1  leads only to a draw. }
3... Rf6+
{ Therefore @@StartFEN@@8/r5p1/6K1/7P/pk4R1/8/8/8 b - - 8 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Kc5!  6.Rxa4  Rxa4  7.Kxg7  Rg4+!  In case of  6.Rg5+  Kd6  or  6...Kc6  transposing into situations that are already familiar to us. For example,  7.Rg2   7.Rg1  a3  7...a3  8.Ra2   8.Rc2+  Kb5  9.Rg2  Rc7!  8...Kc5!  9.Ra1  a2  10.Kh7  Kd5  11.Kg6  Kd6!  etc. 'à la Müller.' }
4. Ke5
{ In spite of Averbakh's opinion,  4.Kg5  does not draw. Black should simply return with his rook to  a6  @@StartBracket@@see the previous annotation@@EndBracket@@. Averbakh's line  4...Kb4  5.Rg4+  Kb3?!   5...Kb5!  6.Rg3  Ra6  7.Kf5  Ra7  8.Kg6  Kb4  9.Rg4+  Kc5!  -+  6.Rg3+  Kc2?  7.Rg2+?   7.Kh4!  Rf7  8.Kg5  Ra7  9.Kg6  Kb2  10.Kh7  a3  11.Rxg7=  7...Kc1  8.Rg3  Ra6?   8...Kb2!  9.Rg2+  Kb3  10.Rg3+  Kb4  11.Rg4+  Kb5  -+  9.Kf5  Ra7  actually leads to a draw:  10.Kg6  Kb2  and now  11.Kh7!   Rather than  11.Rg2+?  Kb3  etc.  11...a3  12.Rxg7=   Ed. note: analyzed in the next variation → Diagram 9-111 and the game continuation is given in Diagram 9-112. }
*

