[SetUp "1"]

{ Taimanov − Averbakh, Leningrad 1947  (analysis)    The rook is a long-range piece that is capable of driving the enemy king with checks far away from the decisive area.   Therefore let us consider }
1. Rg4+
{ The line  4...Kc3  5.Rg3+  Kd4?  6.Rxa3!  Rxa3  7.Kxg7  Rg3+  8.Kf7  Rh3  9.Kg6  Ke5  10.h6  Ke6  11.Kg7!=   In case of @@StartFEN@@8/6K1/8/7P/3k4/r7/8/8 b - - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  7...Ke5  8.h6  Ra7+  9.Kg6!  and if  8...Kf5  9.h7  Ra7+  10.Kh6!=  leads to an immediate draw. }
1... Kb5 2. Rg5+ { 5.Rg2  Rc7! } 2... Kc6 3. Rg1 a2 4. Ra1
{ Diagram 9-111  What can Black undertake? } 4... Kc5
{ Let us try the waiting move } 5. Kh7
{ Now  8...Kc4  9.Rxa2  is useless.   8...g5+  9.Kg6  g4  10.h6  g3  11.h7  Rxh7  12.Kxh7  g2  is not dangerous for White either, because the black pawns are too far away from each other @@StartBracket@@look atDiagram 8-32 again@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Kd5 { The strongest. } 6. Kg6
{ Black does not play  9...Ke5  10.Re1+!  Kd4  11.Ra1!  ∆ 12.Rxa2 @@StartBracket@@the king is too late approaching the pawn@@EndBracket@@.  White should only avoid @@StartFEN@@8/r5p1/6K1/4k2P/8/8/p7/R7 w - - 6 7@@EndFEN@@  10.Kh7?  Kf5  -+ }
6... Kd6 { At first I did not see any danger for White here either: } 7. Kh7
{ 10.Rd1+  is bad because of  10...Ke7!  11.Ra1  Kf8  -+ followed by  12.--  Ra6+  . }
7... Ke5 8. Kg6
{ However, grandmaster Müller finally discovered a winning continuation. Black suddenly sacrifices his g-pawn: }
8... Ra6+ 9. Kxg7 Kf5 10. Kf7 { 13.h6  Ra7+  -+ } 10... Kg5 11. Ke7 Kxh5
{ And, as can easily be seen, his king comes to the queenside in time. } *

