[SetUp "1"]

{ In both cases @@StartSquare@@Ed. this exercise and the next one@@EndSquare@@, your task is to find whether Black can achieve a draw.  9/17. Mednis-Djukic, Nis 1977 }
1... Ra8+
{ An important zwischenschach that entices the white king to reach the b-file.   1...g3?  2.b7  Rf8  3.Rb2!  ∆ Ka6-a7 is bad for Black. }
2. Kb5 g3 { As grandmaster Pal Benko demonstrated, White could win. } 3. Rb2
{ Mednis chose  3.b7  , which also wins, but after  3...Rf8  he erred with  4.Rc2?   If  4.Ka6?  , the same reply follows.  4...Rf2!  Amusingly, the standard exchange offer saves Black even in such an apparently hopeless situation. After  5.b8=Q  Rxc2  6.Qa8  , the simplest is  6...Rxg2=  . A waiting tactic is also possible:  6...Rf2  7.Kc4  Kg1  8.Kd3  Kh2  9.Ke3  Kg1  10.Qd5  Kh1=   Rather than  10...Kh2?  in view of the zugzwang after  11.Qf3!  5.Rc4  Rf8  6.Rc8  Rf2  7.b8=Q  Rb2+  8.Kc4  Rxb8  9.Rxb8  Kxg2  10.Kd3  Kf2  11.Rf8+  Ke1!  Draw. @@StartSquare@@Ed. even after 3.b7 Rf8 White can still win; analysis → Diagram 9-113 EXTRA@@EndSquare@@ }
3... Rf8 4. Kc4 Rf2 5. Kc3 Rf7
{ Black can try  5...Rf8!?  instead,  6.b7  Rb8  7.Kd4  Kg1  8.Kd5  Kh2   8...Rxb7  9.Rxb7  Kxg2  10.Ke4  +-  9.Kc6  Rf8!  , hoping for  10.Kc7  Rf7+  11.Kd6?  Rxb7=  or  11.Kb6?  Rf2!=  However, after  10.Kd6!  , he is in zugzwang, for example,  10...Kg1   10...Rg8  11.Kc7  Rg7+  12.Kb6  Rg8  13.Ka7  +-  11.Kc7  Rf7+  12.Kb6  Rf2  13.Rb1+  or  13.Rb3  , winning. }
6. b7 Rxb7 7. Rxb7 Kxg2 8. Kd2
{ 8...Kf2  9.Rf7+  and the king cannot go to e1. } *

