[SetUp "1"]

{ 9/18 Yusupov-Malaniuk, USSR ch, Moscow, 1983 } 1... Rf8 { ∆ Rf4 } 2. Kc2
{ Yusupov ably prevents Black’s plans. If  2...Rf4?  then  3.Rxf4  gxf4  4.g5  Ke3  5.Kd1!  and if @@StartFEN@@8/8/8/6P1/5p2/5k2/P1K5/8 b - - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Ke2  5.g6  f3  6.g7  f2  7.g8=Q  f1=Q  8.Qc4+  is decisive. }
2... Kg3
{ The king clears the way for the future of the upcoming passed f-pawn. } 3. a4
{ Diagram 16-85   The game continued  3...Rf4?  4.Rxf4  gxf4  5.g5  f3  6.g6  f2  7.g7  f1=Q  8.g8=Q+  Kh4  9.Qd8+!  Black resigned because he could not prevent a queen exchange:  9...Kh5  or  9...Kg4  10.Qd1+  and after @@StartFEN@@3Q4/8/8/8/P6k/8/2K5/5q2 b - - 2 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Kh3  or  9...Kg3  10.Qd3+  .   As can be easily seen, after  8...Kh2  or  8...Kh3  , the white queen gives a pair of checks and enters the d-file with a forced exchange to follow.   After the game, Malaniuk expressed the opinion that a frontal attack could have saved him:  3...Ra8!?  4.Kb3  Kf3  5.Rd4  Kg3  6.Kb4  Rb8+  7.Kc5  Ra8  8.Kb6  Rb8+  9.Kc6  Ra8  10.Kb7  Ra5  11.Kb6  Ra8  12.a5  Rb8+  13.Kc6   13.Ka7?  Rb1=  13...Ra8  14.Ra4  Rxa5  15.Rxa5  Kxg4  . Of course, this would not work: in the final position, both  16.Kd5  and  16.Ra8  Kf3  17.Rf8+!  Ke3  18.Rg8!  Kf4  19.Kd5  g4  20.Kd4  Kf3  21.Kd3  g3  22.Rf8+  win for White. Black’s play can be improved in this line if he abandons his frontal attack in a timely fashion, for the basic plan in such positions, repositioning the rook to  f4  .  Instead of  10...Ra5?  ,  10...Rf8!  11.a5  Rf4=  @@StartBracket@@as given by Müller@@EndBracket@@. Salov and Ionov discovered the same idea in a different setting: they proposed giving a series of checks from the side @@StartBracket@@similar to theTaimanov-Averbakh endgame@@EndBracket@@, to drive White’s king into an inferior position, before offering the exchange of rooks on  f4  . }
3... Rf2+ 4. Kc3 Rf3+ 5. Kb2 { 5.Kd2  Rf2+  6.Kd1  Ra2  7.Kc1  Rf2= } 5... Rf4
6. Rxf4 gxf4 7. g5 f3 8. g6 f2 9. g7 f1=Q 10. g8=Q+ Kh4
{ White can no longer trade queens, so the game should end in a draw. } *

