{ What if Black could not play ...h7-h5 in time? We shall analyze two important endings that may serve as landmarks for both sides: the stronger side may pursue them while the weaker side should avoid these situations.  These endings are thoroughly analyzed in endgame handbooks. We skip some less important lines, limiting ourselves to the conclusions.  Botvinnik – Najdorf, Moscow ol 1956 }
1. Ra5 Rc7 2. Rd5 Ra7 3. e5 fxe5 4. fxe5
{ @@StartFEN@@8/r4kp1/7p/3RPK1P/6P1/8/8/8 w - - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Rd7+!  is threatened. }
4... Ke7 5. e6 Ra4
{ 5...Ra6  6.Rd7+  Kf8  7.Kg6!  Rxe6+  8.Kh7  is quite bad for Black. } 6. g5
{ Diagram 9-117   6.Rd7+  Kf8  7.Rf7+  Kg8  8.g5?  fails in view of  8...Ra5+!  9.Ke4  Ra6=  Black should avoid @@StartFEN@@6k1/5Rp1/4P2p/5KPP/r7/8/8/8 b - - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...hxg5?  9.Kg6  +-  Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 9-117 }
*

