[SetUp "1"]

{ Botvinnik − Najdorf, Moscow ol 1956  (continued) } 6... Ra7
{ The best defense, as suggested by Aronin. The rook may return because there is no danger of trading the rooks any longer:  7.Rd7+?  Rxd7  8.exd7  Kxd7  9.Kg6  hxg5  10.Kxg7  g4=     The actual continuation was @@StartFEN@@8/4k1p1/4P2p/3R1KPP/r7/8/8/8 b - - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...hxg5?!  7.Rd7+  Kf8  8.Rf7+  Kg8  9.Kg6  g4  10.h6!  @@StartBracket@@the shortest way to a win@@EndBracket@@  10...gxh6  11.e7  Ra8  12.Rf6  @@StartBracket@@∆ Rd6-d8@@EndBracket@@ Black resigned. }
7. Re5
{ A key move! White protects the pawn and prepares a king invasion. @@StartSquare@@Ed. 7.gxh6? is analyzed in Diagram 9-118@@EndSquare@@ }
7... hxg5
{ 7...Kd6  8.gxh6  gxh6  9.Kf6  and @@StartFEN@@8/r3k1p1/4P2p/4RKPP/8/8/8/8 b - - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Ra6  8.Kg6  Kf8  9.Kh7  hxg5  10.e7+  Ke8  11.Kxg7  g4  12.h6  +- }
8. Kxg5 { 8.Kg6  Kd6  9.Re1  g4  10.h6!  gxh6  11.Kf6  is also strong. } 8...
Ra1 9. Kg6 Rf1 { 9...Rg1+  10.Rg5  +- } 10. Kxg7 Rg1+ 11. Kh6 Rg2 12. Rg5
{ White wins. } *

