{ Capablanca – Yates, Hastings 1930/31 } 1. Rb6
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed. detailed analysis → Diagram 9-120@@EndSquare@@   White should have played  1.Rd6!  in order to use the rook to protect against checks from the side. }
1... Re3 2. Rb4
{ 2.Rb8  suggested itself. However, after  2...Re4  3.Kf3  Re1  , the straightforward  4.Re8?  allows salvation by  4...h5!  5.gxh5  Rf1+!  6.Ke4  Re1+  7.Kf5  Rh1  , and if  5.g5  Rf1+  6.Ke3  h4=   The most precise is  2.Rb1!  @@StartBracket@@temporarily denying the black rook the first rank@@EndBracket@@. Black is in zugzwang. He must either worsen his king’s position or move his rook off the e-file where it is best placed. In both cases, the invasion of the white rook becomes more effective. For example,  2...Re2+  3.Kf3  Rh2  4.f5  h5  5.Rb7  hxg4+  6.Kg3  Rh5  7.Kxg4  Rh1  8.e6  +-  In case of @@StartFEN@@8/5pk1/7p/4P3/5PP1/4r3/6K1/1R6 b - - 3 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Re4  3.Kf3  Ra4  , and now time has come for the main plan:  4.Rb8!  Ra3+  5.Kg2  Re3  6.Re8!  Re2+  7.Kf3  Re1  8.f5  Rf1+  9.Ke2  Rf4  10.Ke3  Rxg4  11.f6+  Kh7  12.e6  +- }
2... Rc3 3. Kf2 { 3.Rb8 } 3... Ra3
{ Both adversaries missed the fact that after  3...h5!  , Black either trades a pair of pawns  4.gxh5  Rh3  or obtains enough counterplay to save the game  4.g5  h4  . }
4. Rb7 Kg8 { 4...Ra2+!? } 5. Rb8+ Kg7 6. f5 { ∆ 7.f6+ and White won. } *

