[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 9 – Rook Endgames III"]
[Black "Four Pawns vs. Three on the Same Wing 9-120"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/5pk1/5R1p/4P3/5PP1/r7/6K1/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Capablanca − Yates, Hastings 1930/31  (analysis) } 1. Rb6 Ra4 2. Kf3
{ 2.Kg3  Ra3+  3.Kh4  Ra4  4.f5  Ra5  5.e6  fxe6  6.fxe6  Kf6= } 2... Ra3+ 3.
Ke4 Ra4+ 4. Kf5 Rc4 5. Rb7 { ∆ 6.e6. } 5... Kg8
{ With the king on g8, this idea is less effective in view of @@StartFEN@@6k1/1R6/4p2p/4K3/2r2PP1/8/8/8 b - - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Rc5+  8.Kxe6  Rc6+  this version of the “two-pawns-versus-one-pawn” ending is drawn. Let me remind you that we have already dealt with a similar position in the gameSmyslov-Keres @@StartBracket@@Diagram 9-85@@EndBracket@@. And after  8.Kf6  @@StartBracket@@if the king were on f8, this move would win@@EndBracket@@  8...Rc4= }
6. Rb3
{ 6.g5  hxg5  7.Kxg5  Rc5!  is not dangerous @@StartBracket@@with the king on  f8  , the simplest would be Kopaev’s recommendation  7...f6+!  , which is not possible here because of  8.Kg6!  +-@@EndBracket@@. Having occupied the f5-square with his king, White makes the implementation of the strongest plan – the preparation of f4-f5 – more difficult. }
6... Kg7 7. Re3 Rc6 { 7...Ra4  8.Re4  Ra1  9.Rd4 } 8. Ke4 Rc4+ 9. Kf3 Rc6
{ To this point, we have been following Kopaev’s line which demonstrates that  10.f5  Kf8  11.Ra3  Rc1  12.Ra8+  Ke7  13.f6+  Ke6  14.Re8+  Kd5  15.e6  Rc6  leads to a draw. But White’s play can be strengthened. }
10. Ra3
{ A similar continuation was suggested by Jonathan Speelman,  10.Kg3  Ra6  11.Rb3  . We are already familiar with the follow-up  11...f6  12.Rb7+  Kf8  13.exf6  , while on @@StartFEN@@8/5pk1/r6p/4P3/5PP1/1R4K1/8/8 b - - 21 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Rc6  there follows  12.Rb8  Rc3+  13.Kg2  Re3  14.Re8  +- and f4-f5 is inevitable. }
10... f6 11. Ra7+ Kf8
{ White does not play  12.Ke4  fxe5  13.fxe5  Rc1  @@StartBracket@@Averbakh@@EndBracket@@, but: }
12. exf6 Rxf6 13. Kg3 Kg8 14. Ra4
{ Followed by Kh4-h5 @@StartBracket@@the only way to prevent the seizing of the key h5-square – the transfer of the rook to h1 – is too late here@@EndBracket@@. }
