{ Korchnoi − Antoshin, USSR ch, Erevan 1954  (analysis) } 3. Rc8+
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed. In the game,  3.Rc6?!  was played → Diagram 9-124@@EndSquare@@ }
3... Kh7 4. e5
{ ∆ Kg3, f4, f5 +- Diagram 9-123  Black would have been faced with problems one can hardly tackle over the board, but objectively it should be defendable. }
4... Re7
{ In case of @@StartFEN@@4R3/5ppk/7p/4P2P/4r1P1/6K1/5P2/8 b - - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...f6  7.e6  g5  8.hxg6+  Kxg6  9.f3  Re1  10.Kf2  Re5  11.f4  +- and if  6...Ra4  7.Rf8  Ra7  8.f4  +-  Of course, only basic results are shown here, as a detailed explanation would have been rather complicated and too vast. }
5. f4 f6 6. Rc5 fxe5 7. fxe5
{ And now Black must prevent the white king’s march to the center, that would transpose to theBotvinnik-Najdorf ending, by: }
7... Rf7
{ Here Korchnoi gives  8.Kg3  g6!=  and @@StartFEN@@8/5rpk/7p/2R1P2P/6P1/8/6K1/8 w - - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.e6  Re7  9.Rc6  g6  10.Rd6  @@StartBracket@@∆ 11.Rd7@@EndBracket@@  10...Re8  11.Kf3  gxh5  12.gxh5  Kg7  13.Ke4  Kf6  14.Kd5  Re7= }
8. Rd5
{ This prophylactic move is more dangerous for Black.   He cannot play  8...g6?  on account of  9.e6  Rf8   9...Re7  10.Rd7  +-  10.Rd7+  Kg8  11.e7  Re8  12.Rd8  Kf7  13.Rxe8  Kxe8  14.g5!  +-, and  8...g5?  9.e6  Rf8  10.e7  Re8  11.Re5  Kg7  12.Re6  +- are also bad.   Black also loses in the line  8...Rf8  9.Kg3  Rf1  10.Rd7!  ⨀   10.Rd3  g5!  Now on  10...Kg8  or  10...Rf8  the same reply follows.  11.Rd3  g5  12.Rf3  Re8  13.Rf5  followed by 14.Kf3. Nevertheless, as Pogosyan has shown, he manages to save himself by continuing either @@StartFEN@@5r2/6pk/7p/3RP2P/6P1/6K1/8/8 b - - 4 9@@EndFEN@@  9...g5!  @@StartBracket@@instead of 9...Rf1?@@EndBracket@@  10.Rd3  Kg7  11.Rf3  Re8  12.Rf5  Ra8  , or: }
8... Rf4 9. Kg3 Ra4 10. Kf3 Kg8
