{ Piket – Kasparov, Internet Tournament 2000  White has succeeded in bringing his pawn to e5 @@StartBracket@@generally speaking, it would have been favorable for Black if he had prevented this by playing ...f7-f6 at an earlier stage@@EndBracket@@. On the other hand, ...h6-h5 has already been played, so reaching a draw should not be a very difficult problem.  Kasparov had to decide how to react should the white king march to g5 via h3 and h4. The simplest method was to play ...Kh6 at the proper moment.   For example,  1...Kg7  2.Kh3  Ra7  3.Kh4  Kh6!  , and one cannot see how White could make any progress.  Moreover, a king invasion to  g5  is not too dangerous. Even with the white rook on the seventh rank Black can survive. Averbakh analyzes  3...Ra6  @@StartBracket@@instead of 3...Kh6@@EndBracket@@  4.Rc7  Rb6  5.Re7  Ra6  6.Kg5   6.e6  Kf6!  7.Rxf7+  Kxe6=  6...Ra5!   As Bologan says, even  6...Rb6!?  7.e6  Rb5+!  or  7.f5  gxf5  does not lose.  7.f5  gxf5  8.Kxh5  Kf8  ∆ 9...Rxe5, and if @@StartFEN@@8/4Rpk1/8/r3PpKp/8/6P1/7P/8 w - - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.e6  f4+!  9.Kxf4  Kf6  10.Rxf7+  Kxe6= }
1... Rd3
{ In many similar situations, to place the rook behind the e-pawn makes some sense. In particular, such a maneuver is not bad when h-pawns are absent. But here this transfer is wrong. Its slightly modified version does not work either:  1...Rd4  2.Kh3  Re4?  3.Rc7!   3.Kh4?  Kh6  ∆  4.--  g5+  3...Kg7  4.Kh4  Re2  5.Kg5!  , and we come to situations that have actually occurred in the game. }
2. Kh3 Re3
{ 2...Rd7  3.Kh4  Kh6=  draws, but after the text move there is no turning back. }
3. Kh4
{ Playing  3.Rc7!  Kg7  4.Kh4  , Piket could have chained the hostile rook to the e-file and, as we shall see, this was a winning method. }
3... Kg7
{ He should play  3...Kh6!  4.Rc7  Re2!  If  5.Kh3  , then  5...g5!?  is also playable, or  5...Kg7  6.Rb7  g5!  7.fxg5  Kg6  .   The line @@StartFEN@@8/2R2p2/6pk/4P2p/5P1K/6P1/4r2P/8 w - - 7 5@@EndFEN@@  5.g4  hxg4  6.Rxf7  Rxh2+  7.Kxg4  is more dangerous for Black, but after  7...Re2  , he survives. }
4. Kg5
{ An erroneous order of moves; again  4.Rc7!  Re2  5.Kg5  is correct. Now Black could return to Averbakh’s plan: @@StartFEN@@8/5pk1/6p1/4P1Kp/5P2/4r1P1/2R4P/8 b - - 6 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Ra3!  5.Rc7  Ra5=  However Piket could hardly expect his opponent would suddenly change his mind and move the rook back. }
4... Re1 5. Rc7 Re2 6. Re7 Ra2 7. f5 gxf5 8. e6 h4 9. Rxf7+ Kg8 10. Kf6
{ Black resigned.  Ed. note: analyzed in the next variations → Diagram 9-128 & Diagram 9-129. }
*

