{ Piket − Kasparov, Internet Tournament 2000  (analysis)     Finally, instead of  5...Re2  , Black could have played  5...Re4!?  at once. }
5... Re4
{ The point is to meet  6.Re7  with  6...Ra4!  , and  7.f5  , as was played by Piket, is not possible anymore, while if  7.e6  , then  7...Ra5+  8.Kh4  Kf6  9.Rxf7+  Kxe6= }
6. Rb7 { White must wait. } 6... Ra4
{ 6...Re2  7.Re7!  transposes to the actual course of the game. } 7. g4
{ And here Bologan discovered a brilliant solution: a double pawn sacrifice.   Winning another pawn is much weaker:  7.e6  Ra5+  8.Kh4  Kf6  9.exf7  Kg7  10.Re7  Kf8!  11.Re5  Ra2  , or @@StartFEN@@8/1R3Pk1/6p1/r6p/5P1K/6P1/7P/8 w - - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10.h3  Kf8  11.g4  hxg4  12.hxg4  Rc5  13.f5  Rc6!  rather than  13...gxf5?  14.g5  +-. It looks like Black holds in both these lines. }
7... hxg4 { 7...Re4  8.gxh5  gxh5  9.h4  is hopeless. } 8. f5 gxf5 9. e6
{ White wins. } *

