[White "Chapter 9 – Rook Endgames III"]
[Black "The Rook Behind Its Own Pawn 9-133"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/r7/5ppk/p6p/R7/6P1/5P1P/6K1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Botvinnik − Borisenko, USSR ch, Moscow 1955  (analysis)     Let’s see how the fight takes shape after  1...Kg7!?  , instead of  1...Kg5  . }
1... Kg7
{ A.  2.f3  Kf7  3.g4  h4  -+   B.  2.Kf1  Kf7  3.Ke2  Ke6  4.Kd3  Kd5  5.Kc3  Kc5  6.Kb3  Kb5  7.Re4  a4+  8.Ka3  Ra6  9.h4  Kc5  10.Re2  Kd4  11.Re3  g5  -+ @@StartBracket@@Marin@@EndBracket@@   C.  2.h4  Kf7  3.Kf1  Ke6  4.Ke2  Kd6  5.Kd3   5.g4  hxg4  6.Rxg4  a4  7.Rxg6  a3  8.Rg1  a2  9.Ra1  Ke5  10.Kf3  Ra4  -+  5...f5!   Wrong is  5...Kc6?  6.g4  Rd7+  7.Kc3  Rd5  8.Rf4  f5  9.gxh5  gxh5  10.Kc4=  6.f3  Kc5  7.g4  Kb5  8.Rd4  a4  9.Kc2  a3  10.Kb1  Ra4!  11.Rd6  hxg4  12.Rxg6  gxf3  -+ @@StartBracket@@Kopaev@@EndBracket@@   D. @@StartSquare@@Ed. the text continuation@@EndSquare@@ }
2. Kg2 Kf7 3. Kf3 Ke6
{ Diagram 9-133   4.g4  h4  5.g5  fxg5  6.Kg4  Kf6  7.h3  Ra8  -+   4.h4  f5  5.Kf4  Kd5  6.Kg5  Ra6  7.f3  Kc5  8.g4  fxg4  9.fxg4  hxg4  10.Kxg4  Kb5  11.Ra1  a4  -+ @@StartBracket@@Levenfish, Smyslov@@EndBracket@@.  The conclusion that 1...Kg7 won was refuted by Vardan Pogosyan. He found an improvement in Levenfish and Smyslov’s line. }
4. g4 h4 { White, instead of the pawn sacrifice  5.g5?  simply plays  5.Kf4! }
5. Kf4 g5+
{ 5...Kd5  6.g5  f5  7.Ke3  Kc5  8.Kd2  or  8.Kd3=  , the h4-pawn, stripped of its support, becomes an object of attack. As we see, counterplay on the kingside is sometimes connected with Black’s plan in the previous example, of blockading the passed pawn with the king. }
6. Ke4 { Intending 7.f4, holds the balance. } 6... Rb7 7. Rxa5 Rb4+ 8. Kf3 Rf4+
9. Kg2 Rxg4+ 10. Kf3
{ Leads to a drawn ending, with two pawns versus three on one flank. } *

