{ Botvinnik – Borisenko, USSR ch, Moscow 1955  (analysis)     Instead of  4...Ke5  that was played in the game, the other attempt is: }
4... Kg5 5. Kg2 Kh4
{ Diagram 9-134   Kopaev, as well as Levenfish and Smyslov, examined  6.Kg1  Kh3  7.Kh1  f5  8.gxf5  gxf5  9.Kg1  f4  10.Kf2=  and @@StartFEN@@8/r7/5pp1/p7/R5P1/7k/7P/7K b - - 6 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Re7  8.Ra3+  Kxg4  9.Rxa5  , evaluating this position as drawn. But this is not so: after  9...Kf3!  , White is in trouble.   Instead of  6.Kg1?  Botvinnik recommended: }
6. h3 { And Marin continued this line: } 6... g5 7. Kh2 Rb7 8. Rxa5 Rb2+ 9. Kg1
Kxh3 10. Ra6 Kxg4 11. Rxf6 Kg3 12. Rf1
