{ 9/20. Eliseevic-Pytel, Trstenik 1979  What is the outcome with correct play? }
1... Rf4+
{ After  1...a5?  2.Rxe6  Re4  (∆ ...Kf7)  3.Re7  Kf8  4.Ra7  Rxe5  5.Kf2  Black's extra pawn does not offer him any real winning chances. The only promising possibility is to place the rook behind the distant passed pawn. }
2. Kg1 { 2.Ke2  Re4+  and 3...Rxe5. } 2... Rf7
{ In the game, Black's plan was completely successful.  3.Rxe6  Ra7  4.Rd6  a5  5.e6  Kf8  6.Rd3  Ke7  -+  7.Kf2  Kxe6  8.Ke3  a4  9.Ra3  Kd5  10.Kd3  Kc5  11.Kc3  Kb5  12.Kb2  Kc4  13.Rg3  a3+!  14.Ka2  Kd4  15.Rh3  h6  16.Rg3  g5  White resigned.  17.h4  is met with  17...Ra5  and if  18.Rb3  then  18...Ke4  19.Rb6  Kf4  20.Rxh6  g4  ∆  21.--  Kg3  -+   White should have defended his position more actively. Prior to blocking the passed pawn with his rook, he had enough time to win one of the kingside pawns. }
3. Re8+ Rf8 4. Rxe6 Ra8 5. Re7 { 5.Rd6  is worse in view of  5...Ra7!? } 5...
a5 6. e6 a4 7. Rd7 Kf8 { 7...a3  8.e7= } 8. Rf7+ Ke8 9. Rxg7 Ra5 10. Rc7 a3 11.
Rc1 a2 12. Ra1 Ke7 13. Kf2 Kxe6 14. Ke3
{ Black still stands better, but a draw seems very likely. } *

