{ The Rook in Front of the Pawn, with the Pawn on the Seventh Rank   We have seen a section with an identical title in the theory of 'a rook and a rook pawn versus a rook' endgames. The ideas from that section will be useful for our current considerations.   A pawn advance to the seventh rank absolutely shackles the opponent's forces. However, if there are no vulnerable points in his camp, the game is still drawn because a king march to the pawn is useless: no refuge from rook checks from behind is provided.   Pushing the pawn to the seventh rank makes sense, and offers winning chances when one of the following three plans is possible. @@StartSquare@@Ed. → Diagram 9-140 up to and including Diagram 9-145@@EndSquare@@ }
1. -- *

