[Black "The Rook in Front of the Pawn, with the Pawn on the Seventh Rank 9-140"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "R7/P5k1/5p2/1K4p1/4P1P1/8/8/r7 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Plan 1   It is sometimes possible to sacrifice the passed pawn, in order to exchange rooks by means of a seventh-rank check, transposing into a won pawn endgame.   Benko − Gereben, Budapest 1951    If the pawn stood on  a6  , then after @@StartFEN@@R7/6k1/P4p2/1K4p1/4P1P1/8/8/r7 w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Kb6  , the king could escape the checks at  a7  . But here, the king has no shelter, so White's only hope lies in the exchange of rooks. }
1. Kb6 Rb1+ 2. Kc6 Rc1+ 3. Kd6 Ra1
{ The key question in a pawn endgame will be: Who controls the opposition? After this mistake, it turns out to be White.   Black had to continue  3...Rd1+!  4.Ke6  Ra1  5.Re8  Ra6+!  6.Kf5  Rxa7=   And if @@StartFEN@@R7/P5k1/4Kp2/6p1/4P1P1/8/8/r7 w - - 8 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Rd8  Rxa7  6.Rd7+  Rxd7  7.Kxd7  Kh7!=  Note that Black must have the distant opposition, not the close one:  7...Kf7?  8.Kd6  +- We examined very nearly the same situation in the pawn endings chapter @@StartBracket@@Neishtadt's studyDiagram 1-8@@EndBracket@@. }
4. Rc8 { Of course not  4.Re8?  Ra6+! } 4... Ra6+ 5. Rc6 Rxa7 6. Rc7+ Rxc7 7.
Kxc7 { Now White has the distant opposition! } 7... Kh7 8. Kd7 Kg6 9. Ke6 Kg7
10. Ke7 Kg6 11. Kf8 { Black resigned. } *

