[Result "*"]
[FEN "R7/8/P4pp1/7p/4k2P/r5P1/4KP2/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Plan 2   Sometimes the passed pawn can be exchanged for some of the enemy pawns, leading to a winning endgame with the pawns all on the same side.   The following endgame is very important: we shall find ourselves referring to it again and again.  Unzicker − Lundin, Amsterdam ol 1954 }
1. f3+ { 1.a7  Ra2+  ∆ 2...Kf3. } 1... Kf5 2. a7 Ra2+
{ 2...Ra6  changes nothing:  3.Kd3  Rd6+  4.Kc4  Rd7  5.Kc5  Re7  6.Kd6!  Rb7  7.Rb8!  Rxa7  8.Rb5#  and if @@StartFEN@@R7/P3r3/3K1pp1/5k1p/7P/5PP1/8/8 b - - 8 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Re6+  7.Kd7  Ra6  8.Ke7  +- }
3. Kd3 Ra1 4. Kd4
{ Observe the following tactical trick:  4.g4+  hxg4  5.fxg4+  Kxg4  6.h5!  But Black draws with  6...Rd1+  7.Kc2  Rd7=  . In addition, in this particular position it also fails because  4.g4+?  can be met with  4...Kf4! }
4... Ra5 5. Kc4 Ra3 6. Kc5
{ When Black's pawn stands on f7, his king can return to f6 or g7 with an absolutely drawn position. Here, however, White has a clear plan: the transfer of the king to h6 followed by an exchange of the a7-pawn for Black's kingside pawns. Black has nothing to oppose this plan.  Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 9-142 }
*

