[SetUp "1"]

{ Unzicker − Lundin, Amsterdam ol 1954  (continued) } 1... Ra1
{ In case of  6...Rxf3  7.Rf8  Ra3  8.a8=Q  Rxa8  9.Rxa8  Kg4  the simplest solution is  10.Ra3  g5  11.hxg5  fxg5  12.Kd4  h4  13.gxh4  gxh4  14.Ke3  Kg3  15.Ra8  +- }
2. Kd6 Ra3 { 7...Ra6+ } 3. Ke7
{ White follows his plan, missing an immediate winning opportunity:  8.Rc8  ∆ 9.Rc5#. }
3... Ra6
{ 8...Ra2  is slightly more clever; the point is  9.Kf7?!  Ra6!  10.Kg7  g5  11.hxg5  Kxg5  12.Kf7  Kf5  13.g4+?  hxg4  14.fxg4+  Kf4  with an important difference: the f6-pawn is protected by the rook. The squares  a6  and  f7  are corresponding.  The simplest way for White to circumvent the mined square is by playing @@StartFEN@@R7/P3K3/5pp1/5k1p/7P/5PP1/r7/8 w - - 5 4@@EndFEN@@  9.Kf8!  Ra6  10.Kf7!  ⨀  Ra3  11.Kg7  ,  and  11...g5  is absolutely hopeless here. }
4. Kf7 Ra3 5. Kg7 Ra1 6. Kh6 Ra6 7. Rb8 Rxa7 8. Rb5+ Ke6 9. Kxg6 Ra8 10. Kxh5
Rg8 11. g4 Rh8+ 12. Kg6 { Black resigned. } *

