[SetUp "1"]

{ Plan 3  The most important method of playing for the win with the pawn on the seventh rank is to try to win the rook for the passed pawn. For this to work, the enemy king must be decoyed into the path of a rook check @@StartBracket@@as, for instance, we tried to do in the Unzicker-Lundin endgame, in the4.g4+? variation@@EndBracket@@.  Most often, the stronger side will try to create a kingside passed pawn, which will knock the king out of his safe g7-square. An important point to remember is that this end can be achieved by advancing a bishop's pawn, but a knight's or rook's pawn is generally useless. }
1. a7
{ This renders the f4-pawn untouchable; now the king goes after the black pawn, which must fall, because of zugzwang. }
1... Kh7 2. Kd3 Kg7 3. Kc3 Kh7 4. Kb3 Ra1 5. Kb4 Kg7 6. Kc5 Ra6 7. Kd5 Ra1 8.
Ke5
{ It should be noted that the inexact  8.Ke6?!  Ra5  leaves White, not Black, in zugzwang. But he can easily give his opponent the move by playing  9.Kd6   9.Rd8??  Rxa7  10.Rd7+  leads to a drawn pawn endgame.  9...Kh7  And now, either  10.Ke7  Ra6  11.Kf7  ⨀ and if  10...Kg7  11.Ke6  +- Or @@StartFEN@@R7/P6k/3K4/r4p2/5P2/8/8/8 w - - 17 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Kc6  (threatening 11.Kb6)  10...Ra1  11.Kd5  Ra5+  12.Kd6!  Kg7  13.Ke6  ⨀ +- }
8... Ra5+ 9. Ke6 { Zugzwang. } 9... Kh7 10. Kf6 { White wins. } *

