[SetUp "1"]

{ A slightly more complicated example of the same theme.  R. Kholmov, 1983  Here again, two extra pawns are not sufficient for a win. Black can easily prevent creation of a passed f-pawn. }
1. Kf4
{ The threat is @@StartFEN@@R7/P5k1/6p1/7p/5K1P/5PP1/8/r7 w - - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.g4  Ra4+  3.Kg3  hxg4  4.f4!  , followed by h4-h5. And if  2...hxg4  3.Kxg4  ∆ h4-h5 +-   The immediate  1.g4  hxg4  2.fxg4  leads to an obvious draw. Black need only remember to harass his opponent with checks from the rear when the white king comes to the sixth rank, otherwise a winning pawn endgame can arise. }
1... Ra4+ 2. Ke3 Ra3+ 3. Kf2 Ra2+ 4. Kg1 Ra1+
{ The simplest, although  4...Ra3  5.g4  hxg4  6.f4!  Kh7!  also holds. } 5.
Kg2 Ra2+ 6. Kh3 Ra3 { 6...Ra4  7.f4  Ra3  is also good. } 7. f4 Ra2 8. g4 Ra3+
{ The king can only escape from the checks by approaching the rook, but this is too dangerous: Black takes on g4 and his g-pawn rushes to the promotion square. }
*

