{ Let us examine two considerably more complex and eventful examples.  M. Dvoretsky, 2003 }
1. a7
{ White's plan is clear: his king will go after the f5-pawn. If the Black h-pawn were at h5, White would win without the slightest difficulty − just as he does inDiagram 9-143.  However, with the pawn at h6 instead, Black has counter-chances involving the attempt to zip the king up in the stalemate haven at h5. With this configuration, this stalemate defense is well-known from pawn endgames; it does not appear to have been employed before in a rook endgame.   After  1.Kd4?  Rxh2  2.Ke5  Black saves himself by playing for staltemate:  2...Kg6!  3.a7   Or  3.Rg8+  Kh5  4.Rf8  Re2+!  5.Kxf5  Re8!=  And if  5.Kd6  Ra2=  3...Ra2  4.Rg8+  Kh5  5.a8=Q  Ra5+  or  5...Re2+=  − the rook has become a desperado. }
1... Ra4 2. Kd3 Kh7 3. Kc3
{ Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 9-147 } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 9 – Rook Endgames III"]
[Black "The Rook in Front of the Pawn, with the Pawn on the Seventh Rank 9-147"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "R7/P6k/7p/5p2/r4Pp1/2K3P1/7P/8 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ M. Dvoretsky, 2003  (continued) } 1... Kg7
{ The clever attempt  3...Kg6!?  suggested by Gansäuer, is refuted by means of  4.h3!!  gxh3   4...Kh5  5.hxg4+  Kxg4  6.Rg8+  Kh5  7.g4+!  5.Rg8+  Kh5  6.a8=Q  Rxa8  7.Rxa8  Kg4  8.Kd4  h2  9.Ra1  Kxg3  10.Ke5  +-  Note that White wins only because his king can get to e5 in time. If White's king had been cut off on the second rank in the starting position, then as soon as it gets to c2  (or even d2)  , Black plays ...Kg6!, and the move h2-h3 no longer works.  But what would happen if Black's king could reach h5? We shall see about this in the next annotation. }
2. Kb3 Ra6 3. Kc4
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed.  5.Kb4?!  analyzed in → Diagram 9-148@@EndSquare@@ } 3...
Ra5 4. Kb4 Ra1 5. Kc5 Ra6 6. Kd5 Ra1 7. Ke5 Ra5+ 8. Ke6 { Zugzwang. } 8... Kg6
{ On  10...Kh7  the simplest reply is  11.Kf6  ⨀.  Also possible is  11.Rd8  Rxa7  12.Kxf5  obtaining a won ending with all the pawns on the same side − though not, of course,  12.Rd7+?  Rxd7  13.Kxd7  Kg6  14.Ke6  Kh5!= }
9. h3 Ra6+ 10. Ke7 gxh3 11. Rg8+ Kh5 12. a8=Q Rxa8 13. Rxa8 Kg4 14. Kf6
{ White wins. } *

