[Black "The Rook in Front of the Pawn, with the Pawn on the Seventh Rank 9-148"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "R7/P5k1/r6p/5p2/5Pp1/1K4P1/7P/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ M. Dvoretsky, 2003  (continued) } 1. Kb4 { Is not precise. } 1... Kg6
{ 6.h3?  no longer works since the white king is too far away from the f5-pawn. Interesting lines arise after: }
2. Kc5 { @@StartSquare@@Ed.  6.Kb5  would still be winning.@@EndSquare@@ } 2...
Kh5 3. Kd5 Ra2 4. Ke5
{ Diagram 9-148   The obvious  8...Ra5+?  9.Ke6  Ra6+   9...Kg6  10.h3!!  10.Kxf5  Rxa7  would lose to  11.h3!!  Rf7+  (mate was threatened)  12.Ke6  Rb7  , and here  13.Ra5+  Kg6  14.hxg4  Rb3  is less convincing. But White has instead, @@StartFEN@@R7/1r6/4K2p/7k/5Pp1/6PP/8/8 w - - 3 9@@EndFEN@@  13.hxg4+  Kxg4  14.Rg8+  Kh5  15.g4+  Kh4  16.f5  +- }
4... Re2+ 5. Kxf5 Re7
{ Is much stronger. It is reciprocal zugzwang! If  10.Kf6?  Black can already sacrifice his rook:  10...Re8!=   But not  9...Re8?  @@StartSquare@@Ed. the rather amusing solution can be trained next → Diagram 9-148 EXTRA@@EndSquare@@ }
6. Rd8 { White must give up his a-pawn. } 6... Rxa7
{ But here I do not see a clear way to win. For example: } 7. Ke6
{ Or  11.Rd5  Ra6= } 7... Kg6 8. f5+ Kg5 9. Rg8+ Kh5 { Draw. } *

