{ Zurakhov − Vaisman, USSR 1966 } 1. a7
{ Leaving the pawn on a6 made more sense. White could then have played h2-h4-h5 and Ra7, after which his king goes to the queenside at the cost of the g-pawn @@StartBracket@@or the f3-pawn if he could not avoid g2-g4@@EndBracket@@. The win would be rather easy because the black king would be forever locked on h7.  With his actual move, White plans h2-h4 and g2-g4-g5. After a forced double capture on g5, he wants to take the g5 and e5 pawns with his king and to play f5-f6 thereafter. }
1... Ra2
{ If  1...Ra3!?  (∆ 2...e4!=)  , then both  2.Kg4  and  2.Kf2  are good. Black only postpones an advance of the white kingside pawns for a while but cannot prevent it. }
2. h4 Ra3
{ 2...h5?  loses immediately.  After  3.Kh3  Black has no defense against g2-g4-g5-g6+. }
3. Kh2
{ This is correct. White's task is simpler when the king hides behind the pawns.   3.Kg4  Ra4+  4.Kh5  is also playable, but then White has to show more attention and accuracy.  Black would respond with  4...Ra5!?  and on the indecisive  5.g3?  would save the game by means of  5...e4!  6.fxe4  g6+  7.Kg4  gxf5+   Rather than  7...h5+?  8.Kf4  gxf5  9.Rf8 !  Rxa7  10.Kxf5  Rg7  11.Rxf6  Rxg3  12.e5  +-  8.exf5  Kg7  9.Kf4  h5=   After  5.g4!  , however, both  5...g6+?  6.fxg6+  Kg7  7.g5  hxg5  8.hxg5  fxg5   8...e4  9.Re8!  9.Kg4!  ⨀ +-  and @@StartFEN@@R7/P5pk/5p1p/r3pP1K/6PP/5P2/8/8 b - - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...e4?  6.g5   6.fxe4??  g6#  6...hxg5  7.hxg5  g6+  8.fxg6+  Kg7  9.Re8!  +-  fail.  Or  9.f4!?  f5  10.Re8  Rxa7  11.Re5  +-   Black has to play  5...Ra1  6.g5  hxg5  7.hxg5  fxg5  transposing to the game continuation. }
3... Ra2 4. Kh3 Ra3 5. g3 { Zugzwang. } 5... Ra2 6. g4 Ra3 7. Kg2 Ra2+ 8. Kg3
Ra4 9. g5 hxg5 10. hxg5 fxg5 11. Kh3 Rh4+ 12. Kg2 Ra4 13. Kg3 { Zugzwang. }
13... Ra1 14. Kg4 Rg1+ 15. Kh5 Ra1 16. Kxg5 Ra6 17. Kg4 Ra3 18. Kh4
{ Zugzwang. } 18... Ra4+ 19. Kh3 Ra2 20. Kg3 { Zugzwang. } 20... Ra5 21. Kf2
Ra3 22. Ke2 Ra5 23. Kd3 Ra4 24. Kc3 Ra1 25. Kb4 Ra2 26. Kc5 Ra1 27. Kd6 Ra5 28.
Ke6 Ra1 29. Kxe5 Ra6 30. f4 Ra5+ 31. Ke6
{ Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 9-150 } *

