{ Zurakhov − Vaisman, USSR 1966  (continued) } 1... Ra1
{ 31...Ra6+?  loses to  32.Ke7!  ⨀  Ra4  33.f6!  gxf6  34.Kf7!  ⨀  Ra6   34...f5  35.Ke6  Ra5  36.Kf6  ⨀ +-  35.f5  ⨀ The same zugzwang position  (with Black on move)  arises after @@StartFEN@@R7/P5pk/4K3/r4P2/5P2/8/8/8 b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  31...Ra4?  32.Kf7!  Ra6  33.Ke7  .   Now  32.f6  does not bring an easy win in view of  32...Ra6+  33.Ke7   33.Kf7  Rxf6+=  33...gxf6  34.f5  Kg7  and if  34.Kf7  Ra4!  35.f5  Ra6  . }
2. Ke7 Ra6
{ Only this prevents the menacing advance f5-f6.   32...Ra4?  33.f6  gxf6  34.Kf7  ⨀  is an error. We may come to the conclusion that the squares f7/a4 and e7/a6 are corresponding; this is a case of reciprocal zugzwang. And if Black defends himself correctly, he does not fall into the zugzwang. }
3. Kf7 Ra4
{ In case of  33...Rf6+?  White could have passed the move to the adversary by means of triangulation:  34.Ke8!  Ra6  35.Ke7  ⨀ +- }
4. Kf8 { 34.f6  gxf6  35.f5  Ra6  ⨀ } 4... Ra5 { 34...Ra6?  35.Ke7  ⨀ +- } 5.
f6 { He has nothing else. } 5... gxf6 6. f5 Ra1
{ 36...Ra6?  37.Kf7!  ⨀ +-   Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 9-151 }
*

