{ Zurakhov − Vaisman, USSR 1966  (continued) } 37. Kf7
{ It is important to drive the rook to a6. Dolmatov suggested this correct procedure.   Instead, the game continued with the natural move  37.Re8?  (White intends a transition to a winning pawn endgame)  which is wrong. Black has a defense based upon stalemate!  37...Rxa7  38.Re7+  Kh8!  39.Kf7  White cannot take the rook because of stalemate. Hence he goes for the f6-pawn.  Now  39...Ra1  is also good, or  39...Ra6  40.Kg6  Ra8  41.Kxf6  Kg8??  A serious mistake when the goal was within reach.  42.Kg6  Black resigned.   The draw could be achieved by means of  41...Ra1  or  41...Ra6+  42.Re6   42.Kf7  Kh7  43.f6  Ra8  or  43...Ra1  , but not  43...Rb6??  42...Ra1!  43.Kg6  Rg1+  44.Kf7  Rg7+  or  44...Kh7  45.f6  Rg7+!  46.fxg7  stalemate.  And after  46.Ke8  Rg8+  the rook returns to the long side.   By the way, after the immediate  37.Ke7 ?  Kg7  there is no longer a win. }
37... Ra6 38. Ke7 Kg7 { White could of course have had this position earlier. }
39. Kd8 { 39.Ke8?!  Kg8! } 39... Ra1
{ Both  39...Kg8  40.Kc7+  Kg7  41.Kb7  and @@StartFEN@@R2K4/P5k1/r4p2/5P2/8/8/8/8 b - - 5 39@@EndFEN@@  39...Kh6  40.Kc7  Kg5  41.Rg8+  Kxf5  42.a8=Q  Rxa8  43.Rxa8  are hopeless. }
40. Rc8 Rxa7 41. Rc7+ Rxc7 42. Kxc7 Kh6 43. Kd7 Kh5 44. Ke7 Kg5 45. Ke6
{ White wins. } *

