{ Tragicomedies: Y. Averbakh    This example is taken from Averbakh's endgame handbook. It is amusing not only in itself, but also because of several grave errors committed by this famous connoisseur of endgame theory. Averbakh believes the position is drawn on account of  1...Ra2  2.Kxf5  Rxf2+  3.Kxg4  Ra2=  Black applied this defensive method in a similar situation inRovner-Shchipunov @@StartBracket@@Diagram 9-144@@EndBracket@@.  But there, first of all, White's king was less active and he was unable to force the exchange of rooks. Second, White's pawn was at  h2  , which means the pawn endgame would still have been a draw. But here, with the pawn at  h4  , the pawn endgame is won! @@StartFEN@@R7/P5k1/4K2p/5p2/6pP/6P1/r4P2/8 w - - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Re8!  (instead of 2.Kxf5)  2...Rxa7   2...Ra6+  3.Kxf5  Rxa7  4.Kxg4  +-  3.Re7+  Rxe7+  4.Kxe7  Kg6  5.Ke6  Kh5!  (Black's last hope is a chance for a stalemate)  6.Kf6!  ⨀  f4  7.gxf4  Kxh4  8.Kg6  +- or  8.f5  +-.  Another try is: }
1... h5
{ Levenfish and Smyslov analyze this in their book on rook-and-pawn endings. They convincingly prove that the outcome depends on whose turn in is to move.   A. If White is on move, he wins by  2.Re8!  Rxa7  3.Re7+  and if  2...Ra6+!  3.Kxf5  Rxa7  4.Re5!   Averbakh only examines  4.Kg5?  Ra5+  5.Kf4  Ra2=  4...Kh6  (otherwise 5.Kg5)  5.Re6+  Kg7  6.Rg6+  Kh7  7.Rf6!  (∆ 8.Kg5)  7...Rg7  8.Rf8  ⨀ and if  7...Ra5+  8.Kf4  Kg7  9.Rf5  , while after @@StartFEN@@8/7k/5R2/r6p/5KpP/6P1/5P2/8 b - - 9 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Ra2  9.Kg5  Ra5+  10.Rf5  +-  B. @@StartSquare@@Ed. Black, if on move, achieves a draw → Diagram 9-155 EXTRA@@EndSquare@@  Averbakh's evaluations are the opposite: he suggests passing the move to the adversary. Therefore almost all his analysis is erroneous! }
2. Kd6 { ! Averbakh } 2... Kh7 { 2...Ra6+! } 3. Ke7
{ 3.Kc6!  Ra2  4.Rd8!  Rxa7  5.Rd7+  Rxd7  6.Kxd7  +- And  3.Ke6!  +-  Kg7  4.Re8!  Or @@StartFEN@@R7/P6k/4K3/r4p1p/6pP/6P1/5P2/8 b - - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Ra6+  4.Ke5!  Kg7  5.Kf4!  are winning. }
3... Kg7 4. Ke6 Ra2 { 4...Ra6+! } 5. Kxf5 { 5.Re8!  +- } 5... Ra5+
{ 5...Rxf2+?  6.Kg5  Ra2  7.Kxh5  Ra4  8.Re8  Rxa7  9.Kxg4  +- } 6. Kf4 Kh7
{ 6...Ra4+  is a draw. } 7. Rf8 Rxa7 8. Kg5 Ra5+ 9. Rf5 { White wins. } *

