{ 9/22. Kholmov-Timoshchenko, USSR chsf, Pavlodar 1982  As Kholmov discovered after the game, he could have obtained a draw. }
1. Kh2
{ ∆ 2.g3 @@StartBracket@@seeDiagram 9-145@@EndBracket@@.   However, he actually played  1.Ra4+?  Kc3!  (2...Kb3 was threatened)  2.Ra8  and after  2...f5!  his position became lost. Black's winning plan is simple: the pawn comes to f4, the king attacks the h4-pawn and, when this pawn is eliminated, Black gets a passed f-pawn.    3.Kh2  f4  and if @@StartFEN@@R7/8/6p1/5p1p/7P/2k3K1/p5P1/r7 w - - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Ra7  f4+  4.Kh2  Kd4  5.Ra4+  Ke5  6.Ra3  Kf5  7.Ra6  Kg4  8.Rxg6+  Kxh4  9.Ra6  Kg5  10.Ra8  h4  11.Rg8+  Kf6  12.Ra8  h3!  13.gxh3  f3  14.Ra3  Ke5  White resigned. }
