{ The Rook in Front of the Pawn, with the Pawn on the Sixth Rank    If a pawn advance to a7 makes no sense, White leaves the pawn on a6 and brings his king to the queenside where it has a refuge against vertical checks. But it is a long way to go, leaving the black rook enough time to capture one or two pawns, before it must be sacrificed for the a-pawn. This leads to a sharp “Rook vs. Pawns” endgame, the outcome of which will depend on whether White’s king can get back to the kingside in time.   @@StartSquare@@Ed. note: the information presented here is considered essential; the Informational continues in the next variation but does not have to be committed to memory.@@EndSquare@@ }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 9 – Rook Endgames IV"]
[Black "The Rook In Front Of The Pawn, With The Pawn On The Sixth Rank EXTRA"]
[Result "*"]

{ The Rook in Front of the Pawn, with the Pawn on the Sixth Rank   (continued)   For many years, it was believed that with correct defense, the draw was an easy matter, something Black could achieve with a couple of tempi to spare. This point of view was espoused in, among other places, the first edition of my Endgame Manual.  In the latter half of 2003, the theory of this portion of the endgame underwent some revolutionary changes. Black’s position, it turned out, was far more dangerous than it had seemed.  Johannes Steckner, a German player originally from Hamburg and now living in Switzerland, while checking the analysis of one of the basic positions which had been considered drawn, found a tremendous improvement for White, leading to a win. And his discovery led, in turn, to new researches that were conducted by Steckner, grandmasters Karsten Müller and Rustem Dautov, along with other endgame connoisseurs. The results of that research were reflected in the Russian edition of the Endgame Manual, as well as the second and third releases of the American edition and the second, third, and fourth releases of the German edition.  The development of this theory has not remained static. In late 2011, an Armenian chess aficionado, Vardan Pogosyan, found a new method of defense and showed that the position under consideration was nevertheless drawn. Pogosyan also made substantial refinements in the analysis of other endings in this section, and his work was published in the fourth American edition of the Endgame Manual.  More ideas have been found since. This fifth edition of the Endgame Manual brings a new defensive method found by grandmaster Jacob Aagaard, who published it in a Quality Chess blogpost in 2014, and a new drawing method in Pogosyan’s main line, found even more recently by grandmaster Erwin L’Ami.  Here I shall present only the most important and interesting variations, omitting many of the analytical details. For those who seek more detailed information, I would recommend visiting @@LinkStart@@www.chesscafe.com@@LinkEnd@@ and looking for my articles published in October/November 2003, as well as articles by Karsten Müller, the last of which, dedicated to Pogosyan’s discoveries, was published in March 2012.  Nevertheless, even in edited form, the material I offer you for your consideration is so large and complex, that it clearly exceeds the boundaries I tried to maintain when I wrote this Endgame Manual. The excuse I offer is its newness and enormous practical significance to the theory of this sort of endgame. Also, computers have recently begun to correctly analyze many of these variations, making the truth more accessible to today’s grandmasters who know where to look. We don’t want our readers to be left behind.  Even so, nothing could be further from my mind than to label the analysis presented below as the “last word of theory,” for long, complicated variations do not always turn out to be error-free. But in any case, they go a long way to correct and develop the pre-existing conclusions, and may in turn serve as a starting point for additional theoretical research. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 9 – Rook Endgames IV"]
[Black "The Rook In Front Of The Pawn, With The Pawn On The Sixth Rank 9-158"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/R4p2/P4kp1/7p/7P/4K1P1/r4P2/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ V.Kantorovich 1989/J.Steckner 2003, et al  In 1989, Vadim Kantorovich, of Moscow, published an interesting article titled, The Outside Passed Pawn. The article opened with the diagrammed position. It showed how Black quickly captures two pawns on the kingside, and the conclusion was: Black draws with two tempi to spare. But in fact, this method does not work, and a much more refined plan is required.  We present this important position in several stages. First, let’s see how White wins if Black chooses the old, and now refuted, recipe of capturing the pawn on f2.  I. Johannes Steckner’s Amazing Discovery }
1. Kd4
{ The pawn must be sacrificed precisely with the rook on  a7!  1.Ra8?!  Kf5  would be weaker. Please note that  Black’s pieces are optimally placed: the rook holds the f-pawn in the crosshairs, while the king occupies the most active available square.   Black would have an easy draw after  2.Kd4  Rxf2  3.Rf8  Ra2  4.Rxf7+  Kg4=  @@StartBracket@@Kantorovich@@EndBracket@@, or  2.f3  Ra3+  3.Kd4  Rxf3  4.Rf8  Ra3  5.Rxf7+  Kg4  6.Rf6  Kxg3  7.Rxg6+  Kxh4  8.Kc5  Kh3  9.Kb6  h4=  @@StartBracket@@Fine@@EndBracket@@.  On  2.Ra7!?  , the king should not pull back with  2...Ke6  or  2...Kf6  , but Black can immediately begin counterplay with  2...f6!?   2...Kg4  3.Rxf7  Rxa6  does not lose either.  After  3.Kf3  g5!  4.hxg5  fxg5  5.Ra8  g4+  6.Ke3  Kg6  , the king gets back to  g7  , so White plays  3.Ra8  instead, threatening to obtain a winning position with the pawn on the seventh, known to us from theUnzicker-Lundin game @@StartBracket@@Diagram 9-141@@EndBracket@@, by  3...--  4.f3  Ra3+  5.Ke2  Ra2+  6.Kd1  Ra3  7.a7  .  But Black draws by playing @@StartFEN@@R7/8/P4pp1/5k1p/7P/4K1P1/r4P2/8 b - - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Kg4  4.a7  f5!?   4...Ra3+  5.Ke4  f5+  6.Ke5  Kf3=  is also good.  5.Rg8  f4+!  6.gxf4  Ra3+  7.Ke4  Ra4+  8.Ke5  Ra5+  9.Ke6  Ra6+  10.Kf7  Rxa7+  11.Kxg6  Ra6+  12.Kf7+  Kxf4=  @@StartBracket@@analysis by Dvoretsky@@EndBracket@@. }
1... Rxf2 { In the nextsubsection, we will show the correct defense. } 2. Rc7
{ The rook needs to go precisely here, to the c-file. The king is aiming for the b-file, where it can help the rook engineer an interference on the a-file.   2.Rb7?  would only draw. }
2... Ra2 3. a7 Kf5
{ Kantorovich’s analysis continued  4.Rxf7+  Kg4  5.Kc5  Kxg3  6.Kb5  Rb2+  7.Kc6  Ra2  8.Kb7  Kxh4  9.Rf6  Rxa7+=  and the draw is obvious. It was Steckner who offered the powerful improvement: }
4. Kc4
{ Ed. note: his idea becomes clear in the next variation → Diagram 9-159. } *

