{ V.Kantorovich 1989/J.Steckner 2003, et al  (continued)   Steckner's idea becomes clear in the variation: }
4... Kg4 5. Kb3 Ra6 6. Rc4+ Kxg3 7. Ra4
{ Now White forces the sacrifice of Black’s rook without wasting time on the king’s long march to a7, and wins move-on-move @@StartBracket@@“Chess is the tragedy of a single tempo!”@@EndBracket@@. }
7... Rxa7 8. Rxa7 Kxh4 9. Kc3
{ There is no time to take the pawn:  9.Rxf7?  Kg3  . } 9... Kg3
{ 9...f5  10.Kd3  g5  does not help: the rook can deal with all three pawns. }
10. Kd2 h4 11. Ke2 Kg2 { 11...h3  12.Kf1  +- } 12. Rxf7 h3 13. Rf2+ Kg3 14. Rf6
{ Ed. note: a different defense for Black on move 4 is presented next → Diagram 1-160. }
