{ V.Kantorovich 1989/J.Steckner 2003, et al  (continued)   Let’s try a different defense, such as the text move, getting the rook away from the tempo-gaining Kb3. }
4... Ra1 5. Kb5
{ After White's move however, the only way to forestall the threat of closing off the a-file is by a series of checks which drive the white king forward: }
5... Rb1+ 6. Kc6 Ra1 7. Kb7 Rb1+ 8. Kc8 Ra1 9. Rxf7+ Kg4 { Diagram 1-160 } 10.
Rg7
{ 10.Kb8?  loses a critical tempo:  10...Kxg3  11.Rf6  Kxh4  12.Rxg6  Kh3  13.Kb7  Rxa7+  14.Kxa7  h4  . }
10... Kxg3 11. Rxg6+ Kxh4 12. Kb7
{ With the deadly threat of Ra6, which forces Black to capture the pawn when he will be one move too late. }
12... Rxa7+ 13. Kxa7 Kh3 14. Kb6 h4 15. Kc5 Kh2 16. Kd4 h3 17. Ke3 Kh1 18. Kf3
{ Ed. note: the third attempt to save the game for Black on move 4 is presented next → Diagram 9-161. }
