{ V.Kantorovich 1989/J.Steckner 2003, et al  (continued)   The only thing left to try is the text move. }
4... f6
{ Here  5.Kb4?  does not work because after  5...Kg4  6.Kb3  Ra6  7.Rc4+  Kxg3  8.Ra4  Rxa7  9.Rxa7  , Black’s pawn on  f6  enables  9...g5  @@StartBracket@@which he did not have in the 4...Kg4 line@@EndBracket@@, leading to a draw. Now comes a series of forced moves: }
5. Kb5 Rb2+ 6. Kc6 Ra2 7. Kb7 Rb2+ 8. Kc8 Ra2
{ But here White also wins with: } 9. Rg7 { Diagram 9-161 } 9... g5 10. Kb8 Kg4
11. a8=Q
{ But not  11.hxg5?  fxg5  12.a8=Q  Rxa8+  13.Kxa8  h4  14.gxh4  Kxh4  15.Kb7  g4  16.Kc6  Kg3!  17.Kd5  Kf3= }
11... Rxa8+ 12. Kxa8 Kxg3 13. hxg5 fxg5 14. Rxg5+ Kh4 15. Rg8 Kh3 16. Kb7
{ And the king gets back to f3 in time.  At the start of this section, I presented a formula in the most general terms for how play might develop in this kind of ending. Now we can more precisely restate White’s most dangerous plan.   The pawn advances to a6; the rook stands on a7, and at the first opportunity will move aside to c7, clearing the path of the pawn. White’s king selects a path to advance which will allow him to execute the interference idea as quickly as possible – that is, moving the rook with tempo to the a-file.   Ed. note: the correct defense for Black after 1.Kd4! is given next → Diagram 9-162. }
*

