{ V.Kantorovich 1989/J.Steckner 2003, et al  (continued)   II. The Pogosyan/Aagaard Defense  Let’s return to Diagram 9-158. As Pogosyan found, Black can only save himself if, in reply to 1.Kd4!, he refrains from the immediate capture of the f2-pawn. }
1. Kd4 g5 { Diagram 9-162 } 2. Kd5
{ This move was considered particularly dangerous until grandmaster Jacob Aagaard found a very solid defense against it in 2014.   After  2.Kc5  , the Aagaard method cannot be applied, but other methods work, as we show in the following subsections. For now, let’s examine two other tries for White:  2.hxg5+  Kxg5  is not dangerous. For example,  3.Kc5   There is also nothing in  3.f3  h4!  4.f4+  Kg4  5.gxh4  Kxh4  6.Ke5  Kg4=  3...Kg4  4.Kb5  Rxf2  5.Ra8  Rb2+   Only not  5...Kxg3?  6.Rg8+  Kf3  7.a7  Ra2  8.a8=Q+  Rxa8  9.Rxa8  h4  10.Rh8  Kg3  11.Kc4  +-  6.Kc4  Ra2  7.Rg8+  Kf3  8.Kb5  Rb2+  9.Kc6  Ra2  10.Kb7  Rb2+  11.Ka8  f5  12.Rg5  f4  13.gxf4  h4  14.f5  Kf4  15.Rh5  Kg4  16.Rh8  Kxf5  17.Rxh4  Ke6  , and a well-known theoretical position has been reached: if the white rook tries to get to  b8  to free the king from its imprisonment, the black king will have time to get on  c7  .   On  2.f3  , there follows  2...gxh4  3.gxh4  Ke6  4.Kc5  Ke5  5.Kb6   Black’s task is easier after  5.Ra8  Kf4  .  5...Rb2+!  6.Kc7  Ra2!   6...Rc2+?  loses to  7.Kd8!  f5  8.Rh7  Ra2  9.Rh6!  Kf4  10.Kc7  Kxf3  11.Kb7  Kg3  12.a7  Rxa7+  13.Kxa7  Kxh4  14.Kb6  +-  7.Kb8  f6  8.Re7+  Kd6!  9.Rf7  Ke6  10.Ra7  Kf5  or  10...Ke5=  @@StartBracket@@analysis by Wilburt Micawber@@EndBracket@@. }
2... Kg6
{ This is Aagaard’s discovery. By threatening ...f7-f6 and ...Kf5, and not yet trading on h4, Black renders White’s plans harmless.   In the next subsections, we examine  2...gxh4?  which loses, and  2...g4  , which is another way to draw. }
3. Kc5 f6 4. Ra8 Kf5
{ Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 9-162a } *

