{ V.Kantorovich 1989/J.Steckner 2003, et al  (continued)   Now White has a choice. If he plays: }
5. Kb6 { 5.hxg5  fxg5  6.a7  Kg4=  is not dangerous. } 5... Rxf2
{ It is important for Black to keep on resisting the pawn exchange on h4, because the object of counterattack is the g3-pawn which is still left on the board. }
6. Rb8
{ 6.hxg5  Rb2+  7.Kc5  fxg5  8.a7  Ra2  9.Rf8+  Kg4  10.a8=Q  Rxa8  11.Rxa8  Kxg3  12.Kd4  h4= }
6... Rb2+ 7. Ka7 Rg2 8. Rb5+ Kg4 9. Kb6 Re2
{ However, after @@StartFEN@@R7/8/P4p2/2K2kpp/7P/6P1/r4P2/8 w - - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.f3  , the pawn exchange becomes possible @@StartBracket@@just like after2.f3@@EndBracket@@, as the f-pawn is closer to the king and the monarch has time to eliminate it:  5...gxh4!  6.gxh4  Kf4  7.Kb6  Kxf3=  or  7...Rb2+  8.Ka7  Kxf3= }
