{ V.Kantorovich 1989/J.Steckner 2003, et al  (continued)   III. The Pogosyan-L’Ami Defense }
1. Kd4 g5 2. Kd5
{ After the moves which are already familiar to us, Pogosyan had discovered the drawing move: }
2... g4
{ Diagram 9-168   In fact, this was considered to be the only saving move until Aagaard found  2...Kg6  . The  2...g4  method is also important, and it works against both @@StartFEN@@8/R4p2/P4k2/6pp/3K3P/6P1/r4P2/8 w - - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Kd5  and  2.Kc5  .  White can direct his king to the passed pawn, to the enemy rook, or even to the eighth rank on the kingside. But none of these plans leads to a win if Black defends precisely. He checks and captures the f2-pawn at the appropriate moment, or, in the main line, can also save himself with aVancura-like defense, found by GM Erwin L’Ami in 2019.  Diagrams 9-163, 9-164, 9-165, 9-166 and 9-167 have been intentionally omitted. }
3. Kd6
{ If  3.Ra8  ,  3...Ke7  is also good, or  3...Kf5  4.Kc6  Ke4!  draws. } 3...
Rd2+ 4. Kc6 Rc2+ 5. Kb5
{ Going to the eighth rank is interesting but does not win:  5.Kd7  Ra2!   5...Rxf2?  6.Rb7  Ra2  7.a7  +-  6.Ke8  Kg6!  7.Kf8  Rxf2  is also good enough to draw, or  7...Ra3  8.Ra8  Ra2!  9.a7  Kh7!  10.Kxf7  Rxf2+  11.Ke6  Re2+!  12.Kf5  Ra2  13.Kg5  Ra5+  14.Kf6  Ra6+= }
5... Rb2+ 6. Kc4 { Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 9-168a }
