{ V.Kantorovich 1989/J.Steckner 2003, et al  (continued)     Now Black cannot take the pawn  6...Rxf2?  , which would release the white rook and  7.Rb7  Ra2  8.a7  would win. }
6... Rb6
{ An instructive defense, based on theVancura idea @@StartBracket@@See 9-43@@EndBracket@@. Black pins down the white rook by attacking the pawn from the side. He has enough distance to check away the white king.   Let’s also examine the previously found, but more complicated, drawing method:  6...Ra2  7.Ra8  Ke7!!  @@StartBracket@@this is John Hull’s improved version of the Pogosyan solution 7...Ke6, which is inaccurate as we shall see.@@EndBracket@@  8.Kb5  Rb2+  9.Kc6  Rc2+  10.Kb7  Rb2+  11.Ka7  Rxf2  12.Rb8   12.Rh8  Rf3  13.Rxh5  Rxg3  is drawn, but here we see why the king had to go to e7: if the king were on  e6  here, White would win with @@StartFEN@@7R/K4p2/P3k3/7p/6pP/5rP1/8/8 w - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Kb7!  Rb3+  14.Kc6  Ra3  15.Re8+!  , asking the black king to step aside,  15...Kf5  and now  16.Kb5  +-  Now  12...Kd6  also draws, or  12...Kd7!  the king neutralizes the dangerous passed pawn;  13.Rb5  Kc6  14.Rxh5  Rf3!  and White cannot win. }
7. Kc5 Re6 { And Black only needs to make sure not to let the white rook out. }
8. Ra8 Kg7 9. Kb5 Re5+ 10. Kb6 Re6+ 11. Kc5 Re5+ 12. Kd6 Re6+ 13. Kd7 Kh7
{ 13...Rb6?  14.Kc7  Re6  15.a7  Re7+  16.Kb6  Re6+  17.Kb5  Re5+  18.Kb4  Re4+  19.Kb3  +- }
14. Kc7 Re7+ 15. Kb6 Re6+ 16. Kb5 Re5+ 17. Kc4 Re6
{ Diagram 9-168b With a draw just like in the Vancura ending. } *

