{ V.Kantorovich 1989/J.Steckner 2003, et al  (continued)   IV. The lines 2.Kc5 gxh4= and 2.Kd5 gxh4?+-  In this subsection we look at the pawn exchange ...gxh4. }
1. Kd4 g5
{ After the text moves, we have examined two drawing methods after  2.Kd5  . Here we illustrate why  2...gxh4?  loses against that. This will be useful to you if you are the attacking side.   We also show that after  2.Kc5!?  ,  2...gxh4  is another drawing method, in addition to Pogosyan’s  2...g4  . You can keep this in mind if you are the defending side. First, let's look at the move: }
2. Kd5 { and show why taking on h4 loses for Black. } 2... gxh4 3. gxh4
{ As  3...Kf5  4.Rxf7+  Kg4  5.a7  Kxh4  6.Rg7  is completely hopeless, and @@StartFEN@@8/R4p2/P4k2/3K3p/7P/8/r4P2/8 b - - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Rxf2  4.Rc7  Ra2  5.a7  Kf5  6.Kc4!  leads to the Steckner idea again, Black has two main defensive tries.  a. Let’s try to clear the way for the f-pawn with: }
3... Kg6
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed. b. the alternative  3...Rd2+  →Diagram 9-168g@@EndSquare@@ }
4. Kc6 Rc2+
{ 4...f6  5.Ra8  Kf5  6.Kb7  Rb2+  7.Ka7  Kg4  8.Rb8  Rxf2  9.Rb4+  Kg3  10.Kb6  Ra2  leads to almost the same position, with the same result after  11.Kb5  . }
5. Kb6 Rb2+ 6. Kc7 Rc2+ 7. Kb8 Ra2
{ Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 9-168d } *

