{ V.Kantorovich 1989/J.Steckner 2003, et al @@StartSquare@@Ed. continued from Diagram 9-168c@@EndSquare@@   b. Let’s leave the king on f6 and try: }
3... Rd2+ 4. Kc6 Rc2+ 5. Kb6 Rb2+ 6. Kc7 Rc2+ 7. Kb8 { Diagram 9-168g } 7...
Ra2
{ If now  7...Rc6  8.Kb7  Re6  , then  9.f4!  is very strong, taking the e5-square away from the rook and thereby neutralizing the threat of checks from the side. On  9...Kf5  or  9...Re1  , there follows  10.Ra8  , and Black’s counterplay comes too late. However,  7...Ra2  leads to the position inDiagram 9-168d, but with the king having moved from  g6  to  f6  . In several lines this difference is significant. For example, after }
8. Ra8 Rxf2 9. Ka7 Rh2 10. Rh8
{ White, as noted by Pogosyan, takes advantage of the h5-pawn’s vulnerability. }
10... Ke5
{ 10...Kg6  11.Kb7  Rb2+  12.Ka8  Rb4  13.a7  +- is too slow, and @@StartFEN@@7R/K4p2/P4k2/7p/7P/8/7r/8 b - - 3 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Rxh4  11.Kb6  is hopeless. }
11. Rxh5+ f5 12. Kb7 Rb2+ 13. Ka8 Ke4 { 13...Kf6  14.a7  f4  15.Rh8  +- } 14.
Rh8 f4 15. h5 f3 16. h6 f2 17. Rf8
{ 17.Re8+  followed by 18.Rf8 decides matters as well. } 17... Rd2 18. Kb7
{ 18.h7?  Rd8+ } 18... Rd7+ 19. Kc6 { White wins. } *

