{ V.Kantorovich 1989/J.Steckner 2003, et al  V. Position with Black to move.  Let us return once more to the starting position so that we may evaluate how Black should defend if it is his move. It turns out that in this case, Black can also only generate counterplay with the move ...g6- g5! Other plans lose.  Grandmaster Dautov demonstrated the safest line. Before playing ...g6-g5, it makes sense to limit the mobility of the white king. }
1... Ra4
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed. the immediate  1...g5!  is also possible →Diagram 9-174; for  1...Ke5?  →Diagram 9-176 and  1...Ke6?  →Diagram 9-176 EXTRA.@@EndSquare@@ }
2. Kd3
{ On  2.Ra8  , the simplest is  2...Kf5!  2.f4  Ke6!  3.Kd3  f6  4.Kc3  Kf5  5.Kb3  Ra1  6.Kb4  Kg4=  is also not dangerous. }
2... g5 { Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 9-173 } *

