{ V.Kantorovich 1989/J.Steckner 2003, et al  (analysis)     Instead of  1...Ra4  , the immediate  1...g5  is also possible. }
1... g5 2. Kd4
{ Black can thenmake use of one of ourtwo defensive methods from subsections 2 and 3,  2...Kg6  or  2...g4  . }
2... gxh4 { The exchange is also not bad. } 3. gxh4
{ Diagram 9-174 But now it is important to resist the temptation to win one of the pawns:   a.  3...Rxf2?  4.Rc7  Ra2  5.a7  Kf5  6.Kc5  Kg4  7.Kb5  , winning using the Steckner method.   b.  3...Ra4+?  4.Kc5  Rxh4  5.Rb7  Ra4  6.a7  Kg5   6...h4  7.Kb5  Ra1  8.Rb6+  Kg5  9.Ra6  and in case of @@StartFEN@@8/PR3p2/5k2/2K4p/r7/8/5P2/8 b - - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Ra1  7.Kb6  +-  7.Rb5!  +- It is best to follow the recommendation of Dautov and Anand. }
3... Ke6 4. Kc5 Ke5
{ Leading to thedrawing line we saw in the previous subsection, @@StartFEN@@8/R4p2/P4kp1/7p/7P/4K1P1/r4P2/8 w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Kd4!  g5!!  2.Kc5  gxh4  3.gxh4  Ke5! }
