{ V.Kantorovich 1989/J.Steckner 2003, et al  (analysis)   Finally, we want to show how White wins against the other defensive plans. }
1... Ke5 2. Kd3 Kd5
{ 2...Rxf2  3.Rc7  @@StartSquare@@but not to b7: then the king on  b5  will be in the way of the rook@@EndSquare@@  3...Ra2  4.a7  f6  5.Kc4!  is again the Steckner method. }
3. Kc3 Rxf2 4. Rc7 Ra2 5. a7 f6 6. Kb4 Kd6
{ Diagram 9-176  Diagram 9-175 has been intentionally omitted. } 7. Rg7
{ The strongest line. } 7... Kc6
{ After  7...Ke6  ,  8.Kb5  Kf5  9.Kb6  g5  10.Kb7  wins. } 8. Rf7
{ But not  8.Rxg6?  Rxa7  9.Rxf6+  Kd5  10.Rf5+  Ke4  11.Rxh5  Rg7= } 8... f5
9. Rg7 Kb6 10. Kc4
{ And White will win.  Ed. note: the last defensive try for Black → Diagram 9-176 EXTRA }
