{ V.Kantorovich 1989/J.Steckner 2003, et al  (analysis)   There is one more defensive try: }
1... Ke6 2. Kd4 f6
{ We already know the consequences of  2...Rxf2  and want to again remind the reader that the rook should go not to the b-file, but to the c-file with  3.Rc7!  Ra2  4.a7  +- }
3. Ra8
{ 3.Kc5?  Kf5  4.f3  g5!  5.Ra8  gxh4  6.gxh4  Kf4!=  , as the black king attacks the white pawn on  f3  . }
3... Kf5 { 3...Kf7  4.Kc5  is hopeless. } 4. f3 g5 5. hxg5
{ On anything else, White plays @@StartFEN@@R7/8/P4pp1/5k1p/3K3P/5PP1/r7/8 w - - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.a7  , transposing into the ending of the gameUnzicker-Lundin, where White wins by marching his king to  h6  .   So even with Black to move, there is only one saving idea, the one with ...g6-g5.  Our analysis of the Kantorovich/Steckner position acquaints us with the most important contemporary ideas for playing this endgame with the standard pawn structure f7-g6-h5 versus f2-g3-h4.  Diagram 9-177 has been intentionally omitted. }
