{ G.Levenfish, V.Smyslov 1957  Now we proceed to an endgame with a different structure.  Here Black is faced with quite unpleasant problems: even after winning the g3-pawn he cannot activate his king, and creating a passed pawn is difficult, too. In addition, each initial move harms his position in some way, so he has to choose the least of the evils.   An attempt to force the matters loses:  1...Ra2+?  2.Ke3  Ra3+  3.Kd4  Rxg3  4.Rc8  Ra3  5.Rc7+  Kf6  6.a7  Ke6  7.Kc5  Ra1  8.Kb6  Rb1+   8...Kd5  9.Rc5+  Ke4  10.Ra5  +-  9.Kc6  Ra1  10.Kb7  Kd5  11.a8=Q  Rxa8  12.Kxa8  Ke4  13.Rg7  Kxf4  14.Rxg6  Ke3  15.Rg5  Obviously, the king should be cut off along the third rank.   1...Kh7?!  is also dubious,  as after  2.Ra7+!  Kh6  3.Ke2  Rxg3  4.Rb7  Ra3  5.a7  the black king is poorly placed on h6.  But with correct defense, Black nevertheless manages to hold. }
1... Kf7 2. Ke2 { 2.a7?  Kg7= } 2... Kg7
{ He has to lose a tempo, because  2...Rxg3??  3.a7  Ra3  4.Rh8  is bad. } 3.
Kd2 Rxg3 4. Rb8 Ra3 5. Rb7+ Kf6 6. Rb6+
{ On  6.a7  the black king breaks loose:  6...Ke6  7.Kc2  Kd5  and if  8.Kb2  Ra6  9.Kb3  then  9...Kc5!  obstructing the path of the white king. }
6... Kg7 7. Kc2 { Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 9-179 } *

