{ Let us now look at a few examples from current practice, and make use of our knowledge of theory to determine why strong grandmasters should suffer misfortune in drawn positions. We shall also learn some new ideas, which will enrich our theoretical understanding. In order to do this, however, we shall have to dive again and again into analytical maze.  Tragicomedies: Svidler − Akopian, European Cup, Kallithea 2002  This is theKantorovich/Steckner position, with the white king slightly less well-placed. In some lines, obviously, Black will have an extra tempo, which enlarges the sphere of drawing possibilities at his disposal. }
1... Ke5
{ With the king at e3 this move would have lost; here, I believe it is not bad.  He might also have played in 'Dautov style':   1...Ra4!?  2.Ke3  g5  , for example,  3.hxg5+  Kxg5  4.Ra8  Kg4  5.a7  Ra3+  6.Ke4  Ra4+  7.Kd5  or  7.Ke5  Kf3=   The immediate  1...g5  would not have been any worse  (the only move that could have been dangerous in reply would have been 2.Kd4! even though this would not have been fatal, either - but White cannot play that here.) }
2. Ke3 Ra3+
{ In Informant 85, Svidler recommends  2...f6  3.Kd3  Rxf2  4.Rb7  Ra2  5.a7  Kf5  6.Kc4  Kg4  7.Kb3  Ra6  8.Rb4+  Kxg3  9.Ra4  Rxa7=  Our attentive readers may possibly recallthe analysis of the Kantorovich/Steckner position @@StartBracket@@with White to move@@EndBracket@@. In the line @@StartFEN@@8/P1R2p2/6p1/5k1p/3K3P/6P1/r7/8 w - - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Kc4!!  f6  5.Kb4?  Kg4  6.Kb3  , we reached precisely the same position, and concluded that it would be won with Black's pawn at  f7  , but with the pawn at  f6  , it was drawn.   Nevertheless,  2...f6?  is still a bad move in view of  3.Ra8!  Ra3+  4.Ke2  when Black will have a hard time avoiding transposition to the won position from theUnzicker-Lundin game @@StartBracket@@after f2-f3 and a6-a7@@EndBracket@@ without substantial losses. }
3. Kd2 { Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 9-181 } *

