{ Tragicomedies: Svidler − Akopian, European Cup, Kallithea 2002  (continued) }
3... Ra2+
{ Steckner noted that if White had played @@StartFEN@@8/R4p2/P5p1/4k2p/7P/r3K1P1/5P2/8 w - - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Ke2  , the aforementioned plan would not work:  3...f5?  4.Ra8!  Ke4  5.f3+  Kd5  6.a7  +- And  3...f6?  is also a mistake:  4.Ra8!   After  3...Ra2+?  4.Kd3  Rxf2  , White wins as in the main line of the analysis ofDiagram 9-158,  5.Re7+  Kf6  6.a7  Ra2  7.Rc7  Kf5  8.Kc4!   The draw is reached by  3...Ke6!  4.Kd2  f6  5.Kc2   here  5.Ra8  Kf5  , is useless: White does not have f2-f3, and if he cannot play that, the black king gets to g4.  5...Kf5  6.Kb2  Ra5  7.f3  g5  8.Kb3  gxh4  9.gxh4  Kf4  10.Kb4  Ra1  11.Kb5  Rb1+  etc. And in case of  7.Kb3  Kg4  . }
4. Kc3
{ White must play  4.Kd3!  to stop Black’s counterattack via  e4  .   Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 9-181a }
