{ Tragicomedies: Svidler − Akopian, European Cup, Kallithea 2002  (analysis) }
4... f6 5. Kb3 Ra1
{ Black cannot take the f2-pawn; instead he must counterattack with his king. }
6. Kb4 Kf5 { 6...Ke4?  7.Re7+  Kf3  8.Re3+  Kxf2  9.Ra3  +- } 7. Ra8 Kg4 8. Kb5
Rb1+ 9. Ka5 Ra1+ 10. Kb6 Rb1+ 11. Ka7 Rf1
{ It is important to attack from here and not from b2, because the rook is more active on the f-file. }
12. Rg8 g5 13. f4 Kxg3 14. hxg5 fxg5 15. fxg5
{ 15.Rxg5+  Kh4=  , thanks to the rook attacking the f4-pawn. } 15... h4 16. g6
h3 17. Rb8 { Diagram 9-181b  17.g7  Rf7+= } 17... Re1
{ The only move. The rook must be prepared to check on the seventh rank, and this is the only square that works.   Not  17...Rd1?  18.Rb1!  Rxb1  19.g7  +- and @@StartFEN@@1R6/K7/P5P1/8/8/6kp/8/5r2 b - - 1 17@@EndFEN@@  17...h2?  also loses quickly to  18.g7  Rf7+  19.Rb7  . }
18. Rb1 { But now on  18.g7  Re7+  19.Rb7  , Black has  19...Re8  . } 18... Kf2
19. Rxe1 Kxe1 20. g7 h2 21. g8=Q h1=Q
{ And the queen ending is drawn; analysis by Müller and Fishbein, 2019. } *

