{ Tragicomedies: Lerner − Dorfman, USSR ch  (1)  , Tashkent 1980 } 1... Ra4+
{ The rook was placed ideally  (targeting the white pawns)  , but the king could and should have been activated.   After  1...Kf6!  2.Ra6+  Kg7  3.Kd5  Rxf3  is harmless.  And if  2.a6  Ke6  3.Kd4  Kf5!  Black is saved.  For example,  4.Kc4  Rxf3  5.Rd8   5.Kb4  Rf1  6.Rc8  Rb1+  5...Ra3  6.Kb5  Kg4  7.Rd4+  Kxg3  8.Ra4  Rb3+  9.Kc6  Rb8  10.a7  Ra8  11.Kb7  Re8  or  11...Rxa7+  12.Kxa7  f6  13.Kb6  g5= }
2. Kd5 Ra3 3. a6 Rxf3
{ Now the black king is cut off along the sixth rank.   However,  3...Kf6  did not offer real saving chances either:  4.Kc6   Vladimir Vulfson recommended  4.Kc5!?  Having in mind, on  4...Kf5  to drive the rook from the third rank with the move  5.Kb4  and only after  5...Ra1  to play  6.Kb5  4...Rxf3  @@StartSquare@@Ed. 4...Kf5 is analyzed →Diagram 9-183@@EndSquare@@  5.Rd8!  (the most precise.)   Less precise is  5.Rb8  and while it does not let the win slip, it is important to note that after  5...Ra3  the only reply is  6.Kb6!  But not  6.Rb6?  Kf5  7.Kb7  Kg4  8.a7  Rxa7+  9.Kxa7  Kxg3  10.Rb4  f6  and  11.--  g5  .  5...Ra3  6.Kb5  (threatening 7.Rd4)  6...Ke5  7.Rd7  f6  8.a7  (Vulfson)  − it is not clear what can be done against the threat of  8...--  9.Rc7  followed by the interference maneuver  10...--  10.Rc5+  ,  11...--  11.Rc4+  or  11.Rc6+  and  12...--  12.Ra6  or 12.Ra4. }
4. Rb8 Ra3 5. Rb6 Rxg3 6. Kc6 Ra3 7. Kb7 g5
{ Or  7...f6  8.a7  Rxa7+  9.Kxa7  g5  10.Rb4!?  Kg6  11.Kb6  Kf5   11...gxh4  12.Rxh4  Kg5  13.Rh1  h4  14.Kc5  Kg4  15.Kd4  h3  16.Ke3  Kg3  17.Rg1+  − Anikaev  12.Kc5  g4  13.Kd4   13.Rb1  g3  14.Rf1+  Kg4  15.Rxf6  Kxh4  16.Kd4  Kh3  17.Ke3  +-  13...Kf4  14.Kd3+  +- }
8. hxg5 h4 9. a7 h3 10. a8=Q { 10.Ra6?  h2 } 10... Rxa8 11. Kxa8 h2 12. Rh6 f6
13. Rxh2 fxg5
{ Ed. note: analyzed in the next variation → Diagram 9-183 and continued in Diagram 9-184. }
