{ Akopian − Kir. Georgiev, Las Vegas wch, 1999 } 4... f6
{ Better late than never! Black arrives at the aforementioned plan after all, albeit under much worse conditions, having helped the white king to the queenside and released the pressure on the f2-pawn.   In the fourth edition of this book, we also examined two other alternatives,  4...Rf3  and  4...Ra2  , and concluded that they both lost, as did the text move. However, in light ofAagaard’s new defensive method in the Kantorovich/Steckner position, we have re-evaluated this ending. It turned out that two of these three moves draw.  We will analyze the three moves in order of worst to best. The variations are quite complicated, but they are worth going over, as they not only encapsulate the modern practical concepts in this type of ending, but show useful rook ending ideas in general.  Ed. note: the game continuation →Diagram 9-185i and analysis fromDiagram 9-185b up to and includingDiagram 9-185h. }
*

