{ Hollis − Flórián, ol cr 1972  Deep analysis of this example will help us understand the basic patterns of endings with a knight's pawn. According to Adrian Hollis' comments, his victory was legitimate... }
1. Kf1 Rb2 2. Ke1 Kf6 3. f3 Rb3 4. Kd2 Rxf3
{ Although this capture looks natural, as no counterplay on the kingside may be generated without it, nevertheless, as will become clear later, this is the decisive mistake.   Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 9-195 and the correct move for Black,  4...Ke6!  is given inDiagram 9-199. }
