{ Hollis − Flórián, ol cr 1972  (analysis) } 1... Rxg3
{ This principled continuation does not help.   The idea behind it is  6.Rxf7+?  Kxf7  7.b7  Rg2+  8.Kc3  Rg3+  9.Kc4  Rg4+  10.Kc5  Rf4!   10...Rxh4  11.b8=Q  Re4  also deserves attention.  11.b8=Q  Rf5+  12.Kd6  Kg7!  and White cannot breach the black fortress  (Averbakh)  .   Trying for an intermediary series of checks prior to the pawn capture −  5...Rf2+?  6.Kb3  Rf3+  − could have been justified in case of  7.Ka4  Rxg3  8.Rc7  Rg1  9.Rc4  or  9.Rc5  Rb1!  However it is refuted by @@StartFEN@@8/1R3p2/1P3kp1/7p/7P/1K3rP1/8/8 w - - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  7.Kc4!  Rxg3  8.Rc7  Rg1  9.Rc5!  +-  (Yusupov, Dvoretsky.) }
2. Rc7
{ Diagram 9-196 The text move suggested by Hollis and analyzed by Averbakh, is much stronger than the rook sacrifice 6.Rxf7+?.   For example,  6...Rg4  7.Kb3  , and if @@StartFEN@@8/2R2p2/1P3kp1/7p/7P/6r1/2K5/8 b - - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  6...Rg2+  7.Kb3  Rg1  8.Kb2  Rg2+  9.Rc2  Rg4  10.Rc3  Rxh4   10...Rg2+  11.Ka3  Rg1  12.b7  +- or  10...Rb4+  11.Rb3  +-  11.Ka3!  Re4  12.b7  Re8  13.Rc8  Re3+  14.Kb2  Re2+  15.Kc3  Re3+  16.Kd2  Rb3  17.b8=Q  Rxb8  18.Rxb8  Kg5  19.Ke3  Kg4  20.Kf2  +-  Ed. note: analyzed in the next variation → Diagram 9-197 }
*

