[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 9 – Rook Endgames IV"]
[Black "A Knight Pawn 9-198"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/1R3p2/1P3kp1/7p/7P/5rP1/3K4/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Hollis − Flórián, ol cr 1972  (analysis)     @@StartSquare@@Ed. continued from Diagram 9-195: instead of a.  5.Kc2?  White should play the text move, b.  5.Rc7!  @@EndSquare@@ }
1. Rc7 Rb3
{ 6. Rc3 was threatened, while  5...Rxg3  6.Kc2  leads by a transposition of moves to the variation @@StartFEN@@8/1R3p2/1P3kp1/7p/7P/5rP1/3K4/8 w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  5.Kc2?!  Rxg3  6.Rc7  examined inDiagram 9-196, shown to be winning for White.   On  5...Ke6  or  5...Ra3  , the move  6.Rc3  is no longer dangerous, but the simple  6.b7  Rb3  7.Kc2  followed by bringing the king up, is sufficient for White to win. }
2. b7 Kf5 { No better is  6...Ke6  7.Kc2  Rb6  8.Kd3  . } 3. Kc2 Rb6
{ After  7...Rb5  8.Kc3  f6  9.Kc4  , and if @@StartFEN@@ Kg4@@EndFEN@@  8...Kg4  9.Rc4+  Kxg3  10.Rb4  Rxb7  11.Rxb7  Kxh4  12.Rxf7  or  12.Kd3  , the rook and king can easily cope with the pawns. }
4. Rxf7+ { Weaker is  8.Kc3  f6!  9.Rc5+  Ke6= } 4... Kg4
{ Diagram 9-198   Kantorovich had analyzed to this position, believing that White wins by  9.Rd7  Kxg3  10.Rd3+  Kxh4  11.Rb3  . However, Black may decline the immediate capture of the pawn with  9...Kh3!  For example,  10.Kc3  Kxg3!  (now this is possible)  11.Rd3+  Kxh4  12.Rd4+  Kg3  13.Rb4  Rxb7  14.Rxb7  h4=  I therefore did not consider the move 5.Rc7 particularly dangerous for Black  (my mainline was 5.Kc2)  , and the verdict of endgame theory on the sufficiency of the capture of the f3-pawn to draw seemed correct. This viewpoint was reflected in previous editions of my Endgame Manual.  In 2008, master Igor Yanvarev published analysis strengthening White's play. The Dutch analyst Wilburt Micawber had independently come to the same conclusion. }
5. Rg7 { Incidentally, this move is also strong after  9.Rd7  Kh3  . } 5... Kh3
6. Kc3 { And here it turns out that Black is defenseless. } 6... Rb1
{ Not  10...Kxg3  because of the rook deflection  11.Rxg6+  , and if @@StartFEN@@8/1P4R1/1r4p1/7p/7P/2K3Pk/8/8 b - - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  10...Rb5  then  11.Kc4  Rb1  and here, also not bad is  12.Rd7  or  12.Kc5  Rc1+  13.Kd6  Rb1  14.Kc7  Rc1+  15.Kd8  Rb1  16.Kc8  Kxg3  17.Rxg6+  Kxh4  18.Kc7  Rxb7+  19.Kxb7  +- }
7. Rd7
{ Now the idea behind the zwischenzug 9.Rg7! becomes clear. The black rook is now situated not on  b6  , as in my line, but on  b1  , and  11...Kxg3  is no longer possible in view of the interference on b4 or b2 after  12.Rd3+! }
7... Rb6 8. Kc4 Kxg3
{ No better is  12...Rb1  13.Kc5  Kxg3  14.Rd3+  Kxh4  15.Rd4+  and 16.Rb4.  In case of @@StartFEN@@8/1P6/6p1/2K4p/7P/3R2k1/8/1r6 b - - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  14...Kg2  15.Kc6  Rc1+  16.Kd7  Rb1  17.Kc7  Rc1+  18.Kb8  Rb1  19.Ra3  or  19.Rc3  +-. }
9. Rd3+ Kxh4 10. Rb3 Rxb7 11. Rxb7 { White wins. } *

