{ Hollis − Flórián, ol cr 1972  (analysis)     @@StartSquare@@Ed. continued fromDiagram 9-195, where Black erred with  4...Rxf3?  @@EndSquare@@  We come to the most interesting point. The fact the b-pawn is nearer the kingside in comparison with a rook's pawn has its sunny side for Black. He can abandon the idea of a race and apply another, somewhat surprising, strategy: his king is able to prevent the invasion of the enemy king.  The remarkable defensive plan of creating a barrier against the opponent's king was suggested many years ago by Vadim Kantorovich. He did not subject his idea to analysis and was not even sure that it would be sufficient to draw. I examined the position, focusing on the piece placement proposed by Kantorovich: with the rook on b7, the king remains on e6, and in reply to the move Rb8, removing the attack on the f7-pawn, Kd6 is played. In the ensuing complicated variations, Black, it seemed to me, has every right to look forward to saving himself.  In 2011, Vardan Pogosyan made some significant theoretical corrections. First of all, he found the subtle road to victory in one of the lines which I had examined. Secondly, he established that Black achieves a draw much more easily than in my lines, if the king occupies d5, something that is both possible and necessary, even with the rook on b7! }
1... Ke6 { Also good is  4...Ke5  . } 2. Kc2 Rb5 3. Kc3
{ 6.g4  hxg4  7.fxg4  f5  8.gxf5+  Kxf5  or @@StartFEN@@8/1R6/1P2k1p1/1r3p2/6PP/8/2K5/8 w - - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  8.h5  fxg4!  is not dangerous.   It is worth noting that @@StartSquare@@Ed. the upcoming variations → Diagram 9-199 Extra@@EndSquare@@ are not forced − there are other similar defensive set-ups. Moreover, White could sidestep them if, instead of  6.Kc3  , he played  6.Kd3  Kd5  7.Rxf7  Rxb6  8.Re7  But even here, after  8...Rb3+  9.Ke2  Ra3  Black can still count on drawing. }
3... Kd5 { Diagram 9-199 } 4. Kd3
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed.  7.Rxf7  → Diagram 9-199 EXTRA@@EndSquare@@ While on  7.Rb8  Kc6  8.Kd4  Rb4+  and it's useless for the king to move forward:  9.Ke5  Rb5+  10.Kf6  Rf5+  and 11...Rxf3. }
4... Rb3+ { The simplest. } 5. Ke2 Ke5 { Draw. } *

