{ Hollis − Flórián, ol cr 1972  (analysis) } 7. Rxf7
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed.  7.g4  → Diagram 9-200@@EndSquare@@ } 7... Rxb6 8. Re7
{ I came upon this position after analyzing quite a different line. Cutting the opponent’s king off along the e-file, White intends to return his king to the right flank and then begin to set his pawns in motion. Black draws by playing: }
8... Rf6 9. Re3
{ 9.f4  Re6!=  And now Black has two ways to achieve a draw: a. } 9... Ra6
{ b.  9...Rf5!?  10.Kd3  g5=  After @@StartFEN@@8/8/6p1/3k1r1p/7P/2K1RPP1/8/8 w - - 4 10@@EndFEN@@  10.f4  Black must play  10...Kd6   But not  10...Rf6  11.Kd3  Re6?  12.Rxe6  Kxe6  13.Ke4  Kf6  14.f5!  gxf5+  15.Kf4  +-  11.Kd3  Ra5  12.Ke4  Ke6=  And if  12.Ke2  Kd7  @@StartBracket@@Black cannot do without this move: the rook would have to defend the g6-pawn along the sixth rank@@EndBracket@@  13.Kf3  Ra1!?  @@StartBracket@@not allowing 14.g4@@EndBracket@@  14.Re5  Ra3+  15.Kg2  Ra2+  16.Kh3  Ra6  17.f5  gxf5  18.Rxf5  Rh6  19.Kg2  Ke6  20.Rg5  Kf7= }
10. Kd3 Ra2 11. Re4 { 11.f4  Kd6= } 11... Rg2 12. Ke3 Rxg3 13. Kf2 Rg4 14. Rxg4
hxg4 15. fxg4 Ke4 16. Kg3 Ke5 17. Kf3 Kf6
{ We saw this endgame in the game Yusupov-Ljubojevic, inDiagram 1-13. } *

