{ Hollis − Flórián, ol cr 1972  (analysis) } 1. g4 hxg4 2. fxg4
{ Now, premature is  8...f5  9.g5!   9.gxf5  gxf5  10.h5  Kc6=  9...f4  10.Rb8!  For example,  10...f3  11.Kd2  Rb4   11...Rb2+  12.Ke1  Kc6  13.Rg8  Re2+  14.Kf1  Re6  15.Kf2  Kxb6  16.Kxf3  Kc7  17.h5!  gxh5  18.g6  +-  12.h5  gxh5  13.g6  Rb2+  14.Ke1  Re2+  15.Kf1  Re7  16.Rh8  Rg7  17.Rxh5+  Kc6  18.Rg5  Kxb6  19.Kf2  +-  (Dvoretsky)  .  But after the text move, White does not have a win. }
2... Rb1 { Diagram 9-200 a. } 3. h5
{ b.  9.Rb8  Kc6  10.Rc8+  Kd6  , and in case of @@StartFEN@@1R6/5p2/1Pk3p1/8/6PP/2K5/8/1r6 w - - 3 4@@EndFEN@@  10.b7  Rf1=  or  10...Rh1=   c.  9.Kc2  here also possible is  9...Rb5  or  9...Rb4  10.h5  gxh5  11.gxh5  Kc5!  12.Rb8  Rh4=   d.  9.Kd3  f5!?   9...Rb5  is also not bad, or  9...Rb3+  10.Ke2  Ke6=  10.gxf5  gxf5  11.h5  Kc6  12.Rb8  Rh1=  (analysis by Pogosyan)  . }
3... gxh5 4. gxh5 Kc6 5. Rxf7 Kxb6
{ We could, in principle, confine ourselves to this. But I wanted to show what dangers might await Black if he defends less precisely, especially since the variations which arise are rather interesting. }
*

