{ Hollis − Flórián, ol cr 1972  (analysis) } 1... Rb1
{ Instead of  6...Kd5!  @@StartSquare@@Ed. seeDiagram 9-199@@EndSquare@@, I examined the text move, which, while not losing, does give his opponent additional possibilities. }
2. g4
{ I had made a real mistake in the analysis of the line starting with a.  7.g4  − @@StartSquare@@Ed. b.  7.Rb8  is analyzed next, in Diagram 9-201 EXTRA and c.  7.Kc4  →Diagram 9-203@@EndSquare@@ }
2... hxg4 3. fxg4 f5
{ Diagram 9-201   Necessary is  8...Kd5  arriving, by a transposition of moves, to thedrawn position which we just examined. }
4. h5
{ 9.g5  f4  is not dangerous. Or  9.gxf5+  Kxf5  10.Rb8  Kg4  11.b7  Kh3   11...Rb6?  12.h5!  gxh5  13.Rg8+  Kf3  14.b8=Q  Rxb8  15.Rxb8  h4  16.Rh8!  Kg3  17.Kd3  h3  18.Ke2!  +-  12.Kd4  Rb2  13.Kc5  Rb1  14.Kc6  Rc1+  15.Kd6  Rb1  16.Ke6  Kg4  17.Kf6  Rb6+  18.Kg7  Kg3=  And in case of @@StartFEN@@1R6/1P6/3K2p1/8/7P/7k/8/1r6 w - - 9 11@@EndFEN@@  16.Ke5  Rb6!  17.Kf4  Rb5!=   On  9.Kc2  Rb5  10.h5  there follows  10...fxg4!= }
4... gxh5
{ 9...fxg4  10.hxg6  g3  11.g7  Rc1+  12.Kd2  Rc8  13.Ke2  +-   I further examined  10.gxh5  f4!   10...Kf6?  11.h6  +- and if  10...Kd6?  11.Rg7  +- or in case of @@StartFEN@@8/1R6/1P2k3/5p1P/8/2K5/8/1r6 b - - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  10...Rh1?  11.Rc7!  Kd6  12.Rh7  Rb1  13.b7  Ke5  14.h6  Kf6  15.Rd7  +-  11.Kd3  Rh1!  12.Rh7   12.Rc7  Rxh5  13.b7  Rb5  12...Rb1  13.b7  Kf6   13...Kf5?  14.Rg7  , but 13...f3=  14.Ke4  Rb4+  15.Kf3  Kg5=  And in case of  13.Ke4  Rb4+  14.Kf3  Kf5= }
5. Kc2
{ Pogosyan found this powerful zwischenzug, expelling the rook from b1.   On  10...Rg1  the most precise is  11.Rg7  +-   After  10...Rb4  or  10...Rb5  11.gxh5  achieving a draw is not possible, inasmuch as  11...f4  12.h6  is not that effective: the f-pawn, without any support from the rook on the first rank, is easily held back by the king.   10...Rb4  11.gxh5  Kd5  12.Kc3  Rb1  13.h6  Kc5  14.Rf7  Kxb6  15.h7  Rh1  16.Kd4  +-  also does not help. }
5... Rh1 6. Rc7 Kd6 7. Rc8 { Is decisive. } *

