{ Hollis − Flórián, ol cr 1972  (analysis) } 7. Rb8
{ b. On  7.Rb8  , necessary is  7...Kd5!  8.g4  hxg4  9.fxg4  Kc6=  , or @@StartFEN@@1R6/5p2/1P4p1/3k3p/7P/2K2PP1/8/1r6 w - - 2 8@@EndFEN@@ or  8.Rb7  Rb5=   And if  8.b7  Kc6  9.Kd4  Rg1  10.Rf8  Kxb7  11.Rxf7+  Kc8  12.Ke4  Rxg3  13.Kf4  Rg1= }
7... Kd6 { The alternative allows White to improve his king position. } 8. Kc4
Rb2 9. Rb7 Ke6 10. Kc5 Rc2+ 11. Kd4 Rb2 12. g4 { Only now! } 12... hxg4 13.
fxg4 Rb1 14. Rb8 Kd6 15. b7 Kc6
{ And we see why 10.Kc5! was important. White gained a tempo to put his king on d4. With the king on c4, this would be a draw. }
16. Ke5 { But here 16. Ke5 wins. } *

