[SetUp "1"]

{ Hollis − Flórián, ol cr 1972  (analysis)     I had previously noted the choice between 7...Kd5 and 7...Kd6, but preferred to focus on the latter, to demonstrate an interesting attempt for White instead of the correct  9.Rb7!  I will nevertheless provide it, although it has lost its practical significance: }
1. f4 Rb1 2. f5 gxf5
{ Otherwise @@StartFEN@@1R6/5p2/1P1k2p1/5P1p/2K4P/6P1/8/1r6 w - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.fxg6  fxg6  12.Rg8 }
3. Rh8 f6 4. Rh6
{ Diagram 9-202   Now, the natural  12...Ke5?  leads to a loss after  13.Kc5  Rb3  14.Rg6  f4  15.gxf4+  Kxf4  16.Kc6  +- }
4... Ke6 5. Kc5 Rc1+
{ Before attacking g3, it is useful to drive the king to b7 where it will impede its own pawn. Incidentally, with the king on e5, the white king can be protected from checks on b8, not b7. }
6. Kb5 Rb1+ 7. Kc6 Rc1+ 8. Kb7 Rc3
{ And here is the main advantage of the king on e6: White cannot defend the g3-pawn with the rook.  17.Rg6  Kf7! }
9. Rxh5 Rxg3 10. Kc7 Rc3+ { 18...Rg7+  19.Kc6 } 11. Kb8 Rb3
{ 19...f4  20.Rb5  f3 } 12. b7 Rb1
{ And, as shown in subsequent analysis, Black saves the game. } *

