{ Hollis − Flórián, ol cr 1972  (analysis)   c. @@StartSquare@@Ed. the third option for White on move 7@@EndSquare@@ }
1. Kc4 Rc1+ 2. Kb3 Rb1+ 3. Ka2
{ White plans Rb8 followed by a king advance. He could not break through to the pawn along the c-file, but the a-file lies open.   In case of  9.Ka3  Black parries the threat by  9...Kd5!   Both  9...Rb5?  10.Ka4  Rb1  11.Rb8!  Kd6  12.Ka5  , and @@StartFEN@@8/1R3p2/1P2k1p1/7p/7P/K4PP1/8/1r6 b - - 5 3@@EndFEN@@  9...Ra1+  10.Kb2  Ra5  11.Kb3  Ra1  12.Rb8!  Kd6  13.Kb4  Kc6  14.Rf8  Kxb6  15.Rxf7  are bad.  White responds with  10.Ka4!   10.Rb8  Kc6  11.Rf8  Rxb6  12.Rxf7  Kd5=  , or  11.Rc8+  Kd6=  10...Ra1+  11.Kb3  Rb1+  12.Kc2  Rb5  13.Rxf7  Rxb6  and a drawn position, which we have already discussed, has arisen @@StartBracket@@cf. Diagram 9-199, the variation7.Rxf7 Rxb6@@EndBracket@@, only with the insignificant difference that here the king is on  c2  instead of  c3  . }
3... Rb5 4. Ka3 Rb1
{ A quicker draw can be achieved in a pawn endgame with a pawn less:  10...Kd5  11.Ka4  Kc5!?  12.Rc7+  Kxb6  13.Rxf7  Rf5  14.Rxf5  gxf5  15.Kb4  Kc6  16.Kc4  Kd6  17.Kd4  Ke6=  − reciprocal zugzwang! }
5. Rb8 Kd6 6. Ka4 Kc6 7. Rc8+ Kb7
{ 13...Kxb6??  14.Rb8+  and  13...Kd6?  14.Ka5 } 8. Rc7+ Kxb6 9. Rxf7 Kc5 10.
Rf6
{ Diagram 9-203 How should Black proceed?  Ed. note: analyzed further → Diagram 9-203 EXTRA }
