{ Hollis − Flórián, ol cr 1972  (analysis)   Speaking about ideas... Let's return to the very beginning of this ending. @@StartSquare@@Ed. analyzed fromDiagram 9-194@@EndSquare@@   We now have the right to question the natural move  3...Rb3?!  . The idea was to tie down the king to the f3-pawn. But since the king is not going to protect it, and since Black, as has become clear, cannot justify capturing it, why waste a tempo withdrawing the rook? }
1... Ke6
{ Stefan Bücker correctly noted that there is a relatively simple draw after the text move. He even proposed another way to conduct the defense: the immediate activation of the king by  3...Ke5!?  4.Kd1  Kd4  5.Kc1  Rb5  6.Rd7+  Ke3  7.b7  f5!   But not  7...Kxf3?  8.Kc2  with the threat of transferring the rook to the b-file.  The draw is also still attainable here, but the lines are much more intense. Here is one of them:  8.Kc2  Kf2  9.f4  Rb6  10.Rd2+  Ke1  11.Rd1+  Ke2!  12.Rb1  Rc6+  and the white king has nowhere to hide from the checks.   Finally, analogous to the basic defensive idea in the Kantorovich/Steckner position @@StartBracket@@Diagram 9-158@@EndBracket@@, @@StartSquare@@Ed. most probably the author referred toDiagram 9-162@@EndSquare@@  3...g5!?  4.hxg5+  Kxg5  5.Kd1  h4=  and if @@StartFEN@@8/1R3p2/1P6/6kp/8/5PP1/1r6/4K3 w - - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  5.Rb8  Kf6  6.Kd1  Ke7  is worth serious attention. }
2. Kd1 f6 3. Kc1 Rb5 4. Kd2 { Or  6.Kc2 } 4... g5 { Draw. } *

