{ Portisch − Petrosian, Palma de Mallorca cmqf  (12)  1974 } 1... Kh6
{ Petrosian prepares ...f7-f6 and ...g6-g5. The positional defense method @@StartBracket@@à la Kantorovich@@EndBracket@@, starting with  1...Kf6  had not yet been discovered and still is not widely known. }
2. Ke3
{ Portisch suggests a more energetic approach:  2.b5!?  f6  3.b6  g5  4.Rb8   White may try  4.Ke4!?  but here Black saves himself by playing  4...Rxf2  @@StartBracket@@and, most importantly, without exchanging pawns on h4@@EndBracket@@.  4...gxh4  5.gxh4  Kg6  6.Ke4  +-  The evaluation of the final position is correct, but the defense can be improved.  As Pogosyan established, Black draws by continuing @@StartFEN@@1R6/8/1P3p1k/7p/7P/5K2/1r3P2/8 b - - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Rb4  (instead of 5...Kg6?)  6.Ke3  Kg7!  7.Kd3  Rxh4  8.Kc3  Rh1  .   However, to avoid the pitfalls of complicated calculations, the move order can be changed:  3...Rb4!  4.Rb8  g5  5.Ke3  Kg7!=  Or  5...gxh4  6.gxh4  Kg7!= }
2... f6 3. Rb6 Kg7 4. Rb7+ Kh6 5. Rb8
{ In Kantorovich's opinion, the correct line is  5.b5  g5  6.Kd4  gxh4  7.gxh4  Kg6   7...Rb4+  8.Kc5  Rxh4  9.Ra7  Rh1  10.Ra4  h4  11.b6  h3  12.b7  Rb1  13.Rb4  Rc1+  14.Kb6  +-  8.b6  Rxf2?  9.Ra7  Rb2  10.Kc5  Rc2+  11.Kd6  Rb2  12.Kc6  Kf5  13.Ra4  +- However,  8...Kf5!  instead of 8...Rxf2, improves the defense and leads to a draw. }
5... g5 6. b5 gxh4 7. gxh4 Kg6 8. b6 Kf5 9. Kd4
{ 9.b7  does not win in view of  9...Rb4!  10.Kd3  Kf4  11.Kc3  Rb1  12.Kd4  Kf3  13.Kd5  Kxf2  14.Ke6  Rb6+  15.Kf5  Kf3  16.Kg6  Kg4=  (Kantorovich)   Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 9-206 }
