{ Portisch − Petrosian, Palma de Mallorca cmqf  (12)  1974  (continued) } 1...
Rxf2
{ A draw could be achieved rather simply:  9...Kg4!  10.Rg8+  Kxh4  11.Kc5  Rc2+!  (a standard method: the king is driven back with checks so that it is forced to stand in front of the pawn)  12.Kd6  Rb2  13.Kc7  Rc2+  14.Kb8  Rxf2  15.b7  Rb2  16.Kc7  f5=  @@StartBracket@@Averbakh@@EndBracket@@. }
2. Ra8 Rb2 3. Kc5 { ∆ 12.Ra4 +- } 3... Rc2+
{ 11...Kg4  12.Ra4+  Kg3  13.Rb4  Rc2+  14.Kd6  Rc8  15.Ke6  is hopeless. } 4.
Kd4 Rb2 5. Ra5+
{ As noted by Pogosyan, White had to repeat move:  13.Kc5  Rc2+  and now play  14.Kb5!  Rb2+  15.Ka6  Ra2+  16.Kb7  +- @@StartBracket@@after the rook withdraws, 17.Ra4 decides matters@@EndBracket@@ or @@StartFEN@@R7/8/KP3p2/5k1p/7P/8/1r6/8 b - - 11 7@@EndFEN@@  15...Kg4  16.b7  Kxh4  17.b8=Q  +-   Ed. note: analyzed in the next variation → Diagram 9-207 and continued in Diagram 9-208. }
