{ Portisch − Petrosian, Palma de Mallorca cmqf  (12)  1974  (analysis)     Should the king go forward or backwards? Of course,  13...Kg4  suggests itself, and works after  14.Kc5  Kxh4= }
13... Kg4 14. Ra4
{ However White has this strong reply, with the threat 15.Kc3+.   Let us look further:  14...Kg3  15.Kc5  f5  16.Rb4  Rc2+  17.Kd6  Rc8  18.b7  Rb8  19.Kc7  Rh8  20.b8=Q  Rxb8  21.Rxb8  Kxh4   21...f4  22.Kd6  f3  23.Ke5  f2  24.Rf8  Kxh4  25.Ke4  +-  22.Kd6  Kg4   22...Kg3  23.Ke5  h4  24.Kxf5  h3  25.Rb3+  Kg2  26.Kg4  h2  27.Rb2+  Kg1  28.Kg3  +- or  23...f4  24.Ke4  +-  23.Ke5  h4  24.Kd4!   24.Rb4+?  f4!  24...h3  25.Ke3  h2  26.Rg8+  Kh3  27.Kf2  h1=N+  28.Kf3  +- And in case of @@StartFEN@@1R6/8/8/5p2/3K2kp/8/8/8 b - - 1 24@@EndFEN@@  24...f4  25.Kd3  Kf3  26.Rh8!  or  25.Ke4  Kg3  26.Rg8+  +-  Yet Black can survive even after 14.Ra4, as Igor Zaitsev has shown! }
14... Kh3 { He discovered the text resource, instead of  14...Kg3? } 15. Kc5 f5
16. Rb4 Rxb4 17. Kxb4 f4 18. b7 f3 19. b8=Q f2
{ A queen does not win against a bishop pawn! } *

