Ke6 14. Kc5 Rc2+
{ Diagram 9-208 An error that leads to a rapid loss.   He should have played  14...Kd7!  Neither  15.Ra7+  Kc8  16.Rh7  Rc2+  17.Kd5  Rb2  nor @@StartFEN@@2k5/7R/1P3p2/2K4p/7P/8/2r5/8 w - - 7 17@@EndFEN@@  17.Kd6  Rc4!  18.Rxh5  Kb7  19.Rh8  f5  is dangerous.   At first I thought that White would win after  14...Kd7  by continuing  15.Ra8!  f5  16.Rh8   16.Rf8  Ke6!  16...f4  17.Rxh5  f3  18.Rf5  f2   18...Rh2  19.Rf8!  If now  19.h5  then  19...Re2!?  ∆  20.--  Re5+  , so White goes instead  19.Rf8  . However, Black has a way to draw with an attack on the b-pawn:  19...Rc2+  20.Kb5  Rb2+  21.Ka6  Kc6!  22.Rf6+  Kc5= }
15. Kb5 Kd6 16. Ka6 Kc6 17. Ra1 Rc4 18. b7 Rb4 19. Rc1+ Kd7 20. Rc8
{ Black resigned. } *

