{ When the Attacker Achieves g3-g4   In many of the positions we have examined, Black has aimed for an f7-g6-h5 pawn configuration, which is often regarded as the safest for the defending player when down a pawn in a rook ending. There are times when Black is unable to reach this structure, and White tries to prevent it by playing g4 and g5, thereby gaining space on the kingside.  In this case, Black has a defensive scheme which was not well known until recently, although it uses an idea dating back almost 100 years, to Vancura. Former US Champion Alexander Onischuk employed this scheme in 2017, and it immediately became topical:  Urkedal – Onischuk, WchT 2017 }
1... Rd3+ 2. Kg2 h5 3. Rc7
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed.  3.a6  is analyzed next →Diagram 9-208b@@EndSquare@@ }
3... Ra3 4. Rc5 Kf8 5. Re5 f6
{ 5...Kg7  holds as well, but Onischuk uses the opportunity to activate his king and avoid an eternal cut-off. }
6. Rb5 fxg5 7. fxg5 Ke7
{ Ed. note: analyzed in the next variation →Diagram 9-208b and continued inDiagram 9-208c. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 9 – Rook Endgames IV"]
[Black "When the Attacker Achieves g3-g4 9-208 b"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/R4pk1/6p1/P5Pp/5P1P/3r4/6K1/8 w - - 0 3"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Urkedal − Onischuk, WchT 2017  (analysis) } 3. a6 Rd6 4. Kf3 Re6
{ Diagram 9-208b  This is theVancura idea, which we discussed in the section, “A Rook and a Rook’s Pawn vs. a Rook.” Note that the white king is cut off, and f4-f5 is not effective, as he cannot keep his f-pawn. Therefore, this is a relatively simple draw, although modern engines show a “+3” or even “+4” at first. Also note thatL’Ami’s new Vancura defense in the Kantorovich/Steckner position is similar. }
5. Ra8 { 5.Kf2  Kg8  , but not  5...Re4?  6.Rc7  , and White will win. } 5...
Kh7 { 5...f5!?  also draws:  6.gxf6+  Rxf6!  with a Vancura-like defense. } 6.
f5
{ After  6.a7  Ra6  , White’s king has no shelter on the queenside anymore. }
6... gxf5 7. Kf4 Kg7 8. Kxf5 Re1
{ Keeping the king cut off;  8...Rd6  also draws. } 9. Rc8 Ra1 10. Rc6 Ra4 11.
Ke5 Rxh4 12. Kd6 Ra4 13. Kc7 h4 14. Kb7 h3 15. Rh6 Rb4+ 16. Ka8 Rb3 17. a7 f6
{ Draw.  Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 9-208c } *

