{ Tragicomedies: Heinemann − Zelbel, German Bundesliga 2014  (continued) } 9...
Ra4
{ A typical mistake! The rook moves behind the rook pawn, when in fact it should be flexible. The configuration with the white pawn on  g5  was not covered well in the literature. But we already know that Black should prepare the Vancura defense with  9...Rc4!  @@StartBracket@@or to b4/d4@@EndBracket@@  10.a6   10.Rb7  Ra4  11.Rb5  is not dangerous and Black can choose whether  to activate the king via f8 and e7 or go for...f6 counterplay,  (as in theOnischuk game.)  10...Rc6  11.Kg3  Kg7  12.Kf4  Re6  13.Ra8  Kh7  14.a7  Ra6= }
10. a6 Kg7 11. f4 Ra3+ 12. Kg2 Ra2+
{ 12...Ra4  does not help, because after  13.Kf3  Kf8  , White plays  14.Ke2!!   But not the direct  14.Ra8+  Kg7  15.Ke3  Kh7  16.Kd3?  Rxf4  17.Rf8  Kg7  18.a7  Kxf8  19.a8=Q+  Kg7  20.Qa1+  Kg8  21.Qe1  Rg4  which is a fortress.  14...Kg7  15.Ke3!  with the same zugzwang position as in the game. This triangulation idea of 14.Ke2 was found by Anish Giri during a training session with Karsten Müller in August 2018. }
13. Kf3 Ra4 14. Ke3
{ Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 9-208f } *

