{ Tragicomedies: Heinemann − Zelbel, German Bundesliga 2014  (analysis) } 25.
Ka5
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed. in the game,  25.Kc5?  was played → Diagram 9-208 i&j@@EndSquare@@ }
25... Rb8 26. Rc4 Rh8
{ The only defensive attempt: White will have to give up the rook rather than queening the pawn cleanly.   Instead, if  26...h4  27.Rxh4  f6  28.Rb4!  and with the king on  a5  Black has no check, so White wins immediately. }
27. a7 h4 28. Rxh4
{ 28.Rb4?  allows a miraculous escape with  28...Ra8  29.Ka6  h3  30.Rb2  Rc8!!  31.Rb8  h2  32.Rxc8  h1=Q  33.a8=Q  Qa1+=  when despite being a rook up White cannot stop the perpetual, as his heavy pieces are too deep in the opponent’s territory. }
28... Rxh4 29. a8=Q
{ Reaching a position that looks like a fortress. In the 2004 Endgame Corner 37 in chesscafe.com, Karsten Müller and Spanish IM Arizmendi concluded it was a draw, but in 2014 Müller found a win, which was later confirmed by the seven-piece tablebase: mate in 52!  Ed. note: the winning continuation → Diagram 9-208h }
