Kc5 Rb8 26. Rf4
{ Diagram 9-208i   26.Rd4  h4!  27.Rxh4  f6!  28.Rb4  Rc8+!  is why the king should not have gone to c5: Black now creates a passed pawn on the kingside which saves the day. }
26... Rb1
{ Giving White another chance, when  26...h4  draws like in the previous note. }
27. Ra4
{ Missing the opportunity with  27.a7  Ra1  28.Kb6  and Black is a tempo too slow after  28...h4  29.Rxh4  f6  30.gxf6+  Kxf6  31.Rh8  Rxa7  32.Kxa7  g5  33.Kb6  Ke5  34.Kc5  g4  35.Re8+  Kf4  36.Kd4  Kf3  37.Kd3  g3  38.Rf8+  +- Also winning is  27.Rd4  , preventing counterplay with  ...f6, as White can check on the seventh rank. }
27... Rb8 28. a7 Ra8 29. Ra6
{ Not an effective way to stop the f6-break because Black is in time with his counterplay. }
29... h4 30. Kb6 f6 31. gxf6+ Kf7 32. Kb7 Rxa7+ 33. Rxa7 Kxf6 34. Kc6 Ke5
{ Diagram 9-208j A good bodycheck, although it was not the only way to draw. }
35. Rg7 Kf4 36. Rxg6 h3 37. Kd5 h2 38. Rh6 Kg3 39. Ke4 Kg2 40. Rxh2+ Kxh2
{ Draw. } *

