[SetUp "1"]

{ It is almost always sensible to go to the defense from the side, when the passed pawn has not advanced further than the second or third rank, because in that case, the rook is usually protecting its other pawns as well.    This sort of position occurs quite often in practical play but still does not have any definite evaluation. In the previous example, the passed pawn was on the fourth rank, and the rook, defending it from the side, occupied an active position and defended its own pawns. This is often a winning strategy.  However, if the passed pawn is only on the second or third rank, the rook defending it from the side is usually too passive. In the following example, Anatoly Karpov chose this strategy, but it only succeeded as a result of an error by the opponent.  Ed. the game continuation → Diagram 9-210 }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 9 – Rook Endgames IV"]
[Black "The Rook at the Side of the Pawn 9-210"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/R4ppp/5k2/2r5/8/7P/P4PP1/4K3 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Karpov – Knaak, Baden Baden 1992 } 1. Ra3
{ If  1.Kd2  Rd5+  , the king can hardly escape from the rook checks because it must watch the second rank, while  1.a4?!  Rc2  leads to a standard position with the black rook behind the passed pawn. Karpov brings the rook to the second or third rank where it will protect everything. }
1... g5
{ An unfavorable setup, particularly in conjunction with Black’s next move @@StartBracket@@the king should have been kept in the center, to fight against the passed pawn if necessary@@EndBracket@@.   A more clever idea was  1...h5  , with possibly  an eventual ...h5-h4 and ...Rg5. But the move played does not harm anything. }
2. Kd2 Kg6
{ This move makes things difficult for Black. The immediate  2...h5  was called for. }
3. Rc3
{ The twelfth world champion had a unique sense for moves which were not always the best, but which caused his opponents practical problems. Awarding “?!” to 3.Rc3 here, after which he gets a winning position very quickly, is therefore not something we take lightly. However, it can be shown conclusively that now the position is drawn, whereas after the best move here we cannot reach a verdict as to what the outcome should be.   3.Ra6+!?  offers better winning chances. For example:  3...f6  4.a4  Rc4!   4...h5?  allows the rook to regroup with  5.Rb6!  Ra5  6.Rb4  5.a5  Rf4  6.Ke2  Ra4  7.Ra8  and Black’s defense remains very difficult. }
3... Ra5 4. a3 { Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 9-210a } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 9 – Rook Endgames IV"]
[Black "The Rook at the Side of the Pawn 9-210 a"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/5p1p/6k1/r5p1/8/P1R4P/3K1PP1/8 b - - 0 4"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Karpov − Knaak, Baden Baden 1992  (continued) } 4... h5
{ A far from obvious, but decisive, mistake. Necessary was  4...f5  , for example  5.Kc2  g4!  6.Kb3   6.hxg4  fxg4  7.Kb3  Rb5+  8.Ka2  Rf5  9.Rc2  h5=  6...Rb5+  7.Ka2  Ra5  8.Rc4  gxh3  9.gxh3  Rd5  and Black has enough counterplay. }
5. Kc2 Ra8
{ 5...g4  is not as effective here, because after  6.hxg4  hxg4  7.Kb3  Rb5+  8.Ka2  Rf5  9.Rc2  ,  White safely defends everything. Therefore, the more asymmetrical ...f5 and ...g4, with a potential passed h-pawn, was necessary on the previous move.  5...f5  here may still offer a fighting chance, while after the move played, Karpov convincingly marches to victory. }
6. Kb3 Rb8+ 7. Ka2 Ra8
{ 7...Rd8  will not help after  8.Rc2  Rd3  9.a4  Kf6  10.a5  Rd5  11.Rc6+  Ke7  12.a6  +- }
8. Rc4 f5 { 8...Re8  9.Rb4  Re2+  10.Rb2  Re4  11.Kb3  +- } 9. a4 Kf6 10. Ka3
Ke5 11. Rc5+ Ke4 12. a5 h4 13. Ka4 Kf4 14. Rc4+
{ 14.Kb5  is also strong. After  14...Rb8+  ,  15.Kc6  Rb2  16.Rc4+  wins quickly.  16.a6  Rxf2  17.Ra5  Rc2+  18.Kb6  Rc8  19.Kb7  Rh8  20.Ra3!  is also good. }
14... Ke5 15. Rb4 Kd5 16. Rb5+ Ke4 17. Rb6 Kf4 18. a6 g4 19. Ka5 g3
{ 19...gxh3  20.Rb4+!  Ke5  21.gxh3  +- } 20. Rb4+ Ke5 21. f3 f4 22. Re4+ Kf5
23. Re2 Kf6 24. Kb6
{ Black resigned.  Diagram 9-211 has been intentionally omitted. } *

