{ Tragicomedies: Averbakh – Euwe, Switzerland ct 1953 } 1... Rg3
{ A grave mistake as Euwe allows his opponent to bring his rook to g5 with tempo White’s rook will safely protect all his pawns there  @@StartBracket@@after g2-g3 and a4-a5@@EndBracket@@.   After  1...Ra2+!  , a draw was quite obvious. }
2. Rg5 Ra3 3. a5 Kf7
{ Sometimes in similar situations, one succeeds in preventing the king’s approach to the passed pawn by cutting the king off along a file, e.g.,  3...Rc3  4.Kd2  Rc4  5.g3  Rc6  . This method does not work in our case: White plays  6.Kd3  Rc1  7.Kd4  Rc2  8.Rc5  Rg2  9.a6  Ra2  @@StartBracket@@  9...Rxg3  10.Ra5  @@EndBracket@@  10.Rc6  Kf5  11.Kc5  , obviously outrunning his opponent. }
4. Kd2 Ke7 5. Kc2 Kd7 6. Kb2 Ra4 7. g3 Kc6 8. Kb3 Ra1
