{ Tragicomedies: Leko − Anand, Linares 2003    Viswanathan Anand undoubtedly knew that such endgames are, as a rule, drawn. So it is hard to understand why he decided not to set up the standard pawn structure with  1...h5!  After  2.Kg2  Rd3!  and  3.--  Ra3  , the rook gets behind the passed pawn, while also restricting the enemy king, and Black would draw without any particular difficulty.  There was no need to fear @@StartFEN@@8/3r1pk1/6p1/R6p/P6P/6P1/5P2/6K1 w - - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Rc5  and  2...--  3.a5  or  3.Rc4  . He would have to concern himself with the flank defense of the pawn if the a-pawn had already reached the sixth or seventh rank. }
1... Rd1+ 2. Kg2 Ra1
{ It was still not too late to play  2...h5  , returning to a familiar position. “When the engineer starts looking for new paths, the train goes off the rails.” Objectively, the move Anand chose is just as good, but takes the game off the path of known theory @@StartBracket@@at least, at that time@@EndBracket@@. }
3. g4
{ With this structure, Black has a much harder time getting counterplay on the kingside. Black is now in a new situation and must find a drawing path which was only discovered more than a decade later! But we already know it from the earliersection “When the Attacker Achieves g3-g4.” }
3... Kf6
{ 3...h5  4.g5  Rc1  5.f3  Rc4  6.Kg3  Rd4  gets us to the structures we previously discussed:Urkedal-Onischuk andHeinemann-Zelbel, which are drawn. But the text does not spoil anything, either. }
4. Kg3
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed.  4.g5+  is analyzed next →Diagram 9-214a and the game continues in →Diagram 9-214b@@EndSquare@@ }
*

