{ 9/23. Yusupov-Timman, Linares cmsf  (7)  1992  Where should White place his rook, at the side of his passed pawn or behind it? }
1. Re4
{ The winning move! Here the rook protects only one pawn but at the first appropriate opportunity it will go to the fifth rank where it holds everything.   The actual continuation was  1.Ra1??  Ra5!  @@StartBracket@@he should block the pawn as early as possible@@EndBracket@@  2.Ke3  e5!  This is the point: one pair of pawns is exchanged immediately, another will be exchanged soon @@StartBracket@@...g6-g5@@EndBracket@@, and too few pawns remain on the board.  3.Ke4   3.fxe5+  Kxe5  4.Kd3  Kd5  5.Kc3  Kc6  6.Kb4  Re5=  3...exf4  @@StartBracket@@after  4.gxf4  the white pawns are vulnerable.@@EndBracket@@, therefore  4.Kxf4  Ke6  5.Ke4   He probably should have tried  5.Re1+  Kf6  6.Re4  g5+  7.Ke3  , but this position is also drawn.  5...g5!  6.hxg5  Rxg5  7.Kf3  Ra5  , and a draw was soon agreed. }
1... Kf5
{ Or  1...Ra5  2.Ke3  Rd5  3.Re5!  Black has no arguments against a king march to the queenside. }
2. Re5+ Kf6 3. a5 { White wins. } *

