[FEN "4r3/1k5p/p1pK2p1/3p1p2/1P6/R3PP2/P5PP/8 b - - 0 8"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Flohr - Vidmar, Nottingham 1936  (analysis)     a.  8...f4?  is entirely bad in view of  9.exf4  Re2  10.g4  with  f4-f5 +- to follow. Black cannot fight against the passed f-pawn because another pawn, on f3, is blocking the file from rook attacks.   b. Levenfish and Smyslov suggest  8...d4!?  9.exd4  Re2  10.Rc3  Rxg2   10...Rd2  11.Rc4  11.Rxc6  Rxh2  12.a4  g5  ∆ ...g4; ...Rh6+. However, White maintains the advantage by placing the rook behind the g-pawn,  13.Rc7+!  Kb6  14.Rg7!  ,  because his own passed pawn is quite dangerous. Such an alternative  (with consequences that can hardly be calculated and evaluated over the board)  is still practically better than the passive defense with the rook on a8. Moreover, it can be improved: a third way exists, although endgame treatises do not mention it.  c. @@StartSquare@@Ed. see the text move@@EndSquare@@ }
8... g5 9. g3
{ After  9.Rc3  f4  10.exf4  gxf4  , Black maintains enough counterplay, for example,  11.Rxc6  Rd8+  12.Kc5  d4  13.Re6  d3  14.Re1  Rg8= }
9... g4
{ Again,  9...d4?!  10.exd4  Re2  is dubious here in view of  11.Ra5!   11.Rc3  Rxh2  and the c6-pawn is inviolable.  11...h6!  12.a4!   12.Rxf5  Rxa2  13.Rf7+  Kb6  14.Rc7  Rxh2  15.Rxc6+  Kb5  12...Rb2  13.Rxf5  Rxb4  14.Kc5  Rxa4  15.Rf7+  and Black’s position is difficult. }
10. f4 { 10.fxg4  fxg4  11.Rc3  Rf8= } 10... Re4 11. Rc3 Rc4 *

