{ Flohr - Vidmar, Nottingham 1936  (continued from Diagram 9-224) } 5... Rb8
{ Too passive. The rook will be forced back to the unenviable role of bodyguard to the a-pawn as early as the next move. }
6. a3 Ra8 { The b6-square is perhaps even a worse place for the rook than a8. }
7. e4
{ White has achieved the maximum on the queenside and cannot improve his position in this sector anymore   7.a4?  Rb8  . Therefore he applies a standard method: widening the beachhead! After the exchange of the central pawns, the white king attacks the kingside while the rook gets full control over the fifth rank. }
7... fxe4 8. fxe4 dxe4 9. Kxe4 { Diagram 9-226 } 9... Ra7
{ I think that White should not force matters. The restraining method @@StartFEN@@r7/2k4p/p1p3p1/R7/1P2K3/P7/6PP/8 w - - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10.h4!?  Kb6  11.Kf4!?  or  11.g4  Rf8  12.h5  maintains an indisputable advantage; the question is solely whether it is sufficient for a win. }
10. Kf4 h6
{ Otherwise the king passes to h6 with decisive effect:  10...Ra8?  11.Kg5  Ra7  12.Kh6  Ke6  13.g4  ∆ h4-h5 +- }
11. h4 Ke6 12. Kg4 Ra8 13. h5 g5
{ 13...gxh5+?  14.Kxh5  Rg8  15.g4  +-;  13...Rg8!!  was the last chance to activate the rook, with good drawing chances. }
14. g3
{ White has created and fixed a new weakness in Black’s camp: the h6-pawn. Prior to returning his king to the center, he takes control over the f4-square.  14.Kf3  is less accurate in view of  14...Rf8+  15.Ke4  Rf4+  .   Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 9-227 }
