{ Flohr − Vidmar, Nottingham 1936  (continued) } 14... Ra7 15. Kf3 Ra8 16. Ke4
Ra7 17. Kd4 Kd6 18. Ke4 Ke6 { Diagram 9-227 } 19. Re5+ Kd6
{ If  19...Kf6  , then  20.Rc5  Rc7  21.Ra5  Ra7  22.Kd4  Ke6  23.Kc5  +- } 20.
Re8 c5
{ The pawn endgame after  20...Re7+  21.Rxe7  Kxe7  22.Ke5  is absolutely hopeless. }
21. Rd8+
{ Perfect endgame technique. Flohr had calculated the following line:  21...Kc7  22.Rh8  cxb4  23.Rh7+   23.axb4  , of course, also wins.  23...Kb8  24.Rxa7  Kxa7  25.axb4  Kb6  26.Kf5  Kb5  27.Kg6  Kxb4  28.Kxh6  a5  29.Kxg5  a4  30.h6  +-.  Other king retreats lose the c5-pawn. }
21... Kc6 22. Rc8+ Kb6 23. Rxc5 Rh7
{ The rook has changed its parking space, but the new one is as unattractive as the previous. }
24. Re5 Kc6 25. Re6+ Kb5 26. Kf5 Rf7+ 27. Rf6 { Black resigned. } *

