{ Tragicomedies: Ilivitsky − Taimanov, USSR ch, Moscow 1955  (analysis)   The waiting move 6.Rf1 is more stubborn. }
6. Rf1 a5
{ It is appropriate to recall that very important principle of endgame play, “Do not rush, ” and, without forcing matters by  6...Ra4?  , make the move  6...a5!  , strengthening the position. }
7. Rf2
{ On  7.Kf4  Ra4+?  8.Kxf5  g3  9.Rg1!=  does not work, but the simple @@StartFEN@@8/8/8/p4p1k/5KpP/r4P2/P7/5R2 b - - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Rxa2!  leads to a win. }
7... Ra4 { ∆  8.--  f4+ } 8. fxg4+ Rxg4+ 9. Kf3 Kxh4
{ 9...Rxh4  is as good, since  10.Rg2  Rg4  11.Rxg4  fxg4+  12.Kg3  a4!  wins for Black,  while the pawn ending with the pawn on a7 would be drawn. }
10. Rh2+ Kg5 11. Rh8
{ The start of a sharp line.   Marking time,  11.Rc2  Ra4  , is bad: this is almost the same position we saw in the gameMiles-Webb @@StartBracket@@Diagram 9-105@@EndBracket@@. }
11... Rf4+ { Also possible is the immediate  11...Ra4  . } 12. Ke3 Ra4 13. Rg8+
Kf6 14. Rf8+ Ke6 15. Re8+ Kf7 16. Ra8 Rxa2 17. Kf4 Ke6 18. Re8+ { Or  18.Ra6+ }
18... Kd5
{ Black gets there just in time and wins. Were the pawn on a7, his opponent would manage to save himself. }
