{ Tragicomedies: Ilivitsky − Taimanov, USSR ch, Moscow 1955  (continued) } 3.
Kf2 a6
{ An incomprehensible move.   As will soon become clear, it made sense for Black to play  3...Kf7!?  preparing the future activation of the king. }
4. Rb2 Rc3
{ The rook should have stayed on a3 until Black both moved the a-pawn well ahead and also improved his king’s position. White would probably still expect a draw after placing his rook on e2 to prevent the black king’s appearance in the center. }
5. Kg2 a5
{ Diagram 9-230   More precise was  5...Ra3  followed by  6.--  Kf7  . } 6. Rf2
{ The same passive policy  @@StartBracket@@by the way, the game was annotated by many, yet no one revealed the errors that were committed by the players at this stage@@EndBracket@@.   Again, White should have taken the opportunity to activate his rook:  6.Rb7!  Rc2+  7.Kg1  Rxa2  8.Ra7  . Grandmaster Krogius evaluates the resulting position as lost for White “because of the bad position of White’s pawns, and especially that of his king – cut off on the first rank.” But what about Black’s king?  It will stay offside forever, because ...f6-f5 can be always met with Ra6+ followed by gxf5. White’s rook stays on a7, the king calmly waits on g1-h1; Black pushes his pawn ahead, it comes to a3, what then?   As grandmaster Vugar Gashimov has correctly noted, the same idea, albeit in somewhat more complicated form, could have arisen earlier. For example, after @@StartFEN@@8/p7/5pk1/6p1/6Pp/r4P1P/P1R2K2/8 b - - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...a6  ,  4.Rc7!  leads to a draw:  4...Rxa2+  5.Kf1!   Less accurate is  5.Kg1  Re2!  6.Rc6  a5  and on  7.Rc5  there is  7...Re5  .  5...Rb2  6.Rc6!  a5  Rc5!  a4  8.Ra5  on  8...Ra2  or  8...Rb4  the same response follows  9.Ra7!  Rf4  10.Kf2  f5  @@StartBracket@@how else to strengthen the position?@@EndBracket@@  11.Ra6+  Kf7  12.gxf5= }
6... Ra3 7. Kf1 Kf7
{ Black probably rejected  7...f5  because of  8.f4!  A good idea could be @@StartFEN@@8/8/5pk1/p5p1/6Pp/r4P1P/P4R2/5K2 b - - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Ra4  preventing the opponent’s activity on the kingside, although White could then cut off the black king by means of  8.Kg2  Kf7  9.Re2  .   Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 9-231 }
