{ 9/24. Taimanov-Chekhov, Kishinev 1976 } 1... Rd3
{ White wants to play e3-e4+, and then slowly improve his position with a2-a4, f2-f3, Kg4, Rb5 etc. And although objectively Whites's' advantage is insufficient to win, Black should still avoid passive defense. }
2. Rxb6
{ White could have tried  2.a4!?  Ra3  3.Kf3  ⨀ but after  3...g4+!  4.Rxg4  b5!  5.axb5  Rb3  a drawn endgame with two pawns versus one would have arisen. }
2... Ra3 { The white rook must occupy a passive position. } 3. Rb2 Ra4
{ A draw was agreed.  I worked with Valery Chekhov as his coach from 1973 until 1975, and our collaboration was crowned with his victory in the World Junior Chess Championship. All of my students firmly absorbed the most important principles of playing endgames. Therefore, for Chekhov, the utilization of the pawn sacrifice to activate the rook was just a simple technical device. }
