{ 9/25. Larsen-Kavalek, Solingen m  (7)  1970 } 1... h5
{ The only safe defense.   Kavalek chose  1...Kg7??  2.Rc4  Ra7   2...Rb3  3.Rxa4  Rxg3  4.Rg4+  Against such a passively placed rook, White wins without trouble, and the remainder of the game confirms this generalization.  3.Kc3  h5  4.Kb4  Kg6  5.Rc6+  Kg7  6.Rc5  Kh6  7.Kb5  @@StartBracket@@∆ Rc4@@EndBracket@@  7...Re7  8.Kxa4  Re3  9.g4  hxg4  10.hxg4  Re4+  11.Kb5  Rxg4  12.a4  Rg1  13.a5  Rb1+  14.Kc6  Ra1  15.Kb6  Rb1+  16.Rb5  Rf1  17.a6  Rf6+  18.Ka5  Rf7  19.Rb6+  Kg5  20.Rb7  Rf1  21.a7  Kh6  22.Rb6+  Kg7  23.Ra6  Black resigned.  He had to keep the rook active, responding to Rc4 with the counterattack ...Rb3!, for this purpose Black should take measures against a rook check from g4.   1...Kf7  seems natural, as the king approaches the center. White could respond with  2.g4  , intending 3.h4 and 4.Rc4. If  2...Ke6  3.h4  Kd5  , then  4.g5!  ∆ 5.Rg3 followed by either 6.Rg4  (attacking the a4-pawn)  or 6.h5 @@StartBracket@@the rook behind the passed pawn@@EndBracket@@. However, Black seems to escape by playing  4...Rf7!  5.Rg3  Rf4  6.h5  Ke6!  7.g6   7.Kc3  Kf7  +=  7...hxg6  8.hxg6  Rc4+!  @@StartBracket@@it is important to cut the king off from the a-pawn@@EndBracket@@  9.Kd3  Rc8  10.g7  Kf7  . Karsten Müller has demonstrated another way to draw:  2...h5!  3.gxh5   3.g5  h4  and @@StartFEN@@8/1r3k2/8/7p/p5P1/P1R4P/2K5/8 w - - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Rc4  Rb3  3...Kg7  4.h4  Kh7  5.Rc4  Rb3!  6.Rxa4  Rf3  . This is the standard drawing situation with a- and h-pawns: the king blockades one of the pawns  (or in this case – both at once, which is unimportant)  ,  while the rook attacks the other from the side, not letting the enemy rook off the a-file. White’s play can be strengthened by the in-between check  2.Rf3+!  If  2...Kg6?  then  3.Rf4  Now that Black cannot play  3...Rb3  4.Rxa4  Rxg3  5.Rg4+  , and on  2...Ke6  , there comes  3.g4  followed by 4.h4, retaining the advantage – with the king in the center,  the ...h7-h5 pawn sacrifice would be ineffective. }
2. Rc4
{ This is useless now.   If  2.h4  , then  2...Rg7!  ∆...Rg4=  ,  and from g4 the rook attacks the g3-pawn, protects the a4-pawn and prevents White’s king march across the fourth rank.   2.g4  can be met by  2...h4!=  , fixing a target for counterattack @@StartBracket@@the h3-pawn@@EndBracket@@:  3.Rc4  Rb3  ⇆. But  2...hxg4  3.hxg4  Kg7  does not lose either:  4.Rc4  Rb3!  @@StartBracket@@activity at any price!@@EndBracket@@  5.Rxa4  Rg3  6.Kb2  Rg2+  7.Kc3  Rg3+  . As can be seen, after 1...h5!, Black’s rook remains active in all lines, and this is what saves him. }
2... Rb3 3. Rxa4 Rxg3 *

