{ The King’s Activity   The importance of an active king’s position does not require detailed explanations. A few practical examples are enough.  Flear – Legky, Le Touquet 1991 }
1... Kf6
{ King activity is more important than material gain!   1...Rb5?!  2.Kf4  Kf6  3.g4  is too passive. And @@StartFEN@@8/4kp2/3p4/p1pP4/R3P3/4K3/1r4PP/8 b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Rxg2?!  2.Rxa5  Rxh2  3.Ra7+  Kf6  4.Rd7  Ke5  5.Re7+  leads to an immediate draw. }
2. Rxa5
{ As Legky wrote, White could deny the king access to e5 by  2.Kf4!  Rf2+  3.Ke3!   3.Kg3?!  Rf1!  ∆  4.--  Ke5  3...Rxg2  4.Rxa5  , and after  4...Ke5  5.Ra7  , Black, in contrast to the game continuation, has no check along the third rank. If @@StartFEN@@8/5p2/3p1k2/R1pP4/4P3/4K3/6rP/8 b - - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Rxh2  , then  5.Ra7  Rh6  6.Rd7  Kg7  7.e5!?  dxe5  8.Ke4  , and White’s activity compensates for the two missing pawns. }
2... Ke5 3. Ra7
{ Oleg Chebotarev suggested a safer defense,  3.Ra4!  As before,  3...Rxg2  is useless because of  4.Ra7  , while if Black tries the temporizing @@StartFEN@@8/5p2/3p4/2pPk3/R3P3/4K3/1r4PP/8 b - - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...f6  , then  4.g3  . }
3... Rb3+ 4. Kf2
{ This loses.   Correct was  4.Ke2  Kxe4  5.Re7+  Kxd5  6.Rxf7+  . } 4... Kxe4
5. Rxf7
{ 5.h4  loses to  5...Rb2+  6.Kg3  c4  7.h5  c3  8.Rc7  Kd3!  9.h6  c2  10.h7  Rb8  . }
5... c4
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed.  5...Rb2?  was played in the game →Diagram 9-235@@EndSquare@@ }
6. Rc7 c3 7. h4 Kd3 8. h5 c2 9. h6 Rb1 { Black wins. } *

