{ Flear − Legky, Le Touquet 1991 } 5... Rb2+
{ Black returns the favor by letting the white king out.  5...c4  6.Rc7  c3  7.h4  Kd3  8.h5  c2  9.h6  Rb1  wins. @@StartSquare@@Ed. as seen in theprevious variation@@EndSquare@@ }
6. Kg3 c4
{ Diagram 9-235  There is no sense in capturing the d5-pawn; the rapid advance of his own passed pawn is more important. }
7. Rc7 Kd3
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed.  7...Kd4!!  is analyzed next → Diagram 9-236@@EndSquare@@ }
8. h4
{ The decisive error.   8.Rc6!  was necessary. Legky continues the line with  8...c3  9.Rxd6  Rb5!  10.Rc6  Rxd5  11.h4  c2  12.Kh3  Rd4  13.Rxc2  Kxc2  -+ As a matter of fact, the final position is won because of the poor position of the white king.  However, Flear could achieve a draw by sending his king ahead: @@StartFEN@@8/8/2R5/3r4/7P/3k2K1/2p3P1/8 w - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Rxc2!  Kxc2  13.Kf4  Kd3  14.g4  , or  13.Kg4  Kd3  14.h5  Ke4  15.h6  . }
8... c3 9. h5 c2 10. h6 Rb1 11. Kf4 { 11.h7  Rh1  12.Kg4  Rxh7  -+ } 11...
c1=Q+ 12. Rxc1 Rxc1 13. g4 Rf1+ 14. Kg5 Ke4 15. Kg6 Rg1 { White resigned. } *

