{ Flear − Legky, Le Touquet 1991  (analysis)     @@StartSquare@@Ed. Instead of  7...Kd3?!  , as seen inDiagram 9-235 Black should have played the text move, in order to protect indirectly his d6-pawn. }
7... Kd4 8. h4 { 8.Rc6?  c3  9.Rxd6  c2  10.Rc6  Rb3+  and 11...Rc3. } 8... c3
{ Diagram 9-236   After  9.h5  Kd3!   9...c2?  is not precise, White saves himself by an immediate activation of his king:  10.Kf4!  Kd3  11.Kf5  .  10.Kf4  Rxg2  11.Kf5  Re2!  12.h6  c2  13.h7  Rh2  14.Kg6  Kd2  -+ In case of @@StartFEN@@8/2R5/3p4/3P3P/8/2pk2K1/1r4P1/8 w - - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10.h6  c2  11.Kf4  Rb1  12.g4   12.h7  Rh1  13.g4  Rxh7  12...c1=Q  13.Rxc1  Rxc1  14.Kf5  Kd4  15.g5  Rh1!  16.Ke6  Kc5  -+ and if  16.Kg6  Ke5!  -+, and the black king arrives just in time!  But Müller indicated that White could hold this endgame by means of: }
9. Kf3 c2 { 9...Kd3  10.g4  c2  11.g5= } 10. Kf4 Kd3 11. Kf5 Rb5 12. Rxc2 Kxc2
13. Ke6 Kd3 14. g4 Ke4 15. g5 Rxd5 16. g6 Re5+ 17. Kf6 Rf5+ 18. Ke6
{ Is this not a bizarre endgame? In a sharp position, White twice had a good reason for granting a tempo to his opponent  @@StartBracket@@2.Kf4! and 9.Kf3!!@@EndBracket@@, while Black’s best try also involved a loss of a tempo @@StartBracket@@7...Kd4!!@@EndBracket@@. }
