{ Capablanca – Tartakower, New York 1924  (analysis)   Goldin suggested the toughest defense, which is the text move! There was a lively analytical discussion on this subject in Russian chess magazines. }
2... a6
{ Diagram 9-241   Here, some blind alleys await White; for example,  3.g6?  b5  4.axb5  axb5  5.Kg5  b4  6.Rf7+  Kg8  is a draw. Igor Zaitsev found the most convincing solution: }
3. Kh5 b5 4. Kg6 Kg8 { Nor does  4...bxa4  5.Kxf5  a3  6.Rh6  save him. } 5.
Rg7+ Kf8 6. Rf7+ Kg8 7. Rf6
{ With the unstoppable threat of 8.Rxa6.   Had White exchanged pawns earlier on  b5  , his opponent could have parried the threat by @@StartFEN@@6k1/2p5/5RK1/1p1p1pP1/3P1P2/2r5/8/8 b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  8...b4  9.Ra6  Ra3!  10.Rc6  Rc3= }
