{ Capablanca – Tartakower, New York 1924  (continued) } 4... Re4
{ Diagram 9-242   4...Rxd4  5.Kf6  is also hopeless. } 5. Kf6
{ The f5-pawn is useful for the time being – it serves as an umbrella. } 5...
Kg8 6. Rg7+
{ Good endgame technique: prior to capturing the pawn, it is useful to worsen the position of the black king just a little. }
6... Kh8 7. Rxc7 Re8 8. Kxf5
{ It is time to eliminate the f5-pawn, otherwise it could move ahead  8.Kf7  Rd8  ∆ ...f4 ⇆. As we know, a knight pawn, unlike a bishop pawn, cannot be promoted against a passive defense with a rook on the back rank. }
8... Re4 9. Kf6 Rf4+ 10. Ke5 Rg4 11. g7+
{ This is where the zwischenschach on move six tells: White brings his pawn under the protection of the rook with a tempo  11...Rxg7  12.Rxg7  Kxg7  13.Kxd5  +- }
11... Kg8 12. Rxa7 Rg1 13. Kxd5 Rc1 14. Kd6 Rc2 15. d5 Rc1 16. Rc7 Ra1 17. Kc6
Rxa4 18. d6 { Black resigned. } *

