{ Gelfand − Wang Hao, London 2012    Black is not threatened by anything. He can calmly mark time, for example,  1...Ke8  or  1...Rh5  . }
1... f5+ 2. Ke5 Rxe3+ 3. Kf6
{ But now there is trouble. The unfortunate position of the king, trapped against the edge of the board, leads to the inevitable loss of the e6-pawn. }
3... Kg8 { 3...Ke8  4.Re7+  Kd8  5.Rxe6  +- } 4. Rg7+
{ 4.Rc8+  Kh7  5.Kf7  Ra3  6.Kxe6  won easily. And if @@StartFEN@@2R5/5K1k/4p3/5p2/3P1P2/4r3/8/8 b - - 5 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Re1  6.Rc3  Rh1  7.Kxe6  . }
4... Kf8 5. Rh7 Kg8 6. Rh1
{ It was necessary to return to the aforementioned plan by playing  6.Rg7+!  Kf8  7.Ra7  . }
6... Re4 7. Rd1
{ Diagram 9-245   The position is drawn, both after  7...Rxf4  , and the waiting move  7...Kf8  . But then there occurred an incomprehensible blunder – the Chinese grandmaster again forgot about the danger to his king on the edge. }
7... Kh7 8. Kf7 { Black resigned. } *

