{ Cutting the King Off   An important technique in rook-and-pawn endings is cutting the hostile king off from strategically important areas. From his own pawns that need protection, from our pawns that he could attack, from our passed pawn that could otherwise be stopped by him, or from his passed pawn that could be assisted by the king.  Janetschek – U. Geller, Skopje ol 1972 }
1. Rf2
{ Cutting the king off from the passed pawn, White considerably aggravates the threat of its advance.  Ed. note: continued → Diagram 9-247 EXTRA }
