{ Savon – Zheliandinov, Riga 1964     The actual continuation was  1...Rxh4?  2.Kc6  Rxe4  3.Kxd6  Kf8  4.Ra8+  Kg7  5.Ke7  +-  (the d-pawn will cost Black a rook)  5...Rd4  6.d6  e4   6...h4  7.d7  h3  8.d8=Q  Rxd8  9.Rxd8  h2  10.Rd1  a3  11.Rh1  a2  12.f3  ⨀  Kg8  13.Kf6  +-  7.d7  e3  8.fxe3  Re4+  9.Kd6  Rxe3  10.d8=Q  Rd3+  11.Ke5  Black resigned. Black should have cut the king off from the d6-pawn. }
1... Rc3 2. Rxa4 Rc5+
{ The pawn endgame that arises after  2...Kd7  3.Ra7+  Rc7?  @@StartBracket@@  3...Ke8!  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@8/R1rk1p2/3p2p1/1K1Pp1Pp/4P2P/8/5P2/8 w - - 3 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Rxc7+  Kxc7  5.Ka6  is lost. This evaluation is not quite obvious because Black has a chance for a pawn breakthrough:  ...f7-f6 and, after g5xf6, ...g6-g5. However, White wins the race that happens thereafter @@StartBracket@@doubters may check this fact for themselves@@EndBracket@@. But there is no sense in calculating sharp lines because we have a fortress after this check. The white king cannot cross the c-file. }
3. Kb6 Rc1 4. Ra8+ Kd7 5. Ra7+ Ke8 6. Rc7 Ra1 7. Kc6 Ra6+ 8. Kb7 Ra1 { Draw. }
