{ 9/29. Browne-Biyiasas, USA ch, Greenville 1980 } 1... Kc5
{ The way to a draw is to activate the king.   Another way, suggested by Benko, also exists:  1...Kc7!  2.Rh7+  Kc8  3.Kf6  b6  4.Re7  Rh2!  5.Ke6  Rh6+  @@StartBracket@@precisely the same defensive idea as inSavon-Zheliandinov, Diagram 9-248@@EndBracket@@.   Black played  1...Re3?  instead,  allowing  2.Rc8!  so that his king was locked in on the queenside: If  2...Rxb3  then  3.Ke6  is decisive. @@StartFEN@@2R5/1p6/1k1p4/p2P1K2/P1P5/1P2r3/8/8 b - - 2 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Re5+  3.Kf6  Re3  4.c5+!  dxc5  5.d6  Rd3  6.Ke7  Re3+  7.Kd8  Black resigned in view of  7...Rxb3  8.d7  Re3  9.Rc7  ∆ 10.Kc8 +-. }
2. Rh7 b6 3. Rc7+ { 3.Rb7  Re3 } 3... Kb4 4. Rc6 Kxb3 5. Rxb6+ Kxc4 { Draw. } *

