[SetUp "1"]

{ Akiba Rubinstein’s Masterpiece   As Tartakower wrote, “Rubinstein is a rook ending of a chess game that was started by God a thousand years ago.” I want to conclude the chapter on rook-and-pawn endings with an example from the creative work of the outstanding Polish grandmaster.  It is rumored that after the game finished  (the final stage of which we shall study)  Rubinstein’s respected opponent, grandmaster Spielmann, shouted: “Akiba, if you lived in the Middle Ages you would have been burned at the stake: what you do in rook endgames can only be called witchcraft!”   Spielmann – Rubinstein, St Petersburg 1909   A positional disadvantage that occurs often is an abundance of “pawn islands.”  White now has four islands against two; this means that White has more vulnerable pawns that cannot protect each other. Therefore his position is inferior. }
1... Ra8
{ The first stage of Black’s plan is to attack White’s pawns so that the white rook will be chained to their protection.   Chasing after material gain with  1...Rb3?  would have been a grave error, because after  2.Ra2  Rd3  3.a4  Rxd4  4.a5  Rc4  5.a6  , the white rook is actively placed behind a passed pawn while the black rook must stand passively on  a8  . }
2. Rc3
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed.  2.Ra2  is analyzed next → Diagram 9-251a@@EndSquare@@ }
2... Ra4 3. Rd3 Ke7 { The second stage: the king goes to the center. } 4. Kg3
{ 4.d5  is met not with  4...Kf6  5.Rf3+  , but with  4...g5!  5.Kg2  Kf6  6.Rf3+  Kg6  7.Rd3  f6  with the idea of ...Kf5, although White should not lose here either. }
4... Ke6 { Ed. note: continued in Diagram 9-251b. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 9 – Rook Endgames IV"]
[Black "Akiba Rubinstein's Masterpiece 9-251 a"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4k2/5pp1/3p2p1/8/3P4/P6P/2R2P1K/8 w - - 0 2"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Spielmann − Rubinstein, St Petersburg 1909  (analysis) } 2. Ra2
{ This is a passive placement for the rook. @@StartSquare@@Ed. perhaps not corrected from the previous 4th edition, as the line starting with 2.Ra2 seems to hold.@@EndSquare@@ }
2... Ra4 3. Kg3 Ke7
{ Not  3...Rxd4?  4.a4=  , but @@StartFEN@@5k2/5pp1/3p2p1/8/r2P4/P5KP/R4P2/8 b - - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g5  comes strongly into consideration as it fixes the weak white kingside pawns. }
4. Kf3 { 4.h4!  is more precise. } 4... Ke6 5. Ke4 g5 6. Ra1 f6 7. Ra2 f5+
{ Diagram 9-251a } 8. Ke3
{ An improvement over Levenfish and Smyslov’s  8.Kd3?  Kd5  9.Kc3  g6!  @@StartSquare@@Müller 2019@@EndSquare@@  10.Kb3  Rxd4  11.a4  Rh4  -+ }
8... Kd5 9. f3
{ White still has a difficult defense but should probably hold. After the move played, 2.Rc3 the rook’s position on the third rank offers counterchances that, however, Spielmann fails to exploit. }
*

