{ Spielmann − Rubinstein, St Petersburg 1909  (continued) } 7. Rb3
{ Diagram 9-254  Diagrams 9-252 and 9-253 have been intentionally omitted. }
7... f6
{ Another precise move!   After  7...Rxd4?  8.Rd3  , and in case of  7...Kxd4?  8.Rg3!   8.Rb7?  loses to  8...f6!  9.Rxg7  Rxa3  10.h4  gxh4  11.Rg4+  Kc3  12.Rxh4  Ra2+  and Kasparov correctly evaluated this as winning for Black.  8...Ra5  9.Rg4+!  Kc3  10.Rg3+  Kc2  11.f4  draws. The player fighting for a win should avoid pawn exchanges. Rubinstein’s move keeps White in a bind. }
8. Ke3
{ 8.Rb7?  can be met with  8...Rxa3  9.Rxg7  Rxh3  @@StartBracket@@Instead,  9...Kxd4  transposes to an above-mentioned variation which also wins.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@8/6R1/3p1p2/3k2p1/3P4/7r/4KP2/8 w - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Rg6  Ke6  11.Rg8  Rh4  12.Ke3  Kd5  , winning a second pawn and soon the game. }
8... Kc4 9. Rd3
{ 9.Rb7  Rxa3+  10.Ke4  d5+  11.Kf5  Rxh3  12.Rxg7  Rf3+  -+ is hopeless. }
9... d5
{ Black has improved his pawn structure and optimally placed his king. Now it is time for the rook. It has completed its mission on a4 and may find a new application for its talents. }
10. Kd2 Ra8 11. Kc2
{ 11.Ke2?  would lose quickly to  11...Rb8  12.Kd2  Rb2+  13.Ke3  Rb3!  or  13...Rxf2! }
11... Ra7 { Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 9-255 } *

