{ 10/2. Duz-Khotimirsky-Allakhverdian, Erevan 1938 } 1. g6
{ A good idea is to study White's alternatives and discover new positions where a rook and a pawn cannot beat a knight.   After  1.Rh6  Nf7!  2.Rh5!  , but not  2.Ra6?  Nxg5  3.Ra4  Kf3  4.Kc2  Ne6  5.Kc3  Ng5  the white king cannot come closer to the pawn. If White plays  6.Rc4  and directs the king around the rook along the fifth rank, Black brings his king to h4 and attacks the pawn in time. For example,  6...Kg3  7.Kb4  Kh4  8.Kc5  Nh3  9.Kd5  Nf2  10.Ke5  Kg5=   Another attempt can be  1.Rh1?  Kxg4  2.Rg1+  Kf5  3.Ke2  Ng6  4.Ke3  Nh4  5.Rg3  Ng6  6.Kd4  Nf4  7.Kc4  Diagram 16-91 Now the simplest defensive plan is to force the pawn advance to the seventh rank. The edge of the board will then be an obstacle to an invasion by the white king.  7...Ne6!?   A waiting policy is also good:  7...Ng6  8.Kd5  Nf4+  9.Kd6  Ng6  10.Rg1  Nh4!   In this line,  10...Nf4?  (instead of 10...Nh4!)  loses:  11.Ke7  Kg6  12.Rg3 !  Nh5  13.Rg4!  Ng7  14.Kd6!   14.Rg1 ?  Nf5+  15.Ke6  Nd4+  and 16...Nf3.  14...Kf5  15.Rg1  Nh5  16.Ke7  Kg6  17.Ke6  Nf4+  18.Ke5  +-  11.Ke7  Kg6  12.Ke6  Nf3 =  8.g6  Kf6  9.Rg4  Ng7  10.Kd5  Nf5  11.Kc5  Ne7!   Rather than  11...Ng7?  12.Kd6  Nf5+  13.Kd7  , or @@StartFEN@@8/8/5kP1/2K2n2/6R1/8/8/8 b - - 6 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Kg7?  12.Kc6!  Ne7+  13.Kd6  Nxg6  14.Ke6!  12.g7  Kf7  13.Rg5  Ng8  14.Kd5  Ne7+  15.Ke5  Ng8  and White cannot make any progress. }
1... Nxg6 2. Rh6
{ The game continued  2.Rg5?  Nf4  3.Rg8  Ne6!  (∆ ...Kf4, ...Ng5=)  4.Rg6  Nf4  5.Rg8  Ne6  Draw. }
2... Ne5 3. g5 Nf7 4. Rh5 { 4.Rg6?  Kg4= } 4... Ne5 { 4...Kg4  5.g6  +- } 5. g6
{ White wins.  Kromsky, Osanov } *

