{ de Firmian − Alburt, USA ch 1983  (continued) } 2... Kg7 3. Rb6
{ The immediate  3.Ra1  Kf6  @@StartBracket@@intending ...Ng7-e6@@EndBracket@@  4.Rh1  Ng7  5.Rh6+  followed by 6.Kd4 +- was also possible. }
3... Kh7
{ Diagram 10-7   After  3...Kf7  4.Rh6  Nf6  5.Kd4  Ng4  6.Ra6  Ke7  7.Kd5  Kf7  , we reach a position examined in 1941 by Reuben Fine. His analysis:  8.Kd6  Kf6  9.Ra8  Kf7  10.Rd8  ⨀  Kf6  11.Rf8+  Kg6  12.Ke6  Nh6  13.Rf6+  Kg7  14.Rxh6  , and if @@StartFEN@@5R2/8/4K1k1/5p2/5Pn1/8/8/8 b - - 20 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Ne3  13.Rf7  ⨀  Nc2  14.Rf6+  Kg7  15.Kxf5  +- }
4. Rb1
{ As Müller indicates, the immediate  4.Kd4!?  also wins:  4...Nxf4  5.Ke5  Ng6+   After  5...Nh5  6.Kxf5  Ng7+  we come to theAl’Adli position: see Diagram 10-1.  6.Kf6!  For example,  6...f4  7.Rb1  Nf8  8.Rd1!  ⨀   Rather than the hasty  8.Rh1+  Kg8  9.Rg1+  Kh7  10.Kf7?  in view of  10...Kh6!  11.Kxf8  Kh5=  8...Kg8  9.Rd8  , while after @@StartFEN@@5n2/7k/5K2/8/5p2/8/8/3R4 b - - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8...f3  , only now  9.Rh1+  Kg8  10.Rg1+  Kh7  11.Kf7  +- }
4... Kg6 5. Rh1 Nf6 { The same reply wins after  5...Ng7  or  5...Kh6  . } 6.
Kd4 Nd7 7. Kd5 Nf6+ 8. Ke5 { 8.Ke6! } 8... Nd7+ 9. Ke6 Nf8+
{ 9...Nc5+  @@StartSquare@@Ed. would have forced White to come back to the right plan with  10.Kd5  Nd7  11.Kd6  Nf6  12.Ke6!  reaching the position in the note on move 8.@@EndSquare@@ }
10. Ke7 { Black resigned. } *

