{ Larsen − Tal, Bled, cmsf  (7)  1965  The knight at e4 prevents the king's invasion of the kingside, but it will be vulnerable to attack by ...Ke6-e5. In this case, its place is on h5. In his detailed study of these kinds of positions, Averbakh showed that White can obtain a draw. }
1. Ng3 Ke6 { 1...Kg6  2.Ne4! } 2. Kf4 Ra4+ 3. Kf3 Ke5 4. Nh5 Ra8 5. Ke3
{ Bent Larsen is not afraid of a check along the third rank and brings his king to the center.   Here  5.Kg3?  would lose after  5...Rh8!  threatening  6.--  f5  . @@StartSquare@@Ed. in-depth analysis → Diagram 10-9 & 10-10@@EndSquare@@   5.Ng3  Ra3+  6.Kf2  Kf4  7.Nh5  Kg5  loses as well. On the next move Black will win the g-pawn by playing f6-f5.  Ed. note: the game continuation → Diagram 10-11 }
*

