{ Larsen − Tal, Bled, cmsf  (7)  1965  (analysis) } 1. Nf4
{ The best reply. Diagram 10-9  a. The computer gives the following complicated route to victory: }
1... Rh1
{ b. In home analysis, Tal studied the natural  6...Ke4  @@StartBracket@@After 5.Ke3!, this square is not available to the black king@@EndBracket@@. Alas, he was under the mistaken assumption that  7.Nh5!  is refuted by  7...f5  Actually, after  8.Nf6+  Ke5  9.Nd7+  White does save himself:  9...Ke6   9...Kd6  10.Nb6!  Rg8  11.Nc4+  10.Nc5+  Kd5  11.Nd3  Rg8  12.Nf2=  Black therefore has to return with the king, @@StartFEN@@7r/8/5p2/7N/4k1P1/6K1/8/8 b - - 3 2@@EndFEN@@  7...Ke5!  , then proceed as in line a.   Let me give a somewhat refined version of the variation found by Tal.  7.Nh3  Rd8!  (in some lines it is useful to deprive the white knight of the d1-square; Tal had considered the slightly less accurate 7...Rc8)  8.Nf2+  Ke3  9.Nh3   9.g5  f5  -+  9...Rd4  10.Nf2  Rd7 !  (why the rook takes up position on the seventh and not the eighth rank will soon become clear)  11.Nh3  Rg7  12.Nf2  f5  13.Nd1+  Ke2  14.Nf2  f4+  15.Kxf4  Kxf2  16.g5  Once again we have the same situation before us as in theRéti study. With the rook on g8 and Black to move, he would be in zugzwang and there would be no win. But here, Black gives the move to his opponent by  16...Rg8!  ⨀  17.Kg4  Kg2!  ⨀  18.Kf5  Kh3  -+ or  18.Kh5  Kf3  -+ }
2. Nd3+ Kd4
{ With the white king on e3, Black would have to pull back from the center. }
3. Nf4 Ke4 4. Nh5 Rf1 5. Kh4 { 10.Kg2  Rf3! } 5... Rf2
{ But not  10...Rf3?  11.g5!= } 6. Kg3 Rf3+ 7. Kh4 Ke5
{ Ed. note: analyzed further → Diagram 10-10 } *

