{ Larsen − Tal, Bled, cmsf  (7)  1965  (analysis) } 1. g5
{ Waiting tactics also do not help:  13.Ng3  Ra3  14.Nh5  Rb3  and White is in zugzwang. On  15.Ng3  , decisive is  15...Rb4!  16.Kh5   16.Nh5  f5  -+ and if  16.Nf5  Kf4  17.Kh5  Rb5!  -+ followed by the inevitable  18.--  Rxf5+  16...Rb8  17.Kg6   17.Kh4  Rh8+  18.Nh5  f5  -+ and  17.Nf5  Rg8  -+  17...Rg8+  18.Kh5  Rh8+  19.Kg6  Rh4  20.g5  Rg4  -+ And if @@StartFEN@@8/8/5p2/4k2N/6PK/1r6/8/8 w - - 4 3@@EndFEN@@  15.Ng7  then  15...Rb7  16.Nh5  Rh7  17.Kh3!?  f5  18.Kg3  Rh8!  19.Nf4   19.Kf3  f4  -+  19...Rg8  20.Nd3+  Ke4  21.Nf2+  Ke3  22.Nd1+  Kd3  23.Nf2+  Ke2  24.Kf4  (there is nothing else)  24...Kxf2  25.gxf5  Rf8  and White loses because of zugzwang, already familiar to us throughRéti’s study @@StartBracket@@*Diagram 8-10@@EndBracket@@. }
1... f5 2. g6 Ra3 3. g7 Ra4+ 4. Kg3
{ 16.Kg5  Rg4+  17.Kh6  Ke6  and  18.--  Kf7  -+. } 4... Rg4+ 5. Kf2 Ke6 6. Kf3
{ Zugzwang. } 6... Kf7 7. Ng3 Kf6 8. Nh5+ Ke6
{ Black gives his opponent the move, triangulating with the king. } 9. Nf4+ Kf7
10. Nh5 Rg5 { Black wins. } *

