{ Sturua – Yusupov, Baku jr 1979  (analysis)   When Artur Yusupov showed me this ending he had just played, I suggested that it made sense to keep the knight on h3 and the pawn on g4. Why? From h3, the knight not only impedes the approach of the black king, but is also prepared to hit the h7-pawn with Ng5. If Black advances that pawn to h6, then he will have to consider White’s possible g4-g5. After further detailed analysis, Yusupov showed that indeed, White can draw by retreating the knight. }
1. Nh3 { Intending Kh4, g4. } 1... Ra4+ { 1...Ke5  2.Kh5  or  2.Kg5  . } 2. Kh5
Ra3
{ 2...Kf5  3.Ng5  Ra1  4.g4+  Kf6!  is another try. Now  5.Nxh7+??  Kg7  6.Ng5  Rh1+  , or @@StartFEN@@8/7p/5k2/6NK/6P1/8/8/r7 w - - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nf3  Rh1+  6.Nh4  h6  ⨀ is bad; but  5.Nh3!  Rh1  6.Kh4  is sufficient. }
3. Kh4 Ke5 4. g4 Ra1
{ 4...h6  5.Nf2  or  5.Ng1  , but not  5.g5?  h5!  6.Ng1  Kf5! } 5. Kg3 h6
{ 5...Rh1  6.Kg2 } 6. Kh4 Rh1 { 6...Ke4  7.g5 } 7. Kg3 Kd4 8. g5
{ White has a good deal of leeway in these lines; the majority of moves are not “only” moves. On the other hand, after the game continuation, it is much more difficult to defend. Both Yusupov and I thought that in the game White’s position had become lost immediately, and this view was reflected in the first editions of the Endgame Manual. However a new computer examination demonstrated that in fact the draw was only missed much later.  Ed. note: the game continuation → Diagram 10-14 }
*

