Nd8
{ This is the little-noticed error! Also not good is  7.Nf4?  Kf3  8.Nh3  Re1  -+, while on  7.Nf8?  only  7...Rg5!  8.Ne6  Rg8!  leads to the win. The only correct knight retreat is @@StartFEN@@8/8/4N2p/4r3/4k2K/6P1/8/8 w - - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Ng7!!   For example,  7...Kf3  8.g4!  Re1  9.Kh5  Rh1+  10.Kg6  Kxg4  11.Ne8!=  or  7...Rg5  8.Nh5  Kf3  9.Nf6  Rg6  10.Nh7!!   10.Nh5  Rg4+  11.Kh3  Rd4  12.Nf6  Rd1  13.Kh2  Rd6  -+  10...Rxg3  11.Kh5  Rh3+  12.Kg6=  It goes without saying that it is practically impossible to find this kind of concept associated with the sacrifice @@StartBracket@@not the exchange@@EndBracket@@ of the last pawn over the board. }
7... Kf5
{ Black has achieved a great deal in driving the knight away from the pawn. Here, he could win by  7...Re7!?  @@StartBracket@@threatening 8...Kd5 and 9...Rd7@@EndBracket@@  8.Kh5!  Kf5   But not  8...Kd5?  9.Kg6=  9.g4+   9.Nc6  Re4  10.Nd8  Kf6  11.Kxh6  Re8  -+ or @@StartFEN@@3N4/8/5k1p/7K/4r3/6P1/8/8 w - - 9 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Nc6  Rc4  -+ does not change much.  9...Kf6!  10.Kxh6   10.Nc6  Re4  or  10...Re1  11.Kh4  Re4  -+  10...Rg7  11.Ne6  Rg8  12.Kh7  Rxg4  13.Nf8  Kf7  . On the other hand, the move played is no worse. }
8. Nc6
{ 8.Nf7  is met by  8...Rd5!   But not  8...Re1?  9.g4+!  Kf6  10.Nd6=  9.Kh5  Kf6+  and if  9.Nxh6+  Kg6  10.Ng4  Rh5#  , while after  10.Ng8  Rd7  -+ }
8... Re4+ 9. Kh5 Ke6
{ 9...Kf6  was simpler:  10.Kxh6  Rc4  11.Na5  Rg4  or  11...Rc1  12.Kh7  Rc5  , and if @@StartFEN@@8/8/2N2k1K/8/2r5/6P1/8/8 w - - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Nb8  Ke6  , intending  12.--  Kd6  , and the knight is caught.   Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 10-16 }
