{ 10/3. P. Benko, 1986  The white king has already invaded the black camp, therefore Black's idea is to attack the pawn rather than to create a fortress. He will even readily sacrifice his knight for the pawn. }
1. c4+
{ In case of  1.Rh4?  Nb2!  2.Kd7  c4  3.Kc7  Na4  4.Rh3  Nxc3!=  And if @@StartFEN@@8/3K4/8/3k4/2p4R/2P5/1n6/8 w - - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Rh5+  Ke4  4.Kc6  Black holds by means of  4...Nd1!  5.Rh3  Kf5!!  6.Kc5  Kg4  driving the rook back from the fourth rank. White should take this idea into consideration in all lines. }
1... Ke5 { Diagram 16-92 } 2. Rg4
{ The apparently natural  2.Rh4?  could, after  2...Nb2?  3.Kd7  Nxc4  4.Rxc4  Kd5  lead to the position from thefamous study by Réti  (Diagram 8-10)  , where White wins:  5.Rc3  or  5.Rc2!!  c4  6.Rc1!  Kc5  7.Kc7  ⨀ However, Black has an adequate defense: @@StartFEN@@8/4K3/8/2p1k3/2P4R/3n4/8/8 b - - 2 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Ne1 !  3.Kd7  Nf3  4.Rg4  Kf5= }
2... Nb2 { 2...Ne1  is already useless here:  3.Kd7  +- } 3. Rh4
{ Rather than  3.Kd7?  Kf5  4.Rh4  Kg5  5.Re4  Kf5= } 3... Nxc4
{ 3...Kf5  4.Kd6  +- } 4. Rxc4 Kd5 5. Rc1 c4 6. Kd7 Kc5 7. Kc7
{ Zugzwang.   7.Ke6?  Kd4!= } 7... Kb4 { 7...Kd4  8.Kb6 } 8. Kd6
{ White wins. } *

