{ Fridstein − Klaman, USSR ch tt, Riga 1954  White's plan is a routine and simple one: attack the f7-pawn; the king gets to e8 and then forces its way into f6. }
1. Rb8 { Zugzwang. } 1... Ng3 { 1...Kh7  2.Kf6 } 2. Kd6 Nf5+
{ 2...Nh5  does not help:  3.Rb4  Kf8  4.Kd7  wins by zugzwang. Note that  zugzwang is used again and again to bring home the advantage. }
3. Kd7 Kh7 4. Ke8 Kg8 5. Rd8
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed. White has other methods to win as well. For instance  5.Rb6  , stopping the check on  d6  and preparing Rb6-f6, is just as effective.@@EndSquare@@ }
5... Kg7 6. Rd7 Kg8 7. Rc7 { Zugzwang. } 7... Ng7+ 8. Ke7 Nf5+ 9. Kf6 Nd6 10.
Rc6 Ne4+ 11. Ke7 Kg7 12. Rf6 { Black resigned. } *

