{ Vidmar – Alekhine, San Remo 1930  (analysis)   Alekhine considered the position won based on the outcome of the game. Afterwards, however, safe defensive methods were discovered. One of these was proposed by Leykin in 1940. He held that White would do well to place his pawn at g4. Afterwards, his knight could combine threats against the enemy pawns with control over the access routes into his camp @@StartBracket@@the same strategy we saw in the preceding section@@EndBracket@@. }
1. Kh3
{ The best move, intending 2.g4. @@StartSquare@@Ed.  1.Nf2?!  was played in the game → Diagram 10-22@@EndSquare@@ }
1... Ke6
{ 1...Ra3  2.Kg4  Ke6  3.Kf4  g6  4.g4  , and if @@StartFEN@@8/6p1/4k2p/8/4NK1P/r4P2/6P1/8 b - - 5 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Kd5  4.h5  Kd4  5.Nd6  Kd3  6.Nf5  Ra4+  7.Kg3  Ra5  8.Kf4  Ra7  9.g4  Ke2  10.Kg3=    10...Ra3  is met by  11.Nd4+  or even by  11.Nh4  .  In the final position of this variation, the knight would be just as favorably posted, were it to stand anywhere in contact with the f4-square – on e6 or g2, for instance. }
2. g4 Ke5 3. Kg3 g6 { 3...Kd4  4.h5!  Ke3  5.Nd6= } 4. Nf2 Ra3
{ 4...Kd4  5.Nh3  Ke3  6.Nf4  and the knight occupies its ideal square – f4. }
5. Nh3 Ra4 6. Kf2
{ Here,  6.Nf2?  Kd4  7.Nh3  Ke3  is bad.  @@StartSquare@@Ed. White is in zugzwang and after for instance  8.Nf2  Ra1  9.Ne4  Rf1!  the position collapses. White should be ready to meet ...Ke5-d4 with Nh3-f4, in order to get counterplay against the g6-pawn.@@EndSquare@@ }
6... h5 { 6...Kd4  7.Nf4 } 7. gxh5 Rxh4 8. hxg6 { Draw. } *

