Kc7 6. h4 gxh4 7. gxh4 { ∆ Kf4 } 7... Ne7
{ Diagram 10-29   7...Nd6  8.Rf8!  The most precise way.  8...Nf5+  9.Rxf5!  and if @@StartFEN@@5R2/1pk5/3np3/3p3p/1p1P3P/1P2K3/8/8 b - - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Kd7  9.Kf4  Ke7  10.Rh8  Nf5  11.Ke5  Nxh4  12.Rh7+  Kd8  13.Kxe6  +-  Instead of 7...Nd6, the text move is better for Black – from here, the knight is ready to go not just to f5, but also to c6. This would force White to play the sharp 8.Kf4! allowing Black to capture White’s queenside pawns, e.g. }
8. Kf4 Nc6 { 8...Nf5  9.Ke5 } 9. Rh8 Nxd4 10. Rxh5 Nxb3 11. Rg5
{ Observe the resulting position. White has only one pawn, against four of Black’s; nevertheless, it is White who holds the advantage. The rook slings itself instantly from wing to wing, and can stop the enemy passed pawn in one move. The knight, on the other hand, is a short-stepping piece; even if it could get to the kingside, it would leave the b-pawn undefended.   @@StartSquare@@Ed. A possible continuation is  11...Nd4  12.h5  Nf5  13.Rg6  Kd6  14.h6  b3  15.h7  b2  16.Rg1  when the rook shows its strength by stopping the b-pawn while the h-pawn is about to promote.@@EndSquare@@ }
