{ H. Mattison, 1913   1.c7?  Rf8  2.Nd6  fails against  2...c4  . } 1. Ng5+ Kg6
{ Or  1...Kg8  . But  1...Kg7  2.c7  Rf8  3.Ne6+  is completely bad. If @@StartFEN@@8/7k/2P5/2p3Np/P6K/8/8/5r2 b - - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Kh8  or  1...Kh6  , then  2.c7  Rf8  3.Nf7+  and 4.Nd8. }
2. Ne6 Ra1
{ The a-file is the only way for the rook to reach the eighth rank. } 3. c7
{ White only gets a draw from  3.Nf4+?  Kf5  4.c7  Kxf4!  5.Kh3  Kf3  6.Kh2  Ra2+  7.Kh3  Ra1  . }
3... Rxa4+ 4. Nd4 Ra8
{ Either  4...Rxd4+  or  4...cxd4  lets the pawn queen.  Black's hope of creating a fortress with the rook on g4 is illusory: theory holds that such positions are won without difficulty. }
5. Nc6 { Threatening the interference 6.Nb8. } 5... Rc8
{ 5...Re8  fails to  6.Nd8  . } 6. Ne7+
{ @@StartBracket@@a fork@@EndBracket@@, followed by 7.Nxc8+-. } *

