{ 10/6. S. Tkachenko, N. Rezvov, 1997 } 1. d7
{ 1.Ne6+?  is wrong:  1...Ke3  2.d7  Ra4+  3.Kb7  Rb4+  4.Kc7  Rc4+  5.Kd6  Rc1  6.Nc5  Rd1+  7.Nd3  Kxe2= }
1... Ra4+ { 1...Rd4?  2.Ne6+ } 2. Kb7 Rb4+ 3. Kc6
{ 3.Kc7  is useless, as after  3...Rc4+  White must go back to the b-file @@StartBracket@@  4.Kd6?  Rd4+  @@EndBracket@@. }
3... Rb8 { 3...Rc4+?  4.Kb5  Rd4  5.Ne6+ } 4. Kc7 Ra8 5. Kb7 Rh8
{ Diagram 16-93   There is no other square on the 8th rank for the rook:  5...Rd8?  6.Ne6+  , or @@StartFEN@@r7/1K1P2N1/8/4p3/5k2/8/4P3/8 b - - 8 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Rg8?  6.Ne8  . }
6. e4
{ A difficult move to find!   Nothing can be gained by  6.Ne8?  Rh7  7.Kc6  Rxd7  8.Kxd7  Ke3= }
6... Kf3
{ The pawn cannot be captured in view of the knight fork:  6...Kxe4  7.Ne8  Rh7  8.Nf6+  .   If  6...Kg5  then  7.Ne8  Rh7  8.Kc6  Rxd7  9.Kxd7  Kf4  10.Nf6  or  10.Nd6  .   Finally,  6...Ke3  (∆ 7...Rd8)  fails to  7.Kc7  Ra8  8.Nf5+!  Kxe4  9.Nd6+  and 10.Nc8. }
7. Kc6 { 7.Kc7?  Ra8!  8.Nf5  Ra7+  9.Kc6  Rxd7 } 7... Rd8
{ If  7...Ra8  then  8.Nf5  Kxe4  9.Nd6+  ∆ Nc8. } 8. Ne6 Rxd7 9. Ng5+ Kg4 10.
Kxd7 Kxg5 11. Ke6 { 11.Kd6?  Kf6= } 11... Kf4 12. Kd5 { Zugzwang. } *

