{ Rook versus Bishop   The Lone Bishop  This chapter is dedicated solely to static situations, with all pawn on the same wing, in which the weaker side tries, successfully or not, to build a fortress.  In rook-versus-knight duels, precise positions which need to be remembered are rare. However, the case in question is characterized by frequent motifs of "elementary fortresses" which should be included in our endgame arsenal. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 11 – Rook versus Bishop"]
[Black "The Dangerous Corner 11-1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "6k1/1R6/6P1/7K/8/2b5/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ The Dangerous Corner   If there are no pawns on the board, a bishop can usually achieve an easy draw. Even squeezing the king to the edge of the board is not dangerous for the defender provided that  the king is driven to the safe corner @@StartBracket@@opposite to the bishop's color; the dangerous corner, on the contrary, is that of the bishop's color@@EndBracket@@.    When the king is imprisoned in the dangerous corner, the endgame is lost.   B. Horwitz, J. Kling, 1851  The g6-pawn is by no means a precious fighting unit for White. If it stood on g5, its value would have been much greater; here it only robs its own king of the important square g6. White should get rid of it. }
1. g7 Kh7
{ The capture  1...Bxg7  leads to an even more rapid finale:  2.Kg6  Be5  3.Re7  Bd6  4.Re8+  Bf8  5.Rd8  ⨀  But when similar events occur in the safe corner  (Kh8, Bg8)  , the final position @@StartFEN@@3R2bk/8/6K1/8/8/8/8/8 b - - 0 5@@EndFEN@@ is a stalemate rather than a zugzwang! }
2. Rf7
{ It is important to prevent the king's flight from the dangerous corner. }
2... Bd4 3. g8=Q+ Kxg8 4. Kg6
{ If there were no rook on f7, Black could hold by means of 4...Kf8. Now White intends @@StartFEN@@6k1/5R2/6K1/8/3b4/8/8/8 w - - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Rd7  ∆ 6.Rxd4 and 6.Rd8+. }
4... Bg1
{ The only defensive chance: the bishop hides in the 'shadow' of the white king. Unfortunately, the shadow is too short. }
5. Rf1 Bh2 6. Rf2 { 6.Rh1  Bg3  7.Rh3  Bf4  8.Ra3  Kf8  9.Rf3  is also good. }
6... Bg3 7. Rg2 Bd6 { 7...Bh4  8.Kh5+  and if  7...Be5  8.Re2  +- } 8. Rd2 Be7
9. Rc2
{ White wins.   @@StartSquare@@Ed. But not  9.Re2?  Kf8!  and Black escapes.@@EndSquare@@ }
*

