{ B. Guretzky − Cornitz, 1863 } 1. Kh6 Kg8
{ The winning technique after  1...Bd5  is already familiar to us:  2.Rd7  Be6  3.Rd8+  Bg8  4.Kg5  Kg7  5.Rd7+  Kh8  6.Kg6  Bb3  7.Rh7+!  Kg8  8.Rc7!  Kf8  9.Rg7  , and if @@StartFEN@@6k1/2R5/6K1/8/7P/1b6/8/8 b - - 15 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Kh8  9.h5  Bd5  10.Rh7+!  Kg8  11.Re7!  etc. }
2. Rg7+ Kf8
{ 2...Kh8  3.Re7!  White's forthcoming strategy can be described as follows: he creates the threat of the king retreat via h5 to g4 while his rook stands on g5 @@StartBracket@@this is why he should not advance the pawn to h5@@EndBracket@@. If he succeeds, then the black king will be cut off from the pawn. If the black bishop tries to prevent this, it will lose control over the b1-h7 diagonal and White wins à la Lequesne. And, if the black king comes to f6, then a check along the f-file can push him away from the pawn even farther.  Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 11-5 }
*

