{ B. Guretzky − Cornitz, 1863  (continued)   The following lines illustrate how this plan can be carried out. }
1. Rg5 Kf7 2. Rg3 { 4.Kh5  Bf3+ } 2... Bc2 3. Kh5
{ Diagram 11-5  An important position worth knowing. Black is in zugzwang. }
3... Kf6
{ 5...Ba4  or  5...Bd1+  6.Kg5  Bc2  7.Kf4  , and if @@StartFEN@@8/5k2/8/6K1/7P/6R1/8/3b4 b - - 7 4@@EndFEN@@  6...Kg7  7.Rc3!  +-   5...Bb1  6.Rg5!  (∆ 7.Kg4)  6...Kf6  7.Kg4  Bg6  8.h5  Bh7  9.h6  Bg6  10.Kf4  Bh7  11.Rg7  Bd3  12.Ra7  ∆ 13.h7 +- }
4. Rg5 { ∆ Kg4 } 4... Bd1+ { 6...Bf5  7.Kh6  Bc2  8.Rg2!  ∆ Rf2+. } 5. Kh6 Kf7
{ 7...Bf3  8.Rg1  ∆ Rf1. } 6. Rg7+ Kf6 { 8...Kf8  9.Kg6  ∆ Kf6. } 7. Rg1 Be2 8.
Rg2 Bd3 9. Rf2+ { White wins. } *

