[SetUp "1"]

{ Dolmatov – Georgadze, Erevan zt 1982    Dolmatov knew thedel Rio position and built his defense upon it. The game continued:  1...Rf3  2.Ke2  f4?!  3.Rxc2!  Re3+  4.Kd2  Bxc2  5.Kxc2  Re4  6.Kd3  f3  7.Be3  Rxh4  8.Bf2  Rf4  9.Ke3  Rf7  10.Bg3  Ka6  11.Kf2  Kxa5  12.Be5  , and White achieved a draw.  Georgadze did not exploit his chances fully. It is obvious that Black has no other plan than ...Rf3 and ...f5-f4, only he had to carry it out after first bringing his king to a6. }
1... Ka7 2. Ke2 Ka6 3. Kd2
{ 3.Kf2?  f4  and @@StartFEN@@8/8/k7/P1R2pB1/4b2P/7r/2p1K3/8 w - - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Ke1?  Rh2  . }
3... Rf3
{ White would now hold after  4.Rc3!  Rf1  5.Ke2!  Rh1  6.Rc5  . The idea of the exchange sacrifice, successfully implemented in the game does not work here since Black’s having an extra tempo decisively impacts the evaluation of the position. }
4. Ke2 f4 5. Rxc2 Re3+ 6. Kd2 Bxc2 7. Kxc2 Re2+ 8. Kd1 { 8.Kd3?  f3  -+ } 8...
f3 9. Bf4
{ 9.h5?  Re4!  and @@StartFEN@@8/8/k7/P5B1/7P/5p2/4r3/3K4 w - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Bd8?  Re3!  , while after  9.Bd2?  Re8  10.Be1  Rd8+  -+ }
9... Kxa5 10. h5 Kb5
{ Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 11-13 } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 11 – Rook versus Bishop"]
[Black "A Bishop Pawn 11-13"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/8/8/1k5P/5B2/5p2/4r3/3K4 w - - 0 11"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Dolmatov − Georgadze, Erevan zt 1982  (continued) } 11. h6 Re8
{ Threatening  12.--  f2  . The tempting @@StartFEN@@8/8/7P/1k6/5B2/5p2/4r3/3K4 b - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Kc4?  allows White to transpose to the del Rio position with  12.h7  Re8  13.Be3!!   But not  13.h8=Q?  Rxh8  14.Ke1  Kd3  15.Kf2  Ke4  16.Bc7  Rh6!  Black does not let the bishop get to the key g1-a7 diagonal and eventually wins.  13...Kd3  14.Bb6  Rh8  15.Ke1= }
12. Bg3 { And only now: } 12... Kc4 13. h7 Kd3
{ A theoretical fortress now cannot be created in view of the unfavorable position of the bishop @@StartBracket@@bad is  14.Bf2  Ra8  @@EndBracket@@. The game could continue: }
14. Bh4 Rh8 15. Ke1 Rxh7 16. Bd8 Rb7 17. Kf2 Ke4 18. Bf6 Rc7 19. Bg5 Rc2+ 20.
Kf1 f2 21. Kg2 Kd3 22. Kf1 Ra2 23. Bh4 { 23.Bh6  Ke4  24.Kg2  Ra6  -+ } 23...
Ke3 24. Kg2 Rc2 { One more zugzwang. } 25. Bg3 f1=Q+ 26. Kxf1 Kf3
{ Dvoretsky.  This sort of  a rook’s domination over a bishop  is typical for many endings with an extra exchange. We have already seen it in some examples and exercises and will see more of it in the future. }
*

