{ Chances of salvation can result from either  an active defense   (an attack against the hostile pawn by the bishop or king)  , or  building a barrier  that prevents an invasion of the hostile king @@StartBracket@@squares of one color are controlled by the bishop, squares of the other color − by the pawn@@EndBracket@@.  Rubinstein − Tartakower, Vienna 1922  Black must protect his pawn with the king, bring the rook to the fifth rank, and finally move his king ahead again by going around the rook. This plan has no alternatives, but is not sufficient for a win. }
1... Kd4 2. Bd2 Ke5 3. Be3 Kf6 4. Bd4+ Kg6 5. Be3
{ White continues to keep the pawn in the crosshairs.   Another equally good defensive method consists in building a barrier:  5.Be5  Rc8  6.Bg3= }
5... Rb8 6. Bd2 Rb5 7. Ke4 Kf6 8. Bc3+ Ke6 9. Bd2 Kd6
{ 9...Re5+  10.Kf3  Kd5  11.Bc3  Re6  12.Bd2= } 10. Be3 Kc6 11. Bd2 Kb6 12.
Be3+ Ka5 13. Bd2+ Ka4
