{ N. Elkies, 1993  Keres evaluated the diagrammed position as drawn, and numerous authors reproduced this judgment. Yet Noam Elkies, an American mathematician and endgame study composer, discovered a subtle winning method many years later.  Its idea can be briefly described as follows: the king retreats to g4, the rook goes to b5 or d5, denying the bishop important squares. Thereafter, depending on the bishop’s position, the white king breaks through to f6 or h6, while if the bishop is on f8 or g7, the advance g5-g6 is very strong. }
1. Rb3
{ Also possible is  1.Kg4  Bc1!?  2.Kf5  h6?  3.Kg6!  and in case of @@StartFEN@@6k1/1R5p/8/5KP1/8/8/8/2b5 b - - 3 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Bd2  3.Rb2  Be3  4.Rb3  Bd4  5.Rd3  +- If White goes  3.Rb3  , instead of 3.Rb2, Black has  3...Kg7  . }
1... Bd6
{ 1...Bf8  loses rapidly:  2.Rb8  Kg7  3.Rb7+  Kg8  4.g6  . And if @@StartFEN@@6k1/7p/8/6PK/8/bR6/8/8 b - - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Bc5  2.Kg4  Bd6  then  3.Rb5  Bc7  4.Rd5!  and the king is ready for a march. }
2. Kg4 Bf8
{ 2...Bc5  is met with  3.Rb5!  and the bishop cannot prevent an invasion by the king. For example:  3...Bd4  4.Kh5  (∆ Rb8+, Rb7+, Kh6)  4...Bg7  5.g6  h6  6.Rb8+  Bf8  7.Rxf8+  Kxf8  8.Kxh6  +-   Or  3...Ba3  4.Kf5  (∆ 5.Kf6,)  and if @@StartFEN@@6k1/7p/8/1Rb3P1/6K1/8/8/8 b - - 5 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bd6  4.Kf5  Bc7  5.Rd5!  Bb6   5...Bg3  6.Rd8+  Kg7  7.Rd7+  and 8.Kf6.  6.Kf6  Bc7  7.Rd7  Ba5  8.Rg7+!  Kh8  9.Kf7  .   Or  3...Bf8  4.Kf5  h6  , here White has   4...Bg7  5.g6!  h6  6.Rb8+  Bf8  7.Kf6  , and if  4...Be7  5.g6  +-  5.gxh6  Kh7  6.Rb6  Bxh6  7.Rb7+  is also good. Or  5.g6  Be7  6.Rb8+  Kg7  7.Rb7  , while after  5...Bd6  6.Kf6  +-  Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 11-25 }
*

