{ N. Elkies, 1993  (continued) } 1. Kf5
{ Less precise is  3.Rb5?!  because of  3...h6!?  4.g6  Bd6  5.Kf5  Bg3!  Black saves himself if the bishop can get to the c1-h6 diagonal, for example,  6.Ra5?  Bh4  7.Ra8+  Kg7  8.Ra7+  Kg8  9.g7  Kh7  10.Ke6  Kg8=  Nor does @@StartFEN@@8/R5Pk/7p/5K2/7b/8/8/8 w - - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  10.Rf7  Bg5  11.g8=Q+  Kxg8  12.Kg6  Bd2  13.Rd7  Bg5  achieve anything.   The bishop's access to the necessary squares is prevented by  6.Rb4!  Bc7  7.Rd4  Ba5  8.Kg4  Bb6  9.Rd3  and there is no satisfactory defense to the threat of 10.Kh5. }
1... Bc5 2. Rd3 Bb4
{ If  4...Be7  then  5.Rc3!  Bb4  6.Rc8+  Kf7  7.Rc7+  Kg8  8.Kf6  , and in case of @@StartFEN@@8/2R2k1p/8/5KP1/1b6/8/8/8 b - - 9 5@@EndFEN@@  7...Be7  8.Kg4  and Kh5-h6 is irresistible. }
3. Kf6 Ba5 4. Rb3 Bd8+ { 6...Bc7  7.Rb5  Bd8+  8.Ke6!  Kg7  9.Kd7 } 5. Kf5 Ba5
{ 7...Bc7  8.Rb5 } 6. Kg4 Bc7 7. Rb5 Bd6 8. Kf5 Bc7 9. Rd5 { White wins. } *

