{ 11/5. Stoliar-Bobotsov, Albena 1973 } 1... Bg3
{ Also possible is  1...Bh4  .   The position after  1...Be3?  2.Re2  f4  like all similar situations with the pawn on a square of the bishop's color, is lost. The game continuation  1...Bg1?  is also incorrect:  2.Re2+  Kd6  3.f4!  ∆ 4.Kd3, 5.Re5. And in case of @@StartFEN@@8/8/4k3/5p2/2K5/5P2/4R3/6b1 b - - 2 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Kf6  3.Kd5  Ba7  4.Re8!  Bf2  5.f4!  Black resigned. }
2. Re2+
{ Timman has shown that  2...Kd6!  3.Kd4  Bf4  is also sufficient to hold the draw. Or  3...Bh4  ∆ ...Bf6+. However, White can just transpose moves and force the king to retreat to f6: @@StartFEN@@8/8/4k3/5p2/2K5/5Pb1/R7/8 w - - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Kd4!?  Be5+  3.Kc5  Bd6+  4.Kc6  ∆ 5.Re2+ @@StartBracket@@Müller@@EndBracket@@. }
2... Kf6 3. Rg2 Bc7 4. Kd5 Bb8 5. Rg8 { Diagram 16-94 } 5... Bh2
{ Black's last move was given by Pfrommer. Timman had examined  5...Bc7?  6.Rf8+  Kg5  7.Ke6  Kf4  8.Rf7!   Rather than  8.Rxf5+?  Ke3  9.Rc5  Bg3!  10.Rc3+  Kf4  11.Kd5  Bf2  ∆ Be3=  8...Bb8  9.Rb7  , and if  8...Bb6  9.Rxf5+  Ke3  10.Rf7  ∆ 11.f4 +- }
6. Rf8+ { 6.Rh8  Bg3! } 6... Kg5 7. Ke6 Kf4 8. Rxf5+ Ke3 { ∆  9.--  Bf4  . } *

