{ 11/6. Moiseev-Botvinnik, USSR ch, Moscow 1952  Black’s position is won. The challenge is to find the clearest and most convincing way to bring it home. }
1... Rc7
{ Zugzwang.   If  1...Rc3+  , now not  2.Kf2  Kf4  -+, but @@StartFEN@@8/8/4B3/6k1/7p/2r2K2/6P1/8 w - - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Ke4!  Rg3  3.Bh3  and Black is in zugzwang. The solution will be clear if we realize that the zugzwang is reciprocal. }
2. Bh3
{ 2.Ke4  Re7  3.Ke5  Re8  ⨀ is also bad. The remainder of the game was @@StartFEN@@8/2r5/4B3/6k1/7p/5K2/6P1/8 w - - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.g4  Rc3+  3.Kg2  h3+  4.Kh2  Kh4  5.g5  Rc2+  and White resigned. }
2... Rc3+ 3. Ke4 Rg3 { Zugzwang. } 4. Ke5 Re3+
{ The black king takes the key f4-square under control, invades on g3, and an exchange sacrifice decides. }
