{ Rook Pawns   Positions with rook pawns are quite difficult; even top grandmasters cannot avoid errors when playing them. Nevertheless, knowledge of their basic ideas makes certain practical sense.   J. Enevoldsen, 1949  This is perhaps the most favorable situation for the stronger side. The pawn has crossed the middle line and the black king is in the dangerous corner. White forces ...h7-h6, then drives the black king farther away and cuts it off along a file. Finally White comes back to the pawn with his king and sacrifices his rook for the bishop.   However, there is an important caveat. This plan is only feasible because the black king is cut off on the eighth rank. If the king is on g7, the position is drawn. White cannot force the king to the edge of the board, carry out h5-h6 or force his opponent to play h7-h6. }
1... h6
{ Black cannot do without this move.   On  1...Bd2  there could follow  2.Kf6  Bc3+  3.Kf5  Bd2  4.Rd7  Bc1  5.Rd1  Be3  6.Kf6  +- }
2. Kf5 Bd2 3. Kg6 Kf8 4. Rf7+ Ke8
{ If Black keeps his king in the corner he is put into zugzwang very quickly:  4...Kg8  5.Rf3  Bg5  6.Rf2  ⨀  Be3  7.Re2  +- }
5. Rf2 Bg5 6. Kg7 Ke7 7. Re2+ Kd7 8. Kf7 Kd6 9. Re4 { Zugzwang again. } 9...
Bc1 10. Re6+ Kd5 11. Kf6 Bd2 12. Kf5 Bg5 13. Rg6
{ ∆ 14.Rxg5  Ed. note: Continues in → Diagram 11-28 EXTRA } *

