{ Salwe – Rubinstein, Prague 1908  (analysis)   Rubinstein carried out the same plan of driving the king off from the pawn that we have seen in the previous example, and was successful with it. However it was later proven that White could have held the position with a precise defense.  Maizelis found the answer to this endgame puzzle in 1963. It turned out that Black should not drive the white king away from the corner. On the contrary, Black should imprison the white king in the corner, with the idea of putting White in zugzwang. Let us study the analysis by Maizelis. }
1... Kd3
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed.  1...Rf7  was played in the game → Diagram 11-32@@EndSquare@@ }
2. Bf4 Ke2 3. Bg5 Rf3+ 4. Kg2 Ra3 5. Be7 Ra4 6. Bd8 Rg4+ 7. Kh3 Kf3 8. Bc7 Rg1
{ Ed. note: analyzed in the next variation → Diagram 11-30 } *

