{ Salwe – Rubinstein, Prague 1908  Now let us look at what actually happened in the game. }
1... Rf7 2. Bh6 Rf3+ 3. Kg2 Rd3 { 3...Rf7!  ∆ Kd3 -+ } 4. Bg5 { 4.Kf2! } 4...
Kf5
{ He had to move the rook back:  4...Rf3!  Now the white king breaks loose and the position becomes drawn. }
5. Kf2 Kg4 6. Ke2 Rf3 7. Bh6 Kg3 8. Bg5 Rf8 9. Ke3 Re8+ 10. Kd3 Kf3 11. Kd4 Re6
{ Diagram 11-32   11...Re4+  12.Kd3  Rg4  13.Kd2  Kg3  14.Ke1  , White defended against the exchange sacrifice in time. }
12. Kd5
{ The decisive error! As Baranov proved in 1954, White should not be afraid of having his king driven back one more file.   Therefore he had to play  12.Kd3!  Rd6+  13.Kc3  . Subsequent attempts to drive it back will not succeed if White simply avoids placing the kings on the same rank. After  13...Rd7  , both  14.Kc2  and  14.Kc4  are possible. For example,  14.Kc2  there follows  14...Ke2  15.Kc3  Rd3+  16.Kc4!  , rather than  16.Kc2?  Rg3  17.Kb2  Kd1!   Or @@StartFEN@@8/3r4/8/6Bp/7P/2K2k2/8/8 w - - 25 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Kc4  , then  14...Ke4   14...Kg3  15.Kc3  Rd1  16.Bf6  Rh1  17.Kd2  Rxh4  18.Bxh4+  Kxh4  19.Ke2  Kg3  20.Kf1=  15.Kc3  Rd3+  and now  16.Kc2!=  , rather than  16.Kc4?  Rg3  17.Bf6   17.Kb4  Rxg5!  18.hxg5  Kf5  -+  17...Rg6  18.Be7  Rc6+  -+ }
12... Re4 13. Bf6 Kf4 14. Bd8 Kf5 15. Bg5 Rg4 { ∆ ...Rxg5 } 16. Be7 Rg7 17. Bf8
Rd7+ 18. Kc6 { 18.Kc4  Kg4 } 18... Rd4
{ A simpler way was  18...Rf7!  followed by 19...Kg4. } 19. Be7 Ke6
{ 19...Kg4  20.Kc5  Rd3  21.Kc4  Rh3  22.Kd4  Rxh4  23.Ke3  Rh2  -+ } 20. Kc5
Rd5+ 21. Kc4 Rf5 22. Bd8 Kd7 23. Bb6 { 23.Bg5  Rxg5 } 23... Rf4+ 24. Kd3 Rxh4
{ The outcome seems to be clear after the loss of the pawn, but both sides err in the remainder of the game. }
25. Ke2 Ke6 26. Kf3 Rg4 27. Bf2 Kf5 28. Bg3 h4 29. Bh2
{ Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 11-33 } *

