{ Diagram 11-38  (analysis)    Let us check another method of exploiting the same idea: a frontal rook attack against the g6-pawn. }
1. Kd5 Bf6 2. Ke4 Bc3 3. Kf4 Bf6 4. g4 hxg4 5. Kxg4 Be5 6. h3 Bf6 7. Kf4 Kf8 8.
Ke4 Kg8 9. Kd5 Ba1 10. Ke6 Bc3 11. Rc7 Bb2 12. h4 Bd4 13. Rc4
{ Diagram 11-40   A key moment; this position @@StartBracket@@with reversed colors@@EndBracket@@ happened in a grandmaster duel at a 1987 tournament in New York. Ftacnik played against Murey as follows:  13...Bb2?  14.Rg4  Kh7  15.Kf7  and White won @@StartBracket@@see the line 1.h4 Bd4?@@EndBracket@@.   13...Bf2?  14.Kf6  Kh7  15.Rg4  Kh6  16.Rxg6+  Kh5  17.Rg2  +- is no better. Black should have played: }
13... Be3 14. Kf6 { 14.Re4  Bd2  15.Re2  Bc3= } 14... Kh7 15. Rg4 Kh6 16. Rxg6+
Kh5 17. Rg3 Bb6 18. Rh3 Kg4 19. Rh1 Bd8+
{ With a draw. @@StartSquare@@Ed. kindly see the first 13 moves  (before the key moment that was trained)  , for the full overview of Black's defensive ideas.@@EndSquare@@ }
