[SetUp "1"]

{ Khalifman – Leko, Budapest m  (3)  , 2000  This pawn structure has occurred many times in practice and, until recently, was always evaluated as drawn. In fact, White wins by means of h4-h5, transposing to theElkies position  (Diagram 11-24)  , although everything is not so simple – there are many subtle points in this ending. }
1... Bg7
{ Leko is trying to oppose White’s plan. If  2.Kg4?  , then  2...h5+!  3.Kf4  Bb2  or  3.gxh6  Bxh6  with an obvious draw. @@StartFEN@@6k1/3R3p/6p1/6P1/7P/5K2/1b6/8 b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Bc1  , with the same idea, is worse on account of  2.Rd1  Bb2  3.Rd8+  Kg7  4.Rd7+  Kg8  5.Kg4  . }
2. Kf4
{ This is not a bad move, however the most direct way to a victory starts with  2.Rd8+!?  @@StartSquare@@Ed. analyzed in Diagram 11-42@@EndSquare@@ }
2... Bf8
{ If  2...Kf8  , then  3.Rd8+!  Kf7  4.Rb8  +-   2...Bb2  is met by  3.Kg4  . Now  3...Bg7?  only accelerates the loss:  4.h5  gxh5+  5.Kxh5  Kf8   5...Bc3  6.Kh6  and  5...Bf8  6.g6  +-  6.Rb7  ⨀  Kg8  7.g6  . On @@StartFEN@@6k1/3R3p/6p1/6P1/6KP/8/1b6/8 b - - 4 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc3  , White can play  4.h5  right away, but let us look at a somewhat abstract move,  4.Rc7  , that leads to a position from Wolff-Browne, USA ch, Durango 1992. @@StartSquare@@Ed. 4.Rc7 is analyzed inDiagram 11-43@@EndSquare@@ }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 11 – Rook versus Bishop"]
[Black "Two Pawns vs. Two on the Same Wing 11-42"]
[Result "*"]
