[White "Chapter 11 – Rook versus Bishop"]
[Black "Two Pawns vs. Two on the Same Wing 11-43"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "6k1/3R3p/6p1/6P1/6KP/2b5/8/8 w - - 0 4"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Khalifman − Leko, Budapest m  (3)  , 2000  (analysis)   @@StartSquare@@Ed. continued from Diagram 11-41@@EndSquare@@ }
4. Rc7
{ Diagram 11-43   Where should the bishop go? We know from the previous note that  4...Bg7?  5.h5  is bad; @@StartFEN@@6k1/2R4p/6p1/6P1/6KP/2b5/8/8 b - - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bd4?  5.h5  gxh5+  6.Kxh5  @@StartBracket@@∆ 7.Kh6@@EndBracket@@ is no better, because the bishop fails to enter the a3-f8 diagonal.   The toughest resistance can be rendered by  4...Bb2  5.h5  gxh5+  6.Kxh5  Ba3  , and White has to demonstrate a truly complicated winning procedure that, by the way, had not yet been discovered when the game was played. Browne played: }
4... Be5
{ And Wolff managed to carry out h4-h5 in a more favorable situation, avoiding the Elkies position. The main motif is making the access of the bishop to the a3-f8 diagonal most difficult. }
5. Rc6 Bb2 6. Ra6 Bc3 { 6...Bd4  7.Ra5  Bc3  8.Ra4  does not change anything. }
7. Ra4 Be5 { 7...Bg7  8.Ra8+  Kf7  9.Ra7+  Kg8  10.h5  +- } 8. h5 gxh5+
{ In the game, Black allowed h5-h6 and, of course, lost rapidly:  8...Bc3  9.h6  Kf7  10.Rc4  Be5  11.Kf3  Bd6  12.Rc8  Ke6  13.Rh8  Kf5  14.Rxh7  Kxg5  15.Rd7  Black resigned. }
9. Kxh5 Bd6
{ The bishop has finally managed to reach the key diagonal, but it stands badly on d6. White carries g5-g6 out while the black king’s refuge in the dangerous corner fails. }
10. Ra8+ Kg7 11. Ra7+ Kg8 12. g6 hxg6+ 13. Kxg6 Kf8 14. Kf6
{ Here the bad placement of the bishop tells: after  14...Ke8  , White plays  15.Ke6  with a tempo. }
14... Kg8 15. Rg7+ Kh8 { 15...Kf8  16.Rd7  +- } 16. Kg6 { White wins. } *

