{ Khalifman – Leko, Budapest m  (3)  , 2000  (continued) } 3. h5
{ White advances the pawn at the most inappropriate moment.   The simplest solution was  3.Ra7!?  Bg7  4.Rb7!  Bf8  5.Kg4  h5+  6.Kf3  +- @@StartBracket@@seeDiagram 11-42. As Shipov noted, the immediate  3.Kg4  also wins, but after  3...h5+  White should play  4.Kf3!  Bb4   4...Bg7  5.Rxg7+  and if  4...Ba3  5.Rb7  Bd6  6.Rb6  +-  5.Rc7!  @@StartBracket@@preventing 5...Bc3@@EndBracket@@  5...Be1  6.Rc4  Kf7  7.Ke2  ∆ Kd3, Re4, Kc4-d5 +- rather than @@StartFEN@@5bk1/3R4/6p1/6Pp/6KP/8/8/8 w - - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Kf4?  Ba3  @@StartBracket@@∆ 5...Bb2=@@EndBracket@@  5.Rb7  Bd6+  6.Ke4  Bg3  7.Rb3  Bxh4  8.Kf4  Kf7  9.Rb7+  Kg8= }
3... gxh5 4. Kg3 h6 5. g6 Ba3 6. Kh4 Bc1
{ As we know fromElkies’ analysis, this position is drawn. } 7. Kxh5 Bg5 8. Kg4
Bc1 9. Kf5 Bg5 10. Ke6
{ 10.g7  Kh7  11.Ke6  Kg8=   Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 11-45 }
