{ 11/7. A Theoretical Position   This example can be found in many theoretical treatises, given with a wrong or, at least, an imprecise evaluation. }
1. b4
{ 1...a5=  should be prevented. Now this move loses a pawn:  2.bxa5  bxa5  3.Kc5  a4  4.Kb6  Kc8  5.Rg4  +-   1...Bf3  2.a4  Be4  3.a5  bxa5  4.bxa5  is also hopeless for Black @@StartBracket@@seeDiagram 11-28@@EndBracket@@.   Another continutation  1.Rg4!?  also deserves attention:  1...Bb1  2.Kc6!  Bxa2  3.Rg7  +- and after @@StartFEN@@1k6/p7/1p1K4/8/4b1R1/8/PP6/8 b - - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Bf3  2.Rf4  and if  2...Bg2  then  3.b4  planning a2-a4-a5. }
1... Bc2
{ If Black manages to place his bishop on a4, he achieves a draw. The same outcome results from  2.Kc6  Be4+  3.Kb5  Bd3+  4.Ka4  Bc2+  5.Ka3?  a6!=  @@StartBracket@@see*Diagram 11-47@@EndBracket@@. This means that White's next move is obligatory. }
2. b5 Be4 3. a4 Bd3 { 3...Bf3  is equivalent. } 4. Kd5 Bf5
{ Diagram 16-95  The diagrammed position is known from Ljubojevic-Keene, Palma de Mallorca 1972 @@StartBracket@@with reversed colors and wings@@EndBracket@@. Books on theory say it is a draw. We know from theKhalifman-Leko ending that this is not so. The winning plan is simple: White brings his king to b4 and plays a4-a5, arriving at theElkies position, so the most rapid progress can be achieved after: }
5. Kc4
{ The players and the annotators ignored this plan because they did not know that the Elkies position is winning.   Keene tried to invade with his king to  c6  , failed to do so, and a draw was agreed.  5.Rg5  Bd3  6.Rg3  Bc2  7.Rg2   7.Re3?  Bxa4!  8.Kc6  a6  9.Kxb6  Bxb5=  7...Bd3  8.Rf2   8.Rd2  Bg6!  9.Re2  Bh5  10.Rf2  Kc7!  11.Rf6  Be8!  12.Rf5  Bg6  8...Kb7  9.Rf7+  Kb8  10.Re7  Bf1  11.Re8+  Kb7  12.Re7+  draw. After  12...Kb8  White still could have played  13.Re1!+  Bd3?  14.Kc6  , and if  13...Bg2  14.Kc4  +- }
*

