{ Three Pawns vs. Three on the Same Wing   With three pawns on each side, a fortress, as a rule, cannot be built. Salvation is possible only in exceptional cases, when the pawn structure of the stronger side has flaws.  Radev − Pribyl, Tbilisi 1971  This situation resemblesDiagram 11-38, only the f-pawns are added. It again seems as if White cannot overcome the barrier, but in fact he can by means of a spectacular pawn breakthrough.  Two years later, a similar endgame occurred in a game Kholmov-Tseshkovsky, USSR chsf 1973. Grandmaster Kholmov wrote a detailed analysis, which was published in a periodical, and I reproduce it here in a slightly abridged and corrected form. }
1. Kc4 Kf8 2. Kd5 Kg8 3. Ke6 Bc3 4. Rd3 Bb2 5. g4
{ White has a decisive advantage.  Ed. note: In the book, the information presented in this example is considered essential. The game continuation is given in the next variation but does not have to be committed to memory. }
*

