[SetUp "1"]

{ Radev − Pribyl, Tbilisi 1971  (continued)     The game continued  5...hxg4?!  6.h5  Kg7   Or  6...gxh5  7.Kxf5  Bc1  8.Kg6  Kf8  9.f5  , and if  7...Kg7  8.Rd7+  Kg8  9.Kg6  , or @@StartFEN@@8/3R2k1/8/5K1p/5Pp1/8/1b6/8 b - - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  8...Kf8  9.Rh7  . After  8...Kh6  9.Rd6+  Kh7   9...Kg7  10.Rg6+  Kh7  11.Kg5  Bc1  12.Rh6+  Kg7  13.Rxh5  g3  14.Rh3  10.Kg5  Bc1  11.Rd7+  Kg8  12.Kg6  Kf8  13.f5  g3  14.f6  +-  7.hxg6  Kxg6  8.Rd5  Bc1  Black still follows the path of least resistance.   However a rapid finale also occurs after  8...Kh5  9.Kxf5  Kh4   9...g3  10.Rd1  10.Rd6!  Bc1   10...Kh3  11.Rh6+  Kg3  12.Rg6  11.Rg6  +-  9.Rxf5  Bxf4  10.Rxf4  Kg5  11.Ke5  g3  12.Ke4  g2  13.Rf8  Kh4  14.Rg8  Black resigned. Instead of 9...Bxf4,  9...Kh6  wouldn't have helped either:  10.Ke5  ∆ Rg5. }
1... fxg4 { The text move is more stubborn. } 2. f5 gxf5 3. Kxf5 { ∆ 8.Kg6 }
3... Kf7 4. Kg5
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed. the alternative  8.Rd7+  is illustrated next → Diagram 11-53@@EndSquare@@ }
4... Be5 5. Kxh5 g3 6. Rd2 Kf6 7. Kg4 Kg6 8. Re2 Bb8 9. h5+ Kh6 10. Re6+ Kh7
11. Rg6 Bc7 12. Kf5 Bb8
{ Kholmov proceeds with  17.h6  and demonstrates a win after 10 more moves. }
13. Rb6
{ But this wins immediately.  If the pawns are still not in contact  (for example, Black's pawns f7, g6, and h5; White's pawns on their initial squares)  , the winning procedure is easier.  If Black has a white-square bishop that protects the f7-pawn, White comes with his king to e7, places the rook on f6, and advances the pawns @@StartBracket@@h2-h3, g2-g4, f2-f4-f5@@EndBracket@@.    In the case of a dark-square bishop, @@StartFEN@@4K1k1/3R1p2/6p1/7p/1b6/8/5PPP/8 b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ the white king goes to e8 and attacks the f7-pawn in order to force its advance. After  1...f5  , White can build the position that we have just seen; but a simpler way is to come back to e6 with the king, bring all the pawns to the third rank and the rook to g2, and finally carry out the advance g3-g4. }
