{ Queen and Pawn vs. Queen   If the defender’s king stands in front of the pawn, the draw is usually an easy matter.  Botvinnik – Tal, Moscow wm  (12)  1960 }
1... f5+ 2. Kg5
{ After  2.Qxf5  Qxd4+  Black’s defense is even simpler because his king is already standing in front of the pawn and almost every instance of a queen exchange is acceptable for him. }
2... Qxg3+ 3. Kxf5 Qg6+ 4. Kf4 Qf6+ 5. Ke3 Kf8 6. Kd3
{ If Tal had played  6...Ke7  here, there would have been no doubt about a draw. What he did instead made his task more complicated. @@StartSquare@@Ed. until this point, the information is considered essential in Dvoretsky's book. The remainder of the game is given below but does not have to be committed to memory.@@EndSquare@@ }
6... Qf1+ 7. Ke4 Qg2+ { 7...Ke7= } 8. Ke5 Qg5+ 9. Ke6 Qe7+ 10. Kf5
{ If  10...Qh7+  or  10...Qf7+  then  11.Ke5  . Here  11...Qe7+  is better as after  11...Qh5+  12.Kd6  , Black cannot trade queens, the checks will soon expire, and his king will be forced to the g-file, farther from the pawn. According to the tablebase, it is mate in 70 moves. }
10... Qc7
{ “However strange it may seem, Black evidently has secured the draw only with this move ... Now White’s pieces are ideally placed; any move will just worsen his position.” @@StartBracket@@Tal@@EndBracket@@. }
11. Qa8+ Ke7 12. Qe4+ Kd8 13. Qh4+ Kc8 14. Qh8+ Kb7 15. Qe5 Qf7+ 16. Ke4 Qg6+
17. Qf5 Qd6 18. Qf7+ Kc8 19. Qf5+ Kd8 20. Qa5+ Ke8 21. d5 Ke7 22. Qa7+ Kd8 23.
Qa8+ Kd7 24. Kf5 Ke7 { Draw. } *

