[SetUp "1"]

{ Now we come to those exceptionally complicated cases when the king of the weaker side is placed far away from the pawn. Computers have proved that a win, when it exists, can often be achieved  (when both sides play correctly)  only after more than 50 moves!  Practical players should not delve too deeply into this jungle, for these endings occur quite seldom. We shall confine ourselves to basic theoretical statements and the most important practical methods. Botvinnik was the first to find the correct method for the stronger side, during an analysis of the following adjourned game:   Botvinnik – Minev, Amsterdam ol 1954 }
1. Qf6
{ 1.Kh6?  Qh4+  2.Kg7  Ka3!=  is much weaker, as Botvinnik played in a similar position against Ravinsky ten years earlier.  The attacker should not place his king in front of his pawn.    According to computer analysis,  1.Kf5!  is more precise; if  1...Qc8+  @@StartBracket@@this position had already occurred on a previous move@@EndBracket@@, then  2.Kf4!  Qc1+  3.Qe3  Qc7+  4.Kg4  Qd7+  5.Kh4  Qd8+  6.Kg3  @@StartBracket@@there are no checks anymore;  6...Qd6+  loses to  7.Qf4+  @@EndBracket@@, or @@StartFEN@@8/3q4/6P1/8/k6K/4Q3/8/8 b - - 9 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Qg7  6.Kg5  etc. @@StartBracket@@this “etc., ” by the way, lasts more than 20 moves at least@@EndBracket@@. }
1... Qd5+ 2. Qf5 Qd8+ 3. Kh5
{ The stronger side should place the king on the same file or rank where the defender’s king is standing, or an adjacent file or rank @@StartBracket@@this rule is also valid when more pawns are present on the board@@EndBracket@@.   This tactic often enables counter-checks when the queen provides protection from a defender’s check by interference. For example, now Black cannot play  3...Qd1+  in view of  4.Qg4+  or  3...Qh8+  4.Kg4  , and Black cannot play  4...Qd4+  because of  5.Qf4  , as @@StartFEN@@7q/8/6P1/5Q2/k5K1/8/8/8 b - - 7 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Qg7  loses to  5.Qf7!  Qc3  6.g7!   Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 12-3 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 12 – Queen Endgames"]
[Black "Queen and Pawn vs. Queen 12-3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "3q4/8/6P1/5Q1K/k7/8/8/8 b - - 0 3"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Botvinnik − Minev, Amsterdam ol 1954  (continued) } 3... Qe8 { Diagram 12-3 }
4. Qf4+
{ An error that was left unnoticed by Botvinnik. The computer analysis shows that the correct winning process is  4.Kg4!  Qe2+  5.Kf4  Qd2+  6.Ke5  Qb2+  7.Kd6  Qb8+  8.Ke7  Qb4+  9.Kf7  Qb7+  10.Kf6  Qb6+  11.Qe6  @@StartBracket@@this is only an introduction: a lot of precise moves are still required for achieving success@@EndBracket@@.  But why is the move actually played wrong? Because,  when dealing with a knight or rook pawn, the defender’s king is best placed near the corner that is diametrically opposite to the pawn promotion square. Then, when the stronger side defends his king from checks with a queen interference, a counter-check is less probable.  Black could have played @@StartFEN@@4q3/8/6P1/7K/k4Q2/8/8/8 b - - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Ka3!  here and theory says that it is a draw, although it is a long way from a theoretical evaluation to a half-point in the tournament table, because these positions are very difficult to defend.   We should add that  the indicated drawing zone does not exist in case of a bishop or central pawn.  One can only expect that the opponent’s play will not be precise @@StartBracket@@although defender’s errors are more probable in these situations@@EndBracket@@ or ... that the king manages to reach the area in front of the pawn like in the Botvinnik-Tal endgame.  By the way,  the drawing zone, near the pawn, is considerably larger with a rook pawn, compared with other pawns, because the defender can go for a queen exchange much more often.    Having arrived at general considerations about various pawn cases, I add two more remarks:  a. The farther the pawn is advanced, the less the defender’s chance for a draw;  b. The closer the pawn is to the edge of the board, the greater the drawing chances. With central and bishop pawns, practically all positions with a remote king are lost. With a knight pawn, winning positions occur very often. With a rook pawn, a draw can be reached in a majority of positions, although the defense is not simple.   Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 12-4 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 12 – Queen Endgames"]
[Black "Queen and Pawn vs. Queen 12-4"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "4q3/8/6P1/7K/k4Q2/8/8/8 b - - 0 4"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Botvinnik − Minev, Amsterdam ol 1954  (continued) } 4... Ka5
{ The wrong way! But this choice was not made purely by chance. The above-mentioned game Botvinnik-Ravinsky had been thoroughly annotated by Keres, and the Estonian grandmaster erroneously suggested keeping the king on a5 and a4. }
5. Qd2+ Ka4 6. Qd4+ Ka5 7. Kg5
{ Take notice of White’s last moves.  The queen is placed best on the central squares @@StartBracket@@this is usually valid for the defender’s queen as well@@EndBracket@@. The closer the queen is to the edge of the board, the winning process is more difficult and the probability of a perpetual check is higher.   By the way, now we can easily explain why Botvinnik’s @@StartFEN@@3q4/8/6P1/4Q1K1/k7/8/8/8 w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Qf6  was less accurate than  1.Kf5!  His queen should not leave the center unless it is an emergency. }
7... Qe7+ 8. Kf5 Qf8+ 9. Ke4 Qh6 10. Qe5+ Ka4 11. g7
{ Finally the pawn succeeds in moving forward, and the finale is near. The finish is also very instructive: White approaches the black king with his monarch in order to create a situation when every check can be met with a counter-check. This method @@StartBracket@@ king-to-king @@EndBracket@@ is characteristic for queen-and-pawn endings. }
11... Qh1+ 12. Kd4 Qd1+ 13. Kc5 Qc1+ 14. Kd6 { 14.Kd5?  Qc8 } 14... Qd2+
{ 14...Qh6+  15.Kd5! } 15. Ke6 Qa2+ 16. Qd5 Qe2+ 17. Kd6 Qh2+ 18. Kc5
{ Diagram 12-4 Black resigned. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 12 – Queen Endgames"]
[Black "Queen and Pawn vs. Queen 12-5"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "6q1/4K3/1k6/7Q/7P/8/8/8 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Tragicomedies: Shamkovich – Wirthensohn, Biel 1980    We shall not go deeply into intricate lines. Instead, we merely want to match the computer evaluations of the actual moves with the general considerations that are already known to us from the annotations to the previous example. Because of the rook pawn, Black can hope for a successful defense. And, as a matter of fact, the position was still drawn after  1...Qg3  or  1...Qc4  . }
1... Qg7+ 2. Qf7 Qg3 { 2...Qe5+?  3.Qe6+ } 3. Qf6+ Kc7 4. Qg5
{ Shamkovich only worsens the position of his queen, moving it closer to the edge. He should have pushed his pawn in order to obtain a position that can be won in ... 69 moves @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@. }
4... Qa3+ 5. Kf7 Qb3+ 6. Kg7 Qc3+
{ A drawn position @@StartBracket@@not a draw as such – Black would have spent a good deal of sweat for it@@EndBracket@@ could be maintained after a check from b2. It is difficult to explain the choice by general principles, but the black king will get in the queen’s way in some lines now. }
7. Qf6 Qg3+ 8. Kh7
{ But this is not merely an error; this is neglect of principles. As we have stated, the king should not seek exile in front of the pawn. Both  8.Qg5  and  8.Kf7  are winning, but  8.Kf8!  is the most precise. }
8... Qh3 9. Qg5 Kb6
{ This counter-error is also very instructive. As we know, there is a drawing zone near a rook pawn, and this zone is rather spacious @@StartBracket@@its precise borders depend on the placement of the pieces, and most importantly on how far advanced the pawn is; we shall not give precise definitions here@@EndBracket@@.   The king was already standing in the zone, therefore many queen moves were not losing, but the most logical decision was to go towards the pawn:  9...Kd7!  or  9...Kd6!= }
10. h5 { Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 12-6 } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 12 – Queen Endgames"]
[Black "Queen and Pawn vs. Queen 12-6"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/7K/1k6/6QP/8/7q/8/8 b - - 0 10"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Tragicomedies: Shamkovich − Wirthensohn, Biel 1980  (continued) } 10... Qd7+
{ Diagram 12-6 } 11. Qg7
{ White worsens his queen’s position. All king moves were winning. } 11... Qh3
{ The black queen had to guard the central squares.  11...Qd5!  was good enough for a draw. }
12. Qe5
{ The white queen has finally arrived in the center, Black’s king is out of the drawing zone – White’s position is winning! }
12... Qd7+ 13. Kg6 Qd3+ 14. Qf5 Qg3+ 15. Kf7 Qc7+ 16. Kg8 Qb8+ 17. Kg7 Qc7+ 18.
Qf7 Qh2 19. h6 Ka5 20. h7 Qe5+ 21. Qf6 Qg3+ 22. Kh6
{ Black resigned in view of  22...Qh2+  23.Kg6!  and the checks expire because of the correct position of the white king @@StartBracket@@on a rank adjacent to his black counterpart@@EndBracket@@. }
