{ Borisenko – Simagin, USSR ch, Moscow 1955     Contrary to the previous example, the extra pawn cannot be exploited here. If  1.Kh4  Qe2!  is strong, while  1.Kh2  is met by  1...Qe2+  2.Kg1  Qe1+  3.Kg2  Qe2+  4.Qf2  Qd3!  or  4...Qc4!=  Winning chances can only be obtained by a king march to the passed pawn, so Borisenko pushed his king ahead. }
1. Kg4
{ White had only expected  1...Qe2+?  2.Kf4  or  1...Qf5+?  2.Kh4  , and  2...Qf3?  fails to  3.Qd8+  Kg7  4.Qf6+! }
1... f5+
{ White resigned because he cannot avoid mate:  2.Kh4  Qh1#  or  2.gxf6  Qf5+  3.Kh4  Qh5# }
