{ Defensive Tactics   The main tactical tools which can save a difficult queen-and-pawn endgame are  stalemate  and  perpetual check.   Y. Averbakh, 1962  A straightforward implementation of the king-to-king process does not bring any success here. }
1. Kf2
{ Both  1.Qe4+  and  1.Qg4  win, but the simplest winning procedure is moving the king downstairs to g1  (where the black queen cannot reach it)  followed by a queen transfer to f8.  1.Qg1+!  Ka2  2.Qg2+  @@StartBracket@@  2...Ka3  is the same.@@EndBracket@@  2...Ka1  3.Kh2!  Qh7+  4.Kg1  , and if @@StartFEN@@6q1/6P1/8/8/8/8/6QK/k7 b - - 5 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Qb8+  4.Kh1  Qg8  5.Kg1 !  Kb1  6.Qf1+  Kb2  7.Qf8  +- }
1... Qf7+ 2. Ke1 Qe6+ 3. Kd1 Qb3+ 4. Kd2 Qa2+ 5. Ke3
{ The checks seem to be exhausted. } 5... Qb3+ 6. Qd3+
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed. Black escapes now with a draw and the defensive method can be trained next → Diagram 12-15 EXTRA.@@EndSquare@@ }
*

