{ The following example demonstrates an interesting maneuver by the white king. After the threat of perpetual check had been eliminated, White exploited his advantage in an instructive way.   Tukmakov – Agzamov, Erevan zt 1982 }
1. Kg3
{ The premature advance  1.f6?  leads to a draw:  1...Qf4+  2.Kg2  Qg5+  3.Kh3  Qh5+  Therefore Tukmakov brings his king to  h3  first, and only then does he intend to push the f-pawn.   For example,  1...c4!?  2.Kh3!   2.f6?  is still wrong;  2.Qb6+?  also does not win in view of  2...Qxb6  3.axb6+  Kd7!  4.f6  a5  5.Kg4  e4!=  2...Qxb2  3.f6!  ± }
1... Qf4+ 2. Kh3 c4
{ While the white queen protects the h6-square, Black has no perpetual check. }
3. Qe7+ Kc8
{ 3...Kb8  4.Qf8+  Ka7  was more tenacious, although after  5.d6!  e4  6.d7  or @@StartFEN@@5Q2/kp6/p2P4/P3pP2/2p2q2/7K/1P6/8 b - - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Qg5  6.Qf7  , Black’s situation still would have been difficult. }
4. Qf8+ Kd7 5. f6 Qf3+ 6. Kh4 Qf4+ 7. Kh5 Qf3+ 8. Kg6 Qe4+ 9. Kg7 Qg2+ 10. Kh7
Qe4+ 11. Kg8
{ The king, as usual, has found an exile from the checks on an adjacent rank to his adversary. }
11... Qxd5+ 12. f7 Kc6 { 12...Qe6  13.Qg7  e4  14.Kh8  +- } 13. Qc8+ Kb5 14.
Kg7 Qg2+ 15. Kf6 Qf3+ 16. Ke7 { Black resigned. } *

