{ 12/7. Szily-Ozsvth, Hungary ch 1954 } 1... e3
{ The game continued:  1...Qc1?  2.Qf7+  Ke1   If  2...Ke2  3.Qxg6  Qf4+  4.Kg1  Qe5  then  5.Qd6!=  , rather than  5.Qxc6?  Qa1+  6.Kh2  Kf2  with an inevitable mate.  3.Qxg6  Qf4+  4.Kg1  Qf1+  5.Kh2  Qc4  6.Qxc6  e3  7.Qd6  and the game is equal.  Why did Black not push his passed pawn? Presumably, he calculated the line... }
2. Qc4+ { 2.Qf7+  Qf2  3.Qxg6  Qf4+  4.Kh1  e2  5.Qd3  Kf2  6.Qc2  Qg5  -+ }
2... e2 3. Qf4+ Qf2 4. Qc1+
{ Diagram 16-96   ...and  came to the conclusion that it leads to perpetual check:  4...e1=Q?  5.Qc4+  Qfe2  6.Qf4+  Q1f2  7.Qc1+  etc.  However, underpromotion to a knight could prevent the perpetual check. }
4... e1=N 5. Qc4+ Qe2 6. Qf4+ Nf3+ 7. Qxf3+ Qxf3 8. gxf3 Kf2 { Black wins. } *

