{ Larsen − Keres, San Antonio 1972  (continued)   In this case, two pawns win against one. Firstly, because one of them is passed; second, because the white king is cut off from the kingside and the h4-pawn is therefore vulnerable. }
24. Qg5 Qf1 25. Qg4 { 25.Qd8  Kg7  ∆ Qf6. } 25... Qe1+
{ The king is driven away even more. } 26. Kd3 Qe6 27. Qf4 Kg7 28. Qd4+ f6 29.
Qb4 { 29.Qf4  Qe5  30.Qg4  Kh6 } 29... Qf5+ 30. Ke2
{ If  30.Ke3  , Black wins by means of  30...Kh6  31.Qf8+  Kh5  32.Qh8+  Kg4  33.Qh6  Qf3+!  , forcing a queen exchange. }
30... Kh6 31. Ke1
{ After  31.Qf8+  Kh5  32.Qh8+  Kg4  33.Qh6  , the check from f3 is weaker because of 34.Ke1, but Black has  33...Qh5!  , and every queen retreat will be met with ...Kxh4 resulting in a discovered check. Quicker success can be achieved by means of @@StartFEN@@8/8/5ppQ/5q2/6kP/8/4K3/8 b - - 9 33@@EndFEN@@  33...Qc2+!  and 34...Kf3 – a mating attack. }
31... Kh5 32. Qc4 Qg4 33. Qc5+ Kxh4 34. Qe7 Qf5 35. Qb4+ Kh5 36. Qc4 g5 37.
Qf7+ Kh4 38. Qf8 Kg3 39. Qa3+ Qf3 40. Qd6+ Kg2 41. Qd2+ Kh3 42. Qd7+ f5 43. Qg7
g4 44. Qh8+ Kg3 45. Qe5+ f4 46. Qb8 Qe3+ 47. Kd1 Kg2 { White resigned. } *

