{ Averbakh − Suetin, USSR ch, Kiev 1954  White's plan is a king attack and it must be successful because Black's pawn structure is destroyed. }
1. g4 Qd2 { 1...e4  2.Kg3  e3?  fails to  3.Qh5+  Kg8  4.Qe8+  Kh7  5.Qxe3  . }
2. Kg3 Qc3+ 3. Kh4 Qd4 4. Qf5+ g6 { Or  4...Kg8  5.Kh5!  and g4-g5-g6. } 5.
Qf7+ Kh6 6. Qf6 Kh7 7. Kg5 Qd2+ 8. f4 exf4 9. Qf7+ Kh8 10. Kh6
{ Black resigned.  Please pay attention to the fact that White exploits Black's pawns as an  umbrella  giving protection from queen checks. We learned this technique when studying rook-and-pawn endings; it is no less important for queen endgames too. }
