[SetUp "1"]

{ A Passed Pawn   A passed pawn supported by a queen is a powerful instrument. To stop it, the combined efforts of a king and a queen are required; a queen alone cannot manage it. When the passed pawn is well advanced, it can outweigh an opponent's huge material advantage on another wing.  Averbakh − Zurakhov, Minsk 1952 }
1... b5 2. axb5 { 2.Qxa5?  Qe5+ } 2... Qxb5
{ 2...Qe5+?  3.Qxe5+  Kxe5  fails because of  4.h4!  a4  5.h5  a3  6.h6  Kf6  7.b6  +- }
3. Qd6+ Kf7 { 3...Kg7!? } 4. h4
{ If the a-pawn were a bit more advanced, the peaceful outcome would not be in doubt: White would have to submit to perpetual check. But, under current conditions, he still has winning chances.   The point is that if the black king stands in the way of the white pawns, their advance  (and, eventually, a king intervention)  can create mating threats. On the other hand, if Black holds his king aside, then the h-pawn balances Black's passed pawn, while their exchange still leaves White his two extra pawns. }
4... a4 5. Qf4+ Ke6 6. Qg4+ Kd6 7. Qg6+ Kc7
{ 7...Ke7  draws because of the counterplay with the a-pawn. } 8. h5 Qe5+ 9.
Kh3
{ Black resigned in view of  9...a3  10.h6  a2  11.Qg7+  Qxg7  12.hxg7  a1=Q  13.g8=Q  +- }
*

