{ Euwe – Reshevsky, Nottingham 1936  In this sort of position, White’s standard plan is to place his queen on a8 and then to push the a-pawn to the promotion square. The queen not only supports the pawn advance; it also protects the king from checks along the long diagonal. The only constructive idea for the weaker side is to achieve a perpetual check; to this end, he must destroy the position of the white king. }
1. Qa8+
{ 1.b4?  Qc4  2.a3  e4  is not good; @@StartFEN@@6k1/2q2p2/4p1p1/4p2p/7P/1P3QP1/P4PK1/8 w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.a4?  Qa5  is also erroneous. }
1... Kg7 2. a4 Qb6
{ Alekhine indicated that  2...Qc3!  was much more tenacious, but in the long run it should also lose after  3.Qb7  Qe1  4.Qb6  e4  5.b4  e3  6.Qxe3  Qxb4  7.Qe5+  Kf8  8.Qh8+  Ke7  9.Qa8  +- }
3. a5 Qxb3 4. a6 Qa3
{ After  4...Qa2  5.a7  e4  6.Qb7  e3  7.a8=Q  Qxf2+  8.Kh3  , Black has no perpetual check. }
5. a7 e4 6. Qb8 Qf3+ 7. Kg1 Qd1+ { 7...e3  8.a8=Q  Qxf2+  9.Kh1  +- } 8. Kh2
Qe2 9. Qe5+
{ Black resigned @@StartBracket@@  9...Kh7  10.Qf4  @@EndBracket@@. } *

