[Black "A Passed Pawn 12-29"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/5p1k/2pQ2p1/2P2q2/1P5p/5P1P/6PK/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Maróczy – Bogoljubow, Dresden 1936 } 1. b5 cxb5 2. c6
{ The same strategy that we have seen in the previous example, but there is a cardinal difference between these two endings: White’s queen will be obliged to abandon the h2-b8 diagonal in order to take control over the promotion square, giving Black opportunities for checks. The question is whether there will be a perpetual check.   Ed. note: The information presented until this point is considered essential in the book. The game continues in the next variations but it does not have to be committed to memory. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 12 – Queen Endgames"]
[Black "A Passed Pawn 12-29 EXTRA"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/5p1k/2PQ2p1/1p3q2/7p/5P1P/6PK/8 b - - 0 2"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Maróczy − Bogoljubow, Dresden 1936  (continued) } 2... Qc2
{ As will be seen, it would have been better for Black to jettison the b-pawn:  2...b4  3.Qxb4  Qe5+  4.f4  Qc7  . Nevertheless, with  5.Qc4  , White still wins in the long run. }
3. Qd5
{ Simpler was  3.Qd7!  Qc4  4.c7  , coming directly to a position that will occur later in the game. But not @@StartFEN@@8/5p1k/2PQ2p1/1p6/7p/5P1P/2q3PK/8 w - - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3.c7?  Qc3!  , the consequences of which we shall study later. @@StartSquare@@Ed. The position studied later has the Black king placed on  g7  , instead of  h7  , which makes a major difference. In fact, White is winning here too, following  4.Qd7  Qe5+  5.f4  Qxf4+  6.Kg1  when there is no perpetual check and the king will slowly march up the board. In the next example we get to see why the position is indeed drawn with the king on  g7  instead.@@EndSquare@@ }
3... Kh6
{ Black does not allow a capture on  f7  with check.  3...Kg7?  with the same purpose, is weaker in view of  4.Qd4+! }
4. Qd6
{ Maróczy, a recognized expert in queen endings, leaves the b5-pawn alive, hoping that it will eventually serve as an “umbrella” for his king.   However, in this instance Black has a subtle defense. Correct was  4.Qxb5  Qc1  5.Qd5!  , winning. }
4... Qc4
{ 4...Kh7?  5.Qd7!  Qc4  6.c7  leads to a transposition of moves; if @@StartFEN@@8/5p2/2PQ2pk/1p6/7p/5P1P/2q3PK/8 b - - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Kg7?  , then the same check,  5.Qd4+!  , is again very strong. Finally,  4...b4?  is quite bad because of  5.c7  , with threats of 6.Qf8+ and 6.Qd7. @@StartSquare@@Ed. the only defense, 4...Qc3! is given next → Diagram 12-29a@@EndSquare@@ }
5. c7 { Ed. note: continued → Diagram 12-29b } *

