{ Maróczy − Bogoljubow, Dresden 1936  (analysis) } 4... Qc3
{ The only defense. The queen must seek to check from e5 rather than f4. } 5.
c7
{ 5.Qf8+  Kh5  6.Qxf7  Qxc6  7.f4  Kh6  8.Qe7  Qc4  9.Qxh4+  Kg7  10.Qe7+  Kg8  is a position similar to that from theAverbakh-Zurakhov game,  but the g6-pawn is present here; it gives the king protection, and therefore a draw is obvious. }
5... Kg7 6. Qd7 Qe5+ 7. f4 { Diagram 12-29a } 7... Qc3
{ This is the key saving resource @@StartSquare@@Ed. which was not available in the previous example. With the king on h7, White can simply capture on f7. Here@@EndSquare@@ the white queen cannot both help the pawn promote and prevent the perpetual check through e1-g3. Therefore, this is a draw, for example: }
8. Qe7 Qc4 { 8...Qg3+??  9.Kg1 } 9. Qe5+ Kh7 10. f5 g5
{ Or  10...b4  11.fxg6+  Kxg6=  . Now let us see what happened in the game → Diagram 12-29b. }
