{ Prandstetter – Gheorghiu, Warsaw zt 1979    Black obviously stands better because his passed pawn is far more advanced than White’s. But can he exploit this advantage? Black could achieve success by means of a king invasion to support his pawn, but this is not easy to do. Let us study a few of possible attempts.  1...e3?  is harmless in view of  2.Qe4!=  or  2.Qc7!=   The try to activate the king immediately by  1...Ke5?  is tempting. The variation  2.Qc7+  Kd4  3.Qc5+?  Qxc5  4.bxc5  leads to a pawn endgame which quickly converts to a queen ending won for Black:  4...Kxc5!   4...e3?  5.Kg2=  5.Kg2  Kd4  6.Kf2?  Kd3  7.Ke1  a5  -+ And if @@StartFEN@@8/8/p7/1pk5/4p3/P6P/7K/8 w - - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.h4  Kd4!  6.h5  e3   6...Ke5?  7.Kg3  a5  8.h6  Kf6  9.Kf4  b4  10.axb4  a4  11.b5=  7.Kg2   7.h6  e2  8.h7  e1=Q  9.h8=Q+  Qe5+  7...Kd3  8.h6  e2  9.h7  e1=Q  10.h8=Q  Qd2+  and 11...Kc2 However, instead of the exchange of queens,  3.Qd6+!  draws:  3...Kc4  4.Qe6+!  Kd3  5.Qb3+  Even a move earlier  2.Qh8+  can be played:  2...Kd5  3.Qc3!  , and the king cannot make any progress. And on  2...Kf4  3.Qf8+  Ke3  4.Qc5+  the pawn ending is drawn. }
1... Qf4+
{ After  1...Qd2+!  2.Kg3  e3?  Black threatens a further pawn advance as well as 3...Ke5. However, White has  3.Qh4+!  @@StartBracket@@control over the f2-square is vital@@EndBracket@@  3...Ke5  4.Kf3!=  However,  2...Qe3+  @@StartBracket@@instead of 2...e3?@@EndBracket@@  3.Kg2  Qe2+!  4.Kg3  Ke5!  puts White in an extremely difficult position. He can neither exchange queens on c5 nor impede the forward progress of the enemy king. }
2. Kg1 Qg3+ { Black still wins with  2...Qc1+!  3.Kg2  Qd2+  4.Kf1  e3! } 3.
Kf1 Qf3+ 4. Ke1
{ The white king has managed to stand in front of the black pawn, so it is a simple draw. What happens now resembles theLarsen-Keres ending: Black, in search of winning chances, forgets all caution and allows an exchange of queens when it is already winning for White. }
4... Ke5 5. Qc7+ { Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 12-34 }
