{ Tragicomedies: Karpov – Agdestein, Gjovik m  (1)  1991    White should have accepted that there is no win, playing either  1.Qc8+  or  1.Qd5+  Kh8  2.Qxb3  Qxf2+  3.Kh3  Qxd4  . }
1. d5
{ Karpov expected only  1...b2?  2.d6  b1=Q  3.Qxb1  Qxf2+  4.Kh3  , or @@StartFEN@@6k1/6p1/3P3p/5Q2/7P/6P1/1p2qP1K/8 b - - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Qd1  3.d7  b1=Q  4.Qxb1  Qxd7  and wished to torment his opponent some more in a drawn endgame, a delusion that was very unpleasant. }
1... Qc2
{ By taking control over the b1-h7 diagonal Black assures both the safety of his king and the promotion of his pawn. }
2. Qf3 b2 3. d6 b1=Q 4. d7 Qbd1 5. Qa8+ Kh7 { White resigned. } *

