{ 12/8. Ehlvest-Topalov, Novgorod 1995 } 1... Kc7
{ After  1...Kc8??  2.Qg4+  Kc7  , a draw was agreed, in view of  3.Qd1=   1...Kc6  is less precise: after  2.Qa4+  he should go back  2...Kb6  3.Qb4+  Kc7!  because  2...Kc5?  3.Qa5+  Kc6  4.Qa8+  leads to perpetual check. The outcome of the complicated duel between the king and queen in the line @@StartFEN@@8/8/2k5/3qP3/Q7/1P6/3p3P/6K1 b - - 2 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Kc7  3.Qa7+  Kd8  4.Qb6+  Ke7  5.Qf6+  Kd7  is hard to foresee. }
2. Qe7+ { 2.Qc3+  Kd8 } 2... Kc6 3. Qe8+ Kc5 4. Qf8+ Kd4
{ The king has broken through into the opposite camp where it can both find a refuge from checks and support its passed pawn. }
