{ Marshall – Maróczy, Ostende 1905 } 1... Qc5
{ The e5-pawn is White’s main weakness. If it were standing on e3, the position would be even. }
2. Qd8+ { 2.f4?  Qc4+ } 2... Kh7 3. Qd3+ g6 4. Qc3 Qd5 5. a3
{ 5.b3  is no better. Villeneuve gives the following line:  5...Qd1+  6.Qe1  Qd3+  7.Kg1  Qc2  8.Qa1  b4!  9.Kf1  g5  , and if @@StartFEN@@8/5p1k/p3p1pp/4P3/1p6/1P6/P1q2PPP/Q5K1 w - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.f4  Qc3  10.Qf1  Qd4+  11.Kh1  Qb2  -+ }
5... Qd1+ 6. Qe1 Qd3+ 7. Kg1 Qc2 8. Qa1
{ By means of threats to one pawn or another, and sometimes to the king, Black has precisely driven the white queen away to a corner. The pawn sacrifice  8.b4?  Qb2  9.h4  , suggested by Panchenko, brings White no relief:  9...Qxa3   9...h5  10.Qe3  is weaker.  10.Qe4  Qc1+  11.Kh2  Qc4  -+ and if @@StartFEN@@8/5p1k/p3p1pp/1p2P3/1P5P/q7/5PP1/4Q1K1 w - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.h5  Qd3   After  10...gxh5  11.Qe4+  Kg7  12.Qf4  Qd3  13.Qf6+  Kg8  14.Qxh6  White obtains counterplay.  11.hxg6+  Kxg6  -+ }
8... a5 { Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 12-38 } *

