{ 12/9. Kharitonov-Ivanchuk, Frunze 1988 } 1. Qe7
{ White has completely tied down his opponent, having deprived the black queen of the e8- and d7-squares. Now he plans to combine threats to the king with an advance of his queenside pawns. }
1... h5 { Otherwise g3-g4 and h4-h5-h6. } 2. Kg2 Qc8
{ 2...Kh8  3.Qf8+  Kh7  4.Qf7+  Kh6  5.Qg8  Qc3  6.Qxe6  . } 3. b4 Qc6 4. a3
{ Diagram 16-97 } 4... Qc8 5. a4 Qc6 6. Qf6 Kh7 { 6...Qe8  7.b5 } 7. Qf7+ Kh6
8. Qg8 Qc3 9. b5 Qf6 10. Kg1
{ Quicker progress could be achieved with  10.bxa6  Qf3+  11.Kg1  Qd1+  12.Kh2  . }
10... axb5 11. axb5 d4 12. exd4 Qxd4 13. Qxe6 Qd1+ 14. Kh2 Qf3
{ If  14...Qe2  , White does not play  15.Qb6  Kh7!  ∆  16.--  e3  . He has @@StartFEN@@8/8/4Q1pk/1P5p/4p2P/6P1/4qP1K/8 w - - 3 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Qf6!  Kh7  16.b6!  , and if  16...e3  , then  17.Qe7+  . }
15. Qb6 { Black resigned. Diagram 16-98 has been intentionally omitted. } *

