{ Diagram 13-3  (continued) } 1... Rg4
{ Another possibility is  12...Ra4  White cannot win the rook by force. He must drive the black king away to an edge, place his queen optimally and then move his king closer to its counterpart.  The main line is  13.Qe5+  Kh3  14.Qe6+  Kh4  15.Qe7+  Kg3  16.Qd6+!  Kh4  17.Kf3!  (from d6 the queen prevents a rook check from a3)  17...Kh5  (the rook is finally unable to escape from a double attack now)  18.Qd5+  Kh4  19.Qd8+  Kh5  20.Qe8+  +- }
2. Qe5+ Kg2 3. Ke2 { Zugzwang. } 3... Rg3 4. Qh5 Kg1 5. Qd5
{ Zugzwang.  Quiet moves that limit the mobility of enemy pieces or create a zugzwang situation are often much more effective than checks. }
5... Rg6
{ In case of  16...Rg2+  17.Kf3  Kh2  18.Qh5+  Kg1  19.Qh4  ⨀ we come to thePhilidor position that is already familiar to us. The main line brings us the same result. }
6. Qd4+ Kh2 7. Qf4+ Kg1 8. Kf3 Rg2 9. Qh4 { White wins. } *

