{ Diagram 13-3  (analysis)   Now we return to an earlier moment and study the text move, instead of 4...Kf3. }
1... Kf2 2. Kd4 Rf4+
{ With Black's king on  f3  , White could have played  6.Kd3  while now this is weaker in view of  6...Rf3+  7.Kd2  Kg3  . }
3. Ke5 { The computer's suggestion. } 3... Rf3 4. Qa2+ Ke3 5. Qc2 { Zugzwang. }
5... Rg3 6. Qc3+ Kf2 7. Qd2+ Kf3 8. Kf5
{ The same zugzwang again, but this time closer to the edge. } 8... Rg2 9. Qd3+
Kf2 10. Kf4
{ Diagram 13-5   If Black plays  13...Kg1  now,  then  14.Qd4+  Kh2  15.Kf3  Rg3+  16.Kf2  Rg2+  17.Kf1  +-  Examine the final position closely: the rook cannot proceed with checks because the queen controls the g1-square.  This is the method the stronger side uses for approaching with the king: first the queen takes control of one of the adjacent squares. }
10... Ke1 11. Qc4 Kf2 12. Qc6
{ The natural looking  15.Qe4  leads to a reciprocal zugzwang position after  15...Kf1  16.Kf3  Rf2+  17.Kg3  Rd2!  this position should be reached with the adversary on move. If @@StartFEN@@8/8/2Q5/8/5K2/8/5kr1/8 b - - 22 12@@EndFEN@@  15...Kf1  now  16.Kf3  Rf2+  17.Kg3  Rd2  18.Qe4!  ⨀ +- is decisive. }
12... Rh2 13. Qf3+ Kg1 14. Qd5 { But, of course, not  17.Kg3??  Rh3+! } 14...
Kf2 15. Qd4+ Kg2 16. Kg4 { Zugzwang. } 16... Kf1 17. Kg3 Rg2+ 18. Kf3
{ The queen guards the f2-square. } *

