[FEN "8/4k3/4P3/8/3K4/4R3/8/7q b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ N. Grigoriev, 1933  However with Black on move, the evaluation differs. He manages to press White's pieces, by means of zugzwang, closer to the pawn, which means closer to the black king. The king then joins the queen at an appropriate moment with decisive effect. }
1... Qb1 2. Kc3 { 2.Kd5  Qa2+  3.Ke5  Qb2+  4.Kf4  Qf2+  loses even faster. }
2... Qd1
{ The familiar zugzwang position has arisen, but this time with White on move. }
3. Re4 { 3.Kc4  Qc2+  4.Kd4  Qd2+  -+ } 3... Qf3+ 4. Kd4 Qb3 { Diagram 13-8 }
5. Ke5
{ If  5.Re3  then  5...Qc2!  6.Re4  Kd6!  7.e7  Qd2+  8.Kc4  Qd5+  , and if @@StartFEN@@8/8/3kP3/8/3KR3/8/2q5/8 w - - 11 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Ke3  Kd5  -+  After the king move, a similar finale happens on the other wing. }
5... Qb2+ 6. Kf4 { 6.Kd5  Qc3!  ⨀  7.Re5  Qd3+  8.Kc5  Qd6+ } 6... Qf2+ 7. Kg4
{ 7.Ke5  Qf6+  8.Kd5  Qc3!  ⨀ } 7... Qg2+ 8. Kf4 Kf6 9. Ke3
{ 9.e7  Qf2+  10.Kg4  Qf5+ } 9... Kf5 { Black wins. } *

