[SetUp "1"]

{ V. Khenkin, 1981   The closer the pawn is to the edge, the greater the defensive resources.  This sort of position  (with the king in front of the pawn)  is lost when the pawn is central. With a bishop pawn, the outcome depends on specifics of piece placement. Here  (with a knight pawn)  Black holds a draw easily; the same is valid against a white king on e5, but not if the king gets to e7. Khenkin analyzed: }
1... Rf1 { However White wins if he, instead of 2.Qd5? plays: } 2. Qe8+ Kh7
{ 2...Rf7  3.Kh4  Kf6  4.Kh5  +- } 3. Qh5+ Kg8 4. Qd5+ Kf8
{ 4...Kh8  5.Qd8+  Kh7  6.Qd3+  +- } 5. Qc5+ Kg8 6. Qc4+ Rf7 7. Kg5
{ White wins.   To avoid the double attack, Black should place his rook on a dark square. @@StartFEN@@6Q1/6p1/5rk1/8/6K1/8/8/8 b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Rf2!  2.Qd5  Kh7  is an easy draw.  1...Rd6!  and  1...Rb6!  are also good. }
*

