[SetUp "1"]

{ With the rook pawn on the seventh rank, Black is lost because the rook has only one protected square at its disposal.  J. Berger, 1921 }
1. Qe7
{ Black is in zugzwang! Any move drastically worsens his position.   a.  1...Rg2  2.Qd8+  Kg7  3.Qd4+  Kh6  4.Qe3+  Kg7  5.Qc3+!  Kg8  6.Qc8+  Kg7  7.Qb7+  +-   b.  1...Rg1  2.Qd8+  Kf7  3.Qc7+  Kg8  4.Qb8+  Kg7  5.Qa7+  +-   c.  1...Kh8  2.Qf8+  Rg8  3.Qf6+  Rg7  , here  4.Qe5?  h6!=  is wrong: you can find the situation with the rook pawn on the sixth rank in the next section. Therefore, @@StartFEN@@7k/6rp/5Q2/5K2/8/8/8/8 w - - 6 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Ke6!  h5  5.Qh6+  +-   d.  1...Rh6  2.Kg5  Rg6+  3.Kh5  Kh8  4.Qf8+  Rg8  5.Qf6+  Rg7  6.Kh6  +- And if  3...Ra6  4.Qd8+  Kg7  5.Qc7+  +- }
1... Ra6 2. Qd8+ Kg7 3. Qd7+ Kh6 4. Qb7 Rd6
{ 4...Ra3  5.Qc6+  Kg7  6.Qd7+  +- } 5. Qe7 Rg6
{ Now White triangulates with the queen and puts his opponent in zugzwang.   I would like to make a comment here: White could have obtained this position with Black to move by playing @@StartFEN@@8/3Q3p/r6k/5K2/8/8/8/8 w - - 6 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qc7!  ⨀  Rg6  5.Qe7!  at once. }
6. Qf8+ Kh5 7. Qf7 Kh6 8. Qe7 { Zugzwang. } 8... Rg2 9. Qe3+ Kg7 10. Qc3+ Kf7
11. Qc7+ Kg8 12. Qb8+ Kg7 13. Qb7+ { White wins. } *

