{ The Pawn on the Sixth Rank   Our survey starts with a rook pawn. If it stands on its initial position then, as we already know, the stronger side wins. With the black pawn on the sixth rank, the position is drawn.  B. Guretzky-Cornitz, 1864  The rook has only one protected square @@StartBracket@@b5@@EndBracket@@, therefore the white king breaks through using a zugzwang technique. However White's achievements end with that: he can neither force a win of the rook nor smoke the king out from the corner. }
1. Qe7+ Kb8 2. Qe8+ Kb7 3. Qd8 Ka7 4. Qc8 Rb7
{ Black should by no means abandon the corner.   4...Kb6?  loses after  5.Qb8+  Ka5  6.Qd8+  Ka4  7.Qd2  Ka3  8.Qd6+  , and if @@StartFEN@@1Q6/8/pk6/1r6/2K5/8/8/8 b - - 9 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Kc6  6.Qa7  Rb6   6...Ra5  7.Kb4  Rb5+  8.Ka4  Rb6  9.Ka5  +-  7.Kd4  Rb4+  8.Kc3  Rb6  9.Kc4  ⨀, while after  7...Kb5  8.Qd7+  Kb4  9.Qc7  Rh6  10.Qe7+  Ka4  11.Qe8+  Ka5  12.Kc5  +- }
5. Qc5+
{ This is stronger than  5.Kc5  Rb5+  6.Kc6  Rb6+  7.Kc7  Rb5  8.Qg4  Rb7+  9.Kc6  Rb6+  . }
5... Ka8 6. Qd6 Ka7 7. Qd4+ Ka8 8. Kc5 Ka7 9. Kc6+ Ka8
{ Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 13-16 } *

