{ If the black pawn is a central or a bishop pawn and stands on the fifth or sixth rank, Black is lost.    Philidor, 1777  White's plan consists of the following stages:   a. To occupy squares behind the pawn, with the help of zugzwang, and drive the black king to d5 where it will obstruct its own rook. b. To cross the fifth rank with his king. c. To break through with the king via the e-file to the d6-pawn. }
1. Qh7+ Kd8
{ Both  1...Kf8?  2.Qd7  and  1...Ke8?  2.Qc7  are hopeless. In case of  1...Ke6?!  2.Qc7  Rc5  3.Qd8  White's mission becomes easier than after the text move. }
2. Qf7 { Zugzwang. } 2... Kc8
{ This is better than  2...Re7?  3.Qg8+  Kd7  4.Kf5  and @@StartFEN@@3k4/5Q2/3p4/4r3/5K2/8/8/8 b - - 3 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Rc5?!  3.Qe6  Kc7  4.Qe7+  Kc6  5.Qd8  Re5  6.Qc8+  Kd5  7.Qa8+  Ke6  8.Qe8+  Kd5  9.Qc8!  transposes into the main line. }
3. Qa7 Kd8 { 3...Rc5?  4.Qe7 } 4. Qb8+ Kd7 5. Qb7+ Kd8 6. Qc6 Ke7 7. Qc7+ Ke6
8. Qd8 Kd5 { The same is  8...Rf5+  9.Kg4  Re5  10.Qe8+  Kd5  11.Qc8 } 9. Qc8
{ Chéron recommended  9.Qd7!?   Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 13-18 }
