{ Philidor, 1777  (continued)     The first stage ends successfully. Black is in zugzwang and he is forced to give way to the white king because  9...Rh5?  loses immediately:  10.Qa8+  Kd4  11.Qa4+  . If  9...Kd4  then  10.Qc6  Rd5  and, according to Salvioli,  11.Kf3!  Ke5   11...Rf5+  12.Kg4  Rd5  13.Kf4  ⨀  12.Ke3  Rc5  □  13.Qe8+  Kf5  14.Qf7+  Ke5  15.Qe7+  , and if @@StartFEN@@4Q3/8/3p4/2r1k3/8/4K3/8/8 b - - 8 5@@EndFEN@@  13...Kf6  14.Qd7  Rd5  15.Ke4  +- }
1... Re4+ 2. Kf5 Re5+ 3. Kf6 { The second stage is also fulfilled. } 3... Re4
{ Both  11...Re1  12.Qb7+  Kc5  13.Qc7+  Kd5  14.Qa5+  and @@StartFEN@@2Q5/8/3p1K2/3kr3/8/8/8/8 b - - 4 3@@EndFEN@@  11...Re2  12.Qa8+  Kd4  13.Qa4+  Kc5  14.Qa3+  lose rapidly. }
4. Qc3
{ A neat method that stems fromGuretzky-Cornitz @@StartBracket@@1864@@EndBracket@@.   Philidor analyzed a slightly slower process:  12.Qf5+  Re5  13.Qd3+  Kc5  14.Qd2!  , while the computer prefers  12.Qb7+  Kd4  13.Qc6  d5  14.Qb6+  Kc4  15.Kf5  ⨀  and if @@StartFEN@@8/8/1Q3K2/3p4/3kr3/8/8/8 b - - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  14...Kd3  15.Qc5  d4  16.Qa3+  Ke2   16...Kc4  17.Qc1+  and  16...Kc2  17.Qb4  17.Qb2+  Ke3  18.Qc1+  Ke2  19.Qc2+  Ke3  20.Kf5  Rf4+  21.Ke5  d3  22.Qc5+  Kf3  23.Qc6+  Ke3  24.Qh6  . }
4... Re6+ { 12...Re5  13.Kf7!  ⨀ } 5. Kf7 Re5 6. Kf8
{ Zugzwang again. Black must let the white king cross the e-file.  Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 13-19 }
