{ B. Guretzky-Cornitz, 1864  (continued)   The main difference in this position from those with a bishop pawn or a central pawn, is the impossibility of queen attacks against the king from the left. The defensive method is similar to that with thea6-pawn @@StartBracket@@Diagram 13-12@@EndBracket@@.   And, as Khenkin noted, even with the white king on  d8  @@StartBracket@@while the queen is standing on e6 and the rook on c5@@EndBracket@@ there is no win: unlike the case of a rook pawn @@StartBracket@@won for White@@EndBracket@@, Black holds here thanks to the waiting move @@StartFEN@@3K4/1k6/1p2Q3/2r5/8/8/8/8 b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Ka7  . }
1. Qb5 Rc5 2. Qd7+ Kb8 3. Qg4 Rc7 4. Qe2 { ∆ 13.Qa6 } 4... Kb7 { Draw. } *

