[SetUp "1"]

{ F. Dedrle, 1925  If White is on move in the initial position, he wins by preparing a sacrifice of his queen for the rook. }
1. Qb8 Rg6 2. Qb4+ Ke8 3. Qe4+ Re6 { 3...Kf8  4.Qxg6 } 4. Qxe6+ fxe6 5. Kh6
{ From this example, the following conclusions can be drawn:   1. An important technique of exploiting an advantage can be a queen sacrifice that results in a winning pawn endgame.    2. The weaker side should keep his king in front of the opponent's pawn; this can often @@StartBracket@@but by no means always!@@EndBracket@@ neutralize the threat of the queen sacrifice.  If the pawn stands on e5 @@StartBracket@@instead of g5@@EndBracket@@ the king should stay on e7.   3. With the white king on the seventh rank, Black's position is most often lost. }
*

