{ V. Khenkin, 1966  As we know, a similar position, without the g6-pawn, is drawn. But here, when this pawn deprives the rook of the second protected square, White wins: he gradually approaches the black pawn with his king using the zugzwang technique.  It is worth mentioning that White is helpless in making any progress if his king is cut off in the lower right corner, be it in the diagrammed position or in many similar situations. }
1. Qc7 { Zugzwang. } 1... Re3
{ Other moves are no better:  1...Ra6  2.Qc3+  Kh7  3.Qc4!  Re6   3...Ra5+  4.Kd6  Rxg5  5.Qxf7+  Kh6  6.Qf4  Kh5  7.Qh2+  Kg4  8.Qh6  +- or @@StartFEN@@8/5p1k/r5p1/3K2P1/2Q5/8/8/8 b - - 5 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Rb6  4.Qc7  Rb5+  5.Kd6  Rf5  6.Ke7  +-  4.Qc8  (threatening 5.Qxe6)  Re1  5.Qf8  Rf1  6.Kd6  +-  with 7.Ke7 and 8.Qxf7+ to follow.   1...Kf8  2.Qc8+  Ke7  3.Qb8!  ⨀  Kd7  4.Qf8  Re7  5.Qg8  Kc7  6.Qa8  Kd7  7.Qf8  ⨀  and if  6...Rd7+  7.Ke5  +- }
2. Qc2 Kg8
{ If  2...Rg3  or  2...Ra3  ,  3.Qb2+  decides immediately.  If  2...Re6  then  3.Qc3+  Kg8  4.Qc8+  and 5.Qxe6.  , while after @@StartFEN@@8/5pk1/4r1p1/3K2P1/8/2Q5/8/8 b - - 5 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Kh7  4.Qh3+  and if  3...Kf8  4.Qc8+  Ke7  5.Qb8!  ⨀ }
3. Kd6 Re6+ 4. Kd7 Re3 { 4...Kg7  5.Qc4!  +- } 5. Qc4
{ The rook must leave the e-file because  5...Re1  6.Qc8+  is bad. } 5... Ra3
6. Qe4 Kg7 7. Qe5+
{ This decides a bit more rapidly than Khenkin's suggestion,  7.Ke7  Ra7+  8.Ke8  . }
7... Kg8 8. Qb8+ Kh7 { 8...Kg7  9.Qb2+ } 9. Ke7 { White wins. } *

