{ Dorfman – Beliavsky, Lvov zt 1978  Khenkin supplied a detailed analysis for this ending. Where does the rook belong, on e3 or f4? It turns out that both squares are good when the black king is on d5; but the rook should stand on f4  (to protect g4)  while the black king remains on the kingside. A draw could be reached by means of: }
1. Rf4+
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed. Dorfman played  1.Ra3?  →Diagram 13-38 Extra@@EndSquare@@ }
1... Ke5 2. Rf8 { 2.Ra4  is also good. } 2... Qe4+ 3. Kg1 Qc6 4. Rf4 Qc1+ 5.
Kg2 { Ed. note: analyzed in the next variation → Diagram 13-39 } *

