[SetUp "1"]

{ Dorfman − Beliavsky, Lvov zt 1978  (analysis) } 5... Qd1
{ Diagram 13-39   If the rook remains on the fourth rank –  6.Rb4  – then after  6...Kd5  7.Rf4  Kc5  , as theory says,  8.Re4?  loses to  8...Qd5  9.Kf3  Kc6!  10.Ke3   10.Kf4  Qd3!  11.Re8  Kc7!  12.Re7+  Kd8  13.Re4  Kd7  ⨀  10...Qd1!  Therefore White should play  8.Rf8!  , giving way to the black king and planning a rook transfer to e3. This maneuver can even be started immediately: }
6. Rf8 Qd5+ 7. Kg1 Ke4 8. Re8+ Kf3 9. Rf8+ Ke2
{ 9...Kg4?!  10.Kh2  Qd2  11.Kg2!  g5  □  12.hxg5  Kxg5  13.Rf4=  followed by Rh4-f4-h4. }
10. Re8+ Kd2 11. Re3 { Black cannot make any progress. } *

