{ Dorfman – Beliavsky, Lvov zt 1978  (analysis) } 3. Ra7
{ After the text move, the winning process would have been very complicated. In case of even the slightest inaccuracy, White could have reached one of the drawn positions that have been mentioned above @@StartBracket@@with the rook on f4 or e3@@EndBracket@@. }
3... Qc6 { 3...Kg4??  4.Rf7!  +- } 4. Rf7+ { 4.Re7  Qf6!  ∆  5.--  Kg4  -+ }
4... Ke4 5. Kg1 Qd6 { 5...Kd3?  6.Re7!  ∆ Re3= } 6. Kg2
{ 6.Rf4+  Qxf4  and @@StartFEN@@8/5R2/3q2p1/7p/4k2P/6P1/5P2/6K1 w - - 6 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Kh2  Kd3 }
6... Qd5 { 6...Kd3?  7.Rf3+  and 8.Re3=;  6...Qe6?  7.Rf4+ } 7. Rf8 Kd3+ 8. Kg1
Qc6 9. Rf7 { 10.Re7= is threatened. } 9... Qe4 { Diagram 13-40 } 10. Ra7
{ 10.Rf4  Qe2  11.Kg2   11.Rf8  Qe1+  12.Kh2  Qe4!  13.Rf4  Qc6  14.Kg1  Ke2  -+  11...Kd2  12.Ra4  Qe6!  Ra3  Qc6+  14.Kh2  Ke2  , and if @@StartFEN@@8/8/4q1p1/7p/R6P/6P1/3k1PK1/8 w - - 20 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Rb4  Qd5+  14.Kg1  Ke2  15.Rb2+  Kf3  -+ }
10... Qb4 { ∆  11.--  Ke2  . } 11. Kg2
{ 11.Ra8  or  11.Ra6  Qb1+  12.Kh2  Ke2  , while after @@StartFEN@@8/8/R5p1/7p/7P/3k2P1/5P2/1q4K1 w - - 18 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Kg2  Qb7+  . }
11... Qc5 12. Ra6 Qd5+ 13. Kg1 Ke2 14. Rxg6 Qd1+ 15. Kh2 Kf1
{ Rather than  15...Kxf2?  16.Rf6+  Ke3  17.Rf4  , arriving at the drawn position fromDiagram 13-36. }
16. Rb6 { 16.Ra6  Qd4 } 16... Qc2 17. Rf6 Qe4
{ In this last line, Khenkin does not investigate the most stubborn defense, @@StartFEN@@8/R7/6p1/7p/1q5P/3k2P1/5P2/6K1 w - - 16 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Kf1!  , preventing the king invasion to e2. Black responds with  11...Qd6!  , planning to bring his king to g4. For example,  12.Ra1   12.Ra2  Qc6!  and  12.Kg2  Qc5!  12...Qc6!  13.Rd1+  Ke4  14.Kg2  Kf5+  , and if @@StartFEN@@8/8/2q3p1/7p/7P/3k2P1/5P2/R4K2 w - - 20 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Ra3+  Ke4  14.Re3+  Kf5  15.Kg1  Kg4  etc. }
