{ To fully understand the following endgame, we should refresh our memories with the evaluations of several already known positions.  V. Khenkin, 1966  As we know from the previous example, it would have been an easy draw if the white pawn had been standing on h4. Here, on the contrary, White has a clear plan: to push his pawn to g5, obtaining Khenkin's winning position fromDiagram 13-37.   However, the immediate  1.g4?  hxg4  2.hxg4  meets a strong response,  2...g5!=  When White wins the g5-pawn, the drawn position ofDedrle arises @@StartBracket@@Diagram 13-32@@EndBracket@@. When analyzing it, we have mentioned that White wins if his king is on the seventh rank. From this, we come to the correct plan: first White should cross the fifth rank with his king and only then may he push the g-pawn. }
1. Kc5 Kg8 2. Qd4 Kh7 3. Qd8 Kg7 4. Kb5 { Zugzwang. } 4... Re1
{ Nothing else helps, viz.:  a.  4...Kh7  5.Qf8  +-   b.  4...Rf6  5.Qd4  g5  6.Qd8 !  Rg6  7.Kc5  g4  8.h4  +- and if  7...h4  8.g4!  +-   c.  4...Re4  5.Kc6  Rc4+  6.Kd5  Rc3  7.Qb8  Rd3+  8.Ke4  Rd1  9.Qb2+  Kg8  10.Qc3  Rd6  11.Ke5  Re6+  12.Kf4  Kh7  13.Kg5  +- }
5. Qd4+ Kg8 6. Kc6 Re6+
{ 6...Rh1  7.Kd7!  Rxh3  8.Ke7  Rxg3  9.Qf4  Ra3  10.Qxf7+  Kh8  11.Qxg6  is hopeless. }
7. Kd7 Re1 8. g4 hxg4 9. hxg4 g5 { Or  9...Re6  10.g5! } 10. Qd2 Re6 11. Qxg5+
{ We come to one of the aforementioned positions. } *

