{ M. Botvinnik, 1952  Botvinnik investigated this position  (with reversed colors)  when he analyzed his adjourned game versus Troianescu @@StartBracket@@1952@@EndBracket@@. He proved that the inevitable queen sacrifice on d5 leads to a winning pawn endgame. }
1. g4 hxg4 2. hxg4 Kg8 3. Qc7 Kg7 4. Qc6 Kf8
{ Otherwise the white king breaks through:  4...Rd8  5.Qc3+  Kg8  6.Ke5  Kg7  7.f5!  exf5  8.gxf5  Re8+   8...gxf5  9.Qg3+  Kf8  10.Kf6  +-  9.Kf4+  Kg8  10.fxg6  fxg6  11.Kg5  Re6  12.Qc7  Kf8  13.Qd7  +-  (Khenkin)  .  8...f6+!?  9.Kf4  Rd5  is more tenacious; it leads to a theoretical position with a bishop pawn on the sixth rank that is winning for White, although not easily.   4...Rd1  5.Qc3+  Kg8  6.Ke5  Rf1  7.Qc4  Rg1  8.Kf6  Rxg4  9.Qc7  , and if @@StartFEN@@6k1/5p2/4p1p1/4K3/5PP1/2Q5/8/3r4 b - - 8 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Kg7  7.f5!  exf5  8.gxf5  Rf1   8...gxf5  9.Qg3+  Kf8  10.Kf6  +-  9.fxg6  fxg6  10.Ke6+  Kg8  . This line is given a strange verdict in endgame books:  11.Qd3  Rg1  12.Kf6  +- However after  11...Rf5!  , we come to a known drawn position. Therefore, instead of  11.Qd3?  White should play  11.Qh3!  , threatening to invade on h6. }
5. Qa8+
{ Prior to the queen sacrifice, White should drive the black king back. It cannot go to the center:  5...Ke7  6.Qa3+  Ke8  7.Qb4  ⨀ +- }
5... Kg7 6. Qxd5 exd5+ { 6...f5+  7.Ke5  exd5  8.g5  +- } 7. Kxd5
{ Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 13-45 } *

