{ 13/3. V. Khenkin, 1982 } 1... f6+
{ All rook retreats lose:  1...Rf2?  2.Qh6+  Kg8  3.Qh4  Re2  4.Kh6  +- or @@StartFEN@@5Q2/5p1k/6p1/6K1/6P1/8/8/5r2 b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Rf3?  2.Qh6+  Kg8  3.Qh1!  Re3  4.Kh6  +- }
2. Kh4
{ 2...Rf3  is tempting, because Black, after the forced continuation  3.Qe7+  Kh6  4.g5+  fxg5+  5.Qxg5+  Kh7  , is close to the drawnGuretzky-Cornitz position @@StartBracket@@Diagram 13-21@@EndBracket@@: all he needs is to play Rf5 when the king is on the seventh or eighth rank.  However, he fails to reach it: White plays  6.Qe7+  Kh6  7.Qe5!  Kh7  8.Qc7+  Kh6  9.Kg4  Rf5  10.Qe7!  ⨀  Rh5  11.Qf8+  Kh7  12.Qf7+  Kh6  13.Qg8  Rg5+  14.Kf4  Rf5+  15.Ke4  forcing the black king ahead and achieving the winning position fromDiagram 13-23 @@StartBracket@@Dvoretsky@@EndBracket@@. }
2... g5+ 3. Kg3 Rf4 4. Qf7+ Kh6
{ Diagram 16-100   His unfavorably placed king betrays White.  5.Qg8  Rf1  is useless. The king can break through to freedom only by: }
5. Kg2 Rxg4+ 6. Kf3 Rf4+ { 6...f5!?  Dvoretsky. } 7. Ke3 Rh4 8. Qxf6+ Kh5 9.
Qg7 { 9.Qf7+  Kh6  ∆  10.--  Rf4= } 9... Rf4
{ TheGuretzky-Cornitz drawing position  (Diagram 13-24)  arises. } *

