{ 13/4. L. Katsnelson, 1971 } 1. Re6 Nc4+ 2. Kb5
{ Both  2.Kb7?  Rg7+  ∆ 3...Re7 -+  and  2.Ka6?  Rg6!  -+  are inaccurate. }
2... Ne5 3. Rxe5 Rg5 4. Bf5 Rxf5 5. Rxf5 e1=Q 6. Rxf8+ Kh7 7. Rf7+
{ 7.Rf3?  is premature in view of  7...Qf1+  ∆ 8...Qxg2. He should decoy the king to the g-file first. }
7... Kh6 8. Rf6+ Kh5 9. Rf5+ Kg4 10. Rf3
{ The g2-pawn is indirectly protected. } 10... Qc1
{ Diagram 16-101   The outcome of the fight now depends on whether Black succeeds in stalemating the white king, putting him in zugzwang. This danger is quite real as the following analysis shows:  11.Ka4?  Qb2  12.Ka5  Qb7  13.Ka4  Qb6  14.Ka3  Qb5  15.Ka2  Qb4  16.Ka1  Qd2  17.Kb1  Kg5!  18.Ka1  Qc2  ⨀ -+ And if @@StartFEN@@8/8/8/1K6/6k1/5R2/5PP1/2q5 w - - 9 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Kb6?  Qc4  12.Ka5  Qc5+  13.Ka4  Qb6  etc. }
11. Kb4 Qc6 12. Kb3 Qc5 13. Kb2 Qc4 14. Kb1 Kg5
{ 14...Qe2  15.Rg3+  with a perpetual check: the king cannot step on the e-file. }
15. Kb2 Kh6 16. Rh3+ { 16.Kb1?  Qf1+ } 16... Kg6 17. Rf3 { Draw. } *

