{ Other Material Relations   In this chapter we shall discuss various types of endgames with non-standard material relations. We will be brief because their consequent theory is not yet fully developed.  Often one can find a variety  (rich or poor)  of endgame studies and examples from practical play which are not systematized nor coordinated well enough. And even when the theory of a certain type of ending is developed, there is no sense in going deeply into it because the analyses are mostly complicated and perplexing, while the probability of their practical use is utterly unlikely. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 14 – Other Material Relations"]
[Black "Two Extra Pieces"]
[Result "*"]

{ Two Extra Pieces    Checkmating with Bishop and Knight    I was unsure whether this subject should be included in the book, because the mating technique with a bishop and a knight against a lone king is explained in every tutorial for beginners. However, my experience as a chess trainer finally put an end to these doubts because I have seen how many chess players, including very strong ones, either missed learning this technique at an appropriate time or had already forgotten it.  Therefore they risk presenting their opponents with a half-point  (and this has happened more than once)  , particularly under modern time controls when checkmating must often be performed in severe time trouble. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 14 – Other Material Relations"]
[Black "Checkmating with Bishop and Knight 14-1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/1k6/8/1B1N4/4K3/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ The king can be checkmated only in a corner of the bishop's color.  The plan for the stronger side is obvious: first the enemy king is driven to an edge @@StartBracket@@this stage is simple but the king naturally aims to reach a safe corner@@EndBracket@@. Thereafter the king is forced to a proper corner where mate is possible.  This is the type of position that the stronger side aims for. Notice that White's pieces have built  a barrier  that holds the black king in the corner. What remains is only to drive the king into the corner. }
1. Ke5 Kc8 2. Ke6 Kd8 3. Kd6 { Zugzwang. } 3... Kc8 4. Ke7 Kb7 5. Kd7 Kb8 6.
Ba6 Ka7 7. Bc8 Kb8 8. Kd8 Ka7 9. Kc7 Ka8 10. Ne7 Ka7 11. Nc6+ Ka8 12. Bb7# *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 14 – Other Material Relations"]
[Black "Checkmating with Bishop and Knight 14-2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "7k/8/5K2/5BN1/8/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ And this is how the king is driven from one corner to the other. } 1. Nf7+
Kg8 2. Be4 Kf8 3. Bh7 Ke8 4. Ne5 Kd8
{ 4...Kf8  makes White's task easier:  5.Nd7+  Ke8  6.Ke6  Kd8  7.Kd6  Ke8  8.Bg6+  Kd8  9.Nc5  Kc8  10.Be8  Kd8  11.Bb5  Kc8  12.Bd7+  Kb8  13.Kc6  etc.   @@StartSquare@@Ed. The key to the standard winning method is the Nf7–e5–d7–c5–b7 movement of the knight, forming a 'W' shape. To illustrate the maneuver:  @@StartFEN@@2k5/8/3K2B1/2N5/8/8/8/8 w - - 18 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Bf7  Kd8  11.Nb7+  Kc8  12.Kc6  Kb8  13.Kb6  @@StartBracket@@now the king is in the correct position, a knight's move away from the right corner@@EndBracket@@  13...Kc8  14.Be6+  Kb8  15.Bd7  @@StartBracket@@the defending king is confined to the right corner@@EndBracket@@  15...Ka8  16.Nc5  Kb8  17.Na6+  Ka8  18.Bc6#  @@EndSquare@@ }
5. Ke6 Kc7
{ The king has broken loose from the edge of the board, but only for a while. White, with two accurate moves, creates a barrier, and locks the king in the corner. }
6. Nd7 Kc6 7. Bd3 Kc7 8. Bb5 Kb7 { 8...Kd8  9.Nf6  Kc7  10.Nd5+ } 9. Kd6 Kc8
10. Nf6 { 10.Nc5!?  Kd8  11.Nb7+  Kc8  12.Kc6 } 10... Kd8 11. Nd5
{ And we have come to the position of the previous diagram. } *

