{ Checkmating with Two Knights   Driving the king to the edge of the board is an easy task. Alas, you can only stalemate it thereafter, not checkmate, but three knights will win against a single knight.   However  if the defender has a pawn, and this pawn is not too advanced, and it is blocked with one of the knights, an eventual win is quite possible,  although the winning process is very difficult; it may require dozens of precise moves.   As the Russian study composer Troitsky proved in the beginning of the 20th century, a knight together with a king can drive the solitary king either to a corner or towards the "spare" knight @@StartBracket@@the one that is blocking the pawn@@EndBracket@@. Thereafter, the spare knight joins the hunt, and mate is delivered with its help. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 14 – Other Material Relations"]
[Black "Checkmating with Two Knights 14-3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "7k/8/4K3/5N2/8/3N1p2/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ A. Troitsky  From this diagram, play begins: } 1. Nf2 Kg8 2. Ke7 Kh7
{ 2...Kh8?  3.Kf7  Kh7  4.Ne4  f2  5.Nf6+  Kh8  6.Nh4  f1=Q  7.Ng6# } 3. Kf7
Kh8 4. Kg6 Kg8 5. Ng7
{ Troitsky's standard maneuver that enables the knight's transfer to e6, where this piece will be more dangerous for the black king. }
5... Kf8 6. Kf6 Kg8 7. Ne6 Kh7 8. Kg5 Kg8
{ 8...Kh8  9.Kg6  Kg8  10.Ng4  f2  11.Nf6+  Kh8  12.Ng5  f1=Q  13.Nf7# } 9. Kg6
Kh8 10. Kf7 Kh7 11. Ng4 f2 12. Nf8+ Kh8 13. Nf6 f1=Q 14. Ng6#
{ The pawn was very far advanced; therefore, White managed to deliver checkmate because the black monarch was already locked in a corner close to f2-knight. If the king had more freedom it would run to a8, and White's knight cannot reach that corner in time. }
*

