{ Rook and Bishop vs. Rook    Without Pawns   An illustration of the dangers fatal to the defender when his king is pressed to the edge of the board is the following position that was known as early as the 18th century.  Philidor, 1749 }
1. Rf8+ Re8 2. Rf7 { ∆ 3.Ra7 } 2... Re2
{ 2...Kc8  loses rapidly:  3.Ra7  Rd8+  4.Kc6  Kb8  5.Rb7+  Ka8  6.Rb1  Ka7  7.Kc7  . }
3. Rh7
{ Zugzwang.   An important waiting move. The black rook must leave the second rank where it stands best. The following line proves that the 3rd rank is the worst for the rook:  3...Re3  4.Rd7+  Kc8  5.Ra7  , while after  4...Ke8  5.Ra7  Kf8  6.Rf7+  Ke8  7.Rf4  (8.Bc6+ is threatened.)   If Black tries to prevent the back-rank mate with  7...Rd3  , then  8.Rg4  , and if @@StartFEN@@4k3/8/3K4/3B4/5R2/4r3/8/8 b - - 13 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Kd8  8.Be4!  (the point - Black has no check along the d-file)  8...Ke8  9.Bc6+  . }
3... Re1 4. Rb7
{ These alternate threats from both wings are typical for this sort of position. If  4...Kc8  ,  5.Rb2  Rd1  6.Rh2  Kb8  7.Ra2  is decisive. }
4... Rc1 { Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 14-11 } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 14 – Other Material Relations"]
[Black "Rook and Bishop vs. Rook Without Pawns 14-11"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "3k4/1R6/3K4/3B4/8/8/8/2r5 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Philidor, 1749  (continued) } 1. Bb3
{ The key move! If the black rook were standing on the second rank, a check from d2 could follow, while now Black must place his rook on the unfavorable third rank. }
1... Rc3
{ If  5...Kc8  then  6.Rb4  Kd8  7.Rh4  Kc8  8.Bd5  , while after @@StartFEN@@3k4/8/3K4/8/7R/1B6/8/2r5 b - - 5 3@@EndFEN@@  7...Re1  8.Ba4  (there is no saving check along the d-file again)  8...Kc8  and now the fastest win is  9.Rb4  +- @@StartBracket@@  9.Bc6  Rd1+  10.Bd5  Kb8  11.Ra4  wins also.@@EndBracket@@ }
2. Be6 Rd3+ 3. Bd5 Rc3 4. Rd7+ Kc8 { 8...Ke8  9.Rg7 } 5. Rh7 Kb8 6. Rb7+ Kc8 7.
Rb4 Kd8 8. Bc4 Kc8 9. Be6+
{ And mate in two.  Not all positions with the king on the edge are of course lost. But the line between a draw and a loss is quite narrow; it can be easily crossed. }
*

