{ van der Weide − Marovic, Amsterdam 1967  (continued)   The defensive scheme when the kings are not on the same file, as in Philidor's position, but on neighboring files, was examined in the first half of the 19th century by József Szen. You should direct your attention to it when your king is cut off along a rank or file on the edge.   It is useful to know that the position is drawn if the pieces are moved one or two files to the right, while moving them further to the left loses because they are too near the edge of the board. }
1... Rb7 2. Rc5
{ Safer is  4.Rc3+!  Bd3  5.Rc8  , and if  5...Rh7  , then  6.Kc1  . } 2... Kd3
3. Ke1
{ Not there!   After  5.Kc1  it is not obvious how Black is going to make any progress. }
3... Rf7 4. Rc8
{ Only  6.Ra5!  or  6.Rb5!  avoids defeat.   Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 14-14 }
*

