{ In a practical game one can usually avoid danger by means of orientation at the “Cochrane position” or by using “a defense along the seventh rank.”   Both these techniques can be seen from the following instructive example.  Timman – Lutz, Wijk aan Zee 1995 }
1... Ra4+ 2. Bd4 Kg5 3. Rg7+ Kh4
{ @@StartBracket@@Rather than  3...Kh5?  4.Kf5  . @@EndBracket@@ This is called the Cochrane position – the safest defensive method when the king is already pressed to the edge. The rook pins the bishop and does not allow the hostile king to come closer. If @@StartFEN@@8/6R1/8/8/r2BK2k/8/8/8 w - - 5 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Rd7  @@StartBracket@@∆ 5.Kf4@@EndBracket@@, then  4...Kg4  . In case of the waiting attempt  4.Rg8  , Black follows the same policy with  4...Rb4  . }
4. Ke5 Kh3
{ The king escapes from a bishop check in advance, and moves in the opposite direction from the white king. If White had played @@StartFEN@@8/6R1/8/8/r2BK2k/8/8/8 w - - 5 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Ke3  , the reply would have been  4...Kh5! }
5. Rg1 Rb4 6. Be3 Rg4
{ This is the point! In order to bring his king closer, White had to move his bishop away, and Black takes advantage of this circumstance immediately. By offering the rook exchange, he releases his king from the edge. }
7. Ra1 Kg2 8. Bf4 Rg8 9. Ra2+ Kf3 10. Ra3+ Ke2 11. Ke4 Re8+ 12. Be5 Re7 13.
Ra2+ Ke1
{ The Cochrane position has arisen again only rotated by 90 degrees.  Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 14-16 }
*

