[Black "Rook and Bishop vs. Rook Without Pawns 14-16"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/4r3/8/4B3/4K3/8/R7/4k3 w - - 0 14"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Timman − Lutz, Wijk aan Zee 1995  (continued) } 14. Kd4 Kf1 15. Bf4 Re2 16.
Ra8 Re7 17. Kd3 Kg2 18. Rf8 Re6 19. Rf7 Re8 20. Be3 Ra8 21. Bc5 Ra4 22. Ke3 Rg4
{ Black changes his defensive setup. After  22...Kg3!?  23.Rg7+  Kh4  24.Bd4  Kh5!  , he could reach the Cochrane position for the third time. }
23. Bd6 Rg6 24. Rf2+ Kh3 25. Be5 Kg4 26. Ke4 Kh5 27. Bf6 Kg4
{ We are observing “the defense along the seventh rank” that prevents pressing the king to the edge of the board. The rook is placed two squares away from the king, so that after  28.Rg2+  Kh5  , White has no time for  29.Kf5  .  It may seem that the waiting move @@StartFEN@@8/8/5Br1/8/4K1k1/8/5R2/8 w - - 28 28@@EndFEN@@  28.Rf1  puts Black in zugzwang, but here a stalemate bails him out:  28...Kh5  29.Kf5  Rg5+!  @@StartBracket@@this is why this technique works only on the seventh rank or the knight file@@EndBracket@@. The rook cannot be captured, while after  30.Ke6  Rg2  31.Rf4  Kg6  32.Rh4  Re2+  33.Be5  Rg2  34.Rh8  Rg4  , the defense along the seventh rank is recreated.   Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 14-18 }
*

