{ Timman − Lutz, Wijk aan Zee 1995  (continued)     After a few nonchalant moves Black’s position has become suspect. However, as Lutz pointed out, a draw could be still reached by means of  43...Rb1  44.Be5  Rf1+  or @@StartFEN@@8/7k/8/5KR1/1r3B2/8/8/8 b - - 0 43@@EndFEN@@  43...Rb6  44.Be5  Rg6!  45.Rh5+  Rh6  46.Rg5  Rg6!= }
43... Rb5+
{ A decisive error that caused ... an immediate agreement to a draw! The point is that the last pawn had been captured 53 moves ago, and “the rule of 50 moves” was duly applied. }
44. Be5 Rb6
{ 44...Ra5  45.Rh5+  Kg8  46.Kg6   44...Rb7  45.Rh5+  Kg8  46.Rh8+  Kf7  47.Rh7+   44...Kh6  45.Rg8  Rb7  46.Rg1 }
45. Rg7+ Kh6 46. Rg8 Kh5
{ ThePhilidor position, rotated by 90 degrees, could have arisen. The winning procedure is already known: }
47. Rg2 Rb4 48. Rg1 { Zugzwang, the rook is forced away from the b-file, etc. }
