{ Tragicomedies: Gufeld − Rahman, Calcutta 1994 } 1. g4
{ Curiously enough, precisely this position  (with reversed colors)  happened in Gufeld’s earlier game versus Honfi @@StartBracket@@Kislovodsk 1968@@EndBracket@@. In that game Gufeld found the correct idea; he realized that the advance g2-g4 is premature and chose another plan – a rook transfer to the f-file.   That game continued  1.Ke7  Re5+  2.Kd6  Rf5  3.Ra7  Rf6+  4.Kc5  Rf2  5.Ra2   5.Ra3  Kh6  6.Rf3?  Rxg2  5...Rf1  6.Ra3  Re1   6...Kh6  7.Rf3  Rxf3  8.Bxf3  Kg5  9.Bd5  f5  10.Bf7  Kf4  11.Bxg6  Kg3  12.Bxf5  Kxg2  13.Kd5  Kg3  14.Ke5  Kh4  15.Kf6  +-  7.Kd6  Re2  8.Rf3  and Black, like in the Suba-Gurevich endgame, had to push his f-pawn; gradually, this fact caused his loss. After 25 years, Gufeld had forgotten his conclusions drawn during that earlier game; he pushed his g-pawn prematurely and missed a win.   The plan with g2-g4 is nevertheless good, only White should bring his king back beforehand. For example,  3.Rc7  @@StartBracket@@instead of 3.Ra7@@EndBracket@@  3...Rf6+  4.Ke5  Rf5+  5.Ke4  Rf2  6.Ke3  Rf5  7.Bc4!  @@StartBracket@@from here the bishop denies the black rook the important f1-square@@EndBracket@@  7...Kf8   7...Re5+  8.Kd4  Rf5  9.Ke4  Rf2  10.g4  8.g4  hxg4  9.hxg4  Rf6   9...Re5+  does not help, either:  10.Kd4  Re7  11.Rxe7  Kxe7  12.Ke5  f6+  13.Kd5  Kf7  14.Kd6+  and 15.Ke6.  10.Ke4  @@StartBracket@@the threat is 11.g5 and 12.Rxf7+@@EndBracket@@  10...g5  11.Ke5  Rf4  12.Bd3!  Rxg4  13.Kf6  +- @@StartBracket@@the final part of this line was suggested by Yanvarjov@@EndBracket@@.   In Gufeld’s opinion, the move  1.g3?!  wins even more rapidly because of zugzwang: if  1...Rf2  , then  2.Ke8  Re2+  3.Re7  +-. Neither  1...Kf8  2.g4  hxg4  3.hxg4  Rf4  4.g5  Rf5  5.Rxf7+  Rxf7  6.Bxf7  , nor  1...Kg8  2.g4  hxg4  3.hxg4  Rf4  4.Rxf7!  Rxf7  5.Ke8  +- helps.  However, he did not take into consideration the strongest reply,  1...Rg5!  , which makes White’s task considerably more difficult, and perhaps even impossible:  2.Rxf7+  Kh6  3.Be6  Rxg3  4.Ke7  Kg5  . And if @@StartFEN@@3K4/5R2/4B1pk/7p/8/6rP/8/8 w - - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.h4  Rd3+  5.Ke7  Rd4= }
1... hxg4 2. hxg4 Rf4 3. g5
{ It seems that a general exchange on f7 is inevitable. In reality, Black has two possibilities to avoid it: }
3... Rg4
{ White's last pawn must perish. Another good method was  3...Rf5  4.Rxf7+  Kh8!  5.Rxf5  gxf5  6.Ke7  Kg7  7.Bf7  f4  8.Bh5  f3= }
*

