{ Mark Tseitlin – Finkel, Beersheba 1996  In this position, the characteristic difference  (in comparison with those we have seen previously)  is the position of the black h-pawn – here it is far less favorable. First, Black does not have the familiar plan with g6-g5-g4 followed by a transition to a pawn endgame. Second, after an exchange of rooks, White will be able to exchange a pair of pawns without any problem, and Black’s remaining h-pawn will be quite useless against the king in the safe corner h1.   White could achieve a draw by playing  1.Kg1!  , for example  1...Bd4  2.Kg2  Rf6  3.Kg1  Rb6  4.Kg2  Rb2  5.Rxb2  Bxb2  6.g4  hxg4  7.Kg3  Bc1  8.Kxg4  Bh6  9.f4  and 10.h5= @@StartBracket@@Ch. Lutz@@EndBracket@@. }
1. Kf1 Bxf2
{ All of a sudden, it becomes obvious that 2. Rxf2 is bad in view of: } 2. Rxf2
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed. the game continued:@@EndSquare@@  2.Kg2  Bb6  3.Rb2  Bd4  4.Ra2  Ke4  5.Re2+  Be3  6.Ra2  Rd5  7.Ra4+  Kf5  8.Kf3  Bd4  9.Ra3  Be5  White resigned. }
2... Ke3 3. Rxf5 gxf5 4. Kg2 Ke2 { Black wins. } *

