{ An Extra Bishop or Knight with Queens or Minor Pieces   Let us first discuss positions without pawns.  A bishop and a knight can win against a knight only in exceptional cases, and all the more so against a bishop.  But two bishops can practically always cope with a knight.  Kling and Horwitz  (1851)  thought that this position was drawn. As a matter of fact, the knight is quite favorably placed on b7 for defensive purposes. Only in 1983 did computer analysis show that this defensive setup could be destroyed without permitting its restoration in another corner. If both sides play this endgame perfectly, the winning process lasts more than 50 moves; it is too complicated to reproduce it here.  A queen and a minor piece cannot, generally speaking, win against a queen. But exceptions are not so rare with this material: an attack against the king can lead to mate or to a win of the queen.  From the wide variety of positions with pawns, I would like to distinguish those with bishops of opposite colors. It turns out that the drawish tendencies typical in "pure" cases of such bishops  (i.e., with bishops of opposite color and no other pieces)  , are valid here too, helping the weaker side to survive even when a piece down. Two examples of this sort follow. }
1. -- *

