{ Beliavsky – Dolmatov, USSR ch, Minsk 1979    After the natural-looking  1...Rh8  2.Nf2!  Rxh2  3.bxa4  , and if @@StartFEN@@7r/5pk1/5p2/2p5/pp6/1P1B1KP1/P4N1P/8 b - - 2 2@@EndFEN@@  2...axb3  3.axb3  Rxh2  4.Ne4  , the position would remain static; it is usually favorable for the side with two pieces. White would then have had winning chances.  Dolmatov found an amazing resource. }
1... c4 2. Bxc4 { If  2.bxc4  then  2...Rb8!? } 2... Rc8
{ The threat @@StartFEN@@2r5/5pk1/5p2/8/ppB5/1P3KPN/P6P/8 b - - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Rxc4!  4.bxc4  b3  5.axb3  a3  forces White to remove his bishop from c4. }
3. Bd3 a3
{ White must now beware of both @@StartFEN@@2r5/5pk1/5p2/8/1p6/pP1B1KPN/P6P/8 b - - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Rc1  ∆  5.--  Ra1  and  4...Rc3  ∆  5.--  Rxb3  . Black has seized the initiative. }
