{ Miles − Kindermann, 1983  (continued) } 9. Be4+ Kf7
{ Diagram 14-28   As Stefan Kindermann pointed out, an easy win could have been achieved by  9...Kh6  10.Kf5  Rg2  11.Bb4  h3  12.Kf6  Kh5  13.Bg6+  Kh4  14.Be1+  Rg3  . And if @@StartFEN@@8/8/7k/4K1p1/4Bp1p/5P2/7r/4B3 w - - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Kf6  h3  11.Bb4  Re2  12.Bg6  Re6+!  13.Kxe6  Kxg6  . Now White finds a clever method to stubbornly resist. }
10. Bxh4 gxh4 { 10...Rxh4?  11.Kf5  Rh6  12.Kxg5  Rf6  13.Bf5= } 11. Kxf4 Rg2
12. Bf5 Kf6 13. Bh3 Rg1 14. Bg4
{ There were opinions @@StartBracket@@before tablebases@@EndBracket@@ that this position is drawish. However, Dolmatov suggested an uncomplicated plan that could bring Black victory. With  14...Rg3!  , he chained the white king to the f4-square @@StartBracket@@if the king retreats, then h4-h3 wins at once@@EndBracket@@. Thereafter, the black king marches into the hostile camp:  ...Ke7-d6-d5-d4, etc. }
14... Rb1 15. Bh3 Rb4+ 16. Ke3 Ke5 17. Bg4 Rb3+ 18. Kf2 Kf4 19. Kg2 Rb2+ 20.
Kh3 Kg5 21. Bc8 Rb1 22. Kg2 Kf4 23. Bg4 Rc1 24. Kh2 Rc7 25. Kh3 Rc2 26. Bd7 Rc3
27. Bg4 Kg5 28. Kg2
{ And now Black could still win easily with  28...Rc2+  29.Kh3  Rf2  , zugzwang, but he did not find the winning plan and the game soon ended in a draw. }
