{ Alexandria – Chiburdanidze, Borzhomi/Tbilisi wm  (4)  , 1981  The game was adjourned in this position. The minor pieces are stronger than the rook here, but, as analysis has shown, White’s advantage is not sufficient for a win against a precise defense. }
1... Kd7
{ An excellent maneuver that emphasizes the unfortunate position of the white knight. Black will use the time that must be wasted on bringing it into play to set up counterplay on the queenside by means of ...b6-b5. Black’s main goal is to exchange as many pawns as possible. An immediate attack against the e-pawn was much weaker.   After  1...Rf4?  2.e5  Kd7  3.Kg3  Ra4  4.Nd6  Ke6  5.Kh4  , Black loses because of zugzwang:  5...Kd5  6.Nc8!  Kc6  7.Ne7+  Kd7  8.Nd5  Kc6  9.Nf6  b5  10.Kg3!  b4  11.e6!  , or  5...Rf4  6.Ne8!  Kf5  7.Ng7+  Kg6  8.e6  Re4  9.a4!  c4  10.Bd4!  Kh7  11.Bf6  Kg6  12.e7  .   If Black plays  1...Re3?  , then  2.Nc7+!  Kd6  3.Ne8+!  Ke6  4.Ng7+  Kd7  5.e5!  And if @@StartFEN@@4N3/8/1p1k4/2p5/4P1p1/P1B1r3/1P4K1/8 b - - 4 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Ke7  4.Nf6  Ke6  5.Nd5!  Rxe4  6.Nxb6  with excellent winning chances. }
2. e5 Kc6 3. Nd6 b5 4. Kg1
{ A clever trap. The natural-looking  4...Rf4?  @@StartBracket@@∆ 5...b4@@EndBracket@@ would be refuted by  5.e6!!  Kxd6  6.Be5+! }
4... Rg3+ 5. Kf2 Rd3 6. Kg2 { 6.Ne4  b4!  7.axb4  cxb4  8.Bxb4  Rd4 } 6... Rf3
{ Rather than  6...Re3?!  7.Nf5  . } 7. Ne8 Re3 8. Nf6
