{ Tragicomedies: Timman – Karpov, Bugojno 1980  One pair of rooks will certainly be exchanged, but how can White do it favorably? }
1. f3
{ A grave positional error based on a tactical oversight. Timman planned to exchange pawns after  1...Nd6  2.Rxe7  Bxe7  3.h4!  gxh4  4.Re5   4.Rxh5  immediately also draws. If  4...f5  5.g4  or  5.Kh3  , but not  5.gxh4?  Bf6  , trapping the rook with  6.--  Kg6  .  4...Kf6  5.Rxh5=  , but underestimated Black’s strong reply. }
1... Nc5 2. Rxe7 Bxe7 3. Ra7
{ After  3.f4  gxf4  4.gxf4  f5  @@StartBracket@@∆ ...Kf6, ...Bd6, ...Ne6@@EndBracket@@, the f4-pawn is lost. }
3... Bd6
{ The erroneous advance of the f-pawn has weakened the dark squares, and White’s position is hopeless now. }
4. Ra8 h4 5. gxh4 gxh4 6. Kf2 Ne6 7. Ra1 Bg3+ 8. Ke3 Nf4 9. Rh1 Kf6 10. Ke4 Ke6
11. Kd4 Kf5 12. Kc3 Ne6 13. Kd3 Kf4 14. Ke2 Ng5
{ White resigned. Of course, not  14...Nd4+  15.Kd3  Nxf3??  16.Rf1  ∆ Ke2.   Ed. note: analyzed in the next variation → Diagram 14-33 }
