[White "Chapter 14 – Other Material Relations"]
[Black "Rook vs. Two Minor Pieces 14-33"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/4rpk1/5b2/R5pp/4n3/6PP/4RPK1/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Tragicomedies: Timman − Karpov, Bugojno 1980  (analysis)     Let us try to improve White’s defense. The attempt to force pawn exchanges by means of  1.h4?  gxh4  2.Rxh5  should be rejected at once in view of the counterstroke  2...Nxg3!  3.Rxe7  Nxh5  -+. The choice should be made between  1.Ra4  and  1.Kf3  .   Timman recommends  1.Ra4!?  and if  1...Nd6  , then  2.Rxe7  Bxe7  3.f4!  @@StartBracket@@  3...g4  is met by  4.hxg4  hxg4  5.f5  . @@EndBracket@@ But  1...Nc5!  is better:  2.Rxe7  Bxe7  3.Ra7  Bd6  , and if  3.Rc4  Kg6  . In case Black takes the a4-rook instead, @@StartFEN@@8/4Rpk1/5b2/2n3pp/R7/6PP/5PK1/8 b - - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nxa4  3.Rc7  Nc3  4.Kf3  .  This position is certainly better for White than that from the actual game, but still not completely safe. Timman demonstrates that the following disposition of Black’s forces can be successful against White’s passive defense: the pawn goes to f6, bishop to e5, knight to f5, and thereafter ...h5-h4 follows. It is not clear whether White can prevent this setup by active measures. }
1. Kf3 g4+ 2. hxg4
{ Timman condemns 1.Kf3!?, but after 1...g4+! he only analyzes 2. hxg4, which is a mistake as we shall see. @@StartSquare@@Ed.  2.Kg2!  is analyzed next → Diagram 14-34@@EndSquare@@ }
2... Ng5+ { Diagram 14-33 } 3. Rxg5+ Bxg5 4. gxh5
{ The attempt to avoid the exchange of rooks by  4.Ra2  @@StartBracket@@instead of 4.gxh5@@EndBracket@@ would allow Black, by means of  4...h4!  , to execute the exchange of pawns in a more favorable way. White’s setup grows flimsier, and probably will not last.   First, let’s look at @@StartFEN@@8/4rpk1/8/6bP/8/5KP1/4RP2/8 b - - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Kh6?  5.Ra2!  Kxh5  .  Can Black convert his extra bishop to a win? We looked at a similar situation with Black’s pawn on the g-file – then Black retained real winning chances – among other things, there is the idea of pushing the pawn to g4, followed by the exchange of all the pieces at f2. With an f-pawn instead, Black has fewer resources, so the position looks drawn. However, as pointed out by Karsten Müller, the immediate exchange of rooks would lead to victory: }
4... Rxe2 5. Kxe2 Bc1
{ Followed by  6.--  Kh6  . Of course not @@StartFEN@@8/5pk1/8/6bP/8/6P1/4KP2/8 b - - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Kh6?  6.f4  ∆ 7.g4= }
*

