{ 14/2. H. Aloni, 1968 } 1. f5+
{ The active rook on the seventh rank ensures White's advantage. However, he must play energetically, otherwise Black limits the mobility of the rook with ...Nf7.   The idea of the rook sacrifice on b7 comes instantly as we have seen this idea already; see Diagrams2-9 and2-14. However, the immediate  1.Rxb7?  Nxb7  2.a6  is refuted by  2...Nd6  3.a7  Nc4+  and 4...Nb6.   If  1.Kd4?!  Nf7?  would be wrong in view of  2.Kc5  ∆ Kb6. Therefore,  1...Kd6  2.f5  Bf3  or  2...Bg4  and  3.Rxb7?  Nxb7  4.a6  is still wrong,  this time because of  4...c5+!  5.Ke3  Na5!  And after @@StartFEN@@8/1n6/P2k1p2/2p2P1p/1P1K2bP/8/1P6/8 w - - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Ke4  Kc6!  ∆  6.--  Nd6+  . }
1... Kd6 { 1...Kxf5?  2.Rd7 } 2. Kf2
{ The subtle king move makes it inevitable. The chosen square for the king is determined by the necessity to control e2 and f3.  2.Kf4?  Be2!   The rook sacrifice is still premature:  2.Rxb7?  Nxb7  3.a6  Na5!  4.a7  Nc4+  , while after @@StartFEN@@8/8/P1pk1p2/n4P1p/1P5P/4K3/1P6/3b4 w - - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4.bxa5  Kc7  . }
2... Bb3 { Diagram 16-102 } 3. Rxb7
{ The other pawn is less valuable:  3.Rxh5?  Nf7  4.Rh7  Ke7  ∆  5.--  Kf8  or @@StartFEN@@8/1p2kn1R/2p2p2/P4P2/1P5P/1b6/1P3K2/8 b - - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5.--  Bc2  . }
3... Bc4 { 3...Nxb7  4.a6  +- } 4. Rh7
{ From this point, there are many ways to win.  4.Ra7!?  c5  5.a6  is also strong, for example  5...cxb4  6.Rb7!   Rather than  6.Ra8?!  Nc6  7.a7  Bd5!  and the pawn cannot be promoted.  6...Nxb7  7.a7  , and if @@StartFEN@@3n4/1R6/P2k1p2/5P1p/1pb4P/8/1P3K2/8 b - - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bd5  7.Rxb4  or  7.Rb6+  with a decisive advantage. }
4... Nf7
{ Both  4...Bf7  5.a6  Kc7  6.a7  Kb7  7.Rh8  and @@StartFEN@@3n4/7R/2pk1p2/P4P1p/1Pb4P/8/1P3K2/8 b - - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Ke5  5.Rd7!  are hopeless. }
5. Rxh5 { 5.Ke3!? } 5... Ke5
{ Or  5...Ke7  6.Rh7  Kf8  7.Ke3  Kg8  8.Rxf7  +- } 6. b3 Bb5 7. Rh7 Nd6 8. h5
Nxf5 { 8...Kxf5  9.Rg7 } 9. h6 Ke6 10. Rb7 Nxh6 11. Rxb5 cxb5 12. a6
{ White wins. } *

