{ Queen vs. Various Pieces   A rook and a bishop or a rook and a knight  (without pawns)  draw easily against a queen if, of course, they are not so disunited that the opponent can rapidly win one of pieces.  Two knights can resist a queen successfully. They are best placed on squares adjacent to the king. Two bishops, curiously enough, are almost never able to draw against a queen, although the winning process is often complicated and requires many dozens of moves.  The only drawing position was discovered as early as the 18th century. @@StartSquare@@Ed. see → Diagram 14-37@@EndSquare@@ }
1. -- *

