{ G. Lolli, 1763 } 1. Qe7+ Kc8 2. Qe6+
{ If  2.Qd6  Kb7  3.Kc4  , Black should play  3...Ba7!  4.Qe7+  Kb8  with the idea 5...Bb6=, or even  4...Kb6=  , as @@StartFEN@@8/1k6/1bbQ4/8/2K5/8/8/8 b - - 5 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bc7?  loses to  4.Qe7  Kb6  5.Qb4+  Ka6  6.Kc5  . }
2... Kb7 3. Qd6 Ba7
{ 3...Bc7  4.Qe7  Kb6  is also playable; White does not have 5.Qb4+. } 4. Qe7+
Kb6 { Rather than  4...Kb8?  5.Ka5  +- } 5. Qd8+ Kb7 6. Ka5 Bc5
{ White is in zugzwang; every possible move allows the black bishop to return to b6. If White brings his king to e7, the bishop occupies the c7-square, with the same position. This defensive method saves Black only when his king is on b7 @@StartBracket@@or symmetrically on g7, b2, and g2@@EndBracket@@. }
