{ In practical situations  (with pawns on the board)  , one can often save a difficult position by means of a queen sacrifice or by letting an enemy pawn queen for the sake of building a fortress.  Let us come back to the position where we took a break when analyzing theBeliavsky-Dolmatov endgame @@StartBracket@@in the section “Rook versus Two Minor Pieces”@@EndBracket@@.  Beliavsky – Dolmatov, USSR ch, Minsk 1979  (analysis) }
1. Nf2 Rc1
{ 1...Rc3  is weaker because after  2.Ke3  , the sacrifice  2...Rxb3?  fails to  3.Nd1!  @@StartBracket@@  3...Kh6  still draws @@EndBracket@@  3...Rb2?  4.Nxb2  b3  5.Bb1!  +- If @@StartFEN@@8/5pk1/5p2/8/1p6/pPrBK1P1/P4N1P/8 b - - 3 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Rc1  , then  3.Kd2  Ra1  4.Bc2  Rxa2  5.Nd3= }
2. h4 { The pawn should leave the second rank. } 2... Ra1
{ 2...f5  is useless:  3.Bxf5  Rc3+  4.Kf4  Rxb3  5.Nd1!  And if @@StartFEN@@8/5pk1/8/5B2/1p5P/pP3KP1/P4N2/2r5 b - - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Ra1  4.Nd3  Rxa2  5.Nxb4  Rb2  6.Bc2= }
3. Bc4 Rxa2 4. Nd3 Rf2+
{ Or  4...Rd2  5.Nxb4  a2  6.Nxa2  with a draw. The idea behind h2-h4 is clear now – the endgame would have been hopeless without the h-pawn. }
5. Kxf2 a2 6. Nxb4 a1=Q 7. Nd3
{ White has the following setup in mind: Nf4, Bd5, Kg2, and Black can neither create mating threats nor attack the g3-pawn with his king and queen simultaneously.  Ed. note: analyzed in the next variation → Diagram 14-40 }
