Rxa3 Qxe4+ 12. Rf3
{ This is the position Chernin had aimed for from the very beginning. The win is an elementary matter because of Black’s pawn weaknesses. However even with a regular pawn structure @@StartBracket@@the f6-pawn is moved to g6@@EndBracket@@, as happened in Gurgenidze-Averbakh @@StartBracket@@USSR ch, Baku 1961@@EndBracket@@, White won by means of a double rook attack against the f7-pawn. }
12... Kg6 13. Ra6 Qd4 14. Rf4
{ The immediate  14.Raxf6+  was also playable, but this delay of the capture does no harm to White. }
14... Qd5+ 15. Kh2 Qd8 16. Rc6 Qe7 17. Ra6
{ Another way was  17.g4!?  hxg4  18.Kg3  @@StartBracket@@planning 19.Rcxf6+@@EndBracket@@  18...Kh5  19.Rf5+  and if @@StartFEN@@8/4qp2/2R2pk1/8/5RpP/6K1/5P2/8 b - - 1 18@@EndFEN@@  18...Qa3+  19.Kxg4  +- }
17... Qd8 18. Raxf6+ Qxf6 19. Rxf6+ Kxf6 20. Kh3 Kf5 21. f3 f6 22. Kg2
{ 22.g4+?  hxg4+  23.fxg4+  Kf4  ⨀= was premature. } 22... Kg6
{ Or  22...Ke5  23.g4  hxg4  24.fxg4  Kf4  25.Kh3  +- } 23. g4
{ Black resigned. } *

