{ 14/5. Yermolinsky-Kaidanov, USA ch, Long Beach 1993  The threat Rg5+ should be neutralized. }
1... Qd7
{ The correct defense.   Black played  1...Kg7?  because he failed to see the killing reply: after  2.Rg5+  Kf8  , White has  3.Rg6!  with a decisive doubling of the rooks in the f-file.  The game continued  3...e5  4.Rgf6  e4  5.Rxf7+  Kg8  6.Re7  @@StartBracket@@having won a pawn, the rooks regroup for attacking another pawn@@EndBracket@@  6...Qd3  7.Rf4  e3  8.Rfe4  Qc2+  9.Kh3  Qc8+  10.g4  Qc1  11.Rxe3  Qh1+  12.Kg3  Qg1+  13.Kf4  Qf2+  14.Kg5  Qd2  15.Kg6  Black resigned. }
2. Rg5+ Kh7
{ Rather than  2...Kh6?  3.Rf6+  Kh7  4.Rg4  e5  5.Rg5  +- White cannot win a pawn: if @@StartFEN@@8/3q1p1k/4p3/6R1/7P/6P1/5R1K/8 w - - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Rf6  , then  3...Qe7  . }
