{ A king’s advance is mostly directed to the center of the board, from which both wings are equally accessible. However this should not become a strict rule to follow blindly: in principle, a king’s place is wherever the position requires.  Taimanov – Ree, Wijk aan Zee 1981  White has an extra pawn and his rook is more active than Black’s, but how does he bring the advantage home? }
1. Ke2
{ The winning plan involves the king’s march to g3 in order to attack the g4-pawn, regardless of how far the king moves from the center.   The straightforward  1.Re4?!  Kf6!  2.Re5?  lets Black create enough counterplay to save the game after  2...a4!  3.Kd3  axb3  4.axb3  4...Rd8+  or  4...Rb8  5.Kc3  Rb4  . }
1... Rc7 2. Kf1 Rd7
{ Otherwise Kg2-g3 followed by either Rc3-e3-e5+ or a2-a3 and b3-b4. } 3. Rxc5+
Kxf4 4. Kg2 Rd2 5. Rxa5 Rc2 { 5...g3  6.Ra4+ } 6. Ra4+ Kg5 7. Rc4
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed. White temporarily sacrifices the a2-pawn to gain the g4-pawn in return, after a subsequent Kg3. Black will no longer have the check option on c3.@@EndSquare@@ }
7... Rxa2 8. Kg3 { Black resigned. } *

