[SetUp "1"]

{ Sometimes the route for a kings march should be prepared by means of pawn exchanges. This technique is called  'widening the beachhead.'   A. Yusupov, 1995  White has two active possibilities:   a. To create a distant passed pawn by means of f2-f4, g4-g5, and f4xg5; and   b. to widen the beachhead: the move g4-g5 is made when the f-pawn is still on f2, then the king goes to the e-pawn and, eventually, to the queenside.   However both these plans fail if started immediately:  1.f4?  Kg7  2.g5  hxg5  3.fxg5  e5  4.Kh4  Kg6  5.Kg4  e4  6.Kf4  e3  7.Kxe3  Kxg5  8.Ke4  Kf6  9.Kd5  Ke7=   1.g5?  hxg5  2.Kxg5  Kg7  3.Kf4  Kf6  4.Ke4  e5  5.Kd5  Kf5  6.b4   If  6.f3  then both  6...Kf6  and  6...Kf4  7.Ke6  Kxf3  8.Kxe5  Ke3  9.Kd6  Kd3=  are good.  6...b5  7.Kc5  a6  8.Kd5  e4  9.a3  Kf4  10.Ke6  Kg4 !  11.Ke5  Kf3=  @@StartBracket@@  12.Kf5?  e3  . @@EndBracket@@  Before White clarifies the situation on the kingside, he should strengthen his position on the queenside to the utmost by means of a pawn advance. }
1. b4 Kg7
{ Black has to wait.   If  1...b5?  the plan with the distant passed pawn decides:  2.f4!  Kg7  3.g5  hxg5  4.fxg5  e5  5.Kh4!  Kf7  6.Kg3!  (the king detours around the mined g4-square)  6...Kg6  7.Kg4  ⨀  e4  8.Kf4  e3  9.Kxe3  Kxg5  10.Kd4  and Black's queenside pawns perish as a consequence of the weakening advance ...b7-b5. }
2. b5 Kh7 3. a4 Kg7 4. a5 Kh7 5. b6 axb6 6. axb6 Kg7
{ Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 15-4 } *

