{ Böhm – Timman, Amsterdam 1977    1.Ra1?  Ra8  2.Re1  Ke3  followed by  3.--  Rxa7  is quite hopeless for White. }
1. Ra6 e5 2. Ra1 Ra8 3. Re1 Kf3 4. Kd5
{ This is the reason for 1.Ra6!. The white king has enough time to eliminate the e5-pawn. If  4...e4  then  5.Rxe2  . }
4... Rxa7 5. Kxe5
{ The white king is looking at both wings. The black rook can attack any one of the pawns but then the king will support the remaining pawn. }
5... Rb7 6. g4 Kxg4 7. Ke4
{ 7.Rxe2  Re7+  8.Kd6  Rxe2  9.b5=  is also possible. } 7... Re7+ 8. Kd5
{ Draw. } *

