{ The most characteristic case of 'chasing after two birds' is  Réti’s idea:  the king overtakes the hostile passed pawn after initially being out of its square. The necessary tempi are gained by counterthreats @@StartBracket@@supporting ones own passed pawn or attacking enemy's pieces@@EndBracket@@.  M. Zinar, 1982    The trivial continuation  1.Kf6?  Kxc6  2.Kg5  Kb6  3.Kh6  Ka5  4.Kxh7  Kb4  5.Kg6  Kxc4  6.Kf5  loses. The simplest is  6...Kc3  7.Ke4  c4  8.a4  Kb4  -+ here.  But  6...Kd5  7.a4  c4  8.a5  c3  9.a6  Kc6  , or @@StartFEN@@8/8/8/2pk1K2/8/8/P7/8 w - - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Kf4  Kd4!  ('shouldering')  is also strong:  8.Kf3   After  8.a4  c4  9.a5  c3  Black promotes with a check.  8...Kd3!  9.Kf2  c4  10.Ke1  Kc2!  11.a4  c3  12.a5  Kb2  13.a6  c2  14.a7  c1=Q+  -+ And if White tries  9.a4  instead of 9.Kf2, then  9...c4  10.a5  c3  11.a6  c2  12.a7  c1=Q  13.a8=Q  Qh1+  . }
1. Kg7 h5 2. Kf6 h4 3. Ke5
{ Réti's maneuver! If  3...h3  ,  then  4.Kd6  h2  5.c7= } 3... Kxc6 4. Kf4 Kb6
5. Kg4 Ka5 6. Kxh4 { Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 15-7 }
*

