{ M. Zinar, 1982  (continued)   White has neither gained nor lost a tempo compared with the 1.Kf6? line, but the black pawn, because of its provoked advance, was captured on h4 rather than h7. From there the white king has an easier way back to defend. }
1... Kb4 2. Kg3 Kxc4 3. Kf2
{ 8.Kf4?  or  8.Kf3?  is wrong because of the shouldering  8...Kd3  similar to the 1.Kf6? line. }
3... Kc3 4. Ke2
{ The only move!   9.a4?  is premature in view of  9...Kb4  , while after @@StartFEN@@8/8/8/2p5/8/2k5/P4K2/8 w - - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  9.Ke1?  or  9.Ke3?  c4  the c-pawn promotes with a check. }
4... c4 5. a4 { Draw. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 15 – General Endgame Ideas"]
[Black "King's Activity 15-8"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/8/2p5/2K2k1p/p7/P7/7P/8 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ It is obvious that correct endgame strategy involves not only an activation of one's own king, but the prevention of the activation of the hostile king as well. We have already seen one of standard techniques −  shouldering  − in the previous example. Another instructive case follows:  Velea − Vidoniak, Romania 1992    1...Kg4?  leads only to a draw:  2.Kb4!  Kh3  3.Kxa4  Kxh2  4.Kb3!  h4  5.a4  h3  6.a5  Kg3  7.a6=  Black's own pawn on c6 turns out to be an obstacle. }
1... Ke4
{ A move with a double purpose!   Generally, the king intends to go to the queenside, but after  2.Kxc6  it will change direction:  2...Kf3!  3.Kb5   3.Kd5  h4  4.Kd4  Kg2  5.Ke3  Kxh2  6.Kf3  Kh3  -+  Black wins because his a-pawn has already entered the hostile half of the board.  3...h4  4.Kxa4  Kg2  5.Kb3  Kxh2  6.a4  Kg3  7.a5  h3  and White fails to queen his pawn because the c6-pawn does not exist anymore.   As Bologan has shown, @@StartFEN@@8/8/2p5/2K2k1p/p7/P7/7P/8 b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...h4!  also wins:  2.Kb4  c5+  or  2...Ke4  3.Kxa4  c5  4.Kb5  Kd4  5.a4  c4  6.a5  c3  7.a6  c2  8.a7  c1=Q  and after  9.a8=Q  almost every check forces a queen exchange.  Or  4.Kb3  Kd3  5.Kb2  (the defensive technique that we call 'pendulum' does not help here)  5...c4  6.Kc1  Kc3  -+ @@StartBracket@@the same situation as in the 2.Kxc6 Kf3 3.Kd5 line but with reversed wings@@EndBracket@@. }
2. h4 Kd3 3. Kb4
{ 3.Kxc6  Kc4!  -+  (shouldering)  , rather than  3...Kc3?  4.Kd5  Kb3  5.Kd4  Kxa3  6.Kc3= }
3... Kd4 4. Kxa4 Kc4
{ Shouldering again; the white king is being squeezed to the edge of the board.   4...c5?  is wrong in view of  5.Kb3  Kd3  6.Kb2  c4  7.Kc1  Kc3  8.a4  Kb4  9.Kc2=  And if @@StartFEN@@8/8/8/2p4p/7P/P2k4/1K6/8 b - - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Kd2  7.Kb3=  @@StartBracket@@a pendulum@@EndBracket@@. }
5. Ka5 c5 6. Kb6 Kd4 7. a4 c4 8. a5 c3 9. a6 c2 10. a7 c1=Q 11. a8=Q Qc5+
{ White resigned. After the inevitable queen exchange, his king is too far away from the kingside. }
*

[Event "?"]
