{ A king can be kept out of strategically important areas not only by the hostile king but by other pieces as well. A rook can  cut the king off , while other pieces can  create a barrier  @@StartBracket@@usually together with pawns@@EndBracket@@.  Ljubojevic – Xie Jun, Novi Sad ol 1990 }
1... Rf5
{ The most precise, as the white king will be unable to help his rook in its fight against the passed pawn, which will soon march unstoppably ahead with support from its own king. }
2. Ke3 Ke5 3. b3 Kf6 4. Ke4 Kg6 5. Rg1 Rf4+ 6. Ke5 Rb4 7. Rg3 g4
{ The king is cut off from the pawn along the rank now. } 8. Kd5 Rf4 9. Kc5 b4
10. Kb5 Kg5 11. Rg1 Kh4 12. Rh1+ Kg3 13. Kc5 Kg2 { White resigned. } *

