{ Another technique of immobilization is  pawns in the crosshairs:  the king is compelled to defend its own pawns.  Tukmakov – Veingold, USSR 1979    Black has only two pawns for a bishop, but for White to capitalize on his advantage is by no means simple. How should he proceed? His king is out of play; therefore  1.Re1  looks quite natural, but after  1...Rxe1+  2.Kxe1  Kc5  3.Kd2  Kd4  , followed by  ...a7-a5 and ...c6-c5, Black’s king is active. The corner square h8 is of the “wrong” color and this fact will be important in the event of massive pawn exchanges.   Sofia Polgar suggested a promising plan:  1.b4!?  followed by Ra1  (or Rc5-a5)  , Bf3-e2, Ra6+ and b4-b5. Tukmakov has found another plan: he still exchanged the rooks but in a more favorable way. }
1. Bh3 { 2.Bd7 is threatened. } 1... Re7
{ The advance  1...c5?!  just weakens Black’s position, offering new possibilities to the white bishop:  2.Bg2  Re5  3.f4  and if  2...Rd8  3.Ke2  , while after @@StartFEN@@4r3/p4ppp/1k6/2pp4/8/1P4P1/5PBP/2R2K2 b - - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d4  3.Bd5  +- }
2. Re1 Rxe1+
{ Tougher resistance was possible after  2...Rb7  3.Ke2  Kc5  or  3...Kc7  . White probably should have then played the sharp  4.Ra1  or  4.Kd2  . }
3. Kxe1 Kc5 4. Bd7
{ This is the point! By keeping the c-pawn in the crosshairs, White has prevented the activation of the black king. The rest is a rather simple process. }
4... a5 5. Kd2 Kd6 6. Be8 f6 7. h4 c5 8. Bf7 Ke5 9. Ke3 h6 10. f4+ Kd6 11. h5
c4 { Otherwise the white king goes to the a5-pawn. } 12. bxc4 a4 13. Kd4 dxc4
14. Kxc4 { Black resigned. } *

