{ Tragicomedies: Bronstein – Bareev, Rome 1990    White could easily equalize by activating his king, in spite of his pawn minus:  1.Kg3!  Kg7  2.Kf4  ∆ Ke5. In case of @@StartFEN@@6k1/5p2/1p3n2/p2p4/6P1/2N2PK1/1P6/8 b - - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...d4  2.Nb5  d3  3.Kf2=  Bronstein was an outstanding grandmaster, but his Achilles’ heel was always his endgame technique. For example, when he drew the world championship match against Botvinnik in 1951  (12:12)  , he lost five games – three of them from absolutely drawn endgames. Here he also commits an elementary technical error, forgetting to centralize his king at the proper moment. }
1. g5 d4 2. Nb5
{ Even here it is not too late to allow the knight to safely stop the pawn and centralize the king with  2.Nb1!  Nd7  3.Kg4  Nc5  4.Kf4  , which still draws. }
2... d3 3. Kg3
{ After  3.gxf6  d2  4.Nc3  b5!  5.Kg3  b4  6.Nd1  a4  7.Kf2  a3  , the a-pawn promotes. }
3... d2 { White resigned. The finish could be: } 4. Nc3 Nd5 5. Nd1 Kg7 6. f4
{ 6.Kf2  Kg6  7.Ke2  Kxg5  8.Kxd2  Kf4  and Black has an extra pawn and the much more active king. }
6... b5 7. Kf3 Kg6 { Black wins. } *

