{ 15/4. O. Pervakov, 1991 } 1. Kg1
{ The king must hasten to help the b6-pawn. We have already mentioned that the laws of Euclidean geometry are not valid on the chessboard: the king's path to c5 along the fractured line  (via g1)  is by no means longer than the direct route via g3.   On  1.Kg3?  Bd5  (∆ 2...Kb7)  2.Bxa6   2.Nc8  Kb7  3.Bg4  a5  4.Kf4  a4=  2...Bb7  3.Bc4!  Bh1!  Black holds. For example,  4.Nc8   Or  4.Kh2  Bf3!  5.Kg3  Bh1!  4...Kb7  5.Be6  Ka6!  6.Kf4  Bb7  7.Ke5  Bxc8  , and if @@StartFEN@@2N5/1b6/kP2B3/8/5K2/8/8/8 w - - 9 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bc4+  Ka5=  The cunning concept behind White’s initial move is becoming clear: the black bishop is now denied the important h1-square. }
1... Bd5
{ 1...a5  2.Nb5  is absolutely bad. If @@StartFEN@@k7/Nb6/pP6/8/8/8/4B3/6K1 b - - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Kb8  2.Kf2  a5  then the simplest reply is  3.Ke3  , but  3.Nb5  Ba6  4.Nd6  , or  3...Bd5  4.Nc3  Bb3  5.Bf3  a4  6.Nb1  Be6  7.Ke3  Bc8  8.Kd4  is also playable. }
2. Bxa6 Bb7 3. Bc4 { 3.Bd3  Bd5! } 3... Bf3 { 3...Be4  4.Nb5!  +- } 4. Kf2
{ The crucial tempo! } 4... Bh1 5. Be6 { Or  5.Nc8  Kb7  6.Be6 } 5... Kb7 6.
Nc8 { Diagram 16-106 } 6... Ka6
{ If  6...Kc6!?  @@StartBracket@@hoping for  7.Ke3?  Kc5  ∆  8.--  Bb7  =@@EndBracket@@, then @@StartFEN@@2N5/8/1Pk1B3/8/8/8/5K2/7b w - - 9 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bg4!  Kc5  8.Bf3  Bxf3  9.Kxf3  Kc6  10.Ke4  Kb7  11.Kd5  Kxc8  12.Kc6  Kb8  13.b7  +- }
7. Ke3 Bb7 8. Bc4+ Ka5 9. Kd4 Bxc8 10. Kc5
{ The rest is simple. The king goes to c7 and Black loses because the a6-c8 diagonal is too short. }
10... Bb7 11. Bb5 Bc8 12. Kc6 Kb4 { 12...Bd7+  13.Kc7  Bc8  14.Bf1  ⨀ } 13. Bf1
Bg4 14. Bg2 Bc8 15. Kc7 Kc5 16. Bf1 { Zugzwang. } *

