{ 15/5. P. Benko, 1981 } 1. Kb6
{ 1.b6?  Ng4  or  1...Nf3  2.b7  Ne5  leads to an immediate draw. Therefore White applies sharper tactics; his king will fight on two fronts simultaneously, supporting both passed pawns. }
1... Ng4 { 1...Kxf5  2.Kc7  +- } 2. Kc7 Ne3 { 2...Nf6  3.Kc6  +- } 3. Kd7
{ Rather than  3.Kd6?  Kxf5= } 3... Nc4 { 3...Nd5  4.Kd6  Nb6  5.Ke6  +- } 4.
Ke6
{ Diagram 16-107  This position resembles the endingSvidler-Anand  (Diagram 15-13)  , does it not? But while in that case the fight was over when the king joined the f-pawn, here it only enters the most crucial phase. }
4... Nb6 5. f6 Kg6 6. Ke7
{ 6.f7?  is not correct: after  6...Kg7  7.Ke7  Nd5+!  there is no win. Therefore White triangulates to cede Black the turn to move. }
6... Nd5+ 7. Kd6 Nb6 { 7...Nxf6  8.b6  +- } 8. Ke6 { Zugzwang. } 8... Kh7
{ A weaker reply is  8...Nc8  9.f7  Kg7  10.Kd7  Nb6+  11.Ke8  +-, while now immediate attempts to promote the f-pawn will fail. So the king first goes to another wing and only then returns to the kingside. }
9. Ke7 Nd5+ 10. Kd6 Nb6 11. Kc6 Nc4 12. Kd7 Kg6 { 12...Nb6+  13.Ke8!  +- } 13.
Ke7 { 13.Ke6?  Nb6 } 13... Ne5 { 13...Nb6  14.f7  +- } 14. b6
{ Or  14.Ke6  +-  Generally, a knight is a faster runner than the king, but one can get the opposite impression from this ending. }
*

