{ Gufeld – Kavalek, Marianske Lazne tt jr 1962 } 1... Rxd2+
{ Emms suggested another solution to the problem:  1...e4!  2.Rad1  Rd3!  3.Nc4  Rg1  is no better. If White tries @@StartFEN@@3r4/ppp4p/1bp1k3/5p2/4p3/BPP5/P2NKprP/R4R2 w - - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nc4  instead, then  2...f4  3.Nxb6  f3+  4.Ke3  Kf5!  @@StartBracket@@this zwischenzug is the point: 5...Rd3# is threatened@@EndBracket@@  5.Rad1  Rxd1  6.Rxd1  Rg1!  7.Kxf2  Rxd1  8.Nc4  Ra1  with an easy win. }
2. Kxd2 e4 3. Bf8
{ The following curious line, also by Emms, shows the mighty energy of connected passed pawns:  3.h4  f4  4.c4  Bd4  5.Rad1  f3  6.Kc2  e3  7.Rxd4  e2  8.Rdd1  Rg1!  9.Rxg1  fxg1=Q  10.Rxg1  f2  -+ }
3... f4 { Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 15-21 } *

