{ Gufeld − Kavalek, Marianske Lazne tt jr 1962  (continued) } 4. b4
{ Diagram 15-21 } 4... Rg5
{ White has prepared 5.Bc5 in order to interfere with the powerful b6-bishop. To prevent this, Kavalek sacrifices another exchange. This is a very aesthetic solution, but not the only way, as  4...e3+  also wins:  5.Ke2  Kf5  @@StartBracket@@∆ 6...Ke4@@EndBracket@@  6.Kf3  Rxh2  @@StartBracket@@∆ 7...Rh3+@@EndBracket@@  7.Rh1  e2!  8.Kxe2  f1=Q+!  9.Kxf1  Rxh1+  @@StartBracket@@Bologan@@EndBracket@@; or  5.Kd3  Ke5  6.Bc5  Bxc5  7.bxc5  b6  @@StartBracket@@Müller@@EndBracket@@ and White cannot keep the black passed pawns from advancing. }
5. Bc5 Rxc5 6. bxc5 Bxc5 7. Rab1 f3
{ An amazing position! A bishop with pawns turns out to be stronger than a pair of rooks. For example, if  8.Rh1  , then  8...Ke5  9.Rxb7  e3+  10.Kd3  e2  11.Rbb1  Be7!  12.Ke3  Bh4  and  13.--  e1=Q  . }
8. Rb4 Kf5 9. Rd4
{ The bishop is finally neutralized, but now the black king enters with decisive effect. }
9... Bxd4 10. cxd4 Kf4
{ White resigned. @@StartSquare@@Ed. essential information → 'This example demonstrates how dangerous  connected passed  pawns can be.'@@EndSquare@@ }
*

