{ @@StartSquare@@Ed. essential information → 'In many endings, a  distant passed pawn  can be also very important. Fighting against it can be a difficult matter, and even if one succeeds in stopping it, one often loses control of events on the opposite wing. The possibility of creating a distant passed pawn can often be of decisive importance in evaluating a position.'@@EndSquare@@  Lutikov − Gulko, Moscow 1982    White's only way to a draw was  1.e4!  Kg5  2.Kg3  ∆ 3.h4+  and if  1...Ke5  2.Kf3!   Rather than  2.Ke3?  g5  3.Kd3  Kf4  4.Kd4  Kg3  5.Ke5  Kxh3  6.Kf6  Kxg4  -+  2...Kd4  3.Kf4=  and @@StartFEN@@8/5p2/p5pp/1p2k3/1P2P1P1/P4K1P/8/8 b - - 2 2@@EndFEN@@  2...h5  3.gxh5  gxh5  4.Ke3=  In case of  2...g5  3.Ke3  f6  4.Kd3  Kf4  5.Kd4  Kg3  6.Kd5  Kxh3  7.Ke6  Kxg4  8.Kxf6=   This variation is probably rather hard to calculate. An easier task is to come to the conclusion that nothing else is promising. For example, after  1.h4?  Ke5  2.Kf3  both  2...g5  and  2...f5!?  win for Black,  e.g.  3.g5  h5  -+ and if  3.gxf5  Kxf5  creating a distant passed pawn. }
1. Kf3 Kg5
{ Again, the evaluation is rather obvious. After  2.Kg3  f5!  3.gxf5  Kxf5  or @@StartFEN@@8/8/p5pp/1p3pk1/1P4P1/P3P1KP/8/8 w - - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.h4+  Kf6  , Black gets a distant passed pawn; otherwise he brings his king to h4, and thereafter widens the beachhead with decisive effect. }
2. e4 Kh4 3. Kg2 f6
{ 3...g5?  is erroneous in view of  4.e5=  As Naumann has discovered, @@StartFEN@@8/5p2/p5pp/1p6/1P2P1Pk/P6P/6K1/8 b - - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...h5!?  4.gxh5  Kxh5  also wins, although the process is more complicated than in the actual game:  5.Kg3  f6  6.h4  g5  7.hxg5  fxg5  (Black has got a distant passed pawn)  8.e5  Kh6!  (the g6 and g4 squares are mined)  9.Kf3  Kg7  10.Ke4  Kg6!  11.Kd5  Kf7!  -+ }
4. Kh2 h5 5. gxh5 Kxh5 6. Kg3 g5 { Zugzwang. } 7. Kh2 Kh4 { 7...g4?  8.Kg3= }
8. Kg2 g4 { White resigned. } *

