{ A. Seleznev, 1923    Let us try the rook exchange:  1.Re2+?  Kd5  2.Rxe5+  Kxe5  3.Kf3  Kd5  4.Ke3  Kc4  5.Kd2  Kd5  6.Kd3  c4+  7.Ke3  Ke5  − a draw, because Black maintains the opposition.   The consequences of  1.c4?  are harder to calculate. Black plays  1...Ke3  2.Rd3+  Ke2  (3...Re4+ is threatened)  3.Kf4  Rh5  4.Ke4  Rg5  So how do we strengthen the position? White can get the d5-square for his king by means of  5.Rd6  Rh5  6.Re6  Kd2  7.Re5  but after  7...Rh4+  8.Kd5  Kxc2  9.Kxc5  Kd3  10.Rd5+  Kc3  his last pawn is lost.   But what if Black is on move? He will naturally play  1...Ke3  , but White can easily prevent it by moving his rook away. All Black's other moves will only worsen his position. }
1. Rd1 { Zugzwang. } 1... Re6
{ He cannot play  1...Ke3?  2.Re1+  , while after @@StartFEN@@8/8/8/2p1r3/4k1K1/2P5/2P5/3R4 b - - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...c4  White wins by means of  2.Re1+  Kd5  3.Rxe5+  Kxe5  4.Kg5!  (flank opposition)  4...Ke4  5.Kf6  +- @@StartBracket@@outflanking@@EndBracket@@. }
2. Re1+ Kd5 3. c4+ Kd6 4. Rxe6+ Kxe6 5. Kf4 Kf6 6. Ke4 Ke6 7. c3
{ Zugzwang. Finally, the decisive factor was White's spare tempo that had arisen during the earlier fight. }
*

