{ R. Réti, 1923    One should discover the mined squares here: these are g6 and e7. Actually, on  1.Kg6?  Ke7!  ⨀  2.Kf5  Kf7  ⨀ White would win if the d6-pawn did not exist, or if it stood on d5.  In the chapter on pawn endings, we learned to evaluate these situations instantaneously: the queenside pawns are in the'normal' position while the kingside gives White an extra tempo because his king stands in front of the pawn.  But with the pawn on d6 it is a draw because White must spend a tempo capturing it:  3.Ke4  Kg6  4.Kd5  Kg5  5.Kxd6  Kxg4  6.Kc6  Kf5  7.Kb6  Ke6  8.Kxa5  Kd7  9.Kb6  Kc8=   Or  2.g5  d5  3.Kf5  Kf7=  leads to the 'normal' position − the white king stands aside the pawn. And if  3.Kh7  d4  4.g6  d3  5.g7  d2  6.g8=Q  d1=Q=  .   1.Kh6 ?  does not win either:  Kf7  2.Kh7  Kf6  3.Kh6  Kf7  ('pendulum')  4.Kg5  Kg7  5.Kf5  Kf7 =  and if @@StartFEN@@8/5k2/3p3K/p7/P5P1/8/8/8 w - - 6 4@@EndFEN@@  4.g5  Kg8  5.Kg6  d5  6.Kf5  Kg7 =  @@StartBracket@@the 'normal' position again@@EndBracket@@. }
1. Kg5 Kf7 { 1...d5  2.Kf5  +- } 2. Kf5 { Zugzwang. } 2... Ke7 3. Kg6
{ The decisive zugzwang! If  3...Ke6  then  4.g5  d5  5.Kh7  d4  6.g6  +- }
3... d5 4. Kf5 Kf7 { 4...Kd6  5.g5  +- } 5. Ke5 { White wins. } *

