{ G. Kasparian, 1961 } 1. Be8
{ The h6-pawn cannot be captured now:  1.Kxh6??  Rd6+  . And  1.Bf3?  also loses:  1...Rd3!   Rather than  1...Rd6?  2.h4!  Kf5  3.Be2!=  or @@StartFEN@@8/7K/3r3p/4k3/7P/5B2/8/8 b - - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Kf4  3.Bh5!  Kg3  4.Bg6=  2.Bg4  (otherwise 2...Rh3)  2...Kf4  . }
1... Rd8
{ 1...Rd6  2.Bg6  Kf6  3.Kxh6  Rd4  4.Kh5=  is not dangerous for White. } 2.
Bg6 Kf6 3. Kxh6
{ In case of  3.h4?  Black wins by means of either  3...Rd4  4.h5  Kg5  or @@StartFEN@@3r4/7K/5kBp/8/7P/8/8/8 b - - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Rh8+  4.Kxh8  Kxg6  5.Kg8  h5  . }
3... Rh8+ 4. Bh7 Kf7 5. h3
{ 'The Steinitz rule' saves White: he can choose between a single or a double pawn move.   After  5.h4?  Kf6  6.h5  Kf7  he would have been in zugzwang, while now the fight ends in stalemate. }
5... Kf6 6. h4 Kf7 7. h5 Kf6 { Stalemate. } *

