{ Tragicomedies: Zhuravlev – Vasiukov, USSR ch tt, Riga 1968 } 1... Kg1
{ Black could win by means of  1...Rf7!  @@StartBracket@@zugzwang@@EndBracket@@  2.Ka5  Rf2  3.Ra4  Kxg2  4.Ka6  Rf7  -+ And if @@StartFEN@@8/p4r2/K7/1P6/8/6p1/R5Pk/8 w - - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Rb2  Rf2  3.Rb1  Ra2+  4.Kb7  Kxg2  -+ }
2. Rb2
{ White does not exploit his opponent’s error. He had to leave the a-file with his king:  2.Ka5!  Rc4  3.Ka6  and if @@StartFEN@@8/p1r5/8/KP6/8/6p1/R5P1/6k1 b - - 2 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Rf7  3.Kb4  @@StartBracket@@with a draw, because now Rf2 can be always met with Rxa7.@@EndBracket@@ }
2... Rf7 3. Rc2 Kh2 { 3...Rf2?  4.Rc1+ } 4. Ra2 Rf5
{ Zugzwang. When the black rook is on f5 or f7, all White’s moves can only worsen his position. }
5. Ra5 Kxg2 6. Kxa7 Kh3
{ White resigned in view of  7.Ka6  g2  8.Ra1  Rf1  -+ } *

