{ Tragicomedies: Šahovic – Liberzon, Lone Pine 1979  White is in a very dangerous situation. His rook must stand on the seventh or fifth rank to prevent Black’s ...Kf5, and his king cannot go to d3 in view of Black’s maneuver Re1-g1. Meanwhile Black plans ...Re4 and ...h5-h4. The key to this position is reciprocal zugzwang that arises when the black rook stands on e4 and the white rook on a5. The reason can be seen from the following line: }
1. Rb5 Re7 2. Rc5
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed.  2.Ra5?  Re4!  is the mutual zugzwang position that White needs to avoid. We have discussed it in the previousInformational. The text move aims to reach this position with Black to move.@@EndSquare@@ }
2... Re4 3. Ra5 h4 4. Kd3 Rb4 5. Kc3 { 5.gxh4?  loses to  5...Rxf4  6.h5  g5 }
5... Rb1 6. gxh4 Rf1 7. h5 Rxf4 8. hxg6 fxg6 9. Kd3 Rf5 10. Ra1 Re5 11. Rf1+
{ or   11.Rg1  , with a draw. If the black rook could occupy the a4-square, White could not have saved this ending. }
*

