{ 15/11. M. Liburkin, 1947 } 1. e6 a4 2. Kd1
{ After  2.Kc3?  a3  White is in a zugzwang:  3.Kc2  Bh7  and if @@StartFEN@@6bk/8/4PP2/5P2/8/p1K5/8/8 w - - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Kb3  Bh7  4.e7  Bg8+  5.Kxa3  Bf7=  The same zugzwang results from  2.Kc1?  a3  3.Kb1  Bh7= }
2... a3 3. Kc1 { Zugzwang. } 3... Kh7 4. Kb1
{ Only now, when the black king has deprived its own bishop of the h7-square, may White move his king closer to the pawn. Equally good is  4.Kc2  Kh6  5.Kc3  ⨀ +- }
4... Kh6 5. Ka1
{ Zugzwang.   @@StartSquare@@Ed. after  5.Ka2?  Black escapes with a draw  5...Bh7  6.e7  Bg8+  7.Kxa3  Bf7  =@@EndSquare@@ }
5... a2 6. Kb2 { Zugzwang. } 6... Kh7 7. Kxa2 { White wins. } *

