{ 15/12. N. Grigoriev, 1937 } 1. Rf5
{ A deep and a difficult introduction; White foresees the reciprocal zugzwang position that soon arises.   1.Rf1?  loses to  1...g3  2.Kf7  Rc1  and if @@StartFEN@@4K3/8/2r5/8/8/6p1/1k6/5R2 w - - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Rg1  Rc3  3.Kf7  Kc2  4.Kg6  Kd2  5.Kg5  Ke2  6.Kh4  Kf2  . Also bad is  1.Rg7?  Rc4  , because the king cannot go to either f7 or e7, and will be cut off from the pawn:  2.Kd7   Or  2.Rg5  Rf4!  -+.  2...Re4!  3.Kd6  Kc3  4.Kd5  Kd3  -+ }
1... g3
{ 1...Kc3  2.Rg5  Rc4  3.Kf7  Kd3  4.Kg6  Ke3  5.Kh5  Kf3  6.Kh4  Rf4  7.Ra5  g3+  8.Kh3= }
2. Rg5 Rc3 3. Kf7 Kc2 4. Kg6 Kd2 5. Kh5 Ke2 6. Kh4 Kf2 7. Kh3 Rf3
{ The threat is  8.--  Rf8  -+ } 8. Rg4
{ Diagram 16-110  The aforementioned zugzwang position! If White were on move he would be lost. }
8... Rf8 { 8...Ra3  9.Rg8  Rf3  10.Rg4! } 9. Rf4+ Rxf4
{ Stalemate.   After @@StartFEN@@4K3/5R2/2r5/8/6p1/8/1k6/8 w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Rf4?  g3  2.Rg4  Rc3  3.Kf7  Kc2  4.Kg6  Kd2  5.Kh5  Ke2  6.Kh4  Kf2  7.Kh3  Rf3  , it was White who would be in zugzwang:  8.Rg5  Rf8  -+ or  8.Ra4  g2+  . }
*

