{ 15/14. N. Riabinin, E. Markov, 1993 } 1. h6
{ White should first completely tie down his opponent. Neither  1.a7?  c5  nor @@StartFEN@@4k2B/2p1bp2/P1p5/3b3P/6K1/2P5/P7/8 w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.c4?  Be6+  is strong enough. }
1... f6 2. h7 Kf7 3. c4 Be6+ 4. Kh5 Bc8 { 4...Bc5?  5.Bxf6  +- } 5. a7 Bb7 6.
c5 Ba8
{ Diagram 16-112  White must now decide whether the a-pawn should make a single or a double step forward. Generally, it wants to go to a6 in order to deprive the light-square bishop of moves and to put Black in zugzwang. But deeper insight shows that White should get rid of his a7-pawn in order to free this square. This consideration explains the next move. }
7. a3
{ 7.a4?  leads only to a draw:  7...Bb7  8.a5  Ba8  9.a6  Bf8  10.Bxf6  Bg7= }
7... Bb7 8. a4 Ba8 9. a5 Bb7 10. a8=Q Bxa8 11. a6 { Zugzwang. } 11... Bf8
{ 11...Bd8  12.Kh6  ∆ 13.Bxf6 +- } 12. Bxf6 Bg7 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Kg5 Kxh7 15.
Kf6 Kg8 16. Ke7 Kg7 17. Kd7 { Or  17.Kd8  . } 17... Kf7 18. Kc8
{ White should not take the pawn:  18.Kxc7?  Ke7  19.Kb8  Kd7  20.Kxa8  Kc8  21.Ka7  Kc7= }
18... Ke7 19. Kb8 Kd7 20. Kxa8 Kc8 21. a7 { Or  21.Ka7  ⨀ +- } *

