{ Fortresses   We have discussed the construction of a fortress in several chapters @@StartBracket@@opposite-color bishops, a rook versus a minor piece, a queen versus a rook, a bishop versus pawns@@EndBracket@@. These fortresses were mainly elementary and known to theory. Here we shall look at the problem more broadly. You will discover new types of fortresses, together with my own simple classification. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 15 – General Endgame Ideas"]
[Black "A Fortified Camp 15-50"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "4K3/2k1Bp1N/6p1/5PP1/8/7p/b7/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ A Fortified Camp   @@StartSquare@@Ed. essential information → 'We define this as a situation in which a king, with or without the assistance of pieces or pawns, successfully defends a small territory  (as a rule, in a corner)  and cannot be ousted. Almost all the theoretical fortresses that are already known to you belong in this category.'@@EndSquare@@ I add only a single, more complicated example here.  F. Simkhovich, 1926  The h3-pawn will inevitably be promoted. Whites' only chance for a successful defense consists in building a fortress: f5-f6 and Kf8-g7. But to build a reliable fortress he needs to place his bishop on h6. Otherwise Black brings his king to f5, takes the knight with his queen and captures the g5-pawn, winning. The question is whether White can perform this task in time.   The natural  1.f6?  loses:  1...h2  2.Kf8  h1=Q  3.Kg7   3.Kg8  Kd7  4.Bf8  Qa8 !  ∆ ...Ke6-f5 +-  3...Kc6  4.Nf8  Qh4  5.Nh7  Kd5  6.Ba3  Ke4  7.Bb4  Kf5  8.Bd2  Qf2  9.Bc1  Qe1  10.Ba3  Qh1  -+ followed by  11.--  Qxh7+  . }
1. Bf6 Kd6 { 1...h2?  2.Be5+ } 2. Be7+ Kc6
{ The king has been forced to occupy a square on the h1-a8 diagonal. This is precisely what White wanted.   Simkhovich included the moves  2...Ke5  3.Bd8  Kd6  4.Be7+  and only now  4...Kc6  . But after  2...Ke5?  White has a simpler draw:  3.fxg6  fxg6  4.Kd7= }
3. f6 h2 4. Bf8
{ Rather than  4.Kf8?  h1=Q  5.Kg8  Qh2  6.Bf8  Qb8!  7.Kg7  Kd7  etc. } 4...
h1=Q 5. Bh6
{ The queen cannot deliver a check from a8, and the white king comes to g7 safely. White has successfully built an impregnable fortress. }
*

