[SetUp "1"]

{ A Pawn Barrier   @@StartSquare@@Ed. essential information → "Even a huge material advantage sometimes cannot be exploited when a pawn barrier lies across the chessboard. A king  (or, as it may happen in exceptional cases, a king and other pieces)  cannot overcome the barrier, and therefore there is no win."@@EndSquare@@  We saw this situation in theexercise 7/15  (in the chapter on bishop versus knight)  , in the annotation to 4.Kb3!. The alternative possibility led to the win of a piece and to ... an obvious draw caused by erecting a pawn barrier that the king could not breach.  The following curious example is taken from a game between two leading chess players of their time.  Chigorin − Tarrasch, Vienna 1898  Chigorin offered a draw, and Tarrasch unexpectedly rejected this offer. Then Chigorin took his bishop away from the board and suggested his opponent to try to win with an extra piece. Tarrasch immediately accepted the draw proposal. Actually, his king cannot invade White's position, while his bishop alone cannot accomplish anything. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 15 – General Endgame Ideas"]
[Black "A Pawn Barrier 15-52"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/8/3k2pb/1p2p2p/pNp1P2P/P1PnNK2/1P4P1/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Keres – Portisch, Moscow 1967    The b2-pawn is attacked. If there is an exchange on  d3  , the black king gets an open road into White’s camp along the white squares:  1.Nxd3?  cxd3  2.g3  Kc5  3.Kf2  Bxe3+  4.Kxe3  Kc4  5.Kd2  Kb3  -+ And if @@StartFEN@@8/8/3k2pb/1p2p2p/p3P2P/P1PpNK2/1P4P1/8 w - - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nd1  Bc1  ⨀ ...Kc5-c4-b3 -+ }
1. Nd1 Bc1 2. Ke2
{ Obviously  2...Bxb2?  3.Nxb2  Nxb2  4.Kd2=  yields nothing, but why is Black not able to take the pawn with his knight? This was Keres’ idea. @@StartFEN@@8/8/3k2p1/1p2p2p/pNp1P2P/P1Pn4/1P2K1P1/2bN4 b - - 3 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nxb2?  3.Nxb2  Bxb2  4.Kd2  Bxa3  5.Kc2  .  How does one exploit two extra pawns? Black’s bishop is locked, White intends to move his king from c2 to b1 and back. If  5...g5  , then  6.g3!    If Black brings his king to c5 or a5, White gives a knight check from a6 @@StartBracket@@resp. c6@@EndBracket@@ and plays back to b4. Finally, if Black exchanges his bishop for the knight, his king will be unable to cross the barrier, so both passed pawns at a4 and c4 will be useless. Portisch recognized this clever trap and chose: }
2... Nc5 3. Kf3 g5
{ This allowed him to subsequently exploit his positional advantage. } *

