[SetUp "1"]

{ 15/16. V. Chekhover, 1948 } 1. f3
{ The solution is quite unexpected: White should build a fortified camp with a bishop against a queen!   1.Bh2?  loses to  1...a4  2.Kd2  a3  3.Kc2  Kg5  4.f3   4.f4+  exf4  5.e5  a2  6.Kb2  f3  7.exd6  f2  -+  4...a2  5.Kb2  g1=Q  6.Bxg1  Kf4  7.Bh2+  Kxf3  8.Bxe5  dxe5  9.d6  h2  -+ And if @@StartFEN@@8/2p5/2Pp4/3Pp3/4P3/5k1p/pK5B/8 w - - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Kxa2  , not  8...Kg2?  9.Bxe5=  , but  8...Kxe4!  9.Kb3  Kxd5  . }
1... a4 2. Kf2 a3 3. Kg3 a2 4. Kxh3 a1=Q 5. Kxg2 Qb2+
{ 5...Kg5  6.Be3+  Kh4  7.Bf2+= } 6. Bf2 Kg5 7. Kg3
{ Diagram 16-113  It becomes clear that a breakthrough on the kingside is a difficult matter. A king march to the queenside is senseless because the a7-square is not available: the white bishop controls it. }
7... Qc1 8. Ba7 { The only square for the bishop. } 8... Qf4+ 9. Kg2 Qd2+ 10.
Kg3 { Draw. } *

