{ An Imprisoned King   @@StartSquare@@Ed. essential information → 'Sometimes the hostile king can be 'caged' on an edge of the board. Without its participation, the remaining pieces may be unable to achieve any success.'@@EndSquare@@  V. Smyslov, 1998 }
1. Nd5 b1=Q 2. b6+ Kb8
{ If  2...Ka6  then  3.Ne2!  and 4.Nec3=. The black king is locked on a6 and a5, while the queen cannot mate alone. Black could have won if he had managed to put White in zugzwang by stalemating his king.   For example,  3...Qf1  4.Nec3  Qf5  5.Kh6??  Qg4  6.Kh7  Qg5  7.Kh8  Qg6  -+ But after @@StartFEN@@8/1p4K1/kP6/3N1q2/8/2N5/8/8 w - - 5 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Kg8!  he cannot manage this. The queen is denied the important f6-square,  or after  5...Qd7  @@StartBracket@@here of course not  6.Kh8??  Qf7  -+@@EndBracket@@, but  6.Kf8  Ka5  7.Kg8  the e7-square.  5...Qg6+  also gives nothing:  6.Kf8!  Qh7  7.Ke8  Qg7  8.Kd8  Qf7  9.Kc8= }
3. Nh5 Qg1+ 4. Kf7 Kc8 5. Nhf6 Kd8 6. Ke6
{ Here again the draw is obvious because the black king cannot leave the edge. After  6.Kf8?  Qg6!  ⨀ however, White should have released the king. Zugzwang is the main danger in that and all similar situations, but it can usually be avoided in practice.   Even a knight alone can arrest a king. If Black played his king to a8 on move 2 while the white knight was on d7 and his king on an adjacent square, @@StartFEN@@k7/1p1NK3/1P6/8/8/8/8/1q6 b - - 0 2@@EndFEN@@ the second knight would not have been needed. }
*

