{ P. Pechenkin, 1953    After  3...a1=Q  4.N4g5  the black king would have been caged as in the previous example. }
1... Kf7 2. N6g5+ Kg6
{ The king is free, but White manages to save himself by creating a fortified camp around his own king. }
3. Kg2 a1=Q 4. Nf3 Kf5 5. Nfd2
{ The black king cannot go farther than f4 and e2, while the queen cannot come close enough to the white king to deny it the free squares in the corner; therefore the draw is inevitable. }
*

