{ Reshevsky − Fischer, Los Angeles m  (11)  1961    Fischer, in his annotations to the game, wrote that White loses in view of  1.Kf2  Ra2+  2.Kf1  Ra3!  3.Kf2  Rf3+!  4.Kxf3  Kg1  5.Be3+  Kf1  -+  However Murey demonstrated a rather simple way to a draw, based on locking in the king. }
1. Be3 Ra1+ 2. Kf2 Ra2+ 3. Kf1 { 3.Kf3??  Ra3  -+ } 3... Ra3 4. Bb6 Rf3+
{ 4...Rxg3  5.Kf2= } 5. Bf2 Rf7 6. g4 Rg7 7. Bb6 Rxg4 8. Kf2 Rg6 9. Ba7 Rf6+
10. Kg3
{ And the king cannot get away from the corner. Kling and Horwitz found the final position as long ago as the middle of the 19th century. }
