{ A. Gurvich, 1952    1.Rh4?  Kxg8  2.Rg4  Kg7   2...g5?  3.Kb7  ∆ 4.Rg3=  3.Kb7!  is seemingly strong. If  3...Kf6?  White holds by means of permanently pursuing the bishop:  4.Rg3  Bc5   4...Bd4  5.Rg4  Nf3  6.Rf4+  and if  4...Bf2  5.Rg2  .  5.Kc6  Ba7  6.Kb7=  . But @@StartFEN@@8/1K4k1/6p1/8/6R1/4b3/8/6n1 b - - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Kh6!!  is much stronger:  4.Rg3  Bc5!  5.Kc6  Bd4!  6.Rg4   6.Kd5  Ba7  -+  6...Nf3!  7.Rf4  @@StartBracket@@without a check!@@EndBracket@@  7...Ne5+  8.Kd5  Bg1!  , and Black manages to move the pieces away from attacks:  9.Kxe5  Bh2  -+ or  9.Rf1  Bh2  10.Rh1  Ng4  -+ }
1. Rh8
{ The correct method is to keep the bishop rather than the rook, in order to use it for locking in the black knight on g1. }
1... Kg7 2. Bh7 g5 3. Bf5 Kxh8 4. Bg4 Kg7 5. Kc7 Kf6 6. Kd6 Bc1 7. Kd5 Ba3 8.
Ke4 { Or  8.Kd4 } 8... Ke7 9. Kd5 Kd8 10. Kc6 Bf8 11. Kb7 Ke7 12. Kc6 Kf6 13.
Kd5
{ Unfortunately for Black his king, as well as the knight, is also locked in. }
