{ Vaganian – Georgadze, Erevan zt 1982    It is not easy for Black to find an acceptable move. Both  1...Kf3?  2.Rg5  and @@StartFEN@@8/8/p7/P6p/2p2k1P/1pKb4/6R1/8 b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Bc2?  2.Rg5  Bd1  3.Rg6  lose a pawn.   1...Ke4?  is not much better in view of  2.Rg5  Be2  3.Rg6  @@StartBracket@@with the threat 4.Rxa6 b2 5.Rb6 +-@@EndBracket@@  3...Bd3  4.Rh6  +- Georgadze finds the only good possibility: he drives his king forward to help his passed pawns. }
1... Ke3 2. Rg5
{ On  2.Rg3+  , the simplest reply is  2...Kf4!  3.Rg5  Be2  4.Rg6  Bd3=  , and White can play neither  5.Rxa6?  b2  nor @@StartFEN@@8/8/p5R1/P6p/2p2k1P/1pKb4/8/8 w - - 7 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Rh6?  Kg4  . However,  2...Ke2  does not lose either:  3.Rg5  Kd1!   3...b2?  4.Rg2+  4.Rxh5  Kc1  5.Rg5  Be2  6.Rg1+  Bd1  7.Rg2  Bf3!   The squares h5 and h2 are mined:  7...Bh5?  8.Rh2  +-⨀  8.Rh2  Bh5  ⨀= }
2... b2 3. Kxb2 Kd2 4. Rc5 { 4.Rg2+  Be2= } 4... Be2
{ Draw. White cannot make progress because his rook must watch the passed c-pawn. }
