{ V. Smyslov, 2000    1.Ke2  looks quite natural, but after  1...Kc7  2.Kd3  Kb6  3.Ke4  Ra5  -+ And if @@StartFEN@@r7/8/1k6/1P4p1/8/p2K2P1/6P1/1R6 w - - 4 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Kc4  a2!  4.Ra1  g4  -+  White is lost.  5.Kb3  Kxb5  6.Rxa2  Rxa2  7.Kxa2  Kc4  -+ Playing for a stalemate is his salvation. }
1. b6 { The threat 2.b7 forces Black to push his pawn to a2. } 1... a2 2. Ra1
Kc8 3. g4 Kb7 4. g3 Kxb6 5. Kg2 Kb5 6. Kh3 Kb4 7. Rxa2 { Draw. } *

