[SetUp "1"]

{ Goldstein − Shakhnovich, Moscow 1946 } 1... gxf3
{ 1...g3?  is wrong:  2.c7+  Kc8  3.Bf5+  Rd7  4.Bh3  g2  5.Bxg2  +- } 2. Bxf3
{ If  2.c7+  Kc8  3.Bf5+  Rd7=  And if @@StartFEN@@2k5/2P5/1P6/4K3/4B3/5p2/8/3r4 w - - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bxf3  then  3...Rc1  4.Kd6  Rc6+! }
2... Rd7
{ Only this fine move holds the game.   At first I thought that  2...Rc1  3.Kd6  Kc8!  was also sufficient for a draw. For example,  4.c7  Rc6+!  , while after  4.Bd5  Rc2  5.Be6+  Kb8  6.Kd7   6.c7+  Kb7  7.c8=Q+  Rxc8  8.Bxc8+  Kxb6  6...Rd2+  7.Ke7  Rc2  8.Kd6  Rc1  9.Bd5  Kc8!  , or @@StartFEN@@2k5/8/1PPK4/8/8/5B2/8/2r5 w - - 3 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Be2  Kb8!  5.Ba6  Rd1+  , while after  5.Kd7  Rc2!   5...Rc3?  6.Ba6  6.Bd3  Rc1!  Reciprocal zugzwang: Black loses if it is his turn to play, but now White is on move.   However, grandmaster Karsten Müller found the following winning way for White:  4.Bg4+  Kb8  5.Kd7  Rc2  or  5...Rc3  6.Bf5  Rc4   Black must beware of 7.Be4; on  6...Rc1  7.Bd3  , we have the reciprocal zugzwang position from above, but with Black to play.  7.Be6  Rc5  8.Bb3  ⨀, and wherever the rook goes along the c-file, 9.Bd5 will be decisive. }
3. Ke6 Rb7 { Draw. } *

