{ @@StartSquare@@Ed. essential information → 'A situation can arise when the defender has only one mobile piece, and if it can be sacrificed, a stalemate occurs. Even though the opponent rejects the Greek gift,  'the desperado'  continually offers itself for capture.  To escape from the pursuit of a 'desperado queen' is almost impossible. With a rook in the 'desperado' role, everything depends on the specific circumstances.'@@EndSquare@@  A. Frolovsky, 1989 }
1. Ra8
{ 1.Rxh7?  Kf5  2.a7  Ra6  leads to a draw. It seems now that Black may well resign in view of the threat 2.a7. }
1... Rb1+ 2. Kg2
{ This move can be played only if White has discovered Black's stalemate idea and evaluated it well enough.   The apparently natural  2.Ke2?  misses a win because of  2...Ra1  3.a7  Kf6!!  4.Rf8+  Kg7  5.a8=Q  Re1+!  (a desperado rook)  6.Kd2  Rd1+  and if  6.Kf2  Rf1+  7.Kg2  @@StartBracket@@here  7...Rxf8!?  is also good enough for a draw.@@EndBracket@@ or  7...Rf2+!  8.Kg3  Rf3+  9.Kg4  Rf4+  . }
2... Ra1 3. a7 Ra2+
{ After  3...Kf6  4.Rf8+  Kg7  5.a8=Q  the desperado rook is curbed immediately:  5...Rg1+  6.Kh2!  and there are no checks anymore because the queen keeps the squares g2 and h1 under control. }
4. Kg3 Ra3+ 5. Kf4 Ra4+ 6. Ke3 Ra3+
{ 6...Kf6  7.Rf8+  Kg7  8.a8=Q  Ra3+  9.Kf4!  +-   Ed. note: continued in the next variation → Diagram 15-81 }
