{ Tragicomedies: Zapata – Vaganian, Thessaloniki ol 1984 } 1... Bc3
{ As Vaganian demonstrated, the waiting move  1...Bc1!  wins for Black. The main line is then  2.Kh5  Bb2  3.Kh6  Bxf6  -+ And if  3.Kg4  Kg6  4.Kf4  Bc1+  5.Ke5  Bxg5  6.Kd6  Bd2!  7.Kc6  Ba5  or  7.Ke7  Bb4+  8.Ke6  Bc3  9.f7  Bb4!  -+ @@StartBracket@@rather than  9...Kg7?  10.Ke7  Bb4+  11.Ke8  ⨀  Bc5  12.Kd7  Kxf7  13.Kc6  =@@EndBracket@@.   Another winning continuation is  1...Be3  2.Kh5  Bc1  3.Kh6  Bd2!  @@StartBracket@@the bishop will occupy the optimal b4-square because of this triangular maneuver@@EndBracket@@  4.Kh5  Bc3  5.Kg4  Kg6  6.Kf4  Bb4!?   After  6...Bd2+  7.Ke5  Bxg5  we transpose to the Vaganian line.  7.Kg4  Bd2  ⨀ and if  7.Ke5  Kxg5  8.f7  Kg6  9.Ke6  Kg7  10.Kd7  Kxf7  11.Kc6  Ba5  -+ @@StartBracket@@Inarkiev@@EndBracket@@. }
2. g6+
{ In the game Zapata hit on the stalemate idea but the transposition of moves is fatal for him:  2.a5??  bxa5  3.g6+  Kg8!  White resigned. }
2... Kxf6 3. a5 bxa5 4. g7 Kf7 5. Kh7
{ @@StartSquare@@Ed. In order to avoid the g-pawn from queening Black will have to take on g7, forcing a stalemate.@@EndSquare@@ }
