{ Tragicomedies: Hickl – Solomon, Thessaloniki ol 1988 } 1. Rg8+ Kf6 2. Rf8+
{ 2.Rg6+!  led to a stalemate; the spectators saw this possibility, but the players overlooked it. The game was adjourned here. An elementary win was possible after @@StartFEN@@5R2/8/5k2/6p1/5pK1/1r6/8/8 b - - 3 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Ke7  or  2...Kg7  , but Black decided to repeat moves to be “on the safe side” and sealed: }
2... Kg6
{ The captain of the Australian team ordered his player Solomon, to look satisfied, to go back to the hotel immediately, and to stay silent. Hickl did not suspect that his opponent could have sealed such a move and did not want to return for a hopeless resumption, so he resigned the next morning at breakfast.  Many cases of miraculous salvation through stalemate can be mentioned. I want to add just one more. }
*

