{ S. Kaminer, 1925  Unlike the previous examples, here one feels that the black king is in danger. Paradoxically, White must immediately give up his strongest fighting unit to successfully conduct the attack. }
1. Rc2 Qxc2
{ Black must accept the sacrifice.   If  1...Qb8+  then  2.Bc7  Qf8  3.Rc5!  Qxc5  4.Bd8+  and 5.g3#.  @@StartFEN@@2q5/8/6p1/B6p/7k/7P/2R3PK/8 b - - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Qf8  2.Rc4+  Kg5  3.Bd2+  Kf6  4.Rf4+  is also bad. Other queen retreats are met with 2.Rc5, cutting off the kings escape. }
2. Bd8+ g5 3. Ba5
{ An amazing position: a bishop proves stronger than a queen. 4.Be1+ is threatened. Black will be mated immediately after  3...g4  4.Bd8#  Or  3...Qd1  4.g3#  , while after  3...Qf2  4.Bc7  ,  he is put in zugzwang. }
3... Qe2 4. Bc7 { ∆ Bg3# } 4... Qf2 5. Bd6
{ Zugzwang. Rather than  5.Be5?  g4  . } 5... Qf4+ 6. g3+ Qxg3+ 7. Bxg3# *

