{ 15/36. Zakharov-Petrushin, USSR 1973 } 1. Kh6
{ The a-pawn cannot be stopped, for example:  1.Nxf7+?  Kh7!  2.Ne3  Nd4!  -+ or  1.Ne3?  Nd4!  -+   White’s chances lie only in a kingside attack. Zakharov chose  1.Ne7?  He had  1...a2??  2.Kh6!  +- or  1...Kh7?  2.Nd5  @@StartBracket@@∆ 3.Nf6+; 3.Nc3@@EndBracket@@ in mind. However, Petrushin replied with @@StartFEN@@7k/1p2Np2/8/4N1KP/8/pn6/8/8 b - - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...f6+!  2.Kxf6  Kh7  3.Nf5  a2  4.Ng6  Nd4!  The careless  4...a1=Q+?  5.Kf7  could lead to perpetual check @@StartBracket@@Nf8-g6+@@EndBracket@@, while after the move actually played, White had to resign.   According to Gufeld’s comments in Chess Informant, White could have achieved a draw by means of  1.Kf6  a2  2.Kxf7  a1=Q  3.Ng6+  Kh7  4.Nf8+  . However, Nunn indicated that this is wrong – Black could win after  1...Kg8!  2.Nh6+  Kf8  and if  2.Ne7+  Kh7  3.Kxf7  a2  4.Nf5  Nc5!   4...a1=Q?  5.Nd7=  or  5.Ng6=  5.Ng6  Nd7  6.Ke7  a1=Q  . Grandmaster Nunn found a win for White in the initial position. }
1... Kg8
{ 1...a2  2.Ne7!  ∆ Nxf7#; @@StartFEN@@7k/1p3p2/7K/4NN1P/8/pn6/8/8 b - - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...f6  2.Nf7+  Kg8  3.Kg6  a2  4.h6  a1=Q  5.h7+  . }
2. Nd7
{ The threat is @@StartFEN@@6k1/1p1N1p2/7K/5N1P/8/pn6/8/8 w - - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Ne7+  Kh8  4.Ne5  . }
2... f6 { 2...Kh8  3.Nf6  ∆ Nd6 +- } 3. Kg6 a2 4. Nh6+ Kh8 5. Nxf6 a1=Q 6. Nf7#
