{ 1...Kb1  is bad:  2.Nd5  or  2.Ne2  a1=Q  3.Nc3+  Qxc3+  4.Kxc3  a2  5.Rb2+  +- }
2. Rc1 a1=Q
{ 2...Kb2  3.Kd2  a1=Q  4.Nd3+  Ka2  5.Nb4+  Kb2  6.Rxa1  Kxa1  7.Kc1  ⨀  +- }
3. Rxa1 Kb2 { Diagram 16-119 } 4. Rf1
{ The only correct place for the rook retreat, as becomes clear from further events. }
4... a2 5. Kc4 a1=Q 6. Nd3+ Ka2 7. Nb4+ Kb2 8. Rf2+ Kb1
{ Black does not have  8...Ka3?  9.Nc2+  and if  8...Kc1  ,  White wins by means of  9.Na2+  Kb1  10.Kb3  . If the white rook stood on e2, Black could save the game with @@StartFEN@@8/8/8/8/1NK5/8/1k2R3/q7 b - - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Kc1  9.Na2+  Kd1  . }
9. Kb3
{ If the rook were on g2 or h2, Black could parry the mate threat with @@StartFEN@@8/8/8/8/1N6/1K6/6R1/qk6 b - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Qa7  or 9...Qa8 respectively. Now, however, he cannot do it: the knight controls the a6-square. }
