{ The cases when weaker pieces dominate stronger ones are, of course, the most impressive.  J. Sulz, 1941    White cannot win by normal means because Black attacks the a-pawn with his rook and king in time. For example,  1.Bc8?  Kd3  2.Bb7  Ra1  3.Nf4+  Kc4=  , or  1.Bd7?  Ra1  2.Bb5+  Kf3  3.Nh4+  Ke4=  , or @@StartFEN@@6K1/8/P7/8/8/7B/4k1N1/5r2 w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nh4?  Ra1  2.Bc8  Kd3  3.Nf5  Kc4= }
1. Nf4+ Rxf4 2. Bd7
{ A striking situation: all paths to the a-file and to the eighth rank are closed for the rook on an open board.  2...Rf3  3.Bg4  and @@StartFEN@@6K1/3B4/P7/8/5r2/8/4k3/8 b - - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Rf1  3.Bb5+  +- }
2... Rf6 3. a7 Ra6 4. Bb5+
{ An equally sudden and striking capture of a rook on an open board is the point of the next study.  Diagram 15-108 has been intentionally omitted. }
