{ 15/40. A. Kuriatnikov, 1981 } 1. Re7
{ The line  1.Nb6+?  Kb7  2.Rxe2  Rf5  or @@StartFEN@@5r2/1k6/1N6/2P5/4R2K/8/4p3/8 w - - 2 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Kg3  Kc6  3.Na4  Kb5!  ∆  4.--  e1=Q  leads to a rapid draw.   1.Rxe2?  Kb7  is also unpromising. As we soon shall see, the rook belongs on e1 in this sort of position. }
1... e1=Q+
{ 2.Nb6+ was threatened.   If  1...Rf4+  then  2.Kg3  Rc4  3.Nb6+  Kd8  4.Nxc4  Kxe7  5.Kf2  +- In case of @@StartFEN@@N1k2r2/4R3/8/2P5/7K/8/4p3/8 b - - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Kd8  White wins by means of  2.Rxe2  (the king cannot go to b7)  2...Kd7  3.Nb6+  Kc6  4.Re5  Rf1  5.Nc8  Rc1  6.Ne7+  +- }
2. Rxe1 Kb7 3. Nb6
{ Rather than  3.Ra1?  Kc6  4.Ra5  Rf5  5.Ra6+  Kb7  6.Ra5  Kc6= } 3... Rf5
{ 3...Kc6?  4.Re6+  or  4.Re5  . } 4. Nd7 Kc6
{ Diagram 16-120   4...Rd5  5.Re6!  Kc7  6.c6  Rd6  7.Rxd6  Kxd6  8.Ne5  +- After  4...Kc6  5.Rd1?  is useless now:  5...Rd5!  6.Rxd5  Kxd5  7.Kg5  Kc6=  It is an unexpected trapping of the rook that decides. }
5. Ne5+ Kxc5 6. Kg4
{ This is why the white rook went to e1! After 1.Rxe2?, the black rook would have had a safe square @@StartBracket@@f1@@EndBracket@@ in the final position. }
